<HEADER>
A4061 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-EXECS-PAY-METHOD-2TAK     04-01 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECS-PAY-METHOD-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE NUMBERS MEAN, AND HOW THEY WERE CALCULATED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This is a sidebar to EXECS-STOCK-OPTIONS. Also, see
graphics.)  
 (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In examining executive compensation, Money &AMP; Business sought
this year to capture the differences between the pay practices of
companies in the old economy of industrial, service and financial
concerns and those in the new economy of Internet and related
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   After all, one of the biggest worries today of managers at
established companies is the flight of workers to Internet jobs
that promise unprecedented wealth. And one of the great concerns of
economists and market watchers is that the new economy's pay
practices _ especially its generosity with stock options _ may be
contributing to a casino mentality, blind to business fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   To gauge the divide, Executive Compensation Advisory Services,
an Alexandria, Va., division of Harcourt Inc. that collects,
analyzes and sells information on executive pay, collected data on
pay at 160 companies among the early filers of proxies for 1999,
the documents in which compensation details are reported.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the old economy in the survey were 100 of the
largest nontechnology companies (as measured by sales) that had
filed their proxies by March 23.
</P>
<P>
   The 60 new-economy companies had the same proxy deadline and
appeared on one of 10 widely watched indexes of technology stocks:
the Dow Jones Internet composite index; the Fortune e-50; the
Interactive Week Internet index; the USA Today Internet 100;
internet.com's Internet Stock List and ISDEX Internet Stock index;
the Wall Street Research Net e-tailers index; and TheStreet.com's
Internet Sector, e-commerce and e-finance indexes.
</P>
<P>
   (A company in one of these indexes that would also have
qualified, by size, for inclusion in the old-economy list _
Microsoft, for example, or IBM _ was considered part of the new
economy in the study.)
</P>
<P>
   All 160 chief executives had to hold the job for their company's
entire 1999 fiscal year. (That period varied widely, with the
fiscal year for a few companies ending as early as March 1999.)
Several of those listed _ like Bill Gates of Microsoft and Dale F.
Morrison of Campbell Soup _ are no longer chief executive today.
</P>
<P>
   Pay can be added up any number of ways. Pay critics _ and
corporate recruiters _ tend to cite the biggest possible numbers,
while executives and company directors may have an interest in
minimizing the size of pay packages. In any event, the biggest
differences stem from the way stock options are valued.
</P>
<P>
   Any value assigned to an option is a guess; the real worth of a
chance to buy a stock four years from now at, say, $10 a share
depends on the trading price of that stock in four years. The data
in the tables on these two pages represents an attempt to recognize
this uncertainty, and to take into account how people think about
options in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Options granted in 1999 are valued two different ways. One
method, using a widely accepted guideline of 33 percent of the
price at which the options were granted, takes into account the
volatility of stock prices. The other method estimates the value of
options based on recent prices for each company's stock _ the value
that an executive would have in mind if he was keeping one eye on
the stock ticker.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these numbers appears in corporate proxy statements,
which use one of two other methods for valuing options. Simply
using the companies' values would make it impossible to compare
various executives' options grants.
</P>
<P>
   Given the complications, the tables do not try to total cash and
options pay into a single number. Income from exercising options
granted in past years is also reported separately, as it can be
viewed as compensation for previous years' work.
</P>
<P>
   Here are definitions for the columns in the tables. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Direct Compensation &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SALARY Base annual pay that does not directly depend on company
results.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BONUS A cash payment that can very widely depending on the
company's performance. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONG-TERM INCENTIVE AND OTHER A combination of two categories.
The first covers incentive payments that most companies set
approximately three years in advance and pay out depending on the
company's performance. The second includes miscellaneous items like
moving expenses, insurance payments or fees covering personal use
of a corporate jet. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL DIRECT COMPENSATION The sum of the three previous
categories. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At-Risk Compensation &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RESTRICTED STOCK The value, as reported by the company, of
shares conditionally granted to an executive. Typically, executives
get to keep these shares only if they remain with the company for a
predetermined period.
</P>
<P>
   Values are shown only for executives who received restricted
stock. None of the new-economy executives in the study received
restricted stock, so the column does not appear on the new-economy
table. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999 OPTIONS, GRANT-DATE VALUE An estimate of the value of the
stock options granted to an executive in 1999, based on the price
of the company's stock when the options were granted. (The exercise
price of all options in the study is the same as the market price
on the grant date.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the most common methods for valuing options is the
Black-Scholes formula, which takes into account the exercise price
of the option, the time before it can be exercised, the time before
it expires and the volatility of the company's stock. A widely used
approximation of the formula simply takes one-third of the exercise
price. This is the method that Money &AMP; Business used.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if an executive received 100,000 options on a stock
that was trading at $30, the study estimated the grant to be worth
100,000 multiplied by $10, or $1 million. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999 OPTIONS, ESTIMATED CURRENT VALUE An estimate of the value
of the stock options an executive received in 1999, based on recent
prices of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   The study found the average of the company's closing stock
prices at the end of December, January and February. The exercise
price of the option was then subtracted from that average to arrive
at a current value for the option.
</P>
<P>
   Consider again the executive who received 100,000 options on a
stock that was trading, on the grant date, at $30. If the average
recent stock price was $50, each option would be valued at $20, and
the 100,000 options would be worth $2 million. If the stock was
trading at $29, the options would have no current value. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Accumulated Wealth  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS PROFITS REALIZED IN F.Y. 1999 The gain that executives
saw in the 1999 fiscal year by exercising options from previous
years. For each option, this number is the difference between the
price of the stock when the executive exercised the option and the
price at which the option was granted. In some cases, executives
immediately sell the underlying shares, and in other cases they
hold onto the stock. Values are shown only for executives who
realized profits during the fiscal year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VALUE OF STOCK BENEFICIALLY HELD The value of shares held
outright by an executive, based on the closing stock price at the
end of the company's fiscal year. In some cases _ because, for
instance, shares are held in trust for a child _ executives may
disclaim beneficial ownership of a portion of the shares they are
reported as owning. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VALUE OF OPTIONS, F.Y. END Value, at the end of acompany's
fiscal year, of both exercisable and nonexercisable options held by
the executive. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL VALUE OF EQUITY The sum of the previous two numbers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OWNERSHIP STAKE Beneficial stock holdings, plus exercisable
options and options exercisable within 60 days, as a percentage of
the company's total shares outstanding, as reported in the
company's proxy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Performance &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STOCK PERFORMANCE VS. S&AMP;P 500 The amount, in percentage points,
by which the company's performance trailed or exceeded the stock
index during the period through the end of the company's 1999
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Performance comparisons are for a one-year period for
new-economy companies and a three-year period for old-economy
companies.
</P>
<P>
   For those new-economy companies that went public during the 1999
fiscal year, performance is measured against the index for the
portion of the year that they were publicly traded.
</P>
<P>
   Some new-economy companies went public after the end of the
fiscal year; they are shown as N.A. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Averages and Medians &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For each column, these figures take into account only executives
for whom values were reported. For example, the averages for
restricted stock grants to old-economy executives include only the
34 executives who received restricted stock. ``Average'' is the
arithmetic mean; ``median'' is the figure in the middle of the
series of numbers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The performance statistics were calculated by Money &AMP; Business,
based on data provided by Factset Research Systems, a research firm
in Greenwich, Conn., and Bloomberg Financial Markets. All other
data was calculated by Executive Compensation Advisory Services.
</P>
</TEXT>
