<HEADLINE>
CISCO AND PENNEY: 2 COMPANIES' EXPERIENCE WITH STOCK COMPENSATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 2)  
 (sidebar with EXECS-PAY)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT CISCO, OPTIONS MACHINE CHURNS UNFETTERED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warren Buffett has made the point succinctly: if a company has a
choice between paying its employees with a currency that counts
against its earnings and another currency that does not, there is
not a lot of mystery about which one it will pick.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, the Internet equipment maker that is one of the
three most valuable companies in the world, is a good case study.
</P>
<P>
   The company is a heavy user of stock options, the form of pay
that accounting rules say does not have to be counted against
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, Cisco's employees held some 439 million outstanding
options.
</P>
<P>
   And for 1999, the company granted its chief executive, John T.
Chambers, options conservatively valued at $44 million. Valued at
recent stock prices for Cisco, the options are worth a stunning
$159 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco says that giving large option grants to managers ties
their pay to the company's performance _ and few investors would
argue with Cisco's performance.
</P>
<P>
   But some institutional investors and management experts are
worried about the long-term cost of giving employees large,
discounted stakes in their companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Option plans are redistributing corporate ownership,'' Eric D.
Roiter, a general counsel at Fidelity Investments, wrote recently.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco reported $2.1 billion in net income in 1999, but
accounting for options would have erased $500 million of that,
according to a footnote in the annual report. That would amount to
a 24 percent reduction in earnings per share.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Powell, the company's controller, notes that all this
information is available to investors. And, he points out, the $500
million is no more than an estimate, based on one of many economic
formulas for valuing options.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a what-if calculation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. PENNEY BOSSES IN STOCK BIND
</P>
<P>
   Management experts and institutional investors constantly lobby
American executives to own more stock in the companies they run.
Unlike options _ which, at worst, are worth nothing _ ownership of
actual shares brings a downside. When investors lose money, so do
the people running the company.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when many old-economy stocks declined, that danger
became real for top executives. Few lost as much as the bosses at
J.C. Penney, the giant retailer, whose stock lost more than half
its value during 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies require their chief executives to own stock worth
three to five times their annual salary, said James A. Hatch, an
executive vice president at the Compensation Resource Group, a pay
consulting firm in New York. Penney is more aggressive. Its chief
executive, James E. Oesterreicher, must own seven times his annual
salary, according to the company's most recent proxy. The ratio
declines for lower-level executives, down to one and a half times
salary for store managers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the most recent year's proxy available for Penney,
Oesterreicher made $612,000. He did not own quite seven times that
in early 1999, but he did hold about 80,000 shares, worth about $3
million at the time. (The shares had been worth about $4 million
only a few months before.)
</P>
<P>
   Friday, however, with J.C. Penney's stock trading at $14.875,
80,000 shares would be worth just $1.19 million. If Oesterreicher
received no raise last year and still holds 80,000 shares today, he
would have to buy an additional 200,000 to comply with the
company's policy. Through a spokeswoman, he declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Many other chief executives find themselves in similar
predicaments. Coca-Cola, Eastman Kodak, Sara Lee and Sears, Roebuck
all have stock ownership policies, and all saw their price drop in
1999. To follow their own rules, executives there would have to do
some serious value investing _ or persuade their boards to hand
over thousands of free shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
