r s BC-BBA-MONDESI-LADN-(SLA     04-01 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MONDESI-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDESI SETTLES IN THIRD SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Before trading Raul Mondesi to Toronto in November,
Dodgers managing partner and CEO Bob Daly made one last call to
make sure this is what the Dodgers right fielder wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, in fact, was dead set on leaving Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in his Blue Jays duds, Mondesi sports a smile that spreads
from one diamond stud earring to the other. He said he'll miss the
Los Angeles fans and the friends he made along the way, but he
couldn't be happier about the way things worked out.
</P>
<P>
   After lobbying for years for a change, Mondesi is delighted
because he's hitting third in the Blue Jays' lineup. And Toronto
manager Jim Fregosi said he doesn't plan on that changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more bull(stuff), man,'' Mondesi said before the Dodgers'
exhibition game Friday night in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, they told me I'm hitting third all year. Now, I don't
have to worry if I go 0 for 4 a couple times, or go 0 for 10. I
know I'm going to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Dodgers, you had that pressure, because you never
knew what was going to happen. Anything can happen. If you go 0 for
10, the next day you're hitting fifth or sixth, or you're out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Mondesi had a chance to show up his old team.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he was hit with a pair of pitches, the second of which
sent him to Mt. Sinai Hospital for X-rays on his left little
finger. The X-rays were negative, but Mondesi said he'll sit out
today's game because he doesn't want to risk injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say they were trying (to hit him), but why did
they have to hit me twice?'' asked Mondesi, who left the clubhouse
with ice wrapped on his left hand. ``I don't want to make it a big
deal, but why?''
</P>
<P>
   To Mondesi, it's just another way the Dodgers are playing with
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi said he thought about his place in the batting order
nearly every day last season and it weighed heavily on him. He
batted first, third, fourth, fifth and sixth. He was particularly
annoyed when he was dropped from fourth to fifth in the batting
order in late April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please set the record straight,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``Mondi and I didn't have a problem. He was never a
problem for me. He played well for me. I think that Mondi was a
little sensitive to all the expectations put on this ballclub and
put on him.''
</P>
<P>
   The third position in the lineup is where Mondesi always wanted
to hit, and nearly every spring the experiment would take place.
Mondesi would hit third, managers would ask him to be more patient,
and by the second week he'd be hitting somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is different, completely different,'' said the 29-
year-old Mondesi, who spent seven seasons with the Dodgers. ``They
let you play. Everybody's happy. To me, it's the best thing to
happen, to get out of L.A. I still love the fans and everything,
you know, but that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi and those around him said it was simply time for change.
That's why he never went back on his request to be traded, part of
an obscenity-laced tirade aimed at Johnson and Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone last season.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi failed to understand Johnson's philosophy about a
batting order and thought he was singled out when things began
going bad last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, Malone and Johnson, that they wanted me to stay
there,'' Mondesi said. ``I said, `It's over. Get somebody else in.
I don't want to play for you guys anymore.' I appreciate everything
they did for me, but that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the deal that brought Shawn Green to the Dodgers and
sent Mondesi to Canada was left-handed relief pitcher Pedro Borbon,
who said the difference in Mondesi between last season and this
spring is eye-popping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mondi's like a kid in Disney World right now,'' Borbon said.
``You can see the way he plays. He's always been intense, but now
he's comfortable. He's real happy to be here and sometimes you need
a change. I was real happy to get away from the Braves. I don't
think he was thrilled about it, but he knew he needed a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing in baseball, you have to be happy. If you're happy,
you're able to perform better. I feel this is the year he's going
to do the 40-40 thing. He's capable of doing that. It shows on the
field and off the field how happy he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi was a Gold Glove winner with the Dodgers and is one of
eight players to hit at least 30 homers and steal 30 bases in a
season twice. Even during the tumultuous 1999 season, Mondesi set
career highs in homers (33), RBI (99), stolen bases (36) and walks
(71).
</P>
<P>
   But he felt underappreciated and that was compounded by his
constant moving in the batting order. Always wanting to hit third,
Mondesi didn't get much a chance. In the past three seasons, he
batted .271 (113 for 417) with 20 homers and 61 RBI from the third
spot.
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, Mondesi will hit third, in front of lefty Carlos
Delgado, who hit 44 homers and drove in 134 runs last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no perfect world, but I think he fits all the things
you want in a No. 3 hitter,'' Fregosi said. ``He runs well, he can
steal a base, he hits for power, HE can drive in runs. The
strikeouts don't bother me because, God knows, I used to do it
enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
