<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CAN PLAY BETTER, SAYS JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Lakers are on pace for 68 wins, a
total that would rank second in franchise history, but coach Phil
Jackson is stressing to anyone who will listen that they are far
from playing their best basketball of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, he called his team ``cocky'' and mused that
a loss at Sacramento might have been helpful. Jackson is looking
for improvement in the final 10 games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just sometimes step up to the level of competition,'' he
said. ``They can play a quarter and feel like they've got the game
in control and they can just hold people off. There's that tendency
to find a way to get a lead and then play at a level where you
bring it back up again and the team comes close . . . (instead of
playing hard to) break the game open.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking prior to Friday's tipoff against the Philadelphia 76ers
at the Staples Center, Jackson said the Lakers' last ``real good
game'' was the 110-82 victory at Detroit on March 17, the last
victory of the 19-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've really played well for a couple of
weeks,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Lakers' gaudy record, numerous winning streaks
and insurmountable lead in the standings are Bulls-like, Jackson
said there was no comparison to his former Chicago teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``None,'' he said. ``The only thing they can do is they can find
a way to win. Like I said, that's the key to any team that's really
good, is being able to bring a game out of the fire or find a way
to fight back and win, and build momentum, and this is a team
that's really lived on the momentum of being better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think their community feel toward each other _ and winning
breeds that _ is very high. So that's very similar. But as far as
the way they play and the style of game, outside shooting vs.
inside game, they're all different. It's a completely different
mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Peerless: The Seattle SuperSonics and Sacramento Kings
continue to jostle for the seventh and eighth seeds in the West,
but the Lakers _ who get a first-round meeting with the eighth seed
_ aren't concerned with who they'll get.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked a little bit about who our matchup may be,'' said
Derek Fisher. ``But at this point, even in that discussion we
really don't favor one team or the other. We really feel like there
aren't many teams, or any at all, that in a playoff series can beat
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
