<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNRUFFLED SYMINGTON TAKES STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Attorney Michael Man ning charged into his Friday
con frontation with Fife Symington like a boxer at the opening
bell, demanding to know what the former governor knew about his
ill-fated real estate business and when he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You told me that the real estate depression was not affecting
your properties in 1989 or 1990,'' Man ning said, launching his
attack on the 10th day of Symington's trial in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Manning's indignation made an ac cusation out of the reference
to a sworn statement by Symington, who filed for personal
bankruptcy in 1995 during his second term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Symington kept his Harvard-culti vated manners as impeccable as
his charcoal-brown suit, parrying deftly in the opening round of a
battle that will resume Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going a little fast for me, Mr. Manning,'' said
Symington, who was not about to let Manning set the pace of the
inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The two have become intense adver saries, clashing twice in
sworn depo sitions.
</P>
<P>
   Manning's lawsuit, filed on behalf of a consortium of six union
pension funds that lent Symington $10 mil lion in 1990, claims that
Symington lied not only to get financing but also to get elected
governor in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Symington flatly denies he sought to deceive anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart of hearts, I know I didn't do anything wrong,''
Syming ton said after court Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Symington, who at 54 has launched a career as an apprentice chef
in Scottsdale, acknowledges errors on his financial statements, but
he says they were the result either of compu tational failures or
his optimistic belief in the soundness of his long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Rob Shull, helped fend off Friday's assault,
objecting 16 times during Symington's 57 minutes of testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Shull's most common complaint was that Manning was being
argumenta tive. He was particularly indignant when Manning tried to
press Sy mington on an unfavorable appraisal of the Ritz-Carlton,
one of Syming ton's former properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want you to slip away on this one,'' Manning said,
prompting Shull to leap to his feet in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Judge George Nielsen, a veteran of unfailingly even temper,
admonished Manning at one point with patient drollness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's rephrase the question in the usual neutral fashion,''
the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Manning repeatedly tried to pin Symington on his sworn claim
that he believed his business had been thriving until 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Symington said it was only then, a few months after he became
gover nor, that he realized he was being swept away by the riptide
of a Phoenix area real estate recession.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Symington testified, his properties ``were doing
fairly well in a tough market, and I didn't think I was going to
lose them.''
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything in this trial of Arizona's former chief
executive, convicted in 1997 of federal criminal charges of lying
to lenders.
</P>
<P>
   That conviction was overturned last year on appeal, and
prosecutors are weighing whether to retry the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Symington is con fronting the pension funds,
which have the burden of proof in the bankruptcy trial.
</P>
<P>
   The funds are attempting to prove that they acted reasonably
when they accepted a 1990 financial statement from Symington, who
was seeking the governorship as a successful developer who would
bring his hard-nosed business sense and so phistication to
government.
</P>
<P>
   Symington told the pension funds that he had a net worth of $12
mil lion, based on his share of 16 commercial properties.
</P>
<P>
   Manning claims that Symington erected a gaudy and fraudulent
facade as project after project crum bled under debt.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Manning grilled Syming ton about two appraisals on
the Ritz-Carlton at 24th Street and Camelback Road, Symington's pre
mier development.
</P>
<P>
   In his financial statement to the pension funds, Symington said
the hotel was worth $62.9 million, even though an up-to-date
appraisal had put its value at $57.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Manning says Symington's use of his own appraisals was part of a
much broader pattern of deceit. Symington countered Friday that it
showed nothing more than a difference of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't use the lower appraisal ``because I didn't
agree with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I built the project,'' Symington added. ``I felt I was the
better judge of its value.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting afterward with reporters, Symington said he had provided
the pension funds with all the financial information called for
under a previ ous loan commitment. He again insisted that the
pension funds failed to ask a single question about his financial
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't really interested in what was going on,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pension funds were depending on the loan's collateral, the
down town Phoenix Mercado, which the loan financed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Manning told reporters that the pension funds had a right to
believe that Symington's financial statement was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were the pension funds supposed to ask, `Were you lying to me,
Mr. Symington?' '' the lawyer said. ``He should have told us the
truth. He should have told us he was broke.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
