<HEADLINE>
FIRST BRUSH FIRE OF SPRING SPREAD BY HOT, DRY WINDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff writer Erik Nelson contributed to this story) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By   ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunland, Calif. _ The first Santa Ana winds of spring fueld a
small brush fire Friday in Sunland, hinting at what promises to be
a severe wildfire season, with rainfall more than three inches
below normal.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the La Nina paradox, however, state and city
water officials said Friday's last measurements of the year of the
Sierra Nevada's snowpack shows there will be ample water supply _
so higher water bills have been staved off.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, a high-wind warning will remain in effect today, with
winds ranging from 35 to 45 mph and gusts reaching 60 mph,
according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Sunday afternoon, pretty much we'll be back to normal,''
said weather service spokesman Stuart Seto.
</P>
<P>
   Low temperatures today and Sunday will be around 50 degrees. By
Monday, high temperatures should reach the low 80s in the Valley.
Low temperatures will be in the mid to upper 40s.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, 20 mph winds coupled with drying vegetation allowed
the Sunland wildfire to take off at about 10 a.m., charring nearly
5 acres of brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks lush and green now, but you'll be amazed how quickly
it will dry up with winds like this,'' said Los Angeles city Fire
Marshal Jim Hill said during a news conference to announce brush
clearance inspections starting May 1. ``This could be a very tough
fire season. ... We did not have a lot of rain. It is imperative
that homeowners heed this warning and clear the brush.''
</P>
<P>
   About 130,000 property owners in the city reside in high fire
hazard areas. They face fines of as much as $532 if they do not
clear native brush, weeds and grass within 100 feet of any
buildings and trim brush within 200 feet, the prescribed standard.
</P>
<P>
   The La Nina global weather pattern pushed the storm-generating
jet stream away from Southern California, leaving the region
parched despite several weeks of rain last month. As of Friday,
10.08 inches fell on downtown Los Angeles _ a drop from 13.52
inches, the seasonal average to date.
</P>
<P>
   To the north, Los Angeles water officials reported that heavy
snowfall in February boosted water equivalent depths of snow to
exactly the same height, 43.3 inches, as the historical average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lucked out,'' said Los Angeles Department of Water and
Power Water Works Engineer Fred Barker. ``If it had carried on the
way it was in December and the first few weeks of January, we were
looking at jumping right on top of the driest year on record.''
</P>
<P>
   State water officials, who also take measurements in the Sierra
Nevada, said the water supply from snowfall was about 95 percent of
average but that Sierra rainfall well above normal boosted runoff
forecasts to 105 percent of average.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
