<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-UCONN-PENNSTATE-N     04-01 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-PENNSTATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN TAKES THE EXPRESS TO REACH THE WOMEN'S FINAL
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sue Bird is not simply a point guard. She is a
bus driver, the one who knows the lanes and gets her passengers
where they need to go, right on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut sophomore brought her team to the only
destination it had in mind at the beginning of the season, scoring
19 points Friday night in a dominating effort as the Huskies
defeated Penn State, 89-67, in the semifinal of the NCAA women's
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Huskies will have to play the Lady Vols for the
right to claim their crown, as the two meet in the much-anticipated
final Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee handed UConn its only loss of the season in February,
the only glitch in an almost perfect season for the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Bird left Friday night's game with 1 minute 1 second left,
earning a warm handshake and hug from her coach, Geno Auriemma. He
smiled, knowing she was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   With less than five minutes remaining in Friday night's game,
the Huskies had taken a decisive 14-point lead. There was no doubt.
Not that there ever was with Bird in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (35-1) are going to the national championship game
for the first time since 1995, the first and only year they won the
title. That year they capped a perfect season by beating Tennessee
by six points in the final.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies played a near perfect game Friday night, never
trailing. But Penn State did not make it easy for the Huskies,
staying within single digits until late in the second half. When
Swintayla Cash hit a bank shot with six minutes remaining to give
the Huskies a 12-point lead, Connecticut could breathe easily.
</P>
<P>
   With Bird, they could do that all night.
</P>
<P>
   With nine minutes remaining, Bird stood at the top of the court,
dribbling to slow down the game while she collected instructions
from Auriemma, who had been named the national coach of the year by
The Associated Press on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bird was only an honorable mention selection, but her teammates
know her true worth. She called the play and seconds later, Cash
drove to the basket, giving the Huskies a nine-point lead. Bird did
not stop to smile, she had work to do at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't play in the tournament last year; she missed much of
the season, tearing an anterior cruciate ligament after just eight
games. And the Huskies were lost without her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by watching us this year as compared to last year, you
can see the impact she has had on our team,'' Shea Ralph said
before the game. ``She is one of the main reasons for success this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies gladly accepted the pressure of being the best all
season, and the expectation to reach the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   They had Bird to carry such a burden on her back.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Penn State threatened, Bird simply stared down the
Lions, hitting the critical shots at every important intersection
in the second half. When Penn State was within five points with
less than 12 minutes left, she made an 8-footer; when Penn State
had moved within four points with 14:18 left, she knocked down a
3-pointer of her own.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bird who brought her team into the locker room at
halftime with a 37-28 lead, having scored 11 points and playing all
but one minute.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied at 8-8 five minutes into the first half, when
the Huskies sophomore Asjha Jones hit a jumper. On the next play,
the sophomore Tamika Williams grabbed the rebound and the Huskies
hit the fast break hard, with Williams racing back down court to
convert the give-and-go layup from Svetlana Abrosimova.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Bird's back-to-back 3-pointers that capped the 10-2
run for the Huskies and broke the tension, if not the game, to give
them an 18-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   When Penn State pulled within five points, Bird calmly answered
the 3-pointer from Penn State's Katrena Carr with another
long-range bomb. Again, the Huskies led by eight.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their previous meeting this season, on Dec. 5 in Orlando,
Fla., when the Huskies had roared to a 19-4 lead, the Lions stayed
within single digits. They twice got to within four points, but
UConn kept the press and Bird kept the distance.
</P>
<P>
   The game figured to focus on the team's point guards _ the
senior Helen Darling was the reason the Lions were in the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   She had averaged 17 points in the last three NCAA tournament
games for the Lions, including hitting the winning shot in the
Midwest Regional semifinal against Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   But Darling scored no points in the first half Friday night. Her
senior teammate Andrea Garner led the Lions with seven points and
Carr, a sophomore reserve, scored seven points.
</P>
<P>
   For the Huskies, Abrosimova scored a quick eight points, but it
was Bird who made the biggest impact in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   She had averaged 10.9 points and 8.7 assists in UConn's 35
games, but 15.3 points in the last three tournament games. ``That's
who hurt us the most the first time,'' Penn State coach Rene
Portland said. ``You're always going to have Shea and Svet doing
their thing, but Bird really has a peace about her.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Without Bird last season, and with four of her freshman
teammates trying to find their chemistry, UConn lacked direction.
``Last year we worked and worked and we never really got anything
done,'' Ralph said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this year, it's almost like, when you're driving down the
highway and you're just going and you're listening to music and you
have a good time and you look at the speedometer and you're going
90 miles an hour and you're like, `Woah, we were going that fast?'
We're steam-rolling right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bird is driving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
