A4074 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLA     04-01 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVEY ORDERS A DOZEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It was only an exhibition game, but it confirmed
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson's fears. The Dodgers' 10-4 loss to
Toronto also put an end to the discussion about carrying 11 or 12
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be 12 for the first series in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   That came after Orel Hershiser allowed six runs in three
innings. The aid came from long-man Matt Herges, a surprise to be
on the opening-day 25-man roster. Herges allowed four runs in 2
innings, but in this fire drill of a night he did his job in
providing innings and keeping the bullpen fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get innings out of my pen,'' Johnson said.
``Whether it's (Onan) Masaoka or (Alan) Mills, I've given them a
little more work just to be protected. I'd like to have that first
series protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson thought about using one of the Dodgers' young starters _
i.e., Mike Judd, Jeff Williams or Eric Gagne _ but decided it would
be more beneficial to everyone to use the 30-year-old Herges.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what's better, taking one of the young starters and using
them in relief up here or let them stay down and stretch out (their
arms)?'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Once Johnson feels comfortable with 11 pitchers, it's likely
Herges will be sent to Triple-A Albuquerque to close games. And at
that point, outfielder Geronimo Berroa, who accompanied the Dodgers
to Toronto, would have his contract purchased and join the club.
</P>
<P>
   Berroa's addition would give Johnson the right-handed power
hitter off the bench he's seeking. Berroa also offers flexibility
in that he can play left or right field and first base.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between the Dodgers and Berroa is worked out so Berroa
will remain off the roster for the first few games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ White feels right: Dodgers center fielder Devon White, who's
shied away from interviews for most of the spring, said he feels
ready for opening day and has no problem batting leadoff.
</P>
<P>
   Without a prototypical leadoff hitter on the team, White's being
asked to fill that role. He's hit .261 with a .306 on-base
percentage in the Grapefruit League, and he took more pitches than
normal. However, White said not to read too much into how he's
approached the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But White has experience hitting first. He batted leadoff for
Toronto when the Blue Jays won back-to-back World Series in the
early `90s. However, in the last three years, White has hit .261
with a .306 on-base percentage in 450 at-bats from the leadoff
spot. He's also scored 60 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadoff, it's a job,'' White said before the club left
Dodgertown. ``The season may start and I may swing at the first
pitch every time. Who knows? It depends on each pitcher. They're
going to work me differently in spring training and I'm going to
approach the game differently when the season starts, so we'll see
what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: In his first trip to SkyDome since the
November trade, Dodgers right fielder Shawn Green was jeered by the
sparse crowd. An outfield banner read ``$hawn Greed'' and yells of
``Traitor'' echoed throughthe cavernous `Dome. . . . Dodgers
infielder Juan Castro accepted his assignment to Triple-A
Albuquerque and will report with the club Sunday. . . .
Right-hander Antonio Osuna was placed on the 15-day disabled list,
which was expected. He's recovering from surgery performed last
September. He could return in early May. . . . Lefty Pedro Borbon,
who led Dodgers pitchers by appearing in 70 games last season, is
close to signing a two-year contract extension with Toronto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
