<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4084 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MAYS-STATUE-SFCHRON &LR;      04-01 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYS-STATUE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CROWD TURNS OUT FOR UNVEILING OF `SAY HEY' WILLIE MAYS STATUE  &HT;     By STEVE RUBENSTEIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The greatest center fielder in history gazed
upon the 23-ton bronze statue of himself Friday and said something
that Willie Mays does not say often.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scares me,'' Mays said with a smile, and he grabbed the
giant right foot that seemed already halfway to first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too real. When I come to the ballpark, I'm not coming in
this way. I'm going to go in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mays, the real one, was guest of honor at the ceremony to unveil
the colossal sculpture before the first game at Pac Bell Park. More
than 1,000 guests and fans filled Third Street at the park's front
gate and rose as one to applaud when a giant black velvet curtain
surrounding the statue in front of the ballpark was peeled back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the luckiest man in the world,'' Mays said. ``I don't want
to talk too long because the tears begin to flow.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of tears, along with sunshine, autograph
hounds, big shots, limousines, heroes, shutterbugs and a healthy,
uninvited breeze left over from Candlestick Park. The breeze
crashed the party and wafted through the fronds of the 24
ever-incongruous palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   Mays was preceded to the microphone by a half dozen former
Giants, two former managers, one baseball commissioner, one mayor,
two clergymen, the team president, several living legends and any
number of other people who could not have made that catch in 1954
except in their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the living legends had gray hair and some had none. They
clutched the handrail as they gingerly ascended the steps to the
podium, as living legends must eventually do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I'm glad they decided to do this while you were living
and you could hear some of this,'' said Bill Greason, Mays' former
teammate from the Birmingham Barons minor league team. Mays,
sitting in the front row of spectators with a folded sports page
tucked between his legs, laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie, you were the greatest and it was an honor to have
played with you,'' said Bobby Thomson, who hit the home run to win
the 1951 pennant for the then-New York Giants. ``Sitting down
there, you look like you own the world _ and you do, today.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds, an outfielder of some ability, was one of those who
wiped away a tear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie, say hey, Mr. Mays, godfather,'' he said, and he paused
to dab at his eyes. ``You're the greatest athlete I've ever seen in
my life. It's an honor to play in the house named for Willie.''
</P>
<P>
   In return, Mays teased Bonds that he had better plan on hitting
50 home runs this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fence is only 309 feet,'' he said, and he gazed over at
Giants president Peter Magowan. ``If he can't hit 50, get him a pay
cut, Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be playing here,'' Mays said in a voice that did
not sound like he was kidding. ``I think I could get 10 or 20 more
home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans, cheering behind the police barricade behind the rows
of dignitaries, clearly thought so, too.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody who came to the microphone, and there seemed to be
dozens, said that Mays was the greatest and that all lesser
ballplayers, Hall of Famers and all-stars were the merest of
mortals by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many former heroes that the the current ones, the
San Francisco Giants of 2000, were not even sitting in the front
row. They were one row back and they stood en masse when
introduced, like any other bunch of Mays fans.
</P>
<P>
   The chestnuts roasted in the noontime sun. Announcer Lon Simmons
rattled off the one about how God didn't gave Mays a halo because
it would have fallen off when he went after a fly ball. Someone
told how Chronicle sportswriter Bob Stevens once described a
hapless fielder unable to snag a Mays blast _ ``the man who hit it
is the only man who could have caught it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball commissioner Bud Selig recalled watching Mays win a
game with a home run in the 16th inning. Giants president Magowan
recalled watching Mays fire throw after throw to third base from
the outfield, always on target. Giants vice president Larry Baer
recalled taking the bus to Candlestick and watching Mays as a kid.
</P>
<P>
   The statue, by sculptor Will Behrends, shows the gargantuan Mays
gazing westward with his bat in hand, trying to follow the arc of
an imaginary ball that he has just swatted as it sails over Sutro
Tower three miles away. Behrends smiled when Mays said the statue
scared him and said he didn't take it as an insult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know what he means,'' he said. ``I never did a
self-portrait, so I can't really say.''
</P>
<P>
   All around the intersection of Third and King streets, behind
the rows of seats for dignitaries, ordinary fans waited in the sun
for hours to pay tribute to the great Mays. Workers in hard hats,
still on the job to apply the finishing touches, stood atop the
stadium walls and gazed down to watch. The man welding the neon
sign above the souvenir store put down his torch to listen to the
tributes.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Williams drove all night from San Luis Obispo, Calif.,
to arrive early enough to claim a prime spot against the barricade.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the palm trees are stupid,'' she said. ``But Willie Mays
walked on water and he still does.''
</P>
<P>
   John Maier, 13, of Grass Valley, Calif., said he cut
eighth-grade science class to attend the ceremony. He was standing
beside his father, Ron, who understands that some things are worth
playing hooky for.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we would have been doing in class is dissecting
worms,''John said. ``This is a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the statue is situated at 24 Willie Mays Plaza, but
nobody seemed to know exactly where that was. A street sign said
that King Street was Willie Mays Plaza. Magowan said it was Willie
Mays Street. Someone from the city said plazas are plazas and
cannot have numbers. Someone else pointed out that the stadium is
on the south side of the street and would therefore have to have an
odd number, not 24. Nobody cared.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, the invited guests ate a catered box lunch
of garbanzo bean salad and sandwiches from the luxury boxes and put
on their souvenir Willie Mays Plaza hats.
</P>
<P>
   They gazed down on the field, where workers were doing the final
bits of fussing in preparation for last night's first-ever
exhibition game. The outfield fence, which zigs and zags, was the
subject of much discussion. Of late, lesser fielders than Mays have
been pondering how, exactly, to cope with the various caroms and
angles and fence surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Mays is not one of those kind of fielders. Asked how he would
handle such an irregularly shaped fence, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any problem with a ballpark,'' Mays said. ``You
play the hitter, not the ballpark. The ballpark is just there. You
can be playing in the Grand Canyon and if the batter can't hit, you
play shallow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 0055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
