u k BC-EDIT-CENSUS-NYT &LR;      04-01 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CIVIC DUTY AND THE CENSUS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 1:
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional Republicans are seriously undermining the
2000 census by suggesting that the national headcount, which
officially takes place Saturday, is an invasion of privacy. That
bizarre complaint could discourage the public from participating in
a project that is crucial to the functioning of state and federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   The questions on this year's long census form _ including
questions on household income, plumbing facilities and physical
disabilities _ have been part of the census for decades. The only
new question asks for information on grandparents who are
caregivers for children. In fact, this year's long form is the
shortest one in 60 years. All answers on census forms are kept
confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska has suggested in recent days
that people can simply ignore questions on the long form _ which
goes to one out of six American households _ that they find
intrusive. A spokesman for Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader,
has made similarly inappropriate suggestions. Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas has said that people should fill out the forms, but that
if he received a long form, he was not sure he would want to fill
it out either.
</P>
<P>
   These comments are irresponsible. Completing the census form
fully and accurately is not optional; it is a civic duty that is
required by law. Hagel now says that he does not want to encourage
people to break the law, but will introduce legislation to make
most of the questions on the long form voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has spent billions of dollars trying to
produce an accurate count as response rates have continued to
decline with each decennial count. Accuracy is critical because the
census is used to apportion seats in Congress, draw legislative
districts within the states and distribute more than $185 billion
in federal funds. The government uses information from the long
form of the census to allocate money to communities for housing,
school aid, transportation, services for the elderly and the
disabled and scores of other programs. The data are also necessary
to calculate the consumer price index and cost of living increases
in government benefits.
</P>
<P>
   When individuals fail to give complete information about their
households, they risk shortchanging their communities of government
aid that they may be entitled to. That is why many state and local
government officials are working hard to increase census response
rates in their communities. The mindless complaints of some
politicians could well sabotage those efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 0057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CONSERVATION-NYT     04-01 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONSERVATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FOREIGN CONSERVATIONISTS UNDER SIEGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 1:
</P>
<P>
   Some of the world's most dedicated human rights activists have
started as campaigners for the environment. Ken Saro-Wiwa's initial
cause, for example, was the devastation that Royal Dutch/Shell's
oil spills inflicted on Ogoni land in Nigeria's delta region. As
the dictatorship fought back, he found himself taking on more
traditional human rights battles _ for the rights of the Ogoni,
against the military's burning of delta villages and its shooting
of protesters and, finally, against the sham judicial process that
led to his execution in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In many countries, environmental activists are finding that the
line between their causes and human rights has blurred. To protect
the environment, they need both the right to speak out and fair
enforcement of the law. Many are enduring the harassment that human
rights activists have long experienced.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known examples are in Russia. The domestic intelligence
service _ the heir to the KGB _ has tried to silence scientists and
naval officers who document the radioactive pollution emitted by
decommissioned nuclear submarines. The service has spent years
harassing Aleksandr Nikitin, a former Soviet submarine captain who
wrote about the problem. Although Nikitin apparently used entirely
public sources and has been acquitted of espionage, he could still
face more prosecutions. His case goes to Russia's supreme court
later this month. Acting President Vladimir Putin has supported the
crackdown on environmentalists, whom he has accused of spying for
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   In other countries, the activities most likely to incur the
wrath of governments or powerful groups are protests aimed at
against large, lucrative projects _ such as oil production in
Nigeria, Chad, Cameroon and Ecuador, toxic waste dumping in
Cambodia, logging in Kenya and Mexico and new dam construction in
China and India.
</P>
<P>
   The activists tend to emerge from the same isolated communities
that suffer most from pollution. Typical is Rodolfo Montiel, a
peasant who organized small farmers in rural Guerrero, Mexico,
against the clear-cutting of local forests, which was threatening
their harvests and way of life. In May, he and a bystander were
arrested and charged with weapons possession and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International and the Sierra Club, which have begun a
joint campaign to draw attention to the persecution of
environmentalists, say the two men were tortured into confessing.
The arrests are part of a pattern in Guerrero. Five years ago, 17
unarmed peasants protesting logging were shot by the state's
judicial police. Another member of the peasant organization was
reportedly abducted at gunpoint last month.
</P>
<P>
   The interest and intervention of large environmental
organizations is especially helpful to rural activists, who usually
lack the connections enjoyed by their urban counterparts. What
makes the rural activists particularly vulnerable is that they live
in out-of-the-way places that happen to be rich in the very
resources that governments and powerful interests hope to exploit.
For that reason, they can get in the way of a lot of money. To most
developing nations, the economic promise of forests, mineral
deposits or oil and gas outweighs environmental concerns. Such
projects can also produce a river of graft for government
officials.
</P>
<P>
   European and American groups like Amnesty International and the
Sierra Club can also play an important supporting role. Many of the
oil and gas companies, as well as the big customers for foreign
timber and minerals, are based in the industrialized world. These
companies, in turn, can influence how the governments they work
with treat environmental dissidents. The worldwide opprobrium
heaped on Shell for its failure to help Saro-Wiwa has sensitized
corporations to the public relations costs of silence.
</P>
<P>
   The next test is in Chad, where a consortium led by Exxon Mobil
is about to drill, and Cameroon, where the pipeline will lead.
Amnesty International and the Sierra Club say that several people
who have raised environmental concerns have been threatened and
silenced, even though digging has not yet begun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4089 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     04-01 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGINE _ A BALLPARK FIT FOR BALL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ I'm so proud. I earned my Croix de Croissant.
<P>
   Years ago, the Giants gave out medals to folks who survived an
extra-inning night game in the Arctic blasts of Candlestick Park,
and the medals were named the Croix de Candlestick.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a different standard of toughness at the new Pac
Bell Park, which the Giants opened last night.
</P>
<P>
   This place is going to take some getting used to for Giants'
fans. The big change: No more Mr. Tough Guy.
</P>
<P>
   Giants' fans always prided themselves on being hardier than
thou. It took extreme loyalty and courage to watch baseball when
your beer froze to your mustache.
</P>
<P>
   At one game last year, I was enormously proud of my teenage son,
who was the only person in the ballpark in short sleeves. Then we
saw a guy with no shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Giants' fans always looked down on other baseball fans as
effete, pampered, wimpy dilettantes. But what now?
</P>
<P>
   Now the Giants fans' have the cushiest, cutest, coziest ballpark
in the big leagues, at least outside of Fenway and Wrigley, and
though last night was a weather aberration, it looks like the
extreme cold and wind are things of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Now anybody can watch a Giants' game.
</P>
<P>
   How will the fans handle the change? Will they brag, ``We're so
tough, in our luxury suite we use the same fork for our salad
 &UR; and  &LR; for our entree''?
</P>
<P>
   And what about the ballplayers? They used to say the old
ballpark gave them a psychological edge, because visiting players
always griped and whined about the wind and weather, while the
Giants didn't, except for Will Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Now? Now the players don't even need ski parkas in the dugout.
They saunter into a (relatively) balmy ballpark, and they dress in
a clubhouse that is big enough to host a polo match with midgets on
Shetland ponies.
</P>
<P>
   Their locker stalls are made of rosewood. Rosewood! Hearing that
news, Babe Ruth snorted beer out his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Each player each sits on a nicely padded folding chair, except
for Barry Bonds, who has an enormous leather recliner at his
cubicle, and it's plugged in, so I assume it vibrates and massages.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bought it,'' shrugged a club exec.
</P>
<P>
   What the hell, if it weren't for Barry, there might not be a new
ballpark. And you have to admire that kind of style. It's pure
Barry.
</P>
<P>
   The dugouts are monstrous, with two rows of benches and about 15
feet of open space between 'em. Apparently the architects,
anticipating everything, figured Barry might want to bring his
lounger down to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Barry will park his Porsche there.
</P>
<P>
   But few would begrudge Barrisimo his eccentricities. Remember,
before the new ballpark, he was the No. 1 reason people came to see
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   And he's still a strong No. 2, as long as he hits a couple
dingers into the dinghies every week.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the park is the draw. Forty thousand to watch the
Brewers in a practice game? Watching the Brewers is as exciting as
watching paint dry, if the paint is an interesting color.
</P>
<P>
   By now, you're probably sick of hearing how charming the new
park is, but it's true. Where else in major league baseball can you
watch yachts shagging fly balls?
</P>
<P>
   Boats prowl China Basin just beyond the wall and promenade, and
last night, when a batting practice homer plunked into the drink,
two guys in a 45-foot schooner tried to jockey their two-masted
craft so they could pick up the bobbing souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   Finally one of the guys stripped to his Levi's and dived in, to
hearty cheers.
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty of souvenirs at the new park, and maybe a
few casualties. The seats are very close to the field, so there is
some fear that screaming foul balls might wind up embedded in fans'
foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want fans to be aware they need to pay attention,`` said
Dusty Baker, the Giants' manager.
</P>
<P>
   Better make the games interesting, Dusty.
</P>
<P>
   The seats are so close, fans in the front row are in danger of
being hit in the eye with sunflower seeds spit by the on-deck
batter.
</P>
<P>
   One reason so few fans were hurt by foul balls at Candlestick
was that there were so few fans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sellouts every night. We're going to start running into
Yogi Berra syndrome, where if you ask someone if they go to Giants
games, they'll reply, ``Nah, nobody goes there anymore, it's always
too crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   It's nutty. The weather is so mellow, the Giants might bring Stu
Miller out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Stu was the little lefty who gained immortality by being blown
off the mound at Candlestick during the '61 All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants used to require pitchers with ballast, a substantial
caboose. Now ... Calling Stu. It doesn't matter if you're
60-something.
</P>
<P>
   We'll send a yacht for you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 0103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
