<HEADER>
A4093 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SBA-FILM-LADN     04-01 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBA-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBA HELPS SEND FILMMAKERS TO HOLLYWOOD WITH BACKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By   CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glendale, Calif. _ I'm ready for my close-up, Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   In the first deal of its kind, two local filmmakers have
bankrolled their film with taxpayer money through a loan from the
Small Business Administration, rather than seeking studio backing.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, ``Gristle,'' is a comedy about stereotypical
perceptions. It's being made by producers Mychal Wilson and Eugene
Taylor of Los Angeles-based Gristle Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SBA was a way to achieve financing for our film when the
studios wouldn't,'' Wilson said. ``We are already shooting the film
and will wrap up production in a couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   They got the loan approval a couple of months ago but decided to
announce it Friday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The loan was arranged through the SBA's Glendale office, but the
amount is not being disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under federal law, the terms and the amount of the loan will
be kept private,'' said John Tumpak, director of public affairs for
the SBA.
</P>
<P>
   Tumpak described the loan as a ``milestone'' and predicted the
agency would make additional loans to the film industry, which
generates a large number of jobs in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to be very active in making these types of
loans,'' Tumpak said. ``Hopefully, it encourages other filmmakers
to do business with the Small Business Administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Wilson and Taylor are the first to receive this
kind of assistance because they are the first to ask.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the agency has made loans to entertainment-related
businesses, such as production companies that need equipment and
catering firms that supply food to the various studios, Tumpak
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who also co-produced the 1996 short film ``Spartans,''
said his company is working with the SBA to ``facilitate these
types of loans to help other filmmakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The SBA loan for this movie comes through Valley Bank's main
headquarters in Moreno Valley, Tumpak said.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Glendale, the Los Angeles district office is the
agency's largest, making small-business loans to companies in Los
Angeles, Ventura and Santa Barbara counties, he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
