 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-WEB-LIBEL (London) _ A British Internet service provider
has agreed to pay a substantial sum to a physicist who says he was
libeled in messages posted on electronic bulletin boards carried by
the company. The company, Demon Internet, says it will pay about
$25,000 in damages to the physicist, as well as his court costs. By
Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-DEFENSE (Taipei) _ Faced with China's escalating threats
and its growing force of ballistic missiles pointed at the island,
Taiwan's military is campaigning for a major upgrade in its missile
defenses and has put Washington on the spot by asking to buy some
of its best weaponry, including large numbers of a new, improved
version of the Patriot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-TACTICS (New York) _ A few months ago, narcotics
detectives quietly began to swarm about a tree-lined stretch of
Rugby Road in Brooklyn. Their target was Jose Sierra, suspected of
selling heroin from the lobby of his building. They pursued Sierra
aggressively. Two weeks ago, a raid on Sierra's apartment turned up
heroin worth $120. It was, police officials said, an effective
example of Operation Condor, the city's massive narcotics sweep
that has resulted in more than 21,000 arrests. But victory came
with a price. Many there say that the aggressive tactics used
against Sierra and others have too often swept up innocent
bystanders and too often increased neighborhood tensions. By David
Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT27,30,31 are being sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-RUNNING-CLEAN (Alfred, Maine) _ Donald Gean is running
clean. That makes him sound like an engine, but Gean is a
candidate: one of 134 candidates for the legislature who are taking
part in a radical experiment in democracy in Maine. In exchange for
Gean's agreement to refrain from taking further donations, the
state of Maine is giving him his entire warchest for his run for
the state Senate, about $17,000 and possibly more. The election is
months away, but as a Clean candidate participating in the Maine
Clean Elections Act, he will not raise another cent. From Vice
President Gore to Sen. John McCain, national figures are agitating
for campaign finance reform, but states _ Maine first and foremost,
Massachusetts, Vermont and Arizona close behind _ are already doing
it, in their smaller ways. By Carey Goldberg. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JUDIASM-SAMESEX-UNIONS (Greensboro, N.C.) _ On Rabbi Shira
Stern, director of a Jewish chaplaincy program in New Jersey and a
leader of the Women's Rabbinic Network, the caucus that wrote the
resolution declaring that Reform Judaism would allow same-sex
unions. By Gustav Niebuhr. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-PRIVACY (Washington) _ In the final days leading up to
Saturday, the day the Census Bureau tries to take a snapshot of
America, a new battle has broken out over an already embattled
national headcount, with politicians and just plain folks grumbling
that all those questions are too intrusive. By David E. Rosenbaum.
1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE-RIVALS (Undated) _ The makers of Barbie and competing
dolls are now serving up a kind of pint-sized career focus along
with play value, packaging their dolls with literature or CD-ROMs
that emphasize education and other requirements for employability.
This year, for example, shoppers can expect to see Jessica the
Journalist, Get Real Girl and Barbie for President. Some experts
say all this may represent a turning point, in which dolls take on
an expanded educational purpose. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT16-18 Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-COFFEE (Oaxaca City) _ A look at how Mexico, the world's
leading grower of organic and shade-grown coffee, is seeking to
strengthen its share of the market. At a conference this week,
Mexican growers brought together corporate customers ranging from
Starbucks to Dunkin' Donuts, to establish product emblems verifying
their beans are bird-friendly and environmentally safe. By Sam
Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (BOSTON) _ Anthony Lewis on Elian Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-REFORM (Indianapolis) _ Four months ago the National
Collegiate Athletic Association signed a staggering $6 billion,
11-year television contract for its centerpiece event, the NCAA
men's basketball tournament. This weekend, four teams will try to
cap an entertaining and unpredictable run of pressure-packed games
by competing for the national title. This is supposed to be as good
as it gets for college basketball and the body that rules all of
collegiate sports. So why are so many so unhappy? Even as the
tournament peaks with the Final Four here at the RCA Dome, a
consensus is noisily developing among coaches, university
administrators and the NCAA itself that something is seriously
wrong with college basketball and that sweeping changes are needed.
By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LATINAS-ENCYCLOPEDIA (Undated) _ Two distinguished scholars of
Hispanic America are joining forces to produce a monumental work of
reference, Latinas in the United States: An Historical
Encyclopedia. Planned for publication in 2003, the two-volume
encyclopedia is expected to have about 800 entries on prominent
Latina women from the 16th century to the present, along with
essays covering topics including women in religion, the arts,
politics and labor unions as well as intermarriages across cultural
and racial lines. By Barbara Crossette. (1450 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT21-23 are being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DIVORCE-RESEARCH (Undated) _ On the pioneer of divorce research,
E. Mavis Hetherington. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   GENETIC-DIVERSITY (Undated) _ A look at ``Genes, Peoples, and
Languages'' by the geneticist Luigi Luca Cavalli-Sforza.
Taxonomists, he suggests, can be divided into two camps:
``lumpers'' and ``splitters.'' The lumpers try to synthesize
diverse strands of their study; the splitters separate the whole
into its parts. This distinction is a taxonomy too, of course, but
one of Cavalli-Sforza's great achievements is that he straddles the
divide. There may be no other contemporary scholar who has a more
detailed understanding of human diversity, or a more compelling
vision of its unified history. By Edward Rothstein. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   MEDINA-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``El Medina'': Yousry Nasrallah,
director. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   BLEU-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Le Bleu Des Villes'': Stephane
Brize, director; with Florence Brignon. Reviewed by Antia Gates.
</P>
<P>
   IRANWOMEN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Although Tahmine Milani's
film, ``Two Women,'' is set in Iran, the suffering woman at its
compassionate heart may be found wherever those like her are denied
a right to education and work, oppressed and abused by husbands,
stalked by violent, obsessive men and denied recourse in court.
Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   TV-LINDBERGH-REVIEW (Undated) _ On A&AMP;E's Biography Special:
``Charles and Anne Lindbergh: Alone Together.'' Reviewed by Walter
Goodman.
</P>
