<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USBUDGET-DEFICIENCIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENCIES RIPPED IN AUDIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By   BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government numbers crunchers told Congress on
Friday that many federal agencies, including the Internal Revenue
Service and the Pentagon, have only a sketchy idea of how they are
handling billions of taxpayer dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller General David M. Walker, who released the General
Accounting Office's audit of the 1998-99 fiscal year that ended
Sept. 30, said his agency found ``serious deficiencies in the
government's systems, record keeping, documentation and controls''
in financial reports received from 24 major departments.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Walker said, the GAO declined to verify the
reliability of the government's ledgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be outraged by this,'' said Rep. Stephen Horn,
R-Long Beach, chairman of the House Subcommittee on Government
Management, Information and Technology. He noted that millions of
Americans will be required to have their financial records in order
by the April 15 income tax deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Horn's panel issued its own accounting report card Friday,
giving the government's 24 major agencies an overall grade of
D-plus.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO and Horn's report card gave their highest marks to NASA,
the National Science Foundation, the Social Security
Administration, the General Services Administration and the
departments of Labor and Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Flunking grades were issued to the departments of Defense,
Agriculture, Housing and Urban Development, Interior and State, as
well as the Agency for International Development, which handles
foreign aid, and to the Office of Personnel Management.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department and its IRS collection arm were given a
D-minus.
</P>
<P>
   While stressing that the government was in no danger of
financial ruin, Walker said that sloppy bookkeeping had cast doubt
on the accuracy of such benchmark figures as the $1.76 trillion
total federal budget and the current budget surplus of $124
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have consistent information so we don't confuse
people,'' said Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Defense, which accounts for nearly one-fourth
of all government spending, was faulted for not being able to
document or inventory the billions of dollars worth of land,
equipment and buildings under its control.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS was criticized for failing to track income and refunds.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report cited an IRS check of tax returns in 1999 that
turned up $1 billion in fraudulent claims for the earned income tax
credit, which gives relief to low-income workers. But an audit of
the IRS' books turned up no record of whether the agency had paid
out $1 billion in refunds on those claims.
</P>
<P>
   Horn cited another 1999 IRS gaffe in which the agency paid a
$15,000 refund to a man who actually owed the government $350,000
in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Gotbaum, controller of the White House's Office of
Management and Budget, and Assistant Treasury Secretary Donald V.
Hammond admitted that the government's books were in disarray and
both promised improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Gotbaum and Hammond noted that government accounting has
improved since the 1995-96 fiscal year, when only six of 24
departments compiled reports deemed accurate by the GAO.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998-99, they said, 13 department reports were judged to be
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
