<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRIZZLIES-     04-01 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRIZZLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A SIGH OF RELIEF, THE KNICKS MOVE ON
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ There were exasperating moments
when the whip-quick Michael Dickerson left Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy slinging his fist into the scorer's table.
</P>
<P>
   As each arching jumper by the Grizzlies' phenom splashed into
the net, the threat of embarrassment for the Knicks increased and
the potential for a road-trip collapse loomed greater. But these
were the Grizzlies. They created their own undoing Friday night.
After Dickerson helped the Grizzlies pull within one point with two
minutes left, a turnover and a technical foul opened the way for
Patrick Ewing to end the tension.
</P>
<P>
   He was not a factor for most of the night, but Ewing hit two
free throws and a runner in the closing 1 minute 3 seconds to put
the Knicks in position for an 89-83 sigh of relief at General
Motors Place. Instead of having their trip ruined, the Knicks
improved to 3-1 on their West Coast swing, ensuring them of a
winning trip with the Lakers left to play. Instead of having their
spirits crushed, the Knicks (45-27) are within a half-game of the
Miami Heat at the top of the Atlantic Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were led by Latrell Sprewell's 23 points and 24 from
Allan Houston. Marcus Camby added 18 off the bench, and Ewing
finished with 11 points. With the Knicks' frontcourt struggling,
the Grizzlies had a chance. Dickerson, who scored 28 points, gave
them that chance. The Knicks led by nine points early in the fourth
quarter, but a 13-point binge by Dickerson pulled the game tighter.
Dickerson sent the Grizzlies on an 8-2 run to cut the Knicks' lead
to 73-70 with 6:59 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson was everywhere. He put his body on Sprewell, forced
him to turn into traffic on his drive and forced him into a
turnover. The play gave Dickerson a chance to tie the game, but his
pull-up 3-pointer on the fast break cracked off the rim with 4:30
left. Two minutes later, Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who had been held
silent by Sprewell, lined up a 21-footer and pulled the Grizzlies
within 81-80. From there, Ewing took over and saved face for the
Knicks with two free throws with 1:03 remaining and a runner with
43 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy did not issue any warnings about a letdown, not even a
cautionary tale concerning the Knicks' pattern of giving the
league's lowliest team (19-52) a reprieve from its depressing
existence.
</P>
<P>
   But midway through the third quarter, the Knicks' frontcourt of
Ewing and Larry Johnson was 2 for 11 and both Houston and Sprewell
were getting burned by Dickerson. They were keeping up with the
error-prone Grizzlies _ and took a 61-56 lead when a turnover by
Abdur-Rahim gave Houston a dunk on the other end _ but every
possession was a struggle in the fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that saved the Knicks was the Grizzlies'
ineptitude. More of their own making than forced by good defense,
the Grizzlies' had 16 turnovers through three quarters. Despite
outshooting the Knicks, 47 percent to 43.9, the Grizzlies were
down, 65-58.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't exactly an emphatic stand. The early indications
were the Knicks were not mentally prepared for the game. Eight
minutes into the game, a distressed Van Gundy called a timeout
after his team fell behind, 15-6. The only starter on the floor who
showed up was Sprewell. He was focused on his defense of
Abdur-Rahim and hit three of his first four shots. Houston,
Johnson, Ewing and Charlie Ward combined to go 0 for 13.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Knicks did in Seattle, they started the recovery
process. It came with a few frustrations _ which was revealed in
the technical fouls that Camby and Chris Childs picked up _ but the
Knicks went on a 22-9 run.
</P>
</TEXT>
