<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 KILLED TRYING TO ROB OFFICERS, AUTHORITIES SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR and JULIAN BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two men were killed in Brooklyn Friday night by
undercover narcotics police officers who said the men were trying
to rob them, using what turned out to be toy guns, the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the shootings in Bushwick were sketchy, but
senior police officials said that two plainclothes officers
arrested three men on charges of selling marijuana in an apartment
on Cooper Street about 9:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after making the arrests, the two officers were
approached on Cooper Street by five men who pulled out what
appeared to be handguns. The men took a gold chain from one
officer, and a cell phone and a wallet the other, the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Ahlee Jr., the Police Department's chief of
detectives, said Friday night that during the attempted robbery,
``a struggle ensued, during which both officers fired their
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The police did not release the names of the officers or the men
who were killed. The shootings occurred outside a building at 36
Cooper Street, near Bushwick Avenue, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   One man was taken to Woodhull Hospital and pronounced dead at
9:45 p.m., officials said. The other man died at the scene, the
police said. The other three men in the group that approached the
police fled, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday night, senior police commanders held
up the toy guns, which were wrapped in black plastic, to emphasize
how realistic they looked in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look very real, believe me,'' Detective John Giamarino, a
police spokesman, said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the officers were conducting drug sweeps as
part of Operation Condor, started by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to
combat low-level drug crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Some public officials and police commanders have criticized the
operation, which is financed by special overtime funds, for
focusing too many resources on minor crimes and heightening
tensions between the police and members of minority groups. Earlier
this week, police officials said that the operation had resulted in
more than 21,000 arrests _ three-quarters of them for minor
offenses _ since it began in January.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal shootings were the third and fourth in the last five
weeks by members of plainclothes New York City narcotics units,
which have come under scrutiny since the fatal shooting two weeks
ago of Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed security guard, who was killed
in a scuffle outside a Manhattan bar.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a decline in the number of people killed by New York
police officers over the last two years, the recent shootings have
raised questions about Police Department policies.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced plans to
review the department's policy on when officers can unholster their
guns. The announcement came the day after an undercover narcotics
detective was reassigned because he chased a drug suspect through a
crowded schoolyard with his gun drawn.
</P>
<P>
   On March 1, a plainclothes officer shot another unarmed man,
Malcolm Ferguson, in Soundview, two blocks from the doorway where
an unarmed West African immigrant, Amadou Diallo, was killed by
officers from the Street Crime Unit in a hail of 41 bullets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
