<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIZARDS-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS LOSE AGAIN AT BUZZER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Tony Battie in his face and flirting dangerously close to a
foul, Washington guard Mitch Richmond gathered himself for one last
jump shot. He knew time was running out. He knew Battie was a solid
shot-blocker. So when he saw the slightest of openings, he let
loose a high-arcing, 19-footer. The ball sailed over outstretched
arms and safely through the net, leaving just two-10ths of a second
on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   There would not be time for Boston to get another shot off. As a
result, the Wizards went home with a stunning 104-102 victory
Friday night at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it left my hands, it felt pretty good,'' said Richmond.
``It's great to get that here because a couple times I've been on
the bad end of that leprechaun.''
</P>
<P>
   As coach Rick Pitino gathered his team for one last timeout, all
the Celtics could do was shake their heads. Try as they might, the
Boston players could not shake the image of yet another last-second
buzzer-beater from their minds.
</P>
<P>
   They did not have the time or energy to point fingers or pick on
the weak, as they had during second-half timeouts of their
embarrassing loss to Orlando last Tuesday. Although Pitino had
threatened suspensions after the team's graceless display in
Florida, the players convinced their coach not to take such drastic
action.
</P>
<P>
   So Friday night, the Celtics were united in their disbelief and
disappointment as they squandered a 16-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another difficult loss for us,'' said Pitino. ``We played
the play at the end of the game very well. Tony Battie did an
outstanding job switching out, challenging the shot, getting as
high as he could. As has happened to us so many times in recent
weeks, the difficult shot has gone in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the fourth or fifth game this year where
someone's made a shot at the buzzer. So we can't hang our heads
about it. That's the game of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult right now because it's back-to-back games
and sooner or later discouragement sets in, and we can't let that
happen. If we finish up the season playing as hard as we have been
playing and not get discouraged, it will be a credit to their
character.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat extended Boston's losing streak to six games and
sustained its frustration. The Celtics have lost three games in
four weeks at home on the last possession, and now trail Orlando by
6 1/2 games for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the last time Boston played on the parquet floor,
Minnesota's Anthony Peeler sank a buzzer-beater from almost the
same spot as Richmond's last-second winner. Emotionally, the
Celtics have struggled since a double-overtime loss at Philadelphia
a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Washington may be holding down last place in the Atlantic
Division, but Boston still could not reverse its fortunes. Lately,
all the luck has rested with the Celtics' opponents. Postgame in a
virtually empty locker room, the few players who were left pondered
the Celtics' recent run of bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have no answers, no formulas, no reasons,'' said
Antoine Walker, who scored a team-high 21 points. ``(Richmond) just
hit a tough shot. We've just got to keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics had a excellent chance of coming out on the positive
side Friday night, but let their early 16-point cushion slip away.
</P>
<P>
   The good feeling that existed during the early portion of the
contest disappeared. As the fourth quarter got under way, the
Celtics were greeted by a smattering of boos. Dana Barros and
Calbert Cheaney got hot from the perimeter to keep Boston out front
early, but Washington was also making shots from the outside. A
3-pointer by Tracy Murray with 7:15 left produced the first tie of
the contest at 91-91. Barros answered with a 3-pointer, but the
Wizards would not go away.
</P>
<P>
   When Barros had a jumper blocked and Walker missed a wide-open
3-pointer after the ball bounced into his hands, the Wizards took
the lead for the first time, 95-94, on their next possession with
an Aaron Williams dunk with 5:53 left. The two teams battled back
and fourth to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 100-99, Juwan Howard's jump shot put the Wizards ahead
with less than a minute to play. Kenny Anderson missed a shot that
would have returned the lead to the Celtics, but they lucked out on
the other end when Don Reid made only one of two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Vitaly Potapenko, who failed to make a last-second shot against
Philadelphia that would have sent the game to triple overtime, came
through with a jumper that tied it at 102-102 with 14 seconds left.
Then, Richmond, who scored a game-high 30 points, did his damage.
</P>
<P>
   But it was hard to feel sorry for the Celtics. They finished the
first quarter ahead, 34-21. Boston built on its lead at the start
of the second. A driving layup by Walker gave the home team a
16-point advantage (48-32) for the third time with 7:04 left in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into halftime, Washington mounted a comeback behind its
defense. The visitors closed the gap to 5 points (62-57) at
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Boston's lead dwindled to 1 after UConn
alum Richard Hamilton sank a 16-foot jump shot. And from there, the
Celtics traveled down an all-too-familiar path to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to use bad luck, but come on, our luck is not
great right now,'' said Anderson. ``We've got 10 more games. We
can't tank it. We've got to keep playing hard and staying together,
work out things for next year. We've got to try to finish out the
season strong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
