<HEADLINE>
LAKERS KEEP IVERSON QUIET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Allen Iverson might yet defeat Shaquille O'Neal in
the NBA's scoring race, but he's lagging significantly in the
head-to-head matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson was again a nonfactor against the Los Angeles Lakers.
O'Neal was again unstoppable against the Philadelphia 76ers, and
the Lakers are again looking like a team that can't be beat.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal bullied the Sixers for 37 points and 14 rebounds and
abused them with a season-high-tying eight blocked shots, leading
the Lakers to a 100-88 victory Friday before a star-studded 18,997
fans at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers swept the season series from Philadelphia, extended
their winning streak to eight games and, more importantly, knocked
their magic number for clinching the league's best record down to
three. Any combination of Lakers victories and/or Portland losses
adding up to three will ensure the Lakers home-court advantage
throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's nonstop assault at both ends of the court was enough to
make the Sixers see stars (and there were plenty, from Oscar winner
Michael Caine to Oscar nominee Michael Clark Duncan to Pamela
Anderson to Sylvester Stallone).
</P>
<P>
   Iverson entered the game just tenths of a point ahead of O'Neal
in the scoring race, but he barely got half of his average, scoring
15 points on 6-of-20 shooting. That, despite Kobe Bryant getting
into early foul trouble that limited his time defending Iverson.
Bryant also settled for a quiet offensive night, scoring just 10
points on 4-of-12 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper picked up the slack with 16 points and the Lakers got
additional help from A.C. Green (11 points, eight rebounds) and
Rick Fox (13 points).
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won their 13th in a row at home and overall have won
27 of their last 28 games. They also improved to 28-3 against the
Eastern Conference, with one game left to play. If they beat the
New York Knicks on Sunday, the Lakers will post the best winning
percentage (.900) by a Western Conference team against the East in
NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   Although they never surrendered the lead after the opening
minutes of the game, the Lakers had difficulty putting the Sixers
away until the opening minutes of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 13 turnovers, Bryant's early foul trouble and a 15-point
burst from Kukoc, the Lakers took a 51-46 lead into halftime. They
owed much of it to O'Neal's defense, which produced six blocked
shots in the half, and the Lakers held the Sixers to 42.9 percent
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc, alternately guarded by Rice and Fox, made 7 of 11 shots
in the half and posed much more of a problem than Iverson (eight
points, 3 for 11).
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers pulled out an 87-84 victory at Philadelphia in
February, Kukoc had played only one game with his new teammates,
having just been acquired from Chicago. But the former Jackson
pupil has become acclimated since then and was a key part of their
recent seven-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're a different team,'' Jackson said. ``Obviously
they're a lanky, longer team with him out there. Offensively they
have another option to go to. He's a good playmaker, he's a scorer
. . . and a very good shooter, so you have to play on him, and he
can post up.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there's a variety of ways they can use him and I think it
aids their offense. Defensively, George (Lynch) is a real fine
player. I'm sure they're waiting to get him back off the (injured)
list because he's a gooddefender. . . . The combinatoin of those
two guys coming back . . . will make them a better team in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant picked up two quick fouls guarding Iverson and played
just four minutes in the first quarter. He didn't score until
midway through the second, but finished the half with eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Rice also got into early foul trouble against Kukoc and Fox came
off the bench to make all four of his shots for nine points.
</P>
</TEXT>
