<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4107 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLA     04-01 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPING FOR HEALTHY SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels returned to Anaheim Friday, scoring a 6-4
victory over the Padres in 10 innings in their one dress rehearsal
at home before they open the season Monday at Edison Field against
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   They came with a healthy attitude and, for the most part,
healthy bodies. That's a change on both counts from last season,
which will be remembered as much for injuries and clubhouse
backbiting as for the last-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels embark on this season relatively healthy. They'll
have the starting lineup intact, a far cry from last season when
Gary DiSarcina, Mo Vaughn, Tim Salmon and Jim Edmonds missed
considerable time due to injuries. In all, the Angels used the
disabled list 18 times.
</P>
<P>
   Other than injuries to pitchers Ramon Ortiz and Jarrod Washburn,
who are expected back within two weeks, the Angels are the picture
of health.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a chance when it's healthy,'' said DiSarcina,
who missed half the season after he was hit a fungo bat and
suffered a broken bone in his hand. ``We had three or four everyday
players out of the lineup. Last year we were beaten up and I think
it showed from time to time with our body language.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, with 26 players on the roster, have only one more
move to make by Sunday to get down to the major-league limit for
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   The first decision the Angels must make is how many pitchers to
carry since they expect to get Ortiz back in less than two weeks.
The games Friday and Saturday with the Padres may help Scioscia and
his staff make those decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still some decisions to be made,'' he said. ``We'll
have some pretty high energy coaches meeting. Do we go with 11
(pitchers) and for how long. Who's going to help us now? It's been
a competitive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State catcher Bryan Kennedy has emerged from an early
season slump to lift his batting average and older brother Adam,
ticketed for Triple-A with the Cardinals, was dealt to the Angels
just over a week ago in the Jim Edmonds trade. He'll open the
season Monday at second base and in the No. 2 slot in the batting
order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
