<HEADER>
A4116 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-VOL-CSUNVB-LADN-(SLAN     04-01 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOL-CSUNVB-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ROLL PAST CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The rowdies among the 1,062 in attendance called
UCLA's Ed Ratledge ``Shaggy,'' after the cartoon character. They
called Cameron Mount ``Headband'' after what he wore.
</P>
<P>
   A more appropriate moniker for either would be ``Matador
Killer.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men's volleyball players combined for 41 kills to help
fourth-ranked Bruins avoid a season sweep and beat No. 11 Cal State
Northridge 7-15, 15-3, 15-1, 15-12 in a Mountain Pacific Sports
Federation match Friday at Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (22-3, 12-3) lost in four games at the Wooden Center
on Feb. 17 for just the third time in 42 matches with the Matadors
(9-13, 5-11).
</P>
<P>
   Ratledge, who bears a resemblence to the Casey Kasem-voiced
character with his straight brown hair and goatee, had 19 kills
Friday. In the Feb. 17 match, he was the only one who hit the ball,
getting a career-best 46 kills.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do with the hair I've been bestowed with?''
Ratledge said. ``I'm too lazy to shave. I like Shaggy. It's better
than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Ratledge said, if he wanted to, he could shave his
head, but then he would look like Bull Shannon from ``Night
Court.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the razzing that helped Ratledge but rather the small
Northridge block. Ratledge stands 6-foot-8 and often faced 6-3 John
Baxter or 6-2 Junior Mosones.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I like to hit at a small block,'' Ratledge said.
``I'm at an advantage.''|
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as big as they are,'' Baxter said. ``Don't know if
that was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped Mount, a 6-8 freshman who had a team-high and
career-best 22 kills. He, too, heard it from the crowd, but that
wasn't make or break for him, either. In fact, Mount has been
climbing back after spending two years on his Mormon Mission.
</P>
<P>
   He said when he came back he felt strong, as if he had never
left. But two months in, he suddenly lost the ability and has been
battling back ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, now I'm out of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Al Scates hopes so, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cameron has been getting better. He's starting to play like we
knew he could,'' Scates said. ``He's starting to put it together.
His jump is getting better. He's getting more explosive. He's
hitting over the block. They moved Eckhard (Walter, CSUN's 6-10
hitter) on him and it didn't seem to bother him.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter led everyone with 23 kills, but Northridge didn't get
similar output from anyone else. Mosones was next with nine kills.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Burnham added 17 kills for UCLA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 0200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0040 </DOCNO>
