<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4123 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLAN     04-01 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY DEFENDER REGAINS SPOT IN LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Joey Franchino followed D.C. United's Ben
Olsen like an annoying gnat last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy defender hounded and harassed United's U.S. national
team striker. The frustration evident on Olsen's face was also felt
by the rest of United, as the Galaxy routed the defending MLS
champions 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   For Franchino, it was just another step on the new path he has
forged for himself. But it also sent a message to United; Franchino
was on the bench when United defeated the Galaxy 2-0 last November
in Foxboro to claim its third MLS title in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I sat there in Massachusetts and we lost, it was an
awful, awful feeling,'' said Franchino, preparing for tonight's
game with New England at the Rose Bowl. ``Starting last week
against D.C., I felt I had a lot to prove and we had a lot to
prove. We gave it to them pretty good, like we should have
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Franchino speak now, it's as if his career is
reborn.
</P>
<P>
   The Damien High School graduate enjoyed a lot of success as a
rookie in 1998, taking the starting left back position from Greg
Vanney. But in 1999, Vanney earned his job back from Franchino
after a rigorous postseason workout program. Franchino took the
demotion hard, allowing it to affect his personal life and training
habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to watch those guys play everyday and not be out
there last year,'' Franchino said. ``But it was my own fault; I
didn't prepare myself. I didn't come in with the right attitude a
professional is supposed to have.''
</P>
<P>
   After the MLS championship, Franchino recommitted himself,
similar to the way Vanney had. He put soccer first and everything
else second.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Vanney occupying the middle defense with Robin Fraser,
Franchino is back in the picture at left back, starting the first
two games for the Galaxy this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be a professional on and off the field, and it
started by making right choices,'' Franchino said. ``I'm in a
situation now, personally and professionally, that allows me to
feel and be more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchino said his fitness was the first thing he worked on when
the season ended. He is also thinking more clearly after moving
into a new apartment in Huntington Beach, where he can unwind
without distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head is clear and my perception of the game and everything
around me is totally different,'' Franchino said. ``I'm having fun,
I'm smiling and we're winning games.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said Franchino improved his
understanding of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a much better awareness, which means he's reading the
game much better, offensively and defensively,'' said Schmid. ``And
his positioning is much better. He has a better idea of what to do
with his first touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's also more relaxed. He's learned when he gets the ball and
things get tight and busy he doesn't have to fight through it. He's
learned to play away from trouble, reorganize and start again.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Danny Pena said he always knew Franchino was capable
of more, but it was up to Franchino to make the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``His overall game is night and day from last year,'' Pena said.
``But Joey's success and coming a long way has nothing to do with
anybody but himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one said, `Joey you have to do this.' He went out and did
what he did because he knows he has a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either now or never for him. If you look at his first
year when he took Vanney's job, he knew what that feeling was like.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came in here this year, he didn't care who's job he
was taking, but he was taking someone's job.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
