<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4131 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      04-01 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM TURMOIL ROUTS KINGS TO END HOME SKID, CLINCHES PLAYOFF BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If it was safe to assume the Sonics had enough
frustration bottled to fill a winery, then the Sacramento Kings
left KeyArena feeling a little stomped.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Sonics opened up a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   What spilled out was a concentrated attack, and the Sonics
doused the Kings with a 123-108 victory _ their first win in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the threat of big-time changes from Sonics coach
Paul Westphal if the team didn't show a better effort were heeded.
Not only did the Sonics snap a five-game home losing streak, they
clinched a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   And in a grander scheme, the Sonics moved to within a half-game
of the Kings, who hold the seventh seed in the Western Conference
playoff standings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the by-products of their first home win since beating
Vancouver March 16 didn't seem to matter as much as how the Sonics
performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and played hard,'' Westphal said. ``We played
together, hit the boards, moved the ball, moved ourselves, and it
was just a beautiful thing. We like to play that way. Sometimes we
get a little off track ... but the energy was there.''
</P>
<P>
   From start to finish. From end to end. From the top man to the
12th man. From those who weren't part of Westphal's wrath to those
who felt it immensely.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gary Payton guided the Sonics with a 35-point,
15-assist, six-steal performance, all eyes were on power forward
Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Baker was the star of an unflattering film session used Thursday
to point out his weaknesses. Friday night, he received adulation
for best performance in a supporting role. Baker finished with 15
points and 14 rebounds _ his 16th double-double this season.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in 28 games that Baker had a double-digit
rebound performance.
</P>
<P>
   Baker obviously was not concerned with scoring. He concentrated
on rebounding and defense _ two areas of concern for Westphal.
There were at least two occasions when Baker planted himself under
the basket and forced the officials to whistle the Kings for a
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing was not getting caught up in what was being said, but
how I was going to come out and help us win,'' said Baker, who
played 30 minutes. ``I understood defense and rebounding were going
to be more important than scoring. That's what we re-emphasized
(Thursday) in practice and talked about before the game.''
</P>
<P>
   When Baker fouled out with 2:43 left in the fourth quarter, he
did so to an ovation. Westphal even waved his arms, gesturing so
the crowd would get louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played with high energy, he was going after shots to block,
he was rebounding,'' Westphal said. ``I was very happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker may have been too overzealous because he played mostly in
foul trouble. He picked up his fifth foul with 9:40 left in the
game when he pushed off to grab a rebound. The Sonics led 101-81 at
that point, and Baker was doing what had been prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's coaching style allows for players to make mistakes as
long as the miscues are born out of aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vin didn't want to let himself down or his teammates down,''
center Horace Grant said. ``He went out there and played great
basketball. When he took his first foul, when he didn't let
(Corliss Williamson) lay the ball up, I knew he was ready. He had a
bounce in his step. I'd say he left it on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics played with so much more pizzazz that Payton,
normally a nuts-and-bolts player, threw a pass between his legs
just before halftime. Jelani McCoy caught the assist and flipped in
a layup that put the Sonics ahead 68-49.
</P>
<P>
   They held a 69-49 advantage at halftime. It was the most points
the Sonics scored in a half this season. The team's final point
total was the second-highest next to a 127-91 rout of Orlando here
Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics led by as many as 23 points, and their advantage
never slipped below 15 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst team to play is a team in turmoil,'' Sacramento's
Chris Webber said. ``It's almost like they look forward to games
because there's no pressure. What can get worse? When you're
playing like that, you have the wind at your back. We just have to
credit them for coming out and playing well while resolving
whatever issues they had.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time they beat a playoff-bound team since
Feb. 28 at Charlotte. Sacramento also was the first winning team
the Sonics dispatched at KeyArena since Phoenix played here Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   It came at perhaps the best possible time.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are now 1-2 against the Kings with a chance to even
the season series when they meet April 18 _ a day before the
regular-season finale. If the Sonics can even the series with the
Kings, forcing a tie-breaker situation could mean the difference
between the seventh and eighth seeds.
</P>
<P>
   The situation could have been much uglier heading into a game at
Portland Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   To simply say the Sonics had more bounce in their step would be
an understatement. They stomped around KeyArena, playing
aggressively on defense and going after rebounds as if paychecks
were attached to them.
</P>
<P>
   That ignited the team's offense, which operated mostly in
transition to manufacture easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't compare this to winning a championship, but it's up
there,'' Grant said. ``Getting off that skid and guys sharing the
ball and guys coming off the bench doing a fantastic job was great.
It was one of the biggest wins of the season for us. It's like
putting an ingredient in the pot to make it sweet again.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012 or
ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 0241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
