<HEADER>
A4132 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NULAKERS-LADN-(SL     04-01 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NULAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ STARS AGAIN FOR LAKERS; IVERSON SILENCED
</HEADLINE>
 ...WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Allen Iverson might yet trump Shaquille O'Neal in
the NBA's scoring race, but in their last face-to-face meeting of
the season, he couldn't even see the basket.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers chased Iverson, harassed him and occasionally tackled
him when he dared fly toward the Staples Center rims, and in the
final tally, O'Neal got more blocked shots (eight) than Iverson got
field goals (six) Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's 37 points pulled him ahead of Iverson in the scoring
race, and pulled the defensive-minded Lakers past the Philadelphia
76ers 100-88 before 18,997 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq dominated,'' coach Phil Jackson said after the Lakers'
eighth consecutive win. ``It took us a while to figure out how to
initiate our offense and get the ball to him at the best angle, but
once we did, he got it going.''
</P>
<P>
   And going, and going. O'Neal hit 17 of 28 shots and added 14
rebounds and five assists to his blocked-shot barrage, which
matched his season-high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to come out and be very active,'' O'Neal said.
``That team, they have a dangerous midrange game, so we kind of
wanted to either let them shoot the jumper or bring them all the
way. They brought them all the way to me, and I was just trying to
catch them all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big-picture race, the Lakers knocked their magic number
for clinching the league's best record to three. Any combination of
Lakers victories and Portland losses adding up to three will ensure
the Lakers home-court advantage throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the other race, O'Neal pushed his scoring average to 29.1
points, and Iverson _ who settled for 15 points on 6-of-20 shooting
_ slipped to No. 2, at 28.9 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq did a great job having them change up their shots,'' said
Ron Harper. ``He had a great game again tonight. He's for sure
carrying this basketball team and it's good to see. He keeps going
out and the way that he plays, it just feeds our whole team, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a night the Lakers needed O'Neal's best, because their
second and third options were nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant got in early foul trouble against Iverson and
struggled to a 10-point, 4-of-12, four-turnover night. Glen Rice,
returning from an illness, had his own foul trouble trying to
contain Toni Kukoc and finished with eight points in 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Harper picked up the slack, scoring 16 points, and the Lakers
got plenty of support from A.C. Green (11 points, nine rebounds)
and Rick Fox, who scored 13 points and helped contain Kukoc.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc's 19 points and Matt Geiger's 20 kept the Sixers in
striking range until the fourth quarter, but the Lakers' shutdown
of Iverson kept Philadelphia at bay.
</P>
<P>
   When they weren't blocking his shots, they were knocking him
down _ O'Neal and Harper each picked up flagrant fouls defending
against Iverson fast-break layup attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the game,'' Harper said. ``We just ain't giving up any
easy shots. We're trying to go up there and keep playing a
hard-nosed game. (The officials) made some good calls tonight and
they made some bad calls tonight, so we just keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson didn't &LR; 3yQ-H:ee V+k$W.YH3I9Q
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
