<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MONETARY-POLICY-REVIE     04-01 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONETARY-POLICY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES MONETARY POLICY STILL WORK? NO, AT LEAST NOT THE WAY IT ONCE
DID. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan is among the most powerful men in
the world. As chairman of the Federal Reserve, he can alter the
course of the economy by moving interest rates up and down. His
pronouncements can send shudders through markets around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seems as Greenspan tries, with little success so far,
to cool off an economy that is threatening to overheat and impose a
degree of temperance on Wall Street's long-running party.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just Greenspan whose clout is in question. Given that
companies, consumers and investors have proven largely impervious
to a series of rate hikes by the Fed, economists are wondering
whether monetary policy still works, or at least whether it works
the same way it used to.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has pushed interest rates up five times since June. In
the meantime, the economy has continued thundering along at a pace
well above what most economists think is sustainable over the long
run without generating inflation. The government reported last week
that the economy grew at a 7.3 percent annual rate in the last
quarter of 1999, its fastest pace in 16 years, and all the signs
are that growth has moderated only slightly so far in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although stock prices have taken to gyrating wildly, and the
high-flying technology stocks in the Nasdaq index have been hit
hard, the trend on Wall Street has remained upward. And long-term
interest rates have not risen nearly as much as would be expected
when the Fed is driving up the official short-term rates it
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates take time to filter through the economy,
and their full effect may not be felt until later this year. But
the economy and the markets are clearly absorbing the Fed's rate
hikes with a somewhat perplexing equanimity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monetary policy usually works with a lag of six to nine
months, so you shouldn't really expect the rate increases that
occurred starting in mid-1999 to have a noticeable impact on the
economy before the second quarter of this year,'' said L. Douglas
Lee of Economics from Washington, a consulting firm. ``Having said
that, the economy is not as sensitive to interest rate increases as
it used to be. This makes it tougher for the Fed to slow things
down by raising interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   In textbooks, monetary policy sounds pretty simple. Fed
officials make a judgment about how fast the economy can grow
without igniting inflation, based on the growth of the working
population and improvements in productivity. (Over the last few
years those estimates have risen to nearly 4 percent, from just
over 2 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   When growth exceeds that rate over a sustained period, the Fed
drives up the short-term interest rates it controls. Banks then
charge more for loans. The bond market pushes up corporate
borrowing rates. Stock prices come under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   With mortgages and auto loans more expensive, and people feeling
less wealthy, consumers buy fewer houses and cars. With their costs
rising and sales slowing, companies might choose to close a plant,
or not to open a new one. Jobs become less plentiful. The economy
slows and inflation fades.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, it is more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, although growth rates are well above what almost
anyone thinks is sustainable over the long run, there is almost no
inflation. Moreover, the economy and the markets are changing in
ways that tend to dampen the effect of rising rates.
</P>
<P>
   Take mortgages. Rates on traditional fixed-rate mortgages have
shot up over the last year. But homebuyers have learned to maintain
their purchasing power by shifting into adjustable rate mortgages,
which initially carry lower monthly payments. Lee said that at the
beginning of 1999, while rates were quite low, only about 10
percent of homebuyers were choosing adjustable mortgages. By the
end of last year 30 percent of homebuyers were choosing
adjustables. As a result, home sales, a key driver of economic
growth, have kept running at a brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, much of the economic growth in recent years has come
from advances in technology, and technology companies carry
relatively little debt compared with their ``old economy'' cousins
in capital-intensive fields like manufacturing. Companies with
little debt are less sensitive to rising rates than those with big
debt loads, and are therefore less likely to cut back as the Fed
tightens policy.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between old- and new-economy companies is just
one reason the financial markets have not reacted much to the Fed's
tighter monetary policy. Another is psychological: investors have
become so conditioned to Greenspan keeping the economy on an even
keel that they are concentrating not on the pain he is seeking to
inflict on them through rate increases but on the presumed outcome
of his efforts _ an economy that continues growing steadily with
little inflation. Greenspan is in some ways a victim of his own
success.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same phenomenon is at work in the bond market. Because
the government is running huge budget surpluses, the Treasury is
paying off the national debt. In doing so, the government is
creating a shortage of Treasury bonds, driving up the price of
those bonds and driving down the interest rate they carry. In
effect, the Treasury and the Fed are working at cross purposes.
</P>
<P>
   One result has been a call for the Fed to reexamine the tools it
uses. If the key to bringing the economy's growth down to a
sustainable level is reining in the stock market, as Greenspan
says, then perhaps he should consider aiming his fire directly at
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, pressure is mounting on Greenspan to tighten the
rules on buying stocks with borrowed money. But Greenspan has
repeatedly replied that such a move could not be counted on to have
any effect on stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   So the Fed will no doubt continue using its imperfect though not
impotent interest rate tool. And Greenspan may find that he has to
raise rates further, and in bigger increments, than he would
prefer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
