<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-SEASON-3TAKES-NYT     04-01 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SEASON-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL 2000: RED SOX PICKED TO DETHRONE YANKS IN EAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this preview  &UR;  &LR; teams are listed in predicted order of finish.
</P>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   1. Boston Red Sox
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams, fourth year 1999: 94-68, second
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Red Sox have never overcome the loss of Babe Ruth, but
they sure didn't let Mo Vaughn's defection bother them. The Red Sox
played in a second successive post-season, albeit as the wild-card
team, for the first time in 83 years, and now they can make it
three in a row for the first time in their star-crossed history.
</P>
<P>
   It would come as no surprise if they did it as a division
champion. The Red Sox have what it takes to make up their four-game
deficit with the Yankees last season. They have a manager who has
turned into some sort of magician. They have a potentially strong
starting pitching rotation, headed by the inimitable Pedro Martinez
and including his brother Ramon and possibly a pair of youngsters,
Brian Rose and Juan Pena.
</P>
<P>
   They also have Carl Everett (.325, 25 HR, 108 RBI) and Troy
O'Leary (.280-28-103), two emerging sluggers, who could make Vaughn
a faint memory.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Carl Everett, Jeff Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Tom Gordon (right elbow).
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Ramon Martinez and Fassero need to complement
Pedro Martinez, and Derek Lowe has to be effective as the closer in
place of Gordon, who is gone for the season.
</P>
<P>
   2. New York Yankees
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, fifth year 1999: 98-64, first
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that the Yankees can't win yet again, but
if they don't, the reason very likely will be the demise of their
solid starting pitching. David Cone and Roger Clemens won't last
forever, and maybe that elusive fifth starter will become a
problem. And perish the thought, but Mariano Rivera might actually
give up a run, something he didn't do in his final 36 relief
appearances covering 30 and two-thirds innings in the regular
season and 12 and one-third in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, however, would have to collapse completely to miss
the playoffs, which they have made the past five seasons, and not
have a chance for their third consecutive World Series championship
and fourth in the last five seasons. The last team to win three
World Series in a row was the Oakland Athletics of 1972-74.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees have a weakness offensively, it most likely would
be the left field-designated hitter combination of Ricky Ledee and
Shane Spencer. But Derek Jeter, Bernie Williams et al. should
produce more than enough punch.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Roberto Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Joe Girardi, Luis Sojo.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The Yankees' strength has been pitching, and they
need it to continue to be.
</P>
<P>
   3. Toronto Blue Jays
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fregosi, second year 1999: 84-78, third
</P>
<P>
   Combined last season, Carlos Delgado and Shawn Green slugged 86
home runs and drove in 257 runs. Delgado and Raul Mondesi don't
figure to exceed those figures this season.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Blue Jays' problem, or one of their problems. They
need others to increase their contributions; a two-man team isn't
going to boost the Blue Jays any closer to contention. Jose Cruz
Jr. is one of the players who needs to produce more, but what he
has given before (.241 last season) may be all he can give. One
promising sign: he was the MVP of the Caribbean World Series,
hitting .385.
</P>
<P>
   Homer Bush (.320) was a pleasant surprise last year as the
regular second baseman. They need him to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Raul Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Shawn Green, Pat Hentgen.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: No matter what the hitters do, the young pitching
trio of Chris Carpenter, Kelvim Escobar and Roy Halladay have to
become a factor in the team's improvement.
</P>
<P>
   4. Baltimore Orioles
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hargrove, first year 1999: 78-84, fourth
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove brings with him five consecutive division championships
as a manager, but the dysfunctional Orioles may pose too serious a
problem for even him to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   No team has wasted as much money in a two-season span as the
Orioles have, and they didn't do much in the winter to improve
their position. Rather, they are an aging team with only one
starter, catcher Charles Johnson, under 31. The average age of
their everyday players is 35. Cal Ripken, who needs nine hits for
3,000, is one of their oldest, and this very likely will be his
finale. It's time to start breaking up the old gang.
</P>
<P>
   The starting rotation is a mess. It includes the journeyman Pat
Rapp and two pitchers signed as minor league free agents, Calvin
Maduro and Jose Mercedes. KEY ADDITION: Mike Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Arthur Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Maybe Albert Belle can have a good start and
ignite a spark that catapults the Orioles out of their rocking
chairs and into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   5. Tampa Bay Devil Rays
</P>
<P>
   Larry Rothschild, third year 1999: 69-93, fifth
</P>
<P>
   Shaken by the loss of 700,000 fans, nearly a third of their
first-year attendance, the Devil Rays bulked up. If it's offense
the fans want, it's offense they'll get. Or so the Devil Rays hope.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vaughn and Vinny Castilla, newcomers, and Jose Canseco and
Fred McGriff, incumbents, hit a total of 144 home runs last season,
and that with Canseco missing nearly 50 games. Gerald Williams will
be important to the offense, too. He did a good job once he became
Atlanta's leadoff hitter last season.
</P>
<P>
   While their hitters are trying to hit the ball over the fence,
the Rays' pitchers will try to throw it over the plate. They led
the league in walks, averaging 4.3 a game.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Greg Vaughn, Vinny Castilla, Gerald Williams,
Juan Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Rolando Arrojo, Wade Boggs.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If nothing else, the Devil Rays want to be
interesting losers so the fans will return.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   1. Cleveland Indians
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Manuel, first year 1999: 97-65, first
</P>
<P>
   The next voice the Indians hear will be Charlie Manuel's. His is
the one that is supposed to take the Indians to the World Series
championship Mike Hargrove did not get and therefore paid the
price. In making the change, General Manager John Hart said the
Indians needed a new voice. Catcher Sandy Alomar Jr. said he didn't
know what that meant.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel, a member of the team's coaching staff the past six
seasons, has what Hargrove had _ easily the best team in the
division. The six months of the season haven't presented a problem
for the Indians; they have stumbled in October. To try to correct
that shortcoming, Hart signed Chuck Finley, the veteran
left-hander, who has a 16-9 career record against the Yankees, the
best of any active pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing pitchers have to be wary of Richie Sexson, as if they
didn't have enough trouble with Manny Ramirez (44 HR, 165 RBI).
Sexson is an emerging young hitter who last season hit 31 home runs
and drove in 116 runs.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Chuck Finley.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Mike Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The new manager is on the spot to show he can
talk the Indians through to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   2. Chicago White Sox
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Manuel, third year 1999: 75-86, second
</P>
<P>
   If they can solve the mysterious disappearance of Frank Thomas,
the White Sox could have an interesting team this season. For seven
seasons, the league had no better, more consistent hitter than
Thomas. But it's as if an impostor took his place the past two
years. Thomas did raise his batting average 40 points to .305 last
season, but he plummeted to career lows in home runs (15) and RBI
(77).
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad because the White Sox have found some good young
hitters in their outfield: Magglio Ordonez (.301, 30, 117), Chris
Singleton (.300) and Carlos Lee (.293).
</P>
<P>
   They hope to have an upgraded left side of the infield, where
Mike Caruso and Greg Norton made 49 errors last season. But Jose
Valentin, the new shortstop, made 22 errors in 349 chances for
Milwaukee while Caruso was committing 24 in 555.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Jose Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Jaime Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The White Sox need a resurgent Thomas and a
vastly improved defense to maintain their position as the best team
in the rest of the division.
</P>
<P>
   3. Detroit Tigers
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner, first year 1999: 69-92, third
</P>
<P>
   Straight from seven successive losing seasons in Milwaukee, Phil
Garner lands in the Detroit dugout with a $1.2 million-a-year
salary. Nice work if you can get it.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Garner, though, the Tigers brought in Juan Gonzalez
as the centerpiece for their debut in Comerica Park, their new
40,000-seat playground. Club officials only hope that Gonzalez is
more successful at his job than they have been in inducing him to
sign a $140 million contract. Could be a case of here now, gone in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, whom Texas traded when it determined it couldn't sign
him, will lead what could be a potent offense, but the Tigers need
an outpouring of talent from their pitching staff, one of the
league's worst last year. Hideo Nomo, who compiled a 12-8 record
for Garner last season after the Mets released him, has become the
Tigers' No. 1 starter.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Justin Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The pitchers have to give the hitters a chance so
they don't have to score 10 or 12 runs every game.
</P>
<P>
   4. Kansas City Royals
</P>
<P>
   Tony Muser, fourth year 1999: 64-97, fourth
</P>
<P>
   Fallen far from their contending status, the Royals have
actually developed some impressive young players. Right now they
are all on the position side, leaving much to be desired from the
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Damon (.307, 14, 77), Carlos Beltran (.293, 22, 108) and
Jermaine Dye (.294, 27, 119) have formed such a strong outfield
trio that there's no room for Mark Quinn, who after winning his
second consecutive minor league batting title hit six home runs and
knocked in 18 runs in 60 late-season at-bats for the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sweeney, moving from catching to first base, is another
reason (.322, 22, 102) the Royals had one of the best-hitting teams
in the league last season. They could use more home runs, though.
They were 12th in that category.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Ricky Bottalico.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Jeff Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Their pitchers gave up the most runs and had the
fewest strikeouts. They won't climb far if that record doesn't
improve.
</P>
<P>
   5. Minnesota Twins
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly, 14th year 1999: 63-97, fifth
</P>
<P>
   If this bunch of kids doesn't work, try that bunch. Tom Kelly's
kindergarten goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Allen played 133 games in the outfield for the Twins last
season, Doug Mientkiewicz 110 games at first base and Javier
Valentin 76 games as the catcher. All will begin this season in the
minor leagues. Kelly was dissatisfied with the attitude and work
habits of some of his young players and sent a shrill message
throughout the organization.
</P>
<P>
   In their place are more youngsters. Matt LeCroy, for example.
After only two years in the minor league system, he finds himself
the team's starting catcher, or one of the starting catchers. One
of the pitchers he will catch is Brad Radke, whom the Twins have
resisted trading.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Butch Huskey.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Terry Steinbach.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: On-the-job training continues.
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   1. Seattle Mariners
</P>
<P>
   Lou Piniella, eighth year 1999: 79-83, third
</P>
<P>
   If the Mariners had handled the matter more diplomatically, they
could still have Ken Griffey Jr. in their lineup and would have
left no question as to the identity of the division champion. As it
is, they look strong enough to win because they have the best
pitching rotation in their history.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't win this year, who knows when they might because
this is most likely the last season they will have Alex Rodriguez,
who can be a free agent seven months from now. Not many players
become available after winning the M.V.P. award.
</P>
<P>
   Four players expected to be in the opening-day lineup were not
there a year ago. A fifth, Carlos Guillen, was at second base, not
third, and he played only five games before a knee injury ended his
season.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: John Olerud, Aaron Sele, Mike Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Jay Buhner, who missed the equivalent of a full
season in the past two years, needs to stay healthy and provide the
production he did in the previous three years (124 HR, 368 RBI).
</P>
<P>
   2. Oakland Athletics
</P>
<P>
   Art Howe, fifth year 1999: 87-75, second
</P>
<P>
   If the laws of mathematical progression work for the Athletics,
they will win enough games to win the division title. Showing
remarkable progress, they have improved in the past two seasons
from 65 victories to 74 to 87.
</P>
<P>
   A low-revenue team, the A's decided they had advanced far enough
to spend some money and retained three key players, pitchers Kevin
Appier and Omar Olivares and second baseman Randy Velarde, all
acquired last season.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde became a catalyst for an offense that produced the
league's second lowest-batting average but the fourth-best on-base
percentage and the fourth highest total of runs. Jason Giambi, John
Jaha and Matt Stairs form the lusty part of the lineup, combining
for 106 homers and 336 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: They can't let higher expectations throw them off
the game they played so well last year.
</P>
<P>
   3. Texas Rangers
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates, sixth year 1999: 95-67, first
</P>
<P>
   Finishing first isn't enough anymore. Not if you score a total
of two runs in six playoff games with the Yankees over two seasons.
So what do you do? You trade the player who scored both of those
runs.
</P>
<P>
   That's not why the Rangers traded Juan Gonzalez; they determined
they wouldn't be able to sign him to a contract extension. But
without Gonzalez and Todd Zeile, whom they lost unexpectedly as a
free agent, the Rangers are lacking a significant segment of their
offense. They're counting on two young outfielders, Ruben Mateo and
Gabe Kapler, to match their clippings and replace many of the lost
runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have also now pronounced themselves a pitching team
after bringing back Kenny Rogers and Darren Oliver as free agents.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Kenny Rogers, Darren Oliver, Gabe Kapler.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Juan Gonzalez, Todd Zeile, Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If the Rangers want to get a chance to score
against the Yankees in October, their pitchers have to be at least
as good as they hope they can be.
</P>
<P>
   4. Anaheim Angels
</P>
<P>
   Mike Scioscia, first year 1999: 70-92, fourth
</P>
<P>
   This was an even more dysfunctional team than the Orioles in
1999. The manager and general manager are new, and they can only
hope the attitude in the clubhouse is.
</P>
<P>
   A bat-rackful of question marks surrounds the team, but some of
them could be answered with a healthy Mo Vaughn, Tim Salmon and
Gary DiSarcina, all of whom missed significant time or were
hampered by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels seem to be short on starting pitching, especially
with Tim Belcher opening on the disabled list. That's why they
acquired Kent Bottenfield, an 18-game winner, from St. Louis in a
late trade. They need development from a group that includes Jason
Dickson, Ramon Ortiz, Jarrod Washburn and Scott Schoeneweis.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Kent Bottenfield.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Jim Edmonds, Chuck Finley.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: First, they have to learn togetherness. Then,
they need to build a respectable pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
