<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stealing Each Other's Thunder &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One major-party presidential candidate proposed a
multibillion-dollar package of education reforms last week. The
other asserted that a 6-year-old Cuban boy, rescued offshore
Florida, should be made a permanent resident of the United States
and his father should be lured to the United States with a similar
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Which candidate was the Democrat, and which the Republican?
</P>
<P>
   At this early juncture of the general election campaign, Gov.
George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
nominees, are staking claims to positions that belie political
stereotypes. It was the Republican, Bush, who sought to make a
traditional Democratic issue, education, his own, by unveiling an
education plan that included a $5-billion proposal to fight
childhood illiteracy and a five-year, $2.9 billion initiative to
improve teacher training.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the Democrat, Gore, who, backing away from the
Clinton administration on one of the most politically sensitive
issues of the year, announced his belief that Elian Gonzalez should
be granted permanent residency status in the United States and that
his father should be offered the same, rather than leaving a return
to Cuba as the only way to reunite them.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's move so startled Democratic allies _ ``Oh my God, it's
unbelievable!'' declared one official _ that some, like Rep. Maxine
Waters of California, said that they might have to reconsider their
support for Gore. While some liberal Democrats said he was making
an irresponsible vote grab that played politics with a little boy's
emotional state, there was no denying how important those votes, in
the pivotal state of Florida, might be to him in November.
</P>
<P>
   In embracing these positions, Bush and Gore appeared to be
inching closer to each other ideologically: Gore, after all, has
also offered an education program, amounting to $115 billion in aid
over 10 years. And Bush has long been arguing that Elian's father
should leave Cuba and be with his son in the United States, rather
than having the boy sent back to Havana.
</P>
<P>
   And both found ways to demonstrate how in sync they are with the
popular Sen. John McCain. Included in Bush's education proposals,
for instance, was money for one of McCain's favored projects,
enlisting military retirees as teachers. Gore, meanwhile, announced
his desire to raise $7.1 billion as an endowment fund for the
underwriting of House and Senate races beginning in 2008, even if
he did acknowledge that he was ``an imperfect messenger'' for
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The Art War Guns Fall Silent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it began last fall, it was the political equivalent of holy
