<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4158 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-SEASON-NATIONAL-3     04-01 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SEASON-NATIONAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL 2000: BRAVES, REDS AND DIAMONDBACKS PICKED TO WIN
DIVISIONS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this preview &UR;  &LR; teams are listed in predicted order of finish.
</P>
<P>
   N.L. EAST
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA BRAVES
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, 11th year 1999: 103-59, first
</P>
<P>
   An executive of another team was talking this spring about how
impressed he was with the way the Braves shuffle their personnel
every year and keep winning. Let a player go as a free agent, sign
a free agent; trade this one for that one. They have done it again
in preparation for their ninth consecutive division title.
</P>
<P>
   This year they have changed left fielders and second basemen.
They also have a different first baseman, though he's not new.
Andres Galarraga is back, incredibly, from his cancer setback, and
if he can't take the daily grind, Wally Joyner, another newcomer,
will be there to spell him.
</P>
<P>
   Someone will have to spell John Rocker for the first two weeks
while he serves his suspension for boorish behavior. Another
pitcher, John Smoltz, will miss the entire season while he recovers
from elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Quilvio Veras, Reggie Sanders, Wally Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Ryan Klesko, Bret Boone, Gerald Williams.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If the other pitchers pick up Smoltz's usual
load, all will be right in the Braves' new world.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK METS
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine, fourth year 1999: 97-66, second
</P>
<P>
   We know the Mets won't win all 162 games. But will they win
enough games to reach the playoffs again? Last year they had to
play an extra game to get there. They think this is the year they
will beat the Braves, but they might have another thought coming.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, Todd Zeile and Derek Bell are not sufficient
replacements for John Olerud and Roger Cedeno. Mike Hampton (22-4
last year) should be better than any of the departed starting
pitchers, but the rotation doesn't look as deep. Glendon Rusch,
starter No. 5, does not appear to have the potential of Octavio
Dotel or Masato Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   And can Rickey Henderson, 41-year-old Rickey Henderson, be as
spry and as productive as he was last year?
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Mike Hampton, Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: John Olerud, Roger Cedeno, Kenny Rogers, Masato
Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Pitching and defense win pennants. The defense is
there; will the pitching be there, too?
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL EXPOS
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Alou, ninth year 1999: 68-94, fourth
</P>
<P>
   When the players struck with less than two months to go in the
1994 season, the Expos were in first place. That was their year,
they believed. Now they believe this could be their year. For what
exactly, they aren't sure, but they will play with new enthusiasm.
The new managing owner, Jeffrey Loria, has instilled that feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Felipe Alou is so good that he can take whatever edge he
has and translate it into a surprising number of victories. Besides
the new outlook, Alou has Vladimir Guerrero on his side (.316, 42
HR, 131 RBI), and he is worth a certain number of victories
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The team is still young, with Peter Bergeron, the rookie center
fielder, joining five other starting position players and all five
starting pitchers with less than four years of major league
service.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Hideki Irabu, Graeme Lloyd, Lee Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Brad Fullmer.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If the young pitchers, bolstered by a newly
comfortable Irabu, are ready to blossom, the Expos could be a
highly interesting team.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA PHILLIES
</P>
<P>
   Terry Francona, fourth year 1999: 77-85, third
</P>
<P>
   The good young players the Phillies have collected show signs of
turning the team into a contender, but the Phillies' fate seems to
be linked to the health of Curt Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   With Schilling in good health and winning, the Phillies were
only five and a half games out of first place one week into August
last season. Then Schilling went on the disabled list because of a
sore shoulder and the team plummeted in the standing. By the time
he pitched again, about four weeks later, the Phillies were 17
games from first.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling will open the season on the disabled list, working his
way back from surgery. The young players will be on their own until
he returns.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Andy Ashby, Mike Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Steve Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Ashby was acquired to bolster the starting
rotation, but it needs needs more for the team to challenge the
superior teams.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA MARLINS
</P>
<P>
   John Boles, second year 1999: 64-98, fifth
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins just have to keep showing up until their young
players, especially their pitchers, are ready to win in the majors.
Until then, this will be a last-place team.
</P>
<P>
   Youth? The Marlins are full of it. Except for Alex Fernandez and
Cliff Floyd, no starter or potential starter, no starting pitcher,
no closer has played in the majors for as much as two and a half
years. Nine players in this group of 13 don't have two years in the
majors. With nine years to his credit, Fernandez has more service
time than five other starters and the closer combined.
</P>
<P>
   And if this bunch isn't inexperienced enough, the Marlins have
another platoon or two coming up behind them.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Brian Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Patience, patience, patience.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI REDS
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeon, fourth year 1999: 96-67, second
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Jim Bowden has already won the executive of the
year award for securing Ken Griffey Jr. for relatively little, in
both players and money. Now his team has to reward his efforts by
toppling Houston from the top of the division.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Reds fell two victories short of the division
championship and one victory short of the playoffs. They willingly
lost Greg Vaughn, their big power hitter, but added Griffey and
Dante Bichette. They also retained Pokey Reese, the player Bowden
would not give to Seattle in the Griffey trade.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeon, whose slight raise on a one-year contract was not
an appropriate reward for the team's play in 1999, should
nevertheless have fun again this time around.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Ken Griffey Jr., Dante Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Greg Vaughn, Mike Cameron, Brett Tomko.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: For all that Griffey brings, he cannot pitch. The
starters have to do that, and the rotation may be a little thin.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON ASTROS
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dierker, fourth year 1999: 97-65, first
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of Mike Hampton's 22-victory arm and Carl
Everett's burgeoning bat, the Astros will be hard pressed to finish
first for the fourth year in a row. On the other hand, they will
have Moises Alou's battering bat, which they didn't have last year
because of Alou's torn knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   So where does that leave the Astros in their first season in
their new park, Enron Field? Most likely right in the middle of the
division race. Any lineup that has Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell
has to be taken seriously. Roger Cedeno, who came from the Mets
with Octavio Dotel for Hampton, adds stolen bases to the lineup (66
last year), and Daryle Ward brings a potentially explosive bat for
what should be his first full major league season.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Roger Cedeno, Octavio Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Mike Hampton, Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The pitching puzzle: Will Dotel and Scott Elarton
ease Hampton's loss? And is the Jose Lima who won 21 games for
real?
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS CARDINALS
</P>
<P>
   Tony La Russa, fifth year 1999: 75-86, fourth
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Walt Jocketty spent an exhausting off-season,
scurrying hither and yon to fill this hole, bolster that position.
The result should be a contender, something St. Louis hasn't been
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Jocketty made over the pitching staff, bringing in Pat Hentgen,
a former Cy Young award winner; Darryl Kile, once a 19-game winner;
and Andy Benes, once an 18-game winner for the Cardinals, for the
rotation, and Dave Veres, who had 31 saves for Colorado last year,
to be the closer.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vina came from Milwaukee to be the second baseman, and
Jim Edmonds, in a late move, arrived from Anaheim to be the center
fielder. Edmonds' presence means that J.D. Drew, whose rookie
season (.242) was disappointing, has to produce or the veteran Eric
Davis will bump him to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Jim Edmonds, Pat Hentgen, Darryl Kile, Andy
Benes, Dave Veres, Fernando Vina.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Kent Bottenfield, Darren Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If the newly arrived veteran pitchers rediscover
the talent that enabled them to be top-notch pitchers once upon a
time, the home runs Mark McGwire hits may lead to victories.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH PIRATES
</P>
<P>
   Gene Lamont, fourth year 1999: 78-83, third
</P>
<P>
   All but a few teams have enough starting pitching, which means
all but a few teams relentlessly pursued some of the Pirates'
starting pitchers throughout the winter. Jason Schmidt and Kris
Benson were the primary players sought by the multitudes, but the
season, that is, the American League season, begins tomorrow, and
Schmidt and Benson will wear Pittsburgh uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   As they try to claw their way up in the standing, the Pirates
are not just about pitching. Brian Giles (.315, 39 HR, 115 RBI) and
Kevin Young (.298, 26, 106) provide punch, and they hope to be
joined by the team's rookie center fielder, Chad Hermansen, who
posted minor league career highs in homers (32) and RBI (97) last
season.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Wil Cordero.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Albert Martin.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Continued development by the pitchers, a solid
rookie season by Hermansen and a successful comeback by catcher
Jason Kendall, who sustained a season-ending ankle injury at
midseason, could make the Pirates worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO CUBS
</P>
<P>
   Don Baylor, first season 1999: 67-95, sixth
</P>
<P>
   Coveted by the Cubs, as well as other teams, Don Baylor told his
Chicago recruiters that for him to consider taking their job, they
would have to make moves to improve the team that had the league's
second-worst record last season. The Cubs have not presented Baylor
with a pennant winner, but they have made the team better. And it
will be even better when Kerry Wood returns to the Wrigley Field
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi gives Baylor a solid man behind the plate, and Eric
Young gives him an infusion of stolen bases into the offense.
Ismael Valdes, when healthy, should give him a solid starting
pitcher. Another newcomer, center fielder Damon Buford, gained the
first hit and run batted in of the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa isn't new, but his home run act never gets old.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Don Baylor, Ismael Valdes, Joe Girardi, Eric
Young.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Terry Adams.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The division race may be open, but not open
enough for the Cubs unless Wood performs as he did two years ago
and takes the rest of the staff with him.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE BREWERS
</P>
<P>
   Davey Lopes, first year 1999: 74-87, fifth
</P>
<P>
   So the Brewers become part of this big four-team, nine-player
trade and emerge with the pitcher they want, Jamey Wright, but then
Wright suffers a small tear in his rotator cuff and is out for at
least the first month of the season. This is the kind of fortune
the Brewers have had over the years. Why should it change now?
</P>
<P>
   They have not had a season with a winning record since 1992,
which was the year their owner, Bud Selig, became acting
commissioner. But while Selig went on to do the job without acting,
his general manager, Sal Bando, and manager, Phil Garner, paid the
price for overseeing seven successive losing seasons. Dean Taylor
and Davey Lopes will be responsible for No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Jamey Wright, Henry Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Jeff Cirillo, David Nilsson, Hideo Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Lopes has tried to change the losing attitude,
but a display of talent would help his effort immeasurably.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA DIAMONDBACKS
</P>
<P>
   Buck Showalter, third year 1999: 100-62, first
</P>
<P>
   The most successful two-year-old team in baseball history, the
Diamondbacks have room for improvement. They won 100 games and the
division title in their second season, but they lost the
franchise's first playoff series to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   They featured an explosive lineup last year with surprising
production from Jay Bell (38 HR, 112 RBI) and Luis Gonzalez (.336,
111 RBI). The Diamondbacks also discovered a good-hitting first
baseman in Erubiel Durazo (.329). But they begin this season
without their No. 1 run producer, Matt Williams (35 HR, 142 RBI),
whose foul ball broke a bone in his foot last week. He is expected
back in about six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On a pitching staff headed by Randy Johnson, the Cy Young award
winner, Omar Daal (16-9) may be ready to take his place in the
upper echelon of pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: Andy Benes.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: They can't afford any offensive falloff and have
to find a way to offset Matt Williams' absence.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO GIANTS
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Baker, eighth year 1999: 86-76, second
</P>
<P>
   Before the first pitch, the Giants are winners. They have sold a
franchise-record 28,000 season tickets for their first season at
Pacific Bell Park. Now they would like to entertain those fans with
a typical Dusty Baker team, that is, a team that does what it is
necessary to be in the division race.
</P>
<P>
   If they are to be in this race with the Diamondbacks, the Giants
have to find a way to make up 14 games. One way would be to have
Barry Bonds in their lineup every day. Bonds missed 60 games last
year with a series of injuries, playing the fewest games in his
14-year career. His .262 batting average was his lowest since 1989,
and his 83 RBI represented one of his lowest totals.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS: None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Livan Hernandez and Shawn Estes have to carry
their load of the pitching with Russ Ortiz (18-9) and Kirk Rueter
(15-10).
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES DODGERS
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson, second year 1999: 77-85, third
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to correct the disaster they suffered last season,
the Dodgers swapped right fielders, a disgruntled Raul Mondesi for
an expensive Shawn Green (six years, $84 million); brought back
Orel Hershiser, a star pitcher from their past; moved Mark
Grudzielanek from shortstop to second base and resurrected Kevin
Elster to play short.
</P>
<P>
   They have also restored Carlos Perez to the starting rotation,
in which he performed so abysmally last season (2-10, 7.43 earned
run average) that he was sent to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not a good omen that the Dodgers were looking for
Alex Cora to win the shortstop job and Eric Gagne the spot Perez
got in the rotation, and both failed.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Shawn Green.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Raul Mondesi, Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The pitching staff has to restore itself to the
Dodgers' customary level of respectability, and Green has to put
fire into the offense.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO ROCKIES
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Bell, first year 1999: 72-90, fifth
</P>
<P>
   The reputation of Dan O'Dowd, the rookie general manager, will
rise or fall on the success or failure of the Rockies. Deciding a
transformation was needed from a team heading in reverse, O'Dowd
shed some of the heavy hitters in favor of those he thought could
produce a more varied way of scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are Dante Bichette and Vinny Castilla, who in the past five
years combined for 344 home runs. In their place are Jeffrey
Hammonds and Jeff Cirillo.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dowd also set out to find pitchers who could throw strikes and
pitch more intelligently than some of their predecessors. Rolando
Arrojo, Masato Yoshii and Scott Karl are the subjects if this part
of the brave new experiment.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Jeff Cirillo, Jeffrey Hammonds, Tom Goodwin,
Rolando Arrojo, Scott Karl, Masato Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Vinny Castilla, Dante Bichette, Darryl Kile, Dave
Veres.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The danger that the off-season moves will leave
the Rockies short on runs and that the new pitchers won't fare any
better at hitter-friendly Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO PADRES
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy, sixth year 1999: 74-88, fourth
</P>
<P>
   The year has been embarrassing for the Padres; now it can get
bad.
</P>
<P>
   They traded for Albert Martin to play left field and lead off,
thinking they had themselves a solid citizen, and then he becomes
embroiled in a nasty dispute with a woman who contends he is a
bigamist. But can he serve as a catalyst for their offense?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more important to the offense is Ruben Rivera,
Mariano's cousin, who has to be better than his .195 performance
last season for the Padres to be respectable. A healthy Tony Gwynn
(.338 in 111 games) would also help raise the level of an offense
that was just about the league's weakest last year.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Ryan Klesko, Bret Boone, Albert Martin.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Wally Joyner, Quilvio Veras, Andy Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Their new park and the resulting revenue rise
cannot come fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
