<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LONGMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING RIGHT FOR WOMEN'S FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There is a growing movement to shift the women's
Final Four to a weekend separate from the men's Final Four, which
would be the worst decision since women were forced to play six
against six, and midcourt was a forbidden border crossing in the
gender wars.
</P>
<P>
   Those who run the women's game have treated the national
tournament like a Christmas gift bought early, hiding it so no one
can find it. Last weekend's West Regional in Portland, Ore.,
featured Rutgers playing two games that started no earlier than
midnight in the East, guaranteeing a television audience smaller
than the list of Indiana players who claim never to have been
choked or punched by Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Caretakers of the women's game claim to want more visibility,
but they do everything to make the tournament more invisible. They
are so afraid of competing head-to-head against other sporting
events, so insecure about their own product, that they are forever
willing to appease, to acquiesce, to retreat, to accept the label
of second-rate.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the Final Four would diminish, not enhance, the women's
tournament. Right now, the women get two days of marquee billing on
what everyone has come to relish as championship weekend. Shifting
the Final Four would most likely produce less media coverage, not
more. A week later, and the women would be overtaken by the Masters
and the start of baseball. A week or two or three earlier, and the
women would be lost in the clutter of men's conference tournaments
and regional play. Equating the women's championship with the early
rounds of the men's tournament would be the ``Wayne's World''
equivalent of Wayne and Garth bowing before Alice Cooper and
saying: ``We're not worthy, we're not worthy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is time for women to stop apologizing for their perceived
shortcomings and to start praising their assets: engaging
basketball, accessibility, high graduation rates. This women's
Final Four is infinitely more compelling than the men's Final Four,
which has a feeling of consolation and mediocrity. With the
exception of Michigan State, the men's field of Wisconsin, Florida
and North Carolina seemed less like a championship bracket than a
short list for the Poulan/Weed Eater Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the tournament's at the right time,'' said Theresa
Grentz of Illinois, the president of the Women's College Basketball
Coaches Association. ``Maybe the men's tournament should move. Why
should we move?''
</P>
<P>
   Geno Auriemma, the Connecticut coach, favors moving the women's
tournament, but he recognizes that the biggest hindrance to the
women's game comes not from without _ i.e., insufficient media
coverage _ but from within. If women's basketball is to be taken
more seriously by others, it must first be taken more seriously by
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a commitment at every school to be good in women's
basketball,'' Auriemma said. ``A lot of schools still have women's
programs just to comply with Title IX. There's really no emotional
investment of, `We want to be really good at it.' Most of it is,
`How many women do we need on scholarship? Good. Let's have it and
be done with it. What do we have to pay them? Good. Just keep them
out of our hair.'''
</P>
<P>
   Women's basketball should do what women's soccer did last
summer, not go on the run like fugitives, but stand up and demand
to be placed in the best arenas and to been seen by the widest
television audiences. It did nothing for basketball to place the
West Regional in Portland's decrepit Memorial Coliseum, whose floor
had more dead spots than Donald Trump's comb-over.
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer, figure skating, tennis and gymnastics do not
hide from their male counterparts, and neither should basketball.
What's to hide from? The men's game is shriveling from early
departures and academic fraud. Last year's men's tournament was the
lowest rated ever on CBS, while the women's championship game drew
the second-highest rating ever for a basketball game, male or
female, on ESPN. The problem with women's sports, said Julie Foudy,
the co-captain of the American soccer team, is that ``people are
afraid to take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's basketball should also quash another proposal to move
first- and second-round games of the tournament away from the
campuses of the higher-seeded teams and onto predetermined or
neutral courts.
</P>
<P>
   The fan base won't support it. And, at this stage of its growth,
the women's game doesn't need more upsets, it needs fewer. It
doesn't need parity, it needs dynasties like Tennessee and
Connecticut, just as the men's game needed UCLA's marvelous
domination.
</P>
<P>
   The women's Final Four has been sold out for eight consecutive
years. The interest is there for women's basketball; the interest
is there. The tournament doesn't need to be moved, it needs to be
promoted and celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
