A4170 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n BC-BIG-MURAL-LADN     04-01 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-MURAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTS HOPE TO RESTORE LONGEST MURAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By   DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The world's longest mural - a Los Angeles landmark
located in the suburban San Fernando Valley - is fading fast after
25 years of sun, rain and earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Dismayed by the city's neglect of this important artwork, the
artists who painted it over six summers starting in 1975 now are
launching an ambitious plan to restore the Great Wall of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And they want City Hall's help raising an estimated $500,000 to
restore the mural, add to it, and build viewing kiosks in the
adjacent walking park, making it more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Los Angeles can't recognize this important monument, then
maybe we should take it down instead of letting it decay,'' said
world-renowned artist Judith Baca, the brains behind the
half-mile-long mural that depicts Los Angeles history.
</P>
<P>
   Adolfo Nodal, general manager of the city Cultural Affairs
Department, said Los Angeles cannot be expected to pay for the
entire restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Wall is an important part of the city's identity,
and we agree that we can't lose it,'' Nodal said. ``It's a sound
investment to work with kids and produce long-term art. If Judy
says it's time to restore it, then we need to take that
initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Nodal said the mural program has been shortchanged in recent
years, the result of the mayor and council prioritizing other
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Copen, a spokeswoman for Mayor Richard Riordan, said the
city has not received a formal proposal to restore the mural, but
would be willing to consider funding.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, Baca's Social and Public Arts Resource
Center has even asked the county for Proposition A money to restore
the mural, but she said the proposal was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   SAVING ART, KIDS
</P>
<P>
   Restoring the mural would save more than just an important piece
of art.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 at-risk high school students from Watts to East
Los Angeles to the East Valley completed the mural in 1983 along
Coldwater Canyon Avenue in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   Now Baca wants to reach a new generation of artists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Bernardo Munoz and Richard Aguilar, two inner-city
school kids with loads of artistic inclination but little
opportunity, both worked on the mural in the summer during its
first stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the kids that got involved with this mural were at
the crossroads of getting into drugs and gangs,'' said Aguilar, now
a Los Angeles police officer who runs his own graphic arts
business. ``Judy and that mural changed our lives, it opened doors
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar, 43, has received awards from city, county and state
officials over the years for his work painting murals and giving
motivational talks to teen-agers at high schools around Los Angeles
County.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz, who also became a professional artist after a summer of
working on the mural as a teen-ager in the 1970s, says the program
experience helped many of the kids make a positive transition into
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the kids were like butterflies coming out of their
inner-city cocoons,'' said Munoz, who at 43 owns a successful
commercial art production company, Art, Sculpture and Production
Inc., that also does special effects for the movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go from graffiti to doing something that the community
respects and appreciates, that's incredible,'' Munoz said. ``It
takes two people to change, not just the person themselves, but
also support from the community.''
</P>
<P>
   A RAINBOW COMMUNITY'S MURAL
</P>
<P>
   The mural program was about much more than painting, says Baca,
it was about bringing together kids from the city's diverse
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be teaching convivial spirit and civic pride, not
zero tolerance,'' Baca said. ``Reaching out to these kids today
will make them civic leaders tomorrow instead of statistics of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for the program is especially timely, with approval by
state voters last month of Proposition 21, a
get-tough-on-juvenile-crime initiative the state estimates will
cost taxpayers some $1 billion next year and up to $500 million
annually for increased prosecution and incarceration of youthful
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the '70s, the muralists found an ally in Mayor Tom
Bradley, who rode into office on a coalition based on diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Baca said Bradley was a key force in lobbying for local and
state funds for city murals, but that City Hall has dropped the
ball on mural funding in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Riordan administration has a chance to save the mural,
Baca said. She hopes the city will make the funding a priority
during the upcoming budget process, which runs from April through
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spent $1 million last year on millennium celebrations
that flopped,'' she said. ``Here, we're talking about a permanent
piece of art that directly improves the lives of the artists and
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Mike Feuer, chairman of the Budget and Finance
Committee, said the city should not allow the mural to fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would definitely be a good project to restore the mural,''
he said. ``These are the kinds of projects that give us a sense of
community.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
