<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4171 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MILITARY-WOMEN-REVIEW     04-01 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-WOMEN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE U.S. ARMED FORCES SOFTEN THEIR TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every few weeks, it seems, women in the U.S.
military smash through another glass ceiling. In December 1998,
female pilots flew into combat against Iraq for the first time from
the deck of an aircraft carrier. This week, in another first, a
woman is commanding a warship on its way to a combat zone in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   For the Pentagon, these milestones _ and the relative
nonchalance that accompany them _ are unequivocal signs of the
progress made over the last decade in improving the standing of
women in the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   Are they really?
</P>
<P>
   A provocative new book, ``The Kinder, Gentler Military''
(Scribner), challenges the sanguine image the Pentagon would like
to convey of equality in the military's increasing co-ed ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The author, Stephanie Gutmann, accuses the Pentagon's civilian
and military leaders of dangerously eroding U.S. militaty power in
a politically correct pursuit to expand women's opportunities. She
even suggests that the forced integration of men and women has
contributed to some of the sexual scandals that have buffeted the
services in recent years. Just last week, it was revealed that the
Army's highest-ranking woman, Lt. Gen. Claudia J. Kennedy, one of
only three three-star officers in the military, had filed a sexual
harassment complaint against another Army general, accusing him of
groping her in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gutmann, a journalist who often writes about sexual politics,
argues that what sounds great in theory _ equality _ fails when put
into practice in the unique world of military service. The efforts
Pentagon brass have made to integrate women have backfired, she
asserts, causing an erosion of standards and a weakening of the
overtly testosterone-laced mentality she and others believe is
essential to the act of killing other human beings in combat.
</P>
<P>
   To support her thesis, Gutmann dissects the Pentagon's policies
and exposes some of the more extreme efforts to weed out sexist
language or discriminatory practices. At the Army's boot camp for
men and women in Ft. Jackson, S.C., female recruits no longer have
to throw a hand grenade far enough to keep from killing themselves,
and they are allowed to run more slowly in ``ability groups''
rather than keep up with the pack. For a time, young women (and
men) at the Great Lakes Naval Training Center could hold up blue
cards when the stress of training became too much.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the women not driven to physical and mental
extremes, Gutmann contends, but the men are inevitably pushed less
as a result, leaving them unprepared for combat.
</P>
<P>
   Has the military really lowered its standards to accommodate
women? In short, yes, but the full answer is far more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Men headed into Army and Marine ground combat units, which
exclude women, still train at places like Fort Benning, Ga., and
Parris Island, S.C., without the distractions that Gutmann derides.
</P>
<P>
   At other bases, Pentagon officials acknowledge that the rigors
of boot camp are not what they once were, in part out of concern
that the physical stress is more punishing on women's bodies. ``The
presence of women causes us to ask why we do some things,'' said
Richard Danzig, the secretary of the Navy. That has meant changing
everything from the number of situps to the designs of ships.
</P>
<P>
   But he and other leaders also point out that the nature of
military service and warfare has changed. The Air Force, the most
technically focused service, has been putting male and female
enlistees through basic training together at Lackland Air Force
Base in San Antonio, Texas, for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   As technology has advanced, brute force has become less and less
a priority. In these days of cruise-missile strikes and long-range
bombing, the distinctions between what men and women are asked to
do is blurring. Women can fly any Air Force or Navy warplane that
men do. During NATO's bombing in Kosovo, women flew combat raids
over Serbia while the overwhelmingly male ground combat forces sat
out the campaign in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``The muscle we use in combat today is between our ears,'' said
Capt. Barbara L. Brehm of the Navy, the military director of the
Defense Advisory Committee on Women in the Services.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, though, some experts have warned that the
military is growing dangerously out of touch with society's values.
Others have argued that the Pentagon's warrior culture remains
hostile to women, as well as to gays, even as these groups make
strides in civilian society.
</P>
<P>
   Women in uniform say they have long had to endure unwanted
sexual attention, but for a woman of Gen. Kennedy's rank to have
filed a formal complaint suggests that the Pentagon still has a
long way to go to create a comfortable climate for the nearly
200,000 women in the armed services, who make up 14 percent of the
military.
</P>
<P>
   To Gutmann and many in uniform, however, there should be limits
to society's influence on the armed forces. After all, they argue,
the military has the unique responsibility to train people to fight
and die in war. Gutmann's basic question is whether the nation
really wants its fighting forces to look like the rest of
couch-potato America. ``Why shouldn't the military be like the
monastery on the hill?'' she asked in an interview. ``Why shouldn't
it be the institution that is part of us, but still different?''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there is one thing people on both sides of the
argument agree on. And it was best expressed by none other than
Gen. Kennedy, whom Gutmann quotes in her book. ``This is not your
father's Army anymore,'' the general told cadets at West Point a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
