<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      04-01 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, April 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT (Mbarara, Uganda) _ To the believers, the world was
to extinguish at the year 2000, so last December was a time for
forgiveness and, more practically, last-minute recruitment for the
world to come. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BLUEPRINT (Moscow) _ The victory of Vladimir Putin in
last Sunday's presidential elections has focused attention on an
opulent Moscow building known as Alexander House, where a team of
liberal-minded economists and other experts have been quietly
drafting Putin's blueprint for Russia. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   SERBIA-MONTENEGRO (Podgorica, Yugoslavia) _ For the last month,
in an eerie echo of tactics adopted by the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, against Slovenia and other republics that broke
away from Belgrade in the early 1990s, Serbian authorities have
imposed a strict trade ban on goods passing between Montenegro and
Serbia. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Lima, Peru) _ To those outside the Fujimori
administration, President Alberto Fujimori's intelligence chief,
Vladimiro Montesinos, is known as the Rasputin of Peru's politics.
His power in large part derives from his intimate knowledge of the
president's deepest personal secrets. Now, Montesinos is accused by
opponents of running a campaign of dirty tricks intended to assure
Fujimori's re-election on April 9, and Montesinos himself has
become a top issue in the race. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MOB (Kobe, Japan) _ The authorities say that a besieged
Japanese yakuza, or mob, is now feeling the pinch of a weak economy
and an aggressive crackdown by police and community groups. This
accumulated threat to the mob's bread-and-butter businesses _
gambling, the sex trade, drug trafficking, protection rackets _ has
sparked a bitter and often violent struggle among rival gangs for
control of shrinking criminal enterprises. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ A broad look at U.S.-China policy. By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSENT (Beijing) _ The widow of Edgar Snow, the American
journalist who was celebrated here as a ``friend of China'' for his
sympathetic portraits of the communist revolution, was prevented by
police Saturday from meeting a prominent critic of the 1989 army
crackdown on student democracy demonstrators. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE-TRADE (Washington) _ As many as 50,000 women and children
from Asia, Latin America and Eastern Europe are brought to the
United States under false pretenses each year and forced to work as
prostitutes, abused laborers or servants, according to a Central
Intelligence Agency report that is the government's first
comprehensive assessment of the problem. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   ACHING-HEARTLAND (Tryon, Neb.) _ While most of the American
economy is going gangbusters, many rural areas are undergoing a
wrenching restructuring that is impoverishing small ranchers and
farmers, depopulating large chunks of rural America and changing
the way Americans get their food. The gains in farming and ranching
efficiency are staggering, but so too is the blow to the rural way
of life. A special report. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (Sarita, Texas) _ After government vehicles ran
over and injured illegal immigrants on a vast cattle ranch here
twice in the past month, the ranch's owners notified the U.S.
Border Patrol that its agents could no longer pursue their quarry
on ranch property. The John G. and Marie Stella Kenedy Memorial
Foundation, which owns the Kenedy Ranch, made its decision because
it believes that the Border Patrol has been violating immigrants'
human rights. By Ross E. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GAS-PRICES (Los Angeles) _ Gas prices may have risen
across the nation in recent months, as a tight oil supply has
driven up the cost of crude oil. But nowhere in the country are the
increases more astounding than in California. By Christian
Berthelsen.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-IRS (Washington) _ Republicans in the House proposed
legislation Saturday to help taxpayers in their dealings with the
Internal Revenue Service, and called for hearings this month on
developing an entirely new tax system. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   LENDER-CRACKDOWN (Undated) _ After several years of inaction,
pressure is building in Washington to impose tighter rules on banks
and finance companies that specialize in lending money to
homeowners with blemished credit records. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   TIME-CAPSULE (South Hadley, Mass.) _ Over the century, the box
sat quietly in the Mount Holyoke College library, then in the
comptroller's office, then on a shelf in the school archives, and
finally on the dorm room floor of Sara Hines, president of the
class of 2000. Hines had little idea what was in the oak cube,
which measured a little more than a foot on each side. A plaque on
its top described it is as a legacy from the class of 1900 to their
sisters in the class of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Developments in the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHT-CHILDCARE (New York) _ In recent years _ particularly
after the 1996 welfare overhaul sent millions of parents into the
work force, many on shifts at odd hours _ dozens of cities and
states have taken steps to supply working parents with
round-the-clock child care. But New York City, perhaps the most
aggressive in the nation in reducing the welfare rolls and putting
people to work for their benefits, has until recently not been part
of the movement toward publicly financed, flexible-hour child care.
By Sarah Kershaw.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-MONEY (Undated) _ George Gorton had not thought much about
Section 527 of the Internal Revenue Code _ at least not until last
year. That was when Gorton started Shape the Debate, a nonprofit
political organization that, under Section 527, can raise and spend
unlimited amounts of money, with no disclosure requirements for
donors, as long as it does not expressly advocate the election or
defeat of any candidate. The group is among the latest entrants in
a growing field of independent campaign expenditure efforts,
spurred on by recent court rulings interpreting the tax law. By
Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Pennsylvania race sputters to a
close; A Bush loyalist in McCain country; Nader keeps running a bit
like a Corvair. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
