<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-RIVERA-ART-2TAKES     04-01 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RIVERA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL 2000: RIVERA LEADS IN BROKEN BATS AND HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 16 of 3/30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like an adoring mother, Boston right fielder Troy O'Leary
cherishes his favorite Louisville Slugger bats. Model P72, all
black. He owes his professional life to them and treats them well,
protects them. He would never subject them to a terrible fate _ an
awkward collision with the fastball of Yankees closer Mariano
Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary does not want his favorite bats splintered and dispersed
in pieces all over the infield. So he leaves them in the bat rack,
instead using his second-string bats when he faces Rivera, whose
cut fastball _ the name by which it is known _ is considered by
many in baseball as the most devastating pitch in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Ryan Klesko, the slugger who faced Rivera in the last inning
of the last game of last year's World Series. Three times, Klesko
was left holding nothing but a broken bat handle, having shattered
two bats fouling off Rivera's cutter before splitting a third as he
grounded out. Some of his Atlanta teammates, moments away from
losing the World Series, covered their faces to hide or stifle
their laughs, having found comic relief in Klesko's futility
against Rivera's cutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you expect?'' Klesko said recently. ``The guy throws
97-mile-an-hour cutters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best pitch in baseball,'' said Darrin Fletcher,
Toronto's All-Star catcher. ``To face his cut fastball is the
toughest assignment in baseball to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thome, Cleveland's slugger, said: ``If you had to pick one
guy with devastating stuff, it's him, because of that pitch. It's
obvious they've won the world championships they have because of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   When a representative from Louisville Slugger arrived at the
Yankee camp this spring, second baseman Chuck Knoblauch suggested
that Rivera deserved a contract with the company. After all,
Knoblauch postulated, Rivera has single-handedly increased the
demand for bats by breaking so many.
</P>
<P>
   Other great pitchers throw great pitches. Pedro Martinez, the
Boston ace, throws three exceptional pitches, his fastball,
changeup and curveball. Arizona's Randy Johnson throws hard and has
a sweeping slider. Kevin Brown of the Dodgers has a vicious,
hard-sinking fastball.
</P>
<P>
   But the effectiveness of Martinez's changeup and curveball is
helped because hitters must anticipate his fastball, and similarly,
batters often flail at Johnson's slider because they assume he will
throw a fastball. Rivera essentially throws just one pitch, a
four-seam fastball he can manipulate expertly _ particularly
against left-handed batters _ and he dominates with that one pitch.
Batters know Rivera is going to throw his cutter; he might as well
announce it to the world. They still cannot hit it. ``The ball just
explodes on you,'' said Carlos Delgado, Toronto's star first
baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera is a bane to all batters. He didn't allow a run after
July 21 of last season, and carries a streak of 30 and two-thirds
scoreless innings into this year. According to Steve Hirdt of the
Elias Sports Bureau, he and Houston's Billy Wagner were the only
pitchers who held opponents to an on-base percentage and slugging
percentage of under .250. (Opponents had an on-base percentage of
.239 and a slugging percentage of .237 against Rivera.)
</P>
<P>
   But he is especially effective against left-handed batters,
unusual because Rivera is right-handed. Last year, left-handed
batters in the American League averaged one extra-base hit for
every 10.8 at-bats. Against Rivera, left-handed batters had two
extra-base hits _ one double and one home run, the latter hit by
Detroit's Bobby Higginson _ in 140 at-bats, or one every 70
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera fared well in his first three years in the majors, but
late in the 1997 season, he began toying with the grip on his
four-seam fastball. ``I just grabbed the ball one day and started
playing with it,'' Rivera recalled.
</P>
<P>
   By cocking his wrist slightly _ almost imperceptibly _ and
applying pressure on the ball with his fingers, he caused the pitch
to veer sharply to his left, away from right-handed batters and
toward left-handed batters. And he started breaking bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had a good fastball,'' Delgado said, ``but once he
had that, he became tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for left-handed batters is that it is virtually
impossible for them to identify the pitch, either through the spin
or some quirky giveaway in Rivera's delivery. He uses the bodies of
the hitters in establishing his target, and throws the ball about
thigh high and over the inner third of the plate _ down and in,
``where most left-handed hitters like the ball,'' Fletcher said.
</P>
<P>
   And then it breaks, the pitch too hard and the movement too
dramatic for the hitter to stop his swing, and the ball attacks
their bat handles, as if it has a radar lock on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just keeps following you,'' Fletcher said. ``It just keeps
coming at you. You think it's over the inner half of the plate, and
it comes after you. We have this saying that a pitcher `gets in
your kitchen.' Rivera's cutter continually gets in your kitchen,
and you cannot get it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome said, ``It's out of his hand and looks like a regular
fastball, over the plate, and boom, it's on your knuckles.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no official statistics for broken bats, but he
probably averages between one and two per appearance. The Yankees'
fielders have adapted to Rivera's dominance of left-handers. When
there is a matchup of a right-handed pitcher and a left-handed
batter, the fielders normally shift a couple of steps toward the
right-field foul line, owing to the tendency of the batter to pull
the ball, and those fielders on the right side _ the first baseman,
second baseman and right fielder _ will move back a couple of
steps.
</P>
<P>
   But Rivera overpowers left-handers to the degree that Tino
Martinez, the first baseman, will move in because the swing of a
left-handed batter so often results in an exploding, disintegrating
bat and a dribbling ground ball. Ricky Ledee, the left fielder,
shifts in dramatically toward the infield, in the way he might
position himself if a pitcher were batting for the other team.
``They don't hit the ball hard very often,'' Ledee said with a
smile and shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing hitters uniformly mention Rivera's easy, gliding
pitching motion as a significant factor in his dominance. Rivera
begins his delivery by drawing up his leg deliberately, that big,
slow leg kick, before he starts his arm motion and _ pow! There is
the deception, like a timid-looking data entry clerk who turns out
to be spy.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera ``almost kind of lulls you to sleep with his delivery,''
Fletcher said. ``It gives you a false sense of security, and then
the ball is on you and it's exploding.''
</P>
<P>
   The leisurely delivery masks all that is happening as Rivera
throws the baseball. He is relatively frail, by today's major
league standards, with an undeveloped torso, spaghetti arms and a
thin neck. But he has the legs of a sprinter _ when the Yankees'
pitchers run for conditioning early in spring training, they gasp
and gripe about how easy the exercise comes to Rivera _ and his
legs serve him well in his delivery, his left leg leading him, his
right leg driving his body toward the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera draws his arm back and throws, but David Cone, Andy
Pettitte and others believe that Rivera's greatness stems from what
happens right at the end of his delivery: his hand extends far out
in front of him and his wrist snaps and the ball is released, like
a buggy whip.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I call him Inspector Gadget,'' Cone said. ``It's
like his arm has an extra extension that pops out of his shoulder.
He gets lots of extension, and there is that great wrist action;
his wrist is like a blur at the end of the pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To throw a fastball, a pitcher must keep his arm, wrist and
fingers essentially in line, to propel the ball at its center, in
the same way a pool stick is used to strike the cue ball for
maximum velocity at the start of the game. To throw a breaking
ball, a curveball or slider or forkball, pitchers basically grip a
part of the ball, to create an unusual spin _ in the way you would
strike a pool ball on its edges to make it veer _ but the velocity
is decreased dramatically. Increased movement, decreased velocity.
</P>
<P>
   This is what distinguishes Rivera's cut fastball: It has
incredible velocity, 93 to 96 miles an hour, but also incredible
movement, darting and diving as much as a foot by the time it
reaches the plate, according to Yankee catcher Jorge Posada. ``It
moves in on you so late,'' Thome said. ``It's hard to make an
adjustment on him. And this game is all about adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many options for hitters. Sometimes they will move
toward the front of the batter's box, toward the pitcher, against
someone with dramatic late movement in a particular pitch. But
Rivera throws too hard to do that; the hitter, already left with
precious little reaction time, won't move closer to Rivera.
``Moving up in the box sounds great in theory,'' Yankee shortstop
Derek Jeter said, ``but if you're standing there, you couldn't talk
yourself into doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Batters might try to take a pitch or two, try to get ahead in
the count and force Rivera to throw a regular four-seam fastball
over the middle of the plate. But Rivera's control is impeccable.
He has refined his mastery of the pitch, Cone said, and knows how
to control the movement. Rivera went more than 14 months, for
example, without walking the first batter he faced upon entering a
game. ``He throws enough strikes so that you have to be
aggressive,'' Thome said.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher smiled in a self-deprecating way when he revealed his
own approach. ``The best way, like I've told myself every year, is
to try to make sure the ball is in the outer half of the strike
zone, and if it's not, then take it and take a walk,'' Fletcher
said.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to hit Rivera, then, might be to draw a walk. Some
other hitters mentioned O'Leary's approach as unique. He appeared
to step into the pitch as he batted against Rivera in the playoffs
last year, and he had a single and a double in two at-bats. But
when O'Leary was told that other players noted his method of
attacking Rivera, O'Leary was taken aback. He wasn't trying to do
anything special, he said. He usually gets his feet moving in every
at-bat. What he does against Rivera is battle, and save his best
bats.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's cut fastball is not technically a cut fastball, at
least not as it is usually thrown. Pitchers throw cutters with a
different grip, a different motion. ``It's just a four-seam
fastball with unbelievable movement,'' said Mel Stottlemyre, the
Yankees' pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre is persuaded that the size of Rivera's hands and
fingers _ not unusually large or small _ are somehow perfectly
suited to create the break on the ball. It might be his wrist
action, his arm extension. Robert Adair, a professor of physics at
Yale University and a baseball expert, quoted another physicist:
``There are two problems I really don't understand: What is the
fundamental theory of a universe, and the other is why a curveball
curves. In my lifetime, I can see my way to understanding the
first, but not the second.''
</P>
<P>
   Adair went on to offer a simplified explanation: air resistance
affects the movement, so that if the ball is thrown twice as fast,
the air resistance will be four times greater. And if a ball is
thrown 95 miles an hour, Adair said, the hitter must decide so
quickly whether to swing or not that ``their eyes might as well be
closed'' in the last 30 feet of its journey homeward.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Stanton, a Yankee reliever, has a more elementary
theory: ``It's a gift from God,'' he said, ``and he's a freak.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
