<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-FREEAGENCY-ART-1     04-01 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FREEAGENCY-ART-1,035(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL 2000: WHO WANTS TO BE A MULTIMILLIONAIRE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 19 of 3/30 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thinking about it even six months ago, Alex Rodriguez figured
that Ken Griffey Jr. would open the 2000 season in Seattle and that
he would begin it somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I'd be the guy to go, and he would stay
because he was a franchise guy,'' Rodriguez said as he prepared for
what promises to be a tumultuous season for him, Griffey and other
members of the game's elite corps.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, as it turned out, had the locations reversed. He will
be in Seattle for the Mariners' opener Tuesday and Griffey will be
elsewhere _ in Cincinnati Monday afternoon playing center field for
the Reds, who were the only team he wanted to go to once the
Mariners decided they had to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Before signing a discounted deal with the Reds, Griffey had been
eligible to be a free agent at the end of the 2000 season, just as
Rodriguez is. So are Juan Gonzalez and Mike Hampton, who were
traded, and Manny Ramirez, Chipper Jones, Mike Mussina, Brad Radke,
John Wetteland and Robb Nen, who were not. Like Griffey, Shawn
Green was traded and signed a new contract, forgoing his chance to
be a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Griffey and Green, the 2000 class of free agents
promises to be special. Not since the advent of eight-figure
salaries and nine-figure contracts has there been such a glittering
group of players who could make an impact on division races because
of their status as potential free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Their impending availability even made an impact on this past
winter's free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were looking ahead to next year's free-agent list,''
Doug Melvin, the Texas general manager, said, ``and didn't want to
overspend on this year's list when they thought they would have a
chance at next year's list.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, Gonzalez, Hampton and Green were traded because their
clubs determined they would not be able to sign them to contract
extensions. Those players, in effect, became advance free agents,
given a chance to secure a lucrative contract a year early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember this many guys being traded ahead of time the
way they were,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers have tried to sign Gonzalez, offering him
$140 million for eight years, and the Mets talked with Hampton's
agent about a new contract. But neither has signed. Griffey signed
with the Reds and Green with Los Angeles because those were the
cities where they wanted to play.
</P>
<P>
   Of the others in the group, some have been offered contracts,
some not. Some could sign with their teams and not become free
agents, some could remain unsigned and become free agents, some
could be traded during the season if their teams decide they don't
want to lose them and get nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever they go, wherever they stay, at least some will have an
impact on the outcome of the races.
</P>
<P>
   With Griffey, the Mariners would be favored to finish first in
their division; without him, they may still win but not as handily.
The Reds, on the other hand, have been tagged generally as the team
most likely to win their division.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will miss Gonzalez's booming bat and, by extension,
the playoffs. The Tigers think he gives them a chance for
postseason play, but that thought might represent wishful thinking.
The Dodgers believe Green's left-handed hitting will make a big
difference in their season, but that difference won't necessarily
translate into extra October games.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton gives the Mets the legitimate No. 1 starting pitcher
they lacked. Some people think his presence puts the Mets in
position to topple the Atlanta Braves from their perennial
first-place perch. At the same time, Hampton's departure from
Houston leaves a huge void in the Astros' rotation and is expected
to help end their three-year reign as division champions.
</P>
<P>
   Of the potential free agents who remain with their teams,
Baltimore won't be trading Mussina because his contract gives him
the right to veto a trade, and Cleveland won't very likely trade
Ramirez or Atlanta Jones because they are players crucial to the
teams' postseason plans. Rodriguez is certainly that with the
Mariners, who have said they will not trade the power-hitting
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have offered to make Rodriguez wealthy, inviting
him last year to sign an eight-year, $128 million contract. Some
people have speculated, however, that Scott Boras, his agent, will
try to make him the first player to get a $200 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an attractive thing to me,'' Rodriguez said when
asked about being the highest-paid player in history. ``I do
realize as a union member I have a responsibility to try to get
whatever the market value is and then go from there because I feel
I'm one of the leaders in this venue of where we're going. It
affects other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York native actually seemed to find the stratosphere
that salaries have reached repulsive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sick,'' he said, talking about the money. ``I fear a
little bit for the fan. Where's the fan in all of this? Baseball
has some problems that have to be addressed soon. We can't let it
get out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who last season hit 42 home runs in only 502 times at
bat, or one every 12 at-bats, was adamant about leaving his future
for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he said, ``I want to play in Seattle. I'm
focusing on this ball club. When the year is over, I'll give that a
lot more thought.''
</P>
<P>
   How far the Mariners go this year could influence his thinking,
Rodriguez said, but then he added: ``You may have one chance in
your life to be a free agent. I want to really make a smart
decision. I want to talk it over with my mom, my brothers and my
sister and my counselor and then make a wise decision. I don't want
to rush the biggest decision of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm a little bit nervous. I've never been down this
road before. So I'm kind of going into a dark tunnel of
expectations. I don't know what I'm doing. It's not like I'm
sitting here and being a cool guy. This might come back and slap me
in the face. That's the chance I'm going to take.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With Rodriguez, Gonzalez, Ramirez and Jones free agents at the
same time, along with some other highly rated players, baseball's
capacity to find homes for all of them may be tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably more free agents than there are teams who
could sign these guys,'' the Rangers' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   But then no one ever thought the Reds would sign Griffey, even
if they did get a ``discount'' at $116.5 million for nine years.
The Mariners had offered Griffey $138 million for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect I don't really think it was a situation where
they picked me over him,'' Rodriguez said. ``I think it was more
like he wanted to go back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Lincoln, the Mariners' new chairman and chief executive
officer, let the players know, Rodriguez said, that if they didn't
want to be in Seattle, the Mariners didn't want them to be there.
How does that policy apply to him?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't, because I want to be here,'' Rodriguez said. ``I
want to give it a chance. I signed a four-year deal, not a
seven-year deal, and I want to honor that. I had an option to sign
a seven-year deal, but I didn't want to do that. I want to finish
what I start. I want to go quietly about it. Contrary to what
people believe, I'm very happy with what I've got. I'm one of the
best-paid 24-year-olds around.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had played in the major leagues less than two years
when he signed a four-year, $10.6 million contract in July 1996.
Five months earlier Griffey, with seven years in the majors, agreed
to a four-year, $34 million contract. Not that money had anything
to do with it, but Griffey and Rodriguez were not the best buddies
some people assumed they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was the new kid on the block; he was a star,''
Rodriguez said of their relationship. ``It was never where we'd
take off together, visit each other in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, it got much better with time because we both gained a lot
of respect for each other. We were like brothers. Brothers are
always on each other, kind of jiving each other back and forth.
There was an unbelievable amount of respect from both sides. I
think it was mutual. But as we got playing with each other longer,
we both realized we cared about each other's careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Griffey is gone and Rodriguez reigns as the No. 1 player in
the Mariners' domain, at least for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a guy who needs people to say he's the man,'' he said.
``I've felt to a degree I've been a leader on this ball club. I
just go about it in a little different way. I'm not real vocal
about anything. I don't raise the flag and tell everybody I'm a
leader. I'm not that type of guy. If the question is would I rather
play with Grif or without him, I'd rather play with him.
Absolutely. It's not like I'm here throwing a party because he's
gone. That couldn't be further from the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   What is true is Rodriguez's envy of his good friend, Derek
Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he said when asked if he was envious of Jeter's three
World Series rings. ``I would like to win the World Series. I would
love to be in that situation where I'm winning. That's what the
game is all about. Whether he has more home runs than me or he's a
better hitter than me and a better defender, I'm not jealous of
that. But the rings, that's what we play for.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-TORRE-ART-NYT &LR;      04-01 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TORRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL 2000: A SPECIAL SISTER IS PROUD OF HER SPECIAL BROTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 17 of 3/30 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   She didn't want to visit Tampa for spring training. She doesn't
like packing for a trip, driving to the airport or squeezing into a
seat on a cramped plane. She wasn't going to go. But Joe calmly
asked her to reconsider. Visit us, it will relax you, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe made it sound so comforting, so appropriate, so she did it.
She went to Florida. He was right. It was serene. She stayed home
most of the time with Joe's wife, Ali, and their 4-year-old
daughter, Andrea. They ate together after Joe returned from the
ballpark, they rented movies, they talked about everything and
nothing. It was a soothing brand of fun.
</P>
<P>
   She watched her little brother come home with a Barbie dollhouse
one day, patiently put the massive pink structure together and
casually crawl inside it with Andrea. When Andrea invited her to
play in it, too, she told Andrea that she couldn't get down on the
floor because she might never get up again.
</P>
<P>
   She is Sister Marguerite Torre, 69, and Joe is Joe Torre. She is
the principal of Nativity of the Blessed Virgin Mary School in
Queens, N.Y., watching over 400 students. He is the manager of the
Yankees, watching over 25 players. She prays for him and prays with
him, always an older sister looking out for her younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I worry about him,'' she said. ``He's our baby.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been exhilarating for her to watch Joe, who she felt was
unfairly tagged as a lovable loser, manage the Yankees to three
World Series titles in the past four years. She has watched him
succeed through the death of a brother in 1996, through the heart
transplant of another brother five months later and through his own
ordeal with prostate cancer last year. When Sister Marguerite was
asked about the confluence of emotions, she spoke about Joe for
five minutes and barely stopped for a breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really found himself,'' she said. ``He feels good, he's
so happy and he's such a caring person. He really is a special
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people look at Torre and see a quiet, confident manager. He
is the man who has drastically changed the perception of his
career, who has figured out how to coexist with the Yankees'
principal owner, George Steinbrenner, and who will try to lead the
team to its third straight championship. Most people see Joe and
see a winner now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the perfect manager,'' Yankee shortstop Derek Jeter said.
``I think if someone gave me a notepad and asked me to draw up the
perfect manager, he'd be the one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Marguerite looks at Joe and, occasionally, she still sees
a little boy. She still sees Joe as a mischievous kid trying to
emulate Rocco and Frank, his brothers. She gave Joe his first
expensive glove when he was 11 years old. She thought about giving
him rosary beads instead, but she gave him the glove and told him
to say one ``Our Father'' every time he slipped it on.
</P>
<P>
   But, beyond the boy, she also sees a 59-year-old man who has
matured. She sees patience and peacefulness that didn't always
exist, not when Joe was trudging through two unsuccessful
marriages. Sister Marguerite, along with her sister, Rae, looks at
Joe and marvels at the way he has endured and triumphed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a terrific amount of satisfaction about what's happened
and what he's done,'' she said after returning from her weeklong
trip to Tampa. ``Not only what he's done for the Yankees, but what
he's done for New York. He's a great role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe calls whenever he has something important to tell her, even
if it is 2:30 in the morning. The phone in the convent will ring
three times and, if she doesn't answer, he will call again in a few
hours. He won't leave a message. Joe called 13 months ago, didn't
even warn her and blurted out that he had prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not possible,'' she said. ``There's no cancer in our
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe firmly said, ``There is now.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day Joe called and for months afterward, she was numb.
She doesn't know how he stayed so strong through the surgery and
the treatment, but it has a lot to do with Ali, and, of course,
Andrea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful,'' Sister Marguerite said. ``It was a nightmare.
I had an inner lump that I didn't think would ever go away. I just
hope he's better now and it doesn't come back.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not like to talk much about the cancer, she said. He
will answer one or two questions about his health, but it is not
something he wants to elaborate on so she does not pry. She is
amazed about his rigid diet. They went to a fancy Italian
restaurant and he ate spinach. He passed her his plate. He always
does that. She took a bite and it was so bland. There was no
seasoning, but he didn't mind. He doesn't complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people say, `Your poor family' to me,'' she said.
``But we're no different than anyone. We're a typical family. This
happens. This is what life is all about. Joe says that, too. Why
should we be any different?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. A family in Sister Marguerite's parish has an 8-year-old
with cancer. Why should the Torres be any different? Why should
they be absolved from pain and suffering?
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully, though, Joe is different for other reasons. He used
to be a regular Joe, a superb player but a manager with a record
under .500. Now fans feel as if the manager were their Uncle Joe,
an uncle with a golden touch, and Sister Marguerite loves it. When
someone writes to her about Joe, she always responds and includes
an autographed picture. Not a prepackaged 8-by-10, but family
pictures that she compels Joe to sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have such an admiration for him,'' she said. ``I've had
some people tell me they love him, people who don't even know
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe told her during spring training that Andrea's walk is like
hers, but she has a secret for him. When Sister Marguerite walks
across the schoolyard, the students snicker and tell her that she
looks like Joe walking to the mound to change pitchers. So, if
Andrea walks way she does, it's because Joe walks that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   Joe actually got Sister Marguerite to walk regularly in Tampa,
telling her that she would be healthier if she walked 30 minutes a
day. Again, Joe was right. She walked so often that she developed a
heel spur. Joe offered to send an exercise bicycle, but Sister
Marguerite has one and dislikes it, so she will resume walking when
her foot heals and the weather gets warmer.
</P>
<P>
   That will be soon. It is April, time for another baseball
season. She wants Joe to visit her elementary school again this
year. Joe persuaded her to visit Florida, so now Sister Marguerite
wants him to visit her students in Queens before he decides that he
no longer wants to manage the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't ever imagine what he will be like without baseball,''
she said. ``He's a perennial boy of summer. He comes to life with
it. It's a fulfillment. It's part of what he needs to be a person.
He's like a big kid.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
