<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-EXPOS-NYT &LR;      04-01 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL 2000: WITH A LITTLE EXTRA MONEY, THE EXPOS PONDER A
TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ A young man walked over to another man who was
sitting at a table, leaned over and embraced him, placing the side
of his face against the older man's back for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   The young man was Michael Barrett, the Montreal Expos' third
baseman. The man he hugged with obvious sincerity was his boss,
Jeffrey Loria, the Expos' new managing partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't rehearsed,'' Loria quickly said to a reporter as
they sat at the table outside the team's spring training clubhouse.
But the embrace was yet another sign that times have surely changed
with the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat in the sunshine before a recent exhibition game, Loria
was in the shadow of another sign, a row of 10 silver flagpoles
topped by flags that celebrated the native countries of the players
on the team's roster _ the United States, Canada, Japan, Australia,
the rest Latin American contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my gesture,'' Loria said. ``My way of saying we're all in
this together this year as family.''
</P>
<P>
   And there were the T-shirts the players wore under their
uniforms, the ones that sent an eloquent message in Japanese,
French, Spanish and English: ``Why not us?'' on the front, ``Why
not now?'' on the back.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in years, there is life in the Expos' midst.
Players go about their business with smiles on their faces,
determination in their hearts and belief in their minds. Why not
them? Why not now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was a very successful businessman,'' Felipe Alou,
the team's patient and loyal manager, said of the international art
dealer from New York. ``When he took over this club, I believed if
he led this club the way he did his business, this was going to be
a successful time. That was my impression. And so far so good. I
know that the feeling I'm expressing now is unanimous with the
players and the staff. He means business. The ultimate goal is to
win as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   When in his eight-year tenure with the Expos had Alou had that
feeling? ``Never,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since payrolls began escalating exponentially, the Expos
have been the epitome of a low-revenue club. Their $15 million
payroll was lowest in the major leagues last year, but four months
after Loria became chairman and chief executive officer, the
payroll has virtually doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the driving force behind it all,'' said Jim Beattie,
in his fifth year as the team's general manager. ``He's taking the
payroll to a point where you can acquire some players. You can take
a look at some of the avenues that we've not looked at in the past,
like free agency, and acquire in a few trades players that make a
couple million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos have picked up first baseman Lee Stevens and pitcher
Hideki Irabu in trades. They signed Graeme Lloyd, a left-handed
relief specialist, as a free agent, luring him north for $9 million
over three years, a package uncharacteristic of the Expos that
prompted looks of disbelief from other clubs. But the Lloyd
signing, which took place 11 days after Loria assumed command of
the club, was a deliberate message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a surprise to me that I would come to Montreal,'' the
Australian reliever said. ``I wasn't expecting to come here in my
free agency year. I had 9 or 10 teams looking at me. It came down
to the owner bringing me down here, telling me about what has in
line for the future for baseball in Montreal. He really changed my
mind about how the team used to be, where once you got to
arbitration they'd lose their best players. I feel they have a
strong nucleus that has a chance to win. He really changed my mind
in that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire environment has changed. ``I've talked to all the
guys here,'' Lloyd said. ``In the past few years, it's been let's
go out there and develop. Now it's let's go out there and win.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York native, the 59-year-old Loria is trying to salvage
the Expos for Montreal by producing a winning team that will bring
fans back to the ballpark, a new ballpark, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put a lot of pieces together,'' Loria said,
speaking of the effort to get financing for a new park. ``It will
be resolved in the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Life for the Expos, however, is not easy in Montreal. Besides
fighting to get a new place to play, Loria has been unable to
negotiate television and radio deals for the rights to the team's
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give away the product, and I don't want to pay
for the right to be on the air,'' Loria said. ``It should be the
reverse. It's very difficult when a broadcaster comes to you and
says, `Here's my offer and you don't have any options.' The
broadcasters there feel it's a promotional tool that's needed. I
may have gone in there and saved the team, but I don't think it's
reasonable that I continuously have to do that year in and year
out, especially when you know to be competitive the salaries have
to go up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past the Expos have traded players or let them leave as
free agents because they couldn't pay the salaries other teams were
paying. During Alou's tenure as manager, the list of departed
players has included Larry Walker, Moises Alou, Marquis Grissom,
Henry Rodriguez, Mike Lansing, Pedro Martinez, John Wetteland and
Ken Hill.
</P>
<P>
   If Loria had come along five or six years ago, Felipe Alou was
asked, what did he think might have happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be managing right now,'' he said. ``We'd have
probably won two or three pennants. I'd be here with a necktie
watching this camp.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
