<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4202 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SCOTUS-NUDE-REVIEW-NY     04-01 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NUDE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL MINDS AT WORK: DEFINING NUDITY ON A FIRST AMENDMENT
BATTLEFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ind., Pa.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Supreme Court upheld an ordinance last week banning
nude dancing in Erie, Pa., the American public was treated to the
spectacle of hearing Justice Sandra Day O'Connor somberly discuss
the protective qualities of pasties and G-strings, which the law
requires dancers to wear.
</P>
<P>
   The court has tackled such matters before. In 1991 the justices
upheld an Indiana public indecency law that also banned nude
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   And four years ago, in a case involving a similar statute in St.
John's County, Fla., the court refused to overturn lower-court
decisions that rejected the argument that the ban violated erotic
dancers' freedom of artistic expression.
</P>
<P>
   That case also provided an unusual insight into the legal mind
at work. It turns out the St. John's County law, which requires
that about one-third of a dancer's buttocks be covered, went to
great lengths _ 328 words, to be exact _ to define that unlikely
battleground for First Amendment rights:
</P>
<P>
   ``The area at the rear of the human body (sometimes referred to
as the glutaeus maximus) which lies between two imaginary lines
running parallel to the ground when a person is standing, the first
or top of such line being one-half inch below the top of the
vertical cleavage of the nates (i.e., the prominence formed by the
muscles running from the back of the hip to the back of the leg)
and the second or bottom line being one-half inch above the lowest
point of the curvature of the fleshy protuberance (sometimes
referred to as the gluteal fold), and between two imaginary lines,
one on each side of the body (the `outside lines'), which outside
lines are perpendicular to the ground and to the horizontal lines
described above and which perpendicular outside lines pass through
the outermost point(s) at which each nate meets the outer side of
each leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothwithstanding the above, buttocks shall not include the
leg, the hamstring muscle below the gluteal fold, the tensor
fasciae latae muscle or any of the above-described portion of the
human body that is between either the left inside perpendicular
line and the left outside perpendicular line or the right inside
perpendicular line and the right outside perpendicular line. For
the purpose of the previous sentence the left inside perpendicular
line shall be an imaginary line on the left side of the anus that
is perpendicular to the ground and to the horizontal lines
described above and that is one-third the distance from the anus to
the left outside line, and the right inside perpendicular line
shall be an imaginary line on the right side of the anus that is
perpendicular to the ground and to the horizontal lines described
above and that is one-third of the distance from the anus to the
right outside line. (The above description can generally be
described as covering one-third of the buttocks centered over the
cleavage for the length of the cleavage.)''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-01 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN E-MAIL ADDRESS WITH A LOT OF LIP GIVING ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the initial public offering of TheLipsite, which will be
dedicated to dispensing advice (free, if necessary) to the
operating officers of sports organizations important enough to
deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, those honored are Steve Phillips of the Mets, Bill
Parcells of the Jets and whoever succeeds Neil Smith as president
and general manager of the Rangers. Good luck to all of you. Ignore
the following at your peril. Smith did. He was melted.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets returned from Tokyo last week, where they opened the
regular season by splitting two games with the Chicago Cubs, who
got to make the trip because the St. Louis Cardinals, the first
choice of Major League Baseball, voted not to go. The Cards' star,
Mark McGwire, the player whom the Japanese most wanted to see, had
persuaded his teammates that the globalization of the game was just
another exploitational, money-grubbing tactic by the owners and not
in the spirit of the national pastime. Also, as McGwire phrased it,
``To go play worldwide doesn't turn my crank.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, despite his home run record, is no Babe Ruth, who was
such a sensation in Japan that during World War II, when U.S.
troops cursed the emperor, Japanese troops cursed the Bambino.
Furthermore, McGwire's disdain for greed _ settling into St. Louis
three years ago he took less money than he would have earned by
becoming a free agent a year later _ makes him a truly dangerous
influence on the pastime, not to mention the nation. He says, ``I
take the game seriously,'' and we know that he has put his
supplements where his mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where Phillips can make a difference. To show that the
game has as much integrity as McGwire, its reigning diva, the Mets
must buy John Rocker, stash him in the bullpen and never give him
the ball. Eat his salary. Close the spigot on the bigot. To put a
man who saved 38 games last year, with a 2.49 earned run average,
on ice, would show the world that going to Japan wasn't just about
opening a new market, it was about embracing the world, that
big-hearted, bucolic baseball isn't taking its lessons from
in-your-face, mean street basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association _ which forfeited its
purpose as a game when it decided to become a catalog for gear _ is
losing television fans and blaming it on Tiger Woods, who is a more
upscale clothes and equipment model than Vince Carter or any of
hoopla's not-Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, TheLipsite has never given Coach Parcells any advice
because until now he hasn't needed it. But, like Phillips, he is
now in position to save his game.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League has been frantically meeting of
late, supposedly to discuss what seems to be an escalating trend of
off-field violence among its players. This may not actually be the
case; two young men being accused of killing people is not exactly
a new story. And the league has made a convincing case that its
players _ college-educated millionaires _ have no higher a
percentage of felonies than the high school dropouts they left
behind in their farm communities and inner-city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   What the NFL is really concerned about is the obvious; there is
simply not enough violence ON the field. Because players are not
allowed to fully express themselves with sack dances, touchdown
spikes, cheap shots, leg twists, helmet whacks (those pile-on
orgies are not enough), they have to trash bars, beat up
bystanders, wreck cars and abuse domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   This will all become terribly clear when the so-called
``smash-mouth football'' of the World Wrestling Federation and the
National Broadcasting Co. conVinces America that McMahon, not
Lombardi, is our current spiritual coach. The XFL players will
satisfy their violent needs on the field and not have to endanger
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Parcells comes in. He is the only man who can
conVince his friend, Bob Knight, to leave his faltering college
basketball career and start fresh as the Jets' spiritual counselor.
Knight's crude language, abusive behavior and questionable
motivational tactics (he once placed a tampon in a player's locker)
obviously no longer works at Indiana, which yet again failed to
make the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Knight to bring his bag of dirty tricks to pro
football, to fire up those surly meatmen, get them hurting each
other instead of us. The Jets could ignite the entire NFL and keep
death and destruction where it belongs, between the white lines.
</P>
<P>
   Which bring us to the National Hockey League, my personal fave.
Sure, there has been unusual cruelty lately, players viciously
attacking each other with their sticks, but it has been on the ice.
TheLipsite is concerned that restrictive new rules will so
frustrate goons, enforcers and mean streakers that they will begin
to take off the gloves, so to speak, outside the arena and fight
with their fans.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Neil Smith's replacement comes in. It's a little
touchy, because of a possible conflict of interest. The very best
person for the job, and you know who that is, would immediately
bring back the three most ferocious men who ever graced Ranger
blue: Mark Messier, Tie Domi and Coach Mike Keenan. One can only
imagine the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Let any opposing player even breathe heavily on Messier in his
dotage, and think how Domi and Adam Graves would respond.
Meanwhile, Keenan's grasp of motivational psychology _ he makes
Knight seem decently straightforward _ would have the Rangers so
crazed they would be sharpening their skates into straight razors.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle for team control between Messier and Keenan would
have the Rangers using those razors on each others' throats.
Meanwhile, we fans would be safe for another season.
</P>
<P>
   If you have any problems with any of this, let me know at
TheLipsite(at)aol.com. It would really turn my crank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
