<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      04-01 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' HARMONY A CONTRAST TO TENSIONS ON OTHER TEAMS ;  THE ANDRO
DEBATE; UNION STUDIES AGENT ;  LAKERS WANTED RILEY ;  WEBBER SHOWS
EMPATHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the past week, Vernon Maxwell threw a dumbbell
in the vicinity of Gary Payton, who picked up a chair in order to
counter his Seattle teammate. In Utah, Coach Jerry Sloan and Karl
Malone exchanged angry words during the first half of a game. Asked
whether his relationship with Sloan would recover, Malone replied,
``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Antoine Walker traded insults and nearly punches with
Doug Overton in a timeout huddle as the Celtics and their coach,
Rick Pitino, continued to unravel and make their annual lottery
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Last month in San Antonio, where the Spurs once hailed their
locker room as the happiest in the league, Avery Johnson had to be
restrained in the shower after he and Malik Rose went after each
other, an encounter that nearly turned into a melee between
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Amid this sea of discontent in the dying days of the National
Basketball Association regular season stands one completely
harmonious team, one group of players not having words, sharing
shoves or belittling each other.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, it's the once-combustible Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of odd, because usually we're one of them,'' said
Kobe Bryant last week. ``I guess it's because we've been together
for about four years now. We've kind of grown up together. If we
don't understand or know one another by now, then it just wouldn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning helps, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers went into the weekend with a chance to record the
highest winning percentage in history by a Western Conference team
against the East. Victories over Philadelphia on Friday and New
York on Sunday would give Los Angeles a 27-3 mark (.900) _ a
percentage better than the 1971-72 Lakers, who went 33-5 against
the East (.868).
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have won seven in a row and 26 of their last 27
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has found a run against the Eastern teams mainly
because of the dominance of Shaquille,'' said Coach Phil Jackson of
Shaquille O'Neal. ``There perhaps aren't the same number or size of
centers in the East that have been able to at least neutralize
Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   Some also believe Jackson's unconventional coaching philosophy
has much to do with the Lakers' new-found respect for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably has some characteristics of somebody from outer
space,'' said the Lakers' owner, Jerry Buss, his voiced laced with
sarcasm. ``He's an alien with special gifts; that's all that seems
to be happening. In all seriousness, he's probably knows as much
basketball as any person alive. He's seen a lot of talent.
Everybody has known for a long time we've had the talent. It's
pretty close to the same team. But he could see a way to net it
together which apparently other people could not.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to the angry and maudlin masses. In Seattle, Horace
Grant was hurt breaking up the fight between Payton and Maxwell
during practice last Sunday. He wore a padded wrap on the top of
his left shoulder against the Knicks on Wednesday night. And Sloan
and Malone still weren't talking about talking too much on court
when Malone was replaced briefly in the first half by Scott
Padgett.
</P>
<P>
   Fights in practice and verbal sniping in the news media are
common this time a year. Many teams go through rough times a month
before the playoffs, taking stock of who they genuinely are before
it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's astonishing that the Lakers are no longer one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Andro Debate
</P>
<P>
   The NBA issued a statement on Thursday saying the joint drug
committee of the league and the players' association had added nine
substances to its banned list, including androstenedione _ the
testosterone-boosting supplement made famous by Mark McGwire. But
the National Basketball Players Association filed a grievance to
thwart the move, putting the matter before arbitrator Roger Kaplan.
The union's grievance _ considered a long-shot to overturn the
decision even by its own attorneys _ also challenges the addition
of dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) to the banned list.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Olympics and other sports have banned andro, Billy
Hunter, the union's executive director, reasoned that the
supplement has yet to be banned by baseball and the tests on the
muscle-building drug are still inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the union is doing its job. Banning the
supplement was not mutually agreed to by the parties. It could be
said that if the players do not raise a fuss over these issues,
soon they will be tested for hundreds of substances.
</P>
<P>
   And, the league has become adept at announcing policy change _
remember the microphone controversy? _ before consulting its
players.
</P>
<P>
   But the league and the union jointly pay its committee of drug
experts to make these recommendations. And andro use in the NBA is
said to be infinitesimal. Yet by challenging the adding of the
supplement to the banned list, aren't the players drawing more
attention to the possibility of increased usage?
</P>
<P>
   Union Studies Agent
</P>
<P>
   While no formal action has been taken against him, Andy Miller's
troubles may be just beginning. The agent who represents Kevin
Garnett among other clients is under investigation by the players'
association for allegedly contacting prospective clients while they
were still in college _ in violation of state statutes in Florida
and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Miller will appear before the union to give an explanation of
his actions, detailed last week in a New York Times report. If the
union deems Miller's actions in violation of the article governing
agents in its bylaws, he would face disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is also the focus of a $30 million lawsuit by his former
partner, Eric Fleisher, who accused Miller of essentially stealing
his business.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers Wanted Riley
</P>
<P>
   From the Now-It-Can-Be-Told File: Phil Jackson was not always
the Lakers' main man. A Lakers representative approached Pat Riley
about returning to Los Angeles on three separate occasions last
year, a person close to the Miami Heat coach said.
</P>
<P>
   All three overtures were made before the club entered into
serious contract negotiations with Jackson, said the person close
to Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss, the Lakers' owner, earlier this month denied
reaching out to Riley, who was under contract at the time with
Miami and eventually signed a lucrative extension there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone did, they did it without my knowledge,'' Buss said.
``He was under contract. After 20 years in the NBA, I've learned
not to mess with people under contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Webber Shows Empathy
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber has not only become one of the premier players in
the league on the floor; the one-time troubled young soul has also
emerged as one of most thoughtful, introspective players.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento's All-Star forward arranged for a senior from
Columbine High School, Patrick Ireland, to serve as honorary ball
boy during the Kings game against the 76ers at Arco Arena Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland was one of several students wounded on April 20, 1999,
when two students opened fire at the school, killing 12 classmates
and one teacher. Hearing that Ireland loved Michigan, Webber's alma
mater, and especially the Fab Five, Webber extended the invitation
last year to Ireland, who was unable to attend because of ongoing
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to Patrick and his family attending the game
against Philly,'' Webber said. ``I know he's a big basketball fan,
and hopefully the delayed trip was worth the wait.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
