A4228 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-01 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BIOLOGICAL WARFARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many argue that it is an outrage to expect Elian
Gonzalez to live in a place that tolerates no dissent or freedom of
political expression.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't think Miami is so bad.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, this case is not simply about the future of one
6-year-old. This case is about the job prospects of many really
important adults.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, is not only selfish, but
naive. He thinks biology trumps politics? He thinks he can live in
Cuba and be a fit father?
</P>
<P>
   This hotel doorman does not seem to grasp that there are more
urgent things at stake: Who will grab Florida's 25 electoral votes?
Can Diane unseat Katie as the princess of morning TV? Can Miami
Cuban-Americans give a big raspberry to Fidel Castro? Does the Bush
dynasty have a future? Can Janet Reno go home again?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the child watched his mother drown. And the Miami crowd
has worked to turn him against his father. But now the little
castaway can, to use a W. phrase, ``access the American dream.''
His value to us as a metaphor for truth, justice and the American
way surpasses his value to anybody as a child.
</P>
<P>
   He vindicates our culture: celebrity status, play dates with
Diane Sawyer and a free pass to Disney World outweigh blood ties.
</P>
<P>
   Could a communist dad spoil ``Alien,'' as W. calls him, with the
awesome stuff he has now _ Tommy Hilfiger duds, a labrador pup, a
Power Wheels hot rod, a beeper, gold chains, cell phones and his
own Web page?
</P>
<P>
   The debate over his future goes beyond the natural world. It
involves the spiritual world. His protectors in Miami say the
Virgin Mary has appeared in his bedroom mirror and the windows of a
neighborhood bank. So who is Janet Reno to take on Our Lady and
snatch away the Baby Elian?
</P>
<P>
   True, Al Gore looks craven for breaking with the president to
lend his support to the efforts to keep the boy here. But why
shouldn't he try to wrest Florida's Cuban-American vote out of the
grip of the Bush brothers? This is Gore at his Goriest, standing
firm on shifting principles.
</P>
<P>
   As a doting father, the vice president should put his own
family's need to live in the White House ahead of Juan Gonzalez's
need to live with his son in some shack in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   And Bob Graham, the Democratic senator from Florida, can hardly
be blamed for helping Gore by sponsoring a bill to grant Elian
permanent U.S. residency status. The senator's chances to be Gore's
running mate depend on Florida being in play. And Graham knows an
opportunidad when he sees one.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Republicans, the Bush boys believe in family values and
the rule of law _ as long as those beliefs don't get in the way of
a good wedge issue. W. and Jeb pander most fluently in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic mayor of Miami-Dade County, Alex Penelas, has
brazenly warned federal officials that if they have to drag Elian
out of the house, they're on their own. The mayor doesn't seem
overly worried about Miami turning into some riotous Wild West
outpost, defying the U.S. government, daring the president to send
in the National Guard. What's a little mayhem if it helps launch
your Senate bid?
</P>
<P>
   Elian's relatives in Miami should be applauded for refusing to
let Gonzalez take custody of his son in this country while the
legal drama plays out. What child psychologist wouldn't agree that
it is more important for Elian, at this formative age, to spray
Silly String in Diane Sawyer's golden locks than to be restored to
his own father?
</P>
<P>
   While the wishes of a biological parent should be respected, the
lawyer for the Miami branch says, all decisions must be made
according to ``what is best for the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's be blunt. Dads are a dime a dozen. What is best for the
child is to take full advantage of his cachet in the U.S. of A.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani wanted the boy to come help him drop the
ball at the Times Square millennial celebration. Surely Elian will
be asked to sit in the balcony at the first State of the Union
address by either President Bush or President Gore. Hollywood, book
publishers, hucksters and Gloria Estefan will be calling.
</P>
<P>
   The kid will need representation. He can't go back to Cuba.
There isn't a decent publicist on the entire island.
</P>
<P>
   And we must always do what's best for the child.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
