<SLUG> BC-FIRST-PITCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A BIT OF OPENING DAY HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID FISCHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Opening day of the baseball season attained ceremonial status in
1910 when President William Howard Taft threw out the first pitch
in Washington. Since then, New York teams have made a bit of
opening day history themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger Blues
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Dodgers lost to the Philadelphia Phillies, 1-0, on
opening day in 1913, in the first regular-season game ever played
at Ebbets Field. The Dodgers' owner, Charles Hercules Ebbets, had
financially overextended himself building the park that bore his
name, and he was soon forced to sell a controlling interest in the
team to the McKeever brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Ebbets died on opening day of the 1925 season. Six days later,
all National League games were canceled for his funeral. At the
funeral, workers struggled to widen Ebbets' grave because it was
too narrow for his oversize coffin. During the wait, mourners were
soaked by heavy rain. One of them was the club president, Ed
McKeever, who developed pneumonia and died one month later.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx Ballpark
</P>
<P>
   At the Yankee Stadium inaugural in 1923, Babe Ruth slammed the
first home run in its history _ a three-run shot off Howard Ehmke
to help pitcher Bob Shawkey and the Yankees capture a 4-1 victory
over the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   When the renovated Yankee Stadium was unveiled for the 1976 home
opener, Bob Shawkey, now 85, threw out the first ball. The Yanks
won the game, 11-4, but Minnesota Twins outfielder Dan Ford hit the
first homer in the modern Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Inaugural No-Nos
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, the 21-year-old Cleveland Indians fireballer Bob Feller
became the first major league pitcher to throw an opening day
no-hitter when he defeated the Chicago White Sox, 1-0, at Comiskey
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Feller doused many an opening day celebration. At the Yankee
Stadium home opener in 1946, Feller also pitched a 1-0 no-hitter.
The only run was scored by Feller's catcher, Frankie Hayes, who hit
a home run in the top of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants pitcher Red Ames worked nine innings without
allowing a hit in the 1909 opener at the Polo Grounds against the
Brooklyn Dodgers. But Ames surrendered a hit in the 10th and lost
in the 13th when Brooklyn scored three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Barrier Breakers
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 25,000 fans at Ebbets Field for the April 15, 1947,
season opener between the Brooklyn Dodgers and Boston Braves wore
``I'm for Jackie'' buttons, signifying the historic debut of the
first black man to play major league baseball. Although Robinson
went hitless that day in three at-bats against Johnny Sam, the
first of Robinson's 1,382 major league games was a matter of
record.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight years later, Rachel Robinson, his widow, threw out
the ceremonial first pitch on opening day at Municipal Stadium in
Cleveland. Her appearance honored Frank Robinson, whose official
debut that day as baseball's first black manager was a winning one.
As the Indians' player-manager, he stroked a first-inning home run
off Yankees pitcher Doc Medich for his 575th career home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Amazin's
</P>
<P>
   The first game in New York Mets history in 1962 was rained out.
The next morning, the opening day starter, Roger Craig, and a dozen
other Mets were stranded in an elevator for 30 minutes at the Chase
Hotel in St. Louis, where the Mets were to begin the season against
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' opening day lineup on April 11,1962, was: Richie
Asburn (cf), Felix Mantilla (ss), Charlie Neal (2b), Frank Thomas
(lf), Gus Bell (rf), Gil Hodges (1b), Don Zimmer (3b), Hobie
Landrith (c), and Roger Craig (p). Craig lasted three innings and
balked in one run. His teammates committed three errors, and the
Mets lost for the first of a record 120 times that season. Talk
about bad omens: the Mets' home opener was played at the Polo
Grounds two days later, on Friday the 13th.
</P>
<P>
   All Hit, No Field
</P>
<P>
   Ron Blomberg made baseball history when he stepped into the
batter's box on opening day in 1973. The Yankees were playing the
Boston Red Sox in Fenway Park when, in the first inning, Blomberg
became the first designated hitter to bat in a major league game.
Blomberg, who faced Boston pitcher Luis Tiant with the bases
loaded, drew a walk and forced in a run. The first major league
plate appearance by a designated hitter was not an official at-bat,
although Blomberg was credited with a run batted in.
</P>
<P>
   What, No Baby Ruth?
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' home opener in 1978 was when Roger Maris ended his
12-year self-exile by returning to the Bronx. In a pregame
ceremony, Maris and Mickey Mantle raised the team's first world
championship flag in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Standard Brands handed out free ``Reggie!''
candy bars as a sales promotion gimmick to the 44,667 fans who
passed through the turnstiles. In the game's first inning, Reggie
Jackson, who had homered on his last three swings of the 1977 World
Series at Yankee Stadium, connected again on his first cut of the
home season, smashing a three-run homer off Chicago's Wilbur Wood
in the Yankees' 4-2 victory over the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   When Reggie took his position in right field to start the second
inning, the fans threw thousands of ``Reggie!'' bars onto the field
in tribute. The game was delayed about five minutes for
groundskeepers to gather the candy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
