<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     04-01 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE NCAA, MORE THAN A BUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time in Bill Saum's career when he was on ``the
other side.'' Saum is now the staff liaison from the National
Collegiate Athletic Association to its committee that oversees
eligibility and rules compliance. Saum was once one of the
nameless, faceless plow horses that form the foundation of the
NCAA. He was a football coach. He worked the thankless dusk-to-dawn
hours of an assistant, working the field, teaching football.
</P>
<P>
   Today Saum wields more power than he ever imagines, the power to
make athletes' lives miserable _ which he has done _ or more
clearly define the perimeter of what is acceptable and what is not.
Depending on which side of the NCAA rulebook you are looking from,
Saum is either one of the most disliked men in college athletics or
a valiant crusader doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Saum, 40, is the point man for a controversial
initiative that could smash the amateurism model that has defined
college sports for much of the last century. Saum is helping to put
into effect an effort that the NCAA describes with an
ominous-sounding catch phrase: Changing the culture.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Saum met with the executive board of the National
Association of Basketball Coaches to get its members' thoughts
about a proposed rules change that would allow athletes to accept
prize money and play professionally after graduating from high
school while retaining their eligibility in case they later want to
go to college. The legislation would allow outside sports
organizations to pay for benefits such as prep school tuition _ an
activity that, over the last three months, has resulted in the high
profile suspension of Division I basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations by Saum's staff have accounted for the suspension
of these players, among others:
</P>
<P>
   _ UCLA forward JaRon Rush, who was suspended for much of the
season after he admitted to accepting money from his Amateur
Athletic Union coach in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rush's younger brother Kareem at Missouri and Oklahoma State's
Andre Williams, who accepted illicit benefits from the same AAU
coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jamal Crawford, who was suspended for gifts and benefits he
received from a Seattle-area businessman with whom he once lived.
</P>
<P>
   _ St. John's Erick Barkley, who was suspended this season for
swapping cars and accepting money to pay his tuition at a prep
school.
</P>
<P>
   Saum refused to discuss individual investigations but said cases
like these are part of the problem and part of the reason the model
needed to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events of the last two months has raised the awareness of
our coaches and membership that we need to come to the table and
talk about amateurism deregulation,'' he said. ``We need to talk
about agents. We need to work harder _ I need to work harder in my
area _ but we've got to engage the coaches, and we've got to quit
saying that it's horrible. We've got to peel away the layers of the
onion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't tweak the rule and say let's recruit 14 days instead
of 21 days. We need to start over. We need to eliminate people from
college basketball. We need to make education important, we need to
just involve professionals: teachers, guidance counselors,
principals, not all these street people who really. . . .'' Saum
paused to find the right words: ``Their own interest is their best
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the so-called ``street people'' argue that the college
sports infrastructure _ white male dominated _ does not have at
heart the athletes' best interest but only its own coffers. Three
of the Final Four coaches received bonuses for taking their teams
to Indianapolis, and the Final Four site here is surrounded by
crass commercialism that the Carnegie Commission report cited 70
years ago as the cause of college sport's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society demands to have this,'' Saum said referring to the
NCAA tournament. ``This is not basketball games, this is an event.
This possibly is the world's greatest sporting event. Society wants
this; the board of trustees want certain things. We have to deal in
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coaches have agents. What message does that send to our
kids? I'm not saying coaches shouldn't have agents, but I think
that all of us need to be attentive to the role model that we are
to our young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Saum joined the NCAA in April, 1988. Before joining the NCAA, he
coached at The Defiance College in Defiance, Ohio. He was a high
school athlete who did not play at the University of Dayton. At
Dayton he tutored the men's basketball team and coached high school
football. He went to Bowling Green, where he was a graduate
assistant. After that he was at Heidelberg College in Tiffin, Ohio,
as an assistant football coach and head track coach. There were two
years of high school coaching before Defiance.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Saum said he had to look in the mirror and assess where
he was going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to step off the carousel of coaching,'' he said.
``I got to a point where I wasn't sure how good a coach I was. But
I loved athletics and I wanted to have an effect on changing
athletics and I got lucky and got employed in the enforcement
department in the NCAA. I needed to change something.''
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials, especially those involved with enforcement,
rarely talk about themselves, or discuss their backgrounds or the
prism through which they filter rules interpretations. The NCAA
enforcement staff in the past has opted to be the nameless,
faceless stealth bomber that moves under cover of night, swooping
down on so-called wrongdoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I have some credibility with the coaches because I try
to still be a coach and never ever be a bureaucrat,'' Saum said.
``But when you're a football coach, you only live for 11 Saturdays,
and that's not real healthy and it doesn't allow you to look at the
big picture of intercollegiate athletics. Our coaches in America
are so focused on their institution, their team, next year's kids,
last year's kids. Engaging them in a wide-ranging discussion is
hard. That's the way I was when I was coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA says it wants to change the culture. I'm still not
certain what the NCAA wants to change from: Good to bad? Tall to
short? Urban to suburban? Domestic to foreign? Black to white?
Nevertheless, change is coming. You may not like what Saum is
saying, may not like Ced Dempsey's initiative but coaches and
players had better feel the pulse. The culture is changing,
changing in ways we never imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have imagined this?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
