<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, April 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Showers and embedded thunderstorms will surround a sluggish
front from the interior Northeast to the southern Mississippi
Valley. Over two inches of rain will be common by early Monday from
eastern Texas to the Tennessee Valley as a potent jet stream
disturbance lifts sultry air. Farther north, lighter showers will
dampen the eastern Ohio Valley and northern Appalachians. The
Northeast coast will have some sun, which will fade behind
thickening clouds as showers approach from the west.
</P>
<P>
   Colder air will surge from the northern Rockies to the northern
Plains on gusty winds in the wake of a fast-moving cold front.
Scattered showers will mix with wet snow from the Dakotas to the
northern Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Coast states, offshore winds and ample sunshine will
cause unseasonable warmth to persist.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: CHANGING TIMES
</P>
<P>
   Twisting the hands of a clock cannot change the weather, but
Sunday's time adjustment can alter human perception of weather
events. Many daily weather trends begin at sunrise. The flood of
solar energy sets the air in motion, causing wind speed to
increase. The temperature often begins an abrupt rise. Dense fogs
start to dissipate as the sun warms the saturated air. Often,
strong weather systems overwhelm these daily cycles. But, on
average, as most people begin their day, the weather this week will
be calmer, cooler and mistier than last week because of the change
in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
