<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BLUEPRINT-755(     04-01 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BLUEPRINT-755(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN'S TEAM HAMMERS OUT A PLAN TO UNTWIST RUSSIA'S ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The victory of Vladimir Putin in last Sunday's
presidential election has focused attention on an opulent Moscow
building known as Alexander House, where a team of liberal-minded
economists and other experts has been quietly drafting Putin's
blueprint for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   German Gref, head of the Center for Strategic Research and
master of Alexander House, confidently predicted last week that by
late May Putin would be ready to release ``a breakthrough scenario
envisaging the most radical reforms,'' from an overhaul of Russia's
cumbersome tax code to a streamlining of its infamous
bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of tax reform, the contents of the program
are still vague and, on critical issues like land reform, still
under debate. But the Alexander House team _ which includes some of
Russia's best-known pro-market reformers _ has already firmly
established itself as the beachhead of liberal economics in the
coming Putin administration.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Putin prepares to assume his new mandate at inauguration
ceremonies scheduled for early May, the question is how Gref and
his ambitious plan will survive in the battle over access and
influence in the Putin Kremlin, which is being watched as keenly in
the United States as in Russia itself.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in the next round of Byzantine intrigue and
infighting _ a regular feature of former President Boris Yeltsin's
rule _ are unusually high.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a struggle going on over the strategy for Russia,''
noted Boris Nemtsov, once one of the Kremlin's young reformers and
now a leader of the Union of Right Forces, which has broadly backed
Putin. ``Either it will be crony capitalism with tycoons,
corruption, underground deals and social polarization, or it will
be a Western-style economy.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference last week, Gref made clear that he had
Putin's ear, and his backing. He said that Putin had been offered
three plans for growth targets and picked the most ambitious one.
``This means we will really have our work cut out for us,'' Gref
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most significant, Putin last week included Gref in a
small inner Cabinet that has been charged with overseeing the
transition and, in Gref's words, with ensuring that government
practice does not stray from the Alexander House team's policies.
Other members of the working group include First Deputy Prime
Minister Mikhail Kasyanov, Minister of Finance Aleksei Kudrin and
Alexsander Voloshin, the Kremlin chief of staff, who is the most
visible holdover from Yeltsin's inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Gref noted, the working group had been empowered to
amend government legislation, now pending in parliament, that
contradicts the center's policies _ a veiled reference to bills on
state registration of foreign trade transactions and capital flight
that seemed to fly in the face of the center's deregulatory bent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gref is building pressure on his rivals by assuring that the
president and the future Cabinet will need only the center's
program,'' the daily newspaper Segodnya said.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference last week, Gref said: ``There is no
alternative program. There may be different positions on different
issues, and if they are well grounded, they will be presented to
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 35, Gref is the latest fresh face to become the standard
bearer for Russian reform. He is a lawyer with a faint Van Dyke
beard, a church-going Lutheran of German descent who, like his
patron, Putin, has a background in St. Petersburg city government,
where he once headed an experiment in housing reform.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, when the center was created by Putin, then the
prime minister, Gref has been coordinating the collection of
opinions on the full spectrum of Russia's unfinished agenda. His
brief career spans reform of the military and bank restructuring,
strengthening the courts and shrinking one of the world's largest
and most corrupt bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews and meetings and in an open letter to the voters
written for Putin during the election campaign, Gref has elaborated
on Putin's commitment to a strong and efficient government,
property rights, openness and the rule of law _ all elements needed
to turn Russia's twisted economy into a level playing field
suitable for desperately needed investment.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Gref said last week, is to make the Russian economy
``manageable and market-oriented.'' At this point, he said, it has
``stagnated in a semireformed state. Our task is to take it to
normal market conditions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it is not surprising that his efforts have already run into
resistance. Boris Berezovsky, the financier and media tycoon who
boasts of his influence over the tiny group that held sway in the
Yeltsin Kremlin, recently poured scorn on the Alexander House team,
dismissing their efforts as ``unprofessional'' and their ideas as
``naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts see the battle shaping up in the Kremlin as a
repeat of an old rivalry between Berezovsky and Anatoly Chubais,
another Kremlin insider with the credentials of a reformer, who now
heads Russia's national electric utility company. Another group
reportedly vying for influence is headed by Pyotr Aven, a former
minister who is now president of Alfa-Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the real issue is whether Putin, who owes his popularity to
his image as a tough, uncompromising former KGB agent, will be able
to prove his independence from all of these competing clans, and
steer Russia on to a more predictable course.
</P>
<P>
   An even greater challenge, many say, will be to override an
entrenched bureaucracy that has long experience in defeating the
best of plans. For this, they say Putin, when he moves, will have
to strike fast and hard, or risk being overwhelmed by vested
interests at all levels of government.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign business leaders say the appointment of Gref or
members of his team to the new government would be a good start.
``Gref is strongly committed to liberal economics,'' said Glenn
Waller, director of the Petroleum Advisory Forum, a Moscow-based
lobbying group representing foreign oil and gas companies. ``If
Gref or anyone associated with him were to take a senior position
in the government, it would be a clear signal that Putin wants to
pursue reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Gref, the Alexander House team includes such reform
economists as Yevgeny Yasin, considered the captain of the reform
team; Aleksei Ulukayev, a deputy at the economics institute headed
by Yegor Gaidar, Yeltsin's first, reform-oriented prime minister;
Oleg Vyugin, a former deputy finance minister and an analyst at
Troika Dialog, a Moscow investment firm; and Andrei Illarionov, a
liberal economist who was a strong critic of Yeltsin's early reform
governments and is now thought to be in line for a post as Putin's
chief economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial ally of the Gref team is the finance minister, Kudrin,
a longtime associate of Putin from St. Petersburg, who helped bring
the future president into the Yeltsin administration in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a limited number of people in Russia who can advise
the government on macroeconomic policy,'' said Vladimir Mau,
another deputy at Gaidar's institute who is also advising the
Alexander House team. ``The same people keep coming back, in
different proportions, but they are the same people.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last three months, Putin has conducted his own
economic seminars, as he toured the country ahead of the March 26
elections. Meeting with foreign investors on March 13, he impressed
many of them with his advanced preparation, and his attention to
detail, said Waller and other businessmen present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, his commitment to economic reform has remained
largely rhetorical, apparently in anticipation of the actual Gref
program. He has frequently repeated the broad principles of
free-market reforms, although during the campaign, he uttered
occasional populist comments that veered toward blunt
protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the reforms now under discussion, only changes to
Russia's awkward and antiquated tax code have already been drafted,
in preparation for a debate in the parliament later this spring.
The new code, which would reduce tax rates and shift from
revenue-based levies to profit-based levies, must be adopted by
July 1, if it is to be implemented next year.
</P>
<P>
   Gref said he did not expect any political opposition to the
changes in taxation, one of the few issues on the reformers' agenda
that also has the support of Russia's Communist Party. He said
opposition was likely in the parliament on other elements of the
program, but he added, with calm understatement, ``I don't think
there will be an atmosphere of sharp confrontation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4257 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-ABBY-COHEN-REVIEW-NYT     04-01 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABBY-COHEN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GURU CONQUERS WALL STREET. NEXT, THE WORLD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never underestimate the power of Abby Joseph Cohen.
Last week, a warning about stock prices from Cohen, the formidable
chief investment strategist for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.,
singlehandedly caused a broad sell-off in markets worldwide. It
left even the most seasoned traders quivering. ``When she speaks,
markets move,'' one marveled to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   And not just markets. While Cohen has been ubiquitous on Wall
Street, the rest of the world is badly in need of her guidance. But
all that just might change in the months to come if Cohen expands
her spheres of influence. Here's a scenario as played out in a
series of news items:
</P>
<P>
   April 20, 2000 _ Steven Spielberg surprised Hollywood today when
he announced he was dropping plans to develop ``Minority Report,''
a science-fiction thriller set to star Tom Cruise, after the
Goldman, Sachs stock market seer Abby Joseph Cohen told Spielberg
that she believed the highly anticipated film would be a flop. ``I
thought we had a solid script, and Tom is usually bankable,'' he
said, ``but I couldn't take a chance after Abby gave the project a
thumbs down.'' An obviously disappointed Spielberg said, ``I'm
hoping she likes the sequel to `Saving Private Ryan' better.''
</P>
<P>
   May 15, 2000 _ Teen pregnancy rates dropped by nearly one-third
in 1999, to the lowest level in four decades, federal health
officials said yesterday. The National Center for Health Statistics
attributed the encouraging trend, which spanned all racial and
ethnic groups, to the ``Abby Says No'' teen abstinence campaign
featuring the stock market strategist Abby Joseph Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody touches kids like Abby,'' said Donna E. Shalala,
secretary of health and human services. ``Not Britney Spears, not
the Backstreet Boys, no one. She's been so right on the market for
so long that she has what the kids call `cred,' and you can't fake
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey, director of the Office
of National Drug Control Policy, has asked Cohen for the chance to
expand ``Abby Says No'' to its anti-drug campaigns. ``Let's be
honest, those ads with the heroin addicts are getting old,'' said
General McCaffrey. ``We're looking for something a little more
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   July 20, 2000 _ Abby Joseph Cohen took home the top prize at the
World Series of Poker yesterday, winning $1.1 million after
defeating a field of more than 400 of the world's best poker
players. Cohen vanquished her final opponent, poker veteran Huck
Seed, with an ace-high flush, topping Seed's straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no chance,'' he said. ``It was like she could read my
mind!'' The always-modest Cohen attributed her victory mainly to
luck and said she had never played poker before entering the
tournament. ``I signed up mainly because I always wanted to see Las
Vegas,'' Cohen said. ``It's pretty neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 5, 2000 _ ``China and Taiwan will announce today that they
have ended more than a half-century of hostility and agreed in
principle to reunify as one nation by the end of the year, sources
close to the talks said late last night. The shocking deal comes
only days after Goldman, Sachs strategist Abby Joseph Cohen quietly
offered top Chinese and Taiwanese officials a white paper that
predicted stock markets in both countries could fall as much as 90
percent in the event of a Chinese attempt to take Taiwan by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abby found the issue that resonates with the leaders of both
sides when she showed them just how much money a war would cost
them,'' said one American diplomat about the talks, which are being
held at Goldman, Sachs headquarters in New York City. ``She
deserves the Nobel Prize for this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 8, 2000 _ New York voters soundly rejected both New York
City Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton yesterday, instead choosing Abby Joseph Cohen as New York's
newest senator. With 98 percent of precincts reporting late
Tuesday, Cohen, whose name was not listed on the ballot and who did
not campaign, had more than 63 percent of the vote, while Giuliani
and Clinton were locked in a virtual dead heat for second place
with 18 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   After word of Cohen's unexpected triumph was announced
yesterday, New Yorkers statewide rushed into the streets to
rejoice, creating an impromptu block party that stretched from
Buffalo to Montauk. ``I'm so glad it's Abby,'' said Gov. George E.
Pataki of Albany. ``Hillary and Rudy, Rudy and Hillary _ you've
gotta be kidding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
