<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-MARKET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITERARY GHOST IN THE HMO DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the transformation of American medicine over the last 75
years, Dr. Martin Solomon, a central figure in this Tuesday's
edition of the PBS documentary series ``Frontline,'' has little in
common with Dr. Martin Arrowsmith, the hero of Sinclair Lewis'
famous 1925 novel that bears his name. But they share a chronic
discontent: a feeling that they are trapped between the duty to
practice their profession conscientiously and the pressures of a
market society. The complaint, rooted in a clash between the
principles of Hippocrates and those of Adam Smith, may not be fully
curable.
</P>
<P>
   We meet Solomon, a primary care physician, in the prestigious
Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center at Harvard, where he is
examining a man being treated for a dangerous infection and heart
problems. The patient has been in the intensive care unit for more
than six weeks at a cost of $150,000 and rising. Solomon calls his
expensive case ``a loser.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Israel is owned by CareGroup, a network of 7 hospitals,
3,000 doctors and 400,000 patients, which lost $100 million last
year. In an effort to change that, its doctors have been made
responsible for containing treatment costs and turning their
practices into profit centers. Their expenses _ ``Every time I
write a prescription, every time I order a test, every time I send
a patient to the emergency room'' _ are closely monitored, Solomon
laments, and if they spend too much, their incomes suffer.
</P>
<P>
   So there is pressure to shorten hospital stays and office
visits, reduce high-tech tests and discourage patients from seeking
consultations outside the group. And the best hospitals, like
Deaconess, which take on the most complicated cases and do research
and teaching as well, have the highest bills.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the new system is keeping doctors focused on the bottom
line, but is that where they should be? Sinclair Lewis, the son of
a country doctor, would surely have thought not, and his
Bildungsroman is largely given to the earnest young Arrowsmith's
efforts to resist the lures of the profit motive, which keep
getting in the way of the healer's mission.
</P>
<P>
   Practicing in the 1920s, Arrowsmith does not have to worry about
the high cost of diagnostic equipment since there are precious few
of those latter-day wonders, or about reductions in federal
financing since there isn't much of that either, or about the
impositions of HMOs. . But he has plenty of experience with his
profession's greed. As a satirist, Lewis was usually heavy-handed,
but his diagnosis of social ailments could be sharp.
</P>
<P>
   One character describes a successful surgeon as ``riding up to
the hospital in a lovely car with a chauffeur in uniform, and all
his patients simply worshiping him.'' Another doctor, a specialist
in removing any tonsils within reach of his knife, advises medical
students on the value of salesmanship in dealing with a customer:
``Explain to him, also to his stricken and anxious family, the hard
work and thought you are giving to his case, and so make him feel
that the good you have done him, or intend to do him, is even
greater than the fee you plan to charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrowsmith meets still another doctor, who reasons that ``It'd
be better for the general health situation if there weren't any
public health departments at all, because they get a lot of people
into the habit of going to free clinics instead of to private
physicians, and cut down the earnings of doctors and reduce their
number, so there are less of us to keep a watchful eye on
sickness.'' And Arrowsmith discerns ``the slimy trail of the
dollar'' in a Babbitt-like doctor's opposition to pasteurizing milk
and regulating tenements for fear of offending dairymen and
landlords.
</P>
<P>
   Dated though Arrowsmith's concerns are, the members of Solomon's
medical group, whose annual incomes range from $120,000 to
$300,000, also find themselves in thrall to financial constraints
and influenced by incentives that may run contrary to a patient's
well being. For example, they are under pressure to keep patients
from seeing specialists outside of CareGroup lest it reduce their
income. A doctor at another Boston HMO speaks for his patients:
``Are you really serving my best interest as a patient, doctor, or,
in fact, are you looking out for your best interest?''
</P>
<P>
   As the nation struggles to work out rational, compassionate,
economic health-care arrangements, the ethical issues faced by
Arrowsmith and those facing Solomon are not all that different. The
defiant Martin Arrowsmith ends up doing honest research of his own,
freed at last of the opportunism and corruption of the
practitioners around him. When last heard from, Martin Solomon is
explaining how he now must resist sending a patient to another
doctor even if he knows it might be to her benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether that is a good system, Solomon answers, ``I think
it stinks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0118 </DOCNO>
