<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4263 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NIGHT-CHILDCARE-ART-9     04-01 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGHT-CHILDCARE-ART-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODD-HOUR DAY CARE: AN UNMET NEED IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif., Fla., S.C., Tenn., Calif., Mass.)   (Eds.: Grace Francis is woman's name; Francis Grace is day care
center name.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Wednesday at 7 p.m., in a two-story house on
195th Street in St. Albans, Queens, Grace Francis put a 4-year-old
boy to bed. Tucked into his tiny cot, under a Power Rangers
comforter and matching sheets, he chose ``Clifford the Firehouse
Dog'' from a stack of books on the night table, and recited along
from memory as Francis read to him. She reminded him to say his
prayers, and when he was done, she flicked off the light and spent
the next few hours tending to an older boy.
</P>
<P>
   Francis is not the boys' mother or their nanny. She is their day
care provider. At Francis Grace Day Care, which Francis runs in her
home, care can start at any hour and last all week, as it did
earlier in March for the 4-year-old, Aldane Chambers. Last week,
his mother, Maureen Baker, dropped him off early Wednesday morning
on her way to New Jersey, where she works as a nanny, and picked
him up at 9 p.m. Thursday. The mother of the other boy is a nurse
who works until 9 two nights a week.
</P>
<P>
   In Francis' licensed day care center, Aldane's mother and other
parents have found the answer to an urgent need: child care at odd
hours. The center is a rare option for working New Yorkers _ bus
drivers and token clerks, nurses and cocktail waitresses, janitors
and seamstresses _ with no one else to turn to. For their city and
state are behind in the world of night care.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years _ particularly after the 1996 welfare overhaul
sent millions of parents into the work force, many on shifts at odd
hours _ dozens of cities and states have taken steps to supply
working parents with round-the-clock child care.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, particularly California, Florida and South
Carolina, have been aggressive in setting up and financing such
centers, while others have provided incentives and grants to
private programs. Such services have also been offered for years by
private companies, like Saturn and Disney, and by hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But New York City, one of the more aggressive in the nation in
reducing the welfare rolls and putting people to work for their
benefits, has until recently not been part of the movement toward
publicly financed, flexible-hour child care. New York state, still
in the early stages of a plan to encourage odd-hour care, has only
begun to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   One in three parents with young children holds a job that
requires early morning, late night or even lobster shifts,
according to a national study two years ago by the Families and
Work Institute, a nonprofit research organization based in
Manhattan. But New York still has not measured the need for
odd-hour care, so there are no statistics for the city or state to
be compared with the national rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knew Chattanooga would be ahead of New York in anything?''
said Phil Acord, executive director of the Children's
Home/Chambliss Shelter, a 24-hour child care center for low-income
families in Chattanooga, Tenn., that receives government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Although such centers are still unusual, some other cities,
including San Francisco and Winthrop, near Boston, support 24-hour
programs that serve as models in the emerging national conversation
about odd-hour care, according to a 1998 study by Parents United
for Child Care, a Boston advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   But thus far in New York City, it is largely individuals _
entrepreneurial providers like Francis, herself a Jamaican
immigrant who saw a need among Jamaican parents in St. Albans _ who
are stepping in to meet the need.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Bellevue Hospital Center is to open the city's
first round-the-clock child-care center, with space for a total of
117 children in eight-hour shifts. Hospital employees and working
parents from the neighborhood can apply, and the center is seeking
city subsidies for low-income parents.
</P>
<P>
   After heavy lobbying from child-care advocates, the City Council
allocated $500,000 last year to open the center at Bellevue. The
project, rejected by city officials years ago, was spearheaded by a
day care center director and a group of hospital employees,
including a Bellevue clinic worker whose 4-year-old-son died in a
1993 fire at an unlicensed day care program while she was on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   State and city officials insist that they are not ignoring the
child care needs of parents working odd hours, although they
acknowledge that they have little information about the demand.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Human Resources Administration, which distributes day
care aid to parents moving off public assistance, is not tracking
the work schedules of the more than 500,000 recipients with
children. However, officials did estimate that up to 10 percent of
the city's 37,000 workfare participants are working odd-hour
shifts, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After sharply increasing day care financing in 1999, the state
set aside $42 million that local childcare agencies could use for
odd-hour programs, among other things. But state officials have
recently told the agencies they should use the money to improve
existing services and increase reimbursement rates to day care
programs serving low-income parents, according to a recent
memorandum from the State Office of Children and Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   William Van Slyk, a spokesman, said that the higher rates should
encourage providers to stay open longer, and that the state would
make $19 million in grants available to opening day care programs,
including those offering odd-hour services. He said the state would
start sending out grant applications next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more needs are identified, I'm confident we will meet those
needs,'' Van Slyk said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The city's Agency for Child Development, part of the
Administration for Children's Services, has no plans to open
24-hour day care centers, officials said, although as far back as
1988 rules for night care were written into the city code that
regulates licensed day care programs. As the city expands day care
programs, the agency will consider proposals for extended hours and
has already received a few, according to Jennifer Falk, a
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   At Francis' day care center, most parents are immigrants who
have not sought the city's help to pay for day care. Because her
program is licensed (to care for up to six children) eligible
parents could use city vouchers to pay for care there, but none
done so, Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   Francis, 50, a nurse by training, opened her program in
September 1998 after noticing that many of the women in her
neighborhood, immigrants from Jamaica and Barbados, were struggling
to find child care to fit their schedules. With financial help from
her brother, George Francis, she opened her center on the first
floor. She uses the front room as an office and the middle room as
the child care room; it is decorated with children's artwork and is
used for playing, dancing, reading and, when she puts out the cots
stored in the office, sleeping. So far, Aldane is her only regular
overnight customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I slept here the other night, and then I slept here again,''
Aldane said earlier this month. ``I like it because it's fun here.
I like playing and sleeping and dancing and sleeping.'' Aldane's
mother, who immigrated to Queens along with her son a year ago from
West Moreland, Jamaica, said she learned about Francis Grace Day
Care from an advertisement in a local shoppers' guide and placed
him there immediately.
</P>
<P>
   As for leaving her son overnight, sometimes for several nights
in a row, Baker, 36, said: ``It's natural for a mother to miss her
child. But when they're OK, you don't worry about what's happening.
I feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not been easy for Francis financially. She charges a
weekly fee of $120 with $10 added for an overnight stay, but waives
some of that if her clients cannot afford all of it. She said she
was also struggling to save enough money to buy a television and a
computer for the children, having spent a $500 grant from a
neighborhood group for basic needs. She had not heard that the
state was planning to offer grants for odd-hour centers.
</P>
<P>
   Some other day care providers who have experimented with 24-hour
service say the extra costs and worry that a child will get ill, or
worse, in the night are not worth the extra business. Some parents,
too, feel uneasy about leaving their children overnight at either a
day care center or in a stranger's home, child care experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very challenging because it's not clear that parents want
centers, so you have to try to make them available and then look at
other ways of developing odd-hour care,'' said Helen Blank,
director of child care for the Children's Defense Fund in
Washington. ``But you have to provide odd-hour care because parents
are working odd hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Jay Maldonado, executive director of Educare, a day care
center sponsored by Bellevue, said she approached day care
officials 20 years ago with the idea of opening a round-the-clock
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have seen a need for 24-hour day care, but society
wasn't ready for it,'' Maldonado said, adding that she was often
concerned when she heard about nurses and other late-shift workers
leaving their children alone at night, perhaps checking on them
during a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, more and more society has become 24-hour oriented,'' she
said. ``If the city wanted 24-hour care, it could be done
tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
