<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 2, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-INTEGRATION-REVIEW (Undated) _ Less than half a century
after the Supreme Court ruled that school segregation was
unconstitutional, are efforts to achieve racially integrated public
schools legally and politically doomed? A look at recent court
rulings that are making it hard for public schools to maintain even
a semblance of racial diversity in a judicial and political climate
that exalts choice above all other values. By Jeffrey Rosen. WITH
GRAPHIC. (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   GYPSIES-REVIEW (Pavlovce Nad Uhom, Slovakia) _ The Gypsies, or
Roma, are the new Europe's stateless people, at least 8 million of
them scattered and mostly reviled throughout Central and Eastern
Europe. While half a million Roma died in the Holocaust, which the
Roma call ``the devouring,'' they remain the one people in the
modern, democratic, post-communist Europe whom it is largely
acceptable to persecute. By Steven Erlanger. (Moved in `i'
category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-MARKET-REVIEW (Undated) _ Given the transformation of
American medicine over the past 75 years, Dr. Martin Solomon, a
central figure in a PBS ``Frontline'' documentary, has little in
common with Dr. Martin Arrowsmith, the hero of Sinclair Lewis'
famous 1925 novel that bears his name. But they share a chronic
discontent: a feeling that they are trapped between the duty to
practice their profession conscientiously and the pressures of a
market society. The complaint, rooted in a clash between the
principles of Hippocrates and those of Adam Smith, may not be fully
curable. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   ABBY-COHEN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Never underestimate the power of
Abby Joseph Cohen, the ubiquitous chief investment strategist for
Goldman, Sachs. Last week, she almost singlehandedly caused a broad
sell-off in markets worldwide. ``When she speaks, markets move,''
said one trader. And not just markets. Cohen, who appears
frequently on TV, usually just discusses Wall Street, which has
left the rest of the world badly in need of guidance. But all that
just might change in the months to come, if the guru breaks out and
enters other spheres of influence. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   ALEX-COMFORT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Dr. Alex Comfort personified the
sort of tweedy English intellectual who could gracefully range from
subject to subject and from literary form to form. He was a
physician, poet, novelist, anarchist, pacifist and a leading
researcher on how people age. He was best known as the author of
``The Joy of Sex: A Gourmet Guide to Lovemaking'' but a glance at
his other writings reveals a dazzlingly multi-faceted mind. By
Douglas Martin.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-WOMEN-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Pentagon has tried to
emphasize milestones it has achieved in advancing the standing of
women in the nation's armed services. A provocative new book, ``The
Kinder, Gentler Military, '' challenges the sanguine image the
Pentagon would like to convey of equality in the military's
increasing co-ed ranks. The author, Stephanie Gutmann, accuses the
Pentagon's civilian and military leaders of dangerously eroding
U.S. military might in a politically correct pursuit to expand
women's opportunities. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-STUDY-REVIEW (Undated) _ American researchers studying AIDS
tracked heterosexual couples in Uganda. In each case, one partner
was already infected, and the doctors did not tell the uninfected
partner that the other had HIV. After receiving intensive
instruction on how to prevent transmission, and access to free
condoms, the couples were followed for more than two years.
Anti-viral drugs were withheld. When the study ended, 90 more
people were HIV-infected. Many doctors have asked how such studies
in the developing world can be justified on moral grounds. By
Jerome Groopman.
</P>
<P>
   MONETARY-POLICY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Fed Chairman Alan
Greenspan has been trying, with little success so far, to cool off
an economy that is threatening to overheat and impose a degree of
temperance on Wall Street's long-running party. It is not just
Greenspan whose clout is in question. Given that companies,
consumers and investors have proven largely impervious to a series
of rate hikes by the Fed, economists are wondering whether monetary
policy still works, or at least whether it works the same way it
used to. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-NOW-CLOCK-REVIEW (San Francisco) _ The Clock of the Long
Now is a much-anticipated clock designed by the inventor and
scientist Danny Hillis to measure the next 10,000 years and beyond.
The prototype clock, an exquisite object standing some 9 feet high,
has been called the world's slowest-moving computer. Part magic box
and part conceptual art, the clock has become the cause celebre of
a heady cadre of Bay Area thinkers and futurists. By Patricia Leigh
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-ELIAN-REVIEW (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno's
friends and long-time associates say the Elian Gonzalez case has
been especially difficult for her because it is roiling the city
where she was born, grew up and served for 15 years as an immensely
popular state attorney. Miami is also the place where she plans to
return after she leaves the office of attorney general in January,
to live in the ranch house that her mother built on the edge of the
Everglades. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-NUDE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Legal minds at work in defining
nudity and interpreting the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   POPE-REPORTERS-REVIEW (Rome) _ A first-hand account of what it's
like to be a reporter traveling with Pope John Paul II. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
