<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-MOB-ART-(TRIMS)     04-01 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MOB-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING PINCH, JAPAN'S MOBS STRUGGLE FOR CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOBE, Japan _ The crisp, chill air still reeks of smoke outside
the charred Ring Ring House, a telephone dating club where four
patrons died in March in a firebombing that has raised fears of
renewed gangland violence in this otherwise gentle port city.
</P>
<P>
   On fashionable Tor Road near the boarded-up club, where the
police said clients came to arrange dates and prostitution over the
telephone, many passers-by expressed shock and dismay over the
attack, which has been linked to a turf war between rival gangs of
Yamaguchi-gumi, Japan's largest crime syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very scary and very disturbing,'' said Mio Shirakawa,
a 20-year-old college student who came with a friend to take a
picture of the scorched telephone club. ``My grandfather used to
tell me stories about how brutal the yakuza were many years ago,
but I didn't think this sort of violence existed in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the vicious attack, the authorities say, is a besieged
Japanese yakuza, or mob, that once tried to present itself as a
good public citizen but is now feeling the pinch of a weak economy
and an aggressive crackdown by police and community groups. This
accumulated threat to the mob's bread-and-butter businesses _
gambling, the sex trade, drug trafficking, protection rackets _ has
sparked a bitter and often violent struggle among rival gangs for
control of shrinking criminal enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the authorities say it has never been harder to make a
living as a mobster in Japan, and the yakuza's shrinking membership
shows it. The number of full-time yakuza members declined from
48,000 in 1994 to 43,500 in 1998, the last year police statistics
were available.
</P>
<P>
   As the country's largest and wealthiest organized crime group,
Yamaguchi-gumi has more than 17,000 members across Japan. It is
headed by Yoshinori Watanabe, the Japanese godfather of the yakuza,
and has hundreds of affiliated criminal gangs that pay monthly
honorariums to the group's headquarters here in Kobe.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfilling these monthly obligations has become increasingly
difficult as the yakuza, like the rest of Japan, has seen its
profits dwindle during the country's recent economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Those difficulties have been compounded by stricter police
enforcement of new laws intended to limit the mob's money-making
activities, particularly its protection and intimidation schemes,
as well as by successful efforts by many businesses and community
groups to drive yakuza gangs from their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the gangs are scrambling to generate revenues, not
only to meet their monthly obligations to mob bosses but also
simply to survive, the authorities said. While some yakuza groups
are expanding into new areas of business, like waste processing or
providing low-cost labor to the construction industry, other less
entrepreneurial gangs are encroaching on rival territories in
violent attacks, like the one on the Ring Ring House.
</P>
<P>
   The local police have detained two men suspected of carrying out
that fire-bombing for a Yamaguchi-gumi faction that the police say
wanted protection money. The Ring Ring House had refused, the
authorities believe, because it was already paying for protection
from a different Yamaguchi-gumi affiliate, underscoring the
increasing competition among Japanese gangs.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even as the yakuza is being squeezed across Japan, the
authorities say, it still thrives in cities and towns like Kobe,
where its operations are largely invisible to the public until an
occasional violent outburst like that at the Ring Ring House.
</P>
<P>
   On the same evening as the Ring Ring House arson, another Kobe
telephone club, just a few miles away, was also the victim of a
firebomb that injured three people. Gangs related to Yamaguchi-gumi
are the prime suspects.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the police arrested a member of a lower-ranked
Yamaguchi-gumi gang on charges of throwing a gasoline bomb into a
pachinko game parlor in nearby Itami City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody needs to do something to stop all this violence and
corruption,'' said Terumi Okamoto, who owns a women's clothing
store that was damaged in the Ring Ring House fire. ``The problem
is that in Japan, nobody is willing to take responsibility, not the
police, not the head of the mob, no one.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Yamaguchi-gumi tried to present a good public
image, and its members were rarely involved in public acts of
violence. After the devastating earthquake here in 1995, it
distributed food and other aid to quake victims.
</P>
<P>
   At its headquarters here, a heavily guarded compound
encompassing a full city block in an upscale residential district,
Yamaguchi-gumi has posted a list of rules to be followed by its
members.
</P>
<P>
   The rules state that Yamaguchi-gumi members should refrain from
``using or selling narcotics like stimulants and marijuana,'' and
should not commit acts like ``talking with a loud voice, throwing
out dust, cigarettes, or empty cans that cause trouble with the
neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   But today, Yamaguchi-gumi's leadership does not exercise the
same control over its members as it once did, and many low-ranking
gangs are engaged in illegal gun sales and the drug trade, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a telephone call to Yamaguchi-gumi's headquarters,
a man who identified himself as Nakamura said the group did not
make statements to journalists. Asked if someone in the
organization could comment on allegations that affiliate members
were involved in the recent attacks, Nakamura said: ``I don't know
such things. People just talk without any basis.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Local police officials said that while the recent firebombings
of telephone dating clubs were reason for concern, the public
should remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they were using a three-pronged approach to
reducing yakuza activity, including vigorous prosecution of the
mob's executive ranks, large-scale arrests of rank-and-file members
and tougher enforcement of recent laws to deprive the yakuza of
vital revenue sources.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuguaki Shinka, a deputy chief of the anti-mob division of the
prefecture of police, said that so far this year the police had
arrested two senior Yamaguchi-gumi members who were implicated in
gasoline bombing and harassment cases.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Shinka said, under a recently approved anti-mob
law, the police issued 170 ``stop orders'' to yakuza members who
tried to collect protection money or force individuals to pay debts
through intimidation. After issuing more than two such warnings to
a yakuza member, the police are empowered to arrest the offender,
Shinka said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the police, some Japanese citizens are taking
matters into their own hands and forming community and business
groups that are directly confronting the yakuza, and in some cases
driving the gangs away from their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In Amagasaki City, just east of here, and in the Kobe district
of Suma, citizens groups closed down the offices of yakuza gangs
that tried to collect protection fees and extort money from local
businesses and residents.
</P>
<P>
   Kenji Nakayama, a Kobe taxi driver, said, ``As long as the
yakuza remain in their own world, I don't really care if they fight
and kill each other, but I get angry when they cross into our world
and kill innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, representatives from a cross section of local
industries in Hygyo prefecture held a summit meeting here to
discuss ways of combating yakuza influence in the business
community. The meeting resulted in the creation of an industry
association whose goal is to expel mob groups.
</P>
<P>
   Association members have posted anti-mob signs in their shop
windows and at work sites. The signs state: ``We are a company that
rejects the mob. We refuse to donate any money to the mob.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had all grown tired of being pressured and intimidated by
the mob to make payments,'' said Yoshiro Akiyama, a civil
engineering firm executive who is president of the anti-mob
industry group, ``and we decided that we were not going to take it
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
