</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-POLITICS-535(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHADOWY MAN BEHIND PERU'S PRESIDENT BECOMES A POLITICAL ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ President Alberto K. Fujimori's intelligence chief,
Vladimiro Montesinos is rarely seen in public. Former associates
describe him as a loner with a taste for history books and
classical music. The few photographs that do exist show him to be a
man with a wide smile and a fondness for double-breasted suits, a
handkerchief folded neatly in the breast pocket.
</P>
<P>
   To those outside the Fujimori administration, however, the
53-year-old Montesinos is known as the Rasputin of Peru's politics,
whose power in large part derives from his intimate knowledge of
the president's deepest personal secrets and who is held
responsible for a daunting catalog of political sins.
</P>
<P>
   He was, according to a critical book published here this week, a
dominant force behind shutting down the Congress and Supreme Court
in 1992, the eavesdropping on opposition presidential candidates in
the 1995 elections, and years of manipulation of judges and the
news media that has helped keep the president firmly ensconced in
power.
</P>
<P>
   Now Montesinos is accused by opponents of running a campaign of
dirty tricks intended to assure Fujimori's re-election on April 9.
Montesinos himself has become a top issue in the race _ one that
has hurt Fujimori by association.
</P>
<P>
   An opposition newspaper recently obtained detailed information
showing that Montesinos has in recent years had an annual income of
more than $2 million and, refueling old charges leveled by
political enemies but never proved, that he was in the pay of drug
traffickers. Another newspaper published photographs showing trucks
delivering tons of Fujimori campaign paraphernalia to the
headquarters of the National Intelligence Service, the agency
Montesinos runs, for distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos has been a crucial ally of the Clinton administration
in efforts to stop drug trafficking in the Andean region, and U.S.
officials have not mentioned him by name in public criticisms of
the current election campaign. But opposition politicians and
journalists here hold him responsible for television and newspaper
smear campaigns against several presidential candidates as well as
other irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   His role in the campaign is the subject of almost daily
speculation in the opposition media. He is repeatedly the subject
of questions at news conferences given by presidential candidates,
and several have promised to fire him and to conduct criminal
investigations of his activities should they finally succeed after
10 years in wresting the presidency from Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been fatal for the country,'' Alberto Andrade, mayor of
Lima and a leading presidential candidate, told El Comercio, Lima's
leading daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montesinos is the Machiavelli who over the years has built the
machine for Fujimori's re-election,'' Andrade said in a separate
interview, ``from the appointment of friendly members of the
electoral tribunal, to the appointment of friendly judges who have
assisted in substituting the owners of critical television stations
with minority shareholders friendly to the president, to the firing
of judges who opposed his re-election to an unconstitutional third
term.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Montesinos was born into a family of Marxists. He joined the
army and rose to the rank of captain before he was expelled in 1977
on allegations that he sold state secrets to the CIA. He went on to
practice law and defended drug traffickers against prosecution in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A retired general, Francisco Morales Bermudez, Peru's last
military dictator, publicly disclosed that Montesinos, while still
an army captain, had forged signatures to allow him to visit
Washington furtively and meet with American officials.
</P>
<P>
   And in a challenge to the intimate relationship that Montesinos
_ and, by extension, Fujimori _ maintains with the Peruvian army,
Morales Bermudez accused Montesinos of manipulating top military
promotions to aid Fujimori's political interests.
</P>
<P>
   Like a good spy, Montesinos does not answer any of these
charges, and he did not respond to multiple requests for an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori, in an interview, said he had complete confidence
in Montesinos, whom he described as ``superintelligent, very agile,
very analytical.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said that there was nothing unusual about a successful
lawyer acquiring riches and that he had no problem with Montesinos'
having defended shady characters in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He provides the security that allows the government to be
successful,'' the president said, crediting the intelligence chief
with helping to defeat two terrorist insurrections and adding that
he is a crucial ally of the Clinton administration in efforts to
stop drug trafficking and assure stability in the Andean region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very good relationship between the Drug Enforcement
Administration, the CIA and Montesinos,'' Fujimori said boldly.
``The CIA calls Montesinos from time to time. There is cooperation.
It is good for both countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mansfield, a CIA spokesman, said, ``As a matter of policy,
we don't comment on such matters.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials have long refused to confirm or deny any ties
to Montesinos, only noting that last year they cut off a three-year
$200,000 State Department aid program to his intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Peter Romero, the acting assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, called Montesinos last year to lobby for
Peruvian help on a United Nations human rights resolution in Geneva
condemning Cuba. Peru did not vote with the United States, and an
aide to Romero refused to speak about his conversations with
foreign officials or comment on Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been sending a mixed message on Montesinos,'' said
Elliott Abrams, the Reagan administration's assistant secretary of
state for inter-American affairs, who is now a paid consultant for
a Peruvian television station owner who was stripped of control of
his station after it broadcast reports in 1997 criticizing
Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the position of decrying human rights abuses on
Monday while working with Montesinos on Tuesday,'' Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate who has been careful not to attack Montesinos
directly is Alejandro Toledo, a business school professor who is
Fujimori's strongest challenger. Toledo campaign aides say
privately that the intelligence chief is behind news media reports
that Toledo fathered an illegitimate daughter and refused to
support her. The aides and Toledo's wife, Eliane Karp, deny the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, by his own account, has been receiving polling
information from Montesinos' agency, spurring speculation that he
might be ready to make some kind of arrangement with the
intelligence chief after the campaign is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toledo does not want to confront Montesinos directly,'' said
Carlos Tapia, a former lecturer at the Army Intelligence School.
``He'll seek a negotiated settlement but he won't allow Montesinos
to stay on if he wins. The question is how he will work that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos' influence over the military is rooted in his
extensive collection of files of personal information on young
officers beginning from his days as an army intelligence officer in
the 1970s. Furthermore, in his first term as president Fujimori
gave Montesinos broad independent powers as his go-between with a
security apparatus and military with which Fujimori had had little
previous contact.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence officials are supposed to keep a low profile, but
Montesinos has had an uncomfortably high profile since 1996, when a
drug trafficker, Demetrio Chavez, publicly said that he paid
Montesinos $50,000 a month in exchange for landing rights at a
jungle airfield outside an army base. Chavez, appearing visibly
disoriented, later retracted his charge but Montesinos' had already
become a household name.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has tried repeatedly but unsuccessfully to improve
Montesinos' public image, particularly after the 1997 rescue of 71
hostages held for four months at the Japanese ambassador's
residence by terrorists. Montesinos was credited with planning the
rescue, and he appeared for the first time publicly in years when
he triumphantly toured the residence after its liberation.
</P>
<P>
   If Montesinos is a political liability for Fujimori, many
Peruvian analysts wonder why the president does not dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, said Francisco Loayza, a former official at the
intelligence agency who introduced Fujimori to Montesinos 10 years
ago, is that the intelligence chief knows too much about the
president's private life. As Fujimori's personal lawyer during his
first presidential campaign, Montesinos handled some outstanding
tax matters, and later his divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Loayza also charged that Montesinos handled the paperwork to
cover up Fujimori's birth in Japan since the Peruvian constitution
requires that the president be a native-born citizen. Fujimori has
repeatedly denied the charge, saying he was born in Peru shortly
after his Japanese parents immigrated here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fujimori is Montesinos' hostage,'' Loayza said. ``While
Montesinos has everything on Fujimori, Fujimori has nothing on
Montesinos.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to respond, Fujimori began to speak in the third person:
``Please. Fujimori cannot be controlled,'' he said. ``There is no
power above or behind him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
