<P>
   AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS _ LONDON _ Nomsa Mwale, 12, is having to
raise her four siblings in Zimbabwe after the death of both her
parents to AIDS. Last Sunday, the children faced eviction from
their shack by their uncle. We give an update. Also we are looking
at the situation of Lina Smoke, an 88-year-old grandmother forced
to raise four children after the death of her own children to AIDS.
(Roughton, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   With any photos not used in March 26 package.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ECONOMY-$ADV02 _ HAVANA _ Ten years ago the buzzards were
circling over Fidel Castro's communist Cuba as the country nearly
collapsed in tandem with its long-time patron, the Soviet Union.
Despite the fondest hopes of Miami's exiles, though, Castro appears
to have once again beaten the odds, thanks mostly to a booming
tourism industry that attracted more than 1.65 million visitors
last year. With ambitious plans to attract 10 million visitors by
2010, tourism has brought an influx of foreign investment _ and
American dollars _ that is slowly transforming Old Havana's
decaying buildings into gems of dazzling colonial architecture,
with five-star hotels and high-end restaurants to rival the
fanciest Caribbean destination. But the tourists and their dollars
have also opened a crack in the state-run economy, allowing a tiny
private sector to emerge. (Williams, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/CUBA-PRIVATE-$ADV02 _ HAVANA _ Felix Garces doesn't dream of
leaving Cuba to live a better life in the United States, but he
does want a better life for his own family. Trained in Russia as a
linguist, Garces found his salary of US$13 a month as a government
translator wasn't enough to support his family, so he started a
bicycle-taxi service, shuttling tourists and Havana residents
around in his three-wheel, two-seat rig that resembles a ricksaw.
Now he earns up to US$100 a month. But life is still hard _ he must
pay for a license to operate the taxi, and find tires and parts to
keep it running. (Williams, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the week. The layout is
now available)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0401: CUBA'S ECONOMIC RESURGENCE _ Tourism, U.S.
dollars are influencing Cuba in both subtle and dramatic ways as
the island nation wavers between its Soviet-influenced past and an
uncertain future. Ten years after experts predicted the collapse of
the Soviet Union would send Fidel Castro's communist Cuba to the
graveyard of broken socialist dreams, Havana is bustling with
workers, visitors and a tourist invasion that poses stiff
competition for its Caribbean neighbors. (Williams, Cox News
Service). Art includes a 3-column color photo of a busy market in
Cuba, a 1-column color photo of tourists dining at a Cuban tourist
destination, a 18-pica color photo of a Cuban photographer taking
pphotos of tourists and a 18-pica color photo women dresses in
traditional Cuban garb posing for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CUBA'S IMPOVERISHED CITIZENRY _ Since the collapse of the
Soviet Union and the end of its billions in annual aid to Cuba,
day-to-day life for many Cubans has been a ceaseless grind. Trips
to the state-run store to pick up monthly rations sometimes yield
empty shelves, leaving people scrambling to earn American dollars
so they can purchase life's necessities in the free-market stores
that now dot Havana's neighborhoods. (Williams, Cox News Service)
Art includes a 2-column color photo of a Cuban doctor laughing with
her neighborhood friend)
</P>
