<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   DEADFAMILY _ Waynesville, N.C._ For more than 50 years, Earl and
Cora Phillips lived a simple life in a tiny cinder block house high
above I-40, a curious speck of Appalachian Americana on the edge of
the Great Smoky Moutains. But the house must have shone like a
beacon to the two men accused of killing the couple and three other
members of the Phillips clan. Authorities say the suspects already
had killed one man and were running from police when their pickup
truck broke down not far from Earl Lane. The case stands as one of
North Carolina's worst spree killings in modern history. It also
represents the worst nightmare of isolated country people: a
lonesome vulnerability to strangers at the door. (Scruggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AL-AMIN-CHESTNUT _ When his law office was on Jeff Davis Avenue,
J.L. Chestnut Jr. poured his heart _ and funny bone _ into the sign
he hung on the brick wall outside. ``PARKING FOR AFRO AMERICAN
ONLY,'' the red block letters still proclaim. ``ALL OTHERS WILL BE
TOWED.'' The name of Selma's first black attorney _ J.L.Chestnut _
is written inside a black double-pointed arrow at the bottom of the
sign, showing where the rule applied. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the week. The layout
will be available Friday before 2 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0402: A SEASON ON THE LAND _ More flue-cured
tobacco is grown in Pitt County, North Carolina, than anywhere else
in the nation. The culture and the economy are rooted in tending
the leaf, and in the self-reliant way of life such labor demands.
Yet as court rulings, public opinion and pressure from Washington
alter the fortunes of tobacco, change has made its way into the
fields. There will be fewer and fewer lives like the ones Betty and
W.C. Moore of Bethel live, shaped and bound by the rituals of
passing seasons on the farm. (Schulken, The Daily Reflector)
</P>
<P>
   w/TOBACCO PRIMER In their infancy tobacco plants look like tiny
shamrocks. As many as a million plants have taken root in the
warmth of W.C. Moore's greenhouse, snug in Styrofoam seed crates,
resting on a bed of water. They were sowed in mid-March, and in
April, when the threat of a hard freeze is past, they will be
transplanted in the field, the first crop of a new century. The
green fuzz sprouting in the seed crates doesn't look like much. But
with an average price, the half-million pounds of leaf it will grow
into could net $850,000. (Schulken, The Daily Reflector)
</P>
<P>
   PHYS-ED _ ORLANDO _ Thousands of physical education teachers are
starting an uphill battle to reverse the gradual disappearance of
phys ed classes in American schools, especially in grades 7 through
12. The decline makes kids fatter and sicker, says Surgeon General
David Satcher. It can also make them mean, says Senate
Appropriations Committee chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, who
believes that the lack of a place to let off steam increases
violence and misbehavior by adolescents. Sporting goods
manufacturers are supplying $1 million and international sport and
phys ed groups are offering moral support and research findings to
back up the crusade, which will have its first test in a Senate
vote on a $400 million physical education bill this spring.
(Mollison, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/PHYS-ED-POLL_ New national poll shows parents (81 percent) and
teens (71 percent) overwhelmingly favor requiring phys ed daily in
all grades in K-12 schools. Yet fewer than half the teens report
having daily phys ed. Teens and parents offer slightly different
excuses for not voluntarily getting as much physical activity as
they should. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SWEATSHIRT-CAPITAL _ MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ This town used to call
itself the ``Sweatshirt Capital of the World.'' Now, it may be the
closed textile factory capital of the world. Town officials are
even offering to give away land and closed facilities to entice new
employers, but are finding _ like other towns in Dixie _ that cheap
offshore labor is hard to fight. (Dart, Cox New Service) MOVED
Monday in (a) national and (l) lifestyule categories. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The National Rifle Association's phony
cry-babying over the Clinton administration's supposed failure to
enforce existing gun laws bids fair to make ``crocodile
indignation'' a companion cliche to ``crocodile tears.'' The NRA's
lament is thick and oily with insincerity. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ You hear lots of talk these days
among the winners of the Cold War about how the Russians still
can't get their act together. A decade after the collapse of
communism, it's fashionable to kick around a nation led by an
ex-KGB spy with a knack for stirring up a patriotic fever over
rebellious Chechnya. Brand the Russian voters as dysfunctional
dupes if you want. But they sure do know how to reach their polling
places to perform their civic duty. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVES
THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   COKE-DAFT _ Doug Daft never had time to enjoy a honeymoon period
since becoming the effective leader of the Coca-Cola Co. in
December. But if he did, it would surely end on Tuesday. That's
when Coke's new chairman and chief executive will be facing
information-hungry analysts, who will be loaded for bear. Daft will
be on Wall Street for his most important meeting with analysts to
date. The stock has fallen substantially since he took over from M.
Douglas Ivester. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-DAY _ Just two weeks from today, unfinished income tax
returns will turn into a crisis for millions of Americans. We get
two extra days this year to fill out the paperwork and write the
checks. Pprocrastination is a mistake: The closer we get to the
deadline, the harder it will get to find help, professional or
volunteer, and the tougher it will get to find copies of any
missing forms and instructions. Even on the Internet, which has
been a blessing to millions, you can't be surprised if last-minute
traffic jams develop. Here's advice on what to do right now.
(Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHO-INVEST _ Investors are people, too. Theoretically, that
suggests that understanding investor psychology can give you a
better understanding of market trends. And indeed it can, according
to David Hirshleifer of Ohio State University, whose specialties
include investor psychology. (McNaughton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   GIVERS _ You don't have to be a Rockefeller to be a
philanthropist. With the economic tide floating all our boats, it's
easier than ever to give back, particularly in small increments.
For instance: pay back your college scholarship, donate a book in
memorial (or for a gift), recycle your newspaper for a good cause
... . (Grand Junction)
</P>
<P>
   MOVEDSLEEP _ Sleep is a highly valued commodity, yet surveys
show that we are too busy during the day to get a good night's
sleep at night. (Waco Tribune-Herald) WITH PHOTOS.
MOVEDENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-ATLANTA _ The parallels between Houston and Atlanta are
compelling. Sun-belt giants of industry, both are striving to
establish themselves as cultural centers. Houston has an edge in
some regards. Both cities have resident symphony, opera, ballet
companies and major regional theaters. But Houston's main museum
has ten times the money the High does. And the Alley Theatre has
won a regional Tony Award, while the Alliance has been ignored.
Atlanta, however, won what is rapidly becoming known as the Robert
Spano sweepstakes; the ASO secured the heralded Spano as its new
music director, while the Houston Symphony still looks to fill its
vacancy. Houston's Grand Opera, however, has a national reputation
for introducing new works, a trend it continues on April 14 when it
debuts ``Cold Sassy Tree.'' This story will be an overall look at
Houston as a culture capital, with specifics about how ``Cold Sassy
Tree'' came to be done by the Houston Opera as opposed to, say, the
Atlanta Opera. (Sabulis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
