<HEADER>
A4283 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-RACER-SANDERS02-C     04-01 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RACER-SANDERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanders back on track
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ronnie Sanders could be called short-track racing's
Comeback Kid. Except he's no kid anymore.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Sanders, 54, appeared to be nearing the end of a
remarkable career on the short tracks of the Southeast. Since his
first race in 1967, he had won more than 500 races and at least 10
track championships.
</P>
<P>
   But by the late 1990s, his career appeared to be nearing its
end. The victories that once came so readily were becoming elusive.
And his car owner and biggest booster, his uncle Bob Stinchcomb,
died of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if I could make it without Bob,'' Sanders said.
``This is a very expensive sport.''
</P>
<P>
   But it changed, starting with the 1999 season opener for the
Southern All Stars, a series of short-track stock-car races across
the South.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders won the first race at Birmingham International Raceway
and went on to score five more victories, including the prestigious
World Classic, also at Birmingham. The Fayetteville driver won the
All Stars' Hard Charger award, given to the driver who improves his
position the most during each race. And he was honored for leading
more laps than any other driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been 10 years since I had done anything like that,''
Sanders said. ``When we weren't winning, we didn't ever stop
trying, but it got awfully discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   He has started this season with another victory and a
second-place finish in the first two races of the season and is the
Southern All Stars points leader.
</P>
<P>
   Age, it seems, is not a hindrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as good as I ever did,'' Sanders said. ``And with the
way my cars are driving now, age is not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The only change evident is a little more patience behind the
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past couple of years, I've tried to drive a little bit
smarter than I used to,'' Sanders said. ``Last year, I ran second a
lot at times during races when I could have been leading. Years
ago, I tried to lead every lap, if I could.''
</P>
<P>
   During the years, Sanders has built a reputation as one of the
fiercest competitors in the sport. Former Atlanta Falcons head
coach Jerry Glanville now drives stock cars and has raced against
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie's a great competitor,'' Glanville said. ``Every single
lap, he's trying to beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Glanville said Sanders reminds him of one of pro football's most
durable players. ``Ronnie's the Chuck Bednarik of racing,'' he
said. ``He goes to work every day, lines up and kicks your tail.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Hansard, a Southern All Stars driver from Tyrone, has raced
against Sanders and worked on his pit crew. He said Sanders is one
of the hardest-working people he knows _ on and off the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man gets up at 5:30 every morning and does what needs to
be done,'' Hansard said. ``And he's in better shape physically than
99 percent of the drivers out there. When you get down to the last
10 laps of a 200-lap race, some drivers are about given out, but
not Sanders; he's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansard said a trip to Sanders' race shop is a good indicator of
how hard Sanders works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have chairs in our shop, because we like to sit down and
read the paper sometimes,'' Hansard said. ``There aren't any chairs
in Ronnie's shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said the only regret he has about his racing career is
that he didn't try harder to break into Winston Cup. He ran about a
dozen Winston Cup and ARCA superspeedway races in the '80s, but his
team was underfunded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could have gotten a good ride then,'' Sanders said.
``But at that time, our interest was more in winning on the short
tracks, and our Winston Cup effort was secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back on it, it should have been the other way
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Still he is proud of his accomplishments in his short Cup
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always had very little financially, but we were able to do
some things that teams with millions of dollars haven't been able
to do,'' he said. ``We made the Daytona 500 three times. I ran
seventh in the 125-mile qualifying race in 1981 and finished 18th
in the 500, even though we had a wheel break and cracked a cylinder
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1987, we ran the tires that Bill Elliott's crew took off
his car and we still finished 21st. During the day, we ran with a
lot of good cars, but there is only so much you can do on old
tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Winston Cup driver Donnie Allison, now a consultant for
Winston Cup teams, raced against Sanders in his driving days. He
said Sanders had a good chance of being a Winston Cup star.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the skills,'' Allison said. ``He just never got with
the right team or car owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison and most of the other drivers Sanders ran against in the
1980s are retired, while Sanders continues to race against drivers
that are his children's age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other night I loaned a driver a Winston jacket that I won
in 1981,'' Sanders said. ``I told him the jacket was older than he
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
