<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SERBIA-MONTENEGRO-2TA     04-01 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-MONTENEGRO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIA'S BLOCKADE RAISES TENSION WITH ITS SMALLER PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ Once, even after the old Yugoslavia
disintegrated in bloodshed, the traveler might barely have noticed
there was a border in the mountains between Serbia and Montenegro.
Other republics left the Yugoslav fold, but these two were still
joined in a federation, and relations were so good that there was
no need for police to oversee the lively traffic on a practically
invisible border.
</P>
<P>
   Today, that traffic has slowed to the barest trickle, and police
forces on both sides keep a careful watch on any vehicles that do
cross.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside the town of Bijelo Polje, the last big Montenegrin
town before the border with Serbia, a handful of police in dark
navy blue uniforms wave down cars heading for Serbia and check
documents. Ten miles down the twisting mountain road in Brodarevo,
and again at the main junction town of Prijepolje, Serbian police
in grey uniforms carry out more thorough checks.
</P>
<P>
   For the last month, in an eerie echo of tactics adopted by the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, against Slovenia and other
republics that broke away from Belgrade in the early 1990s, Serbian
authorities have imposed a strict trade ban on goods passing
between Montenegro and Serbia. The few drivers traveling through to
Montenegro said they were unable to bring even small quantities of
goods bought in Serbia for personal use. The only truck driver
coming through this day had special papers from the army.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they wouldn't even allow a tin of ham,'' said
Zoran Laric, a restaurant owner who had checked the new rules with
the Serbian police.
</P>
<P>
   The trade ban appears to be Belgrade's latest attempt to
undermine the government of Montenegro and its westward-leaning
president Milo Djukanovic, and it is already hurting local
Montenegrin businesses. Coming alongside a propaganda onslaught and
increased military activity by the Yugoslav army in the region, it
has added an urgency to the sharp debates raging between the
pro-and anti-Milosevic factions in Montenegro, an enclave of
600,000 fiercely proud people divided into clans whose
centuries-old feuds and alliances are riven with bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   The blockade has raised the specter of a permanent split and
even a forced division of the two republics. ``We already feel the
separation,'' said a Muslim businessman in Bijelo Polje who would
give his name only as Daco. ``I am very scared that the same thing
that happened in Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Macedonia will
happen to Montenegro. The scenario so far is the same, and the man
guiding it is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Daco and a fellow businessman, both local shoe manufacturers,
complained that 31 of the 32 items they need for making their shoes
come from Serbia. Only the leather is produced in Montenegro and
even that supply is in jeopardy as the leather producers have also
been hit by the trade ban. ``We have a huge problem, production has
fallen drastically,'' said the second businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to make us believe we cannot live without them,''
said Daco of the Serbian action.
</P>
<P>
   In Montenegro, which was never a wealthy region and has been
further impoverished by 10 years of war and international sanctions
that go with being formally tied to Milosevic, the immediate
effects of the Serbian blockade are rising prices and falling
production. Until last month, 85 percent of Montenegro's trade was
with Serbia. Now, a fraction of that business continues along
special channels apparently sanctioned by the Serbian leadership,
forcing the Montenegrins to think about other markets.
</P>
<P>
   There is an underlying feeling of dread in Bijelo Polje, a town
where half the population is Muslim, and that has already been
buffeted by the tensions of the wars in neighboring Bosnia and then
in the nearby Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian refugees from Kosovo have swelled the town's population
and added an element of anger. Among them are former police
officers from Kosovo, and people suspected of committing war crimes
there before NATO troops entered Kosovo last June. Crowds of young
people throng Bijelo Polje's main street, sitting around with
nothing to do while Montenegrin police patrol the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army is also in evidence. On Thursday, a truck full
of tough-looking soldiers in combat gear, some with bandannas on
their heads and camouflage paint smeared on their faces, pulled
into a base on the edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   A refugee from Kosovo blanched at the description of that scene.
``That means they are here, they are preparing something, believe
me,'' he said, referring to pro-Milosevic forces.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a grenade exploded in the town's police station.
The local authorities put it down to a couple of drunkards and say
it was not a political gesture, yet admit it is a symptom of social
tension.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin police, who number approximately 20,000, have
the assignment of keeping the lid on any violence, providing
everything from traffic police to specialist paramilitary teams
capable of taking on the Yugoslav army if need be.
</P>
<P>
   The government is open about some of its preparations. On a
stretch of wasteland just south of the capital, Podgorica, a
special police anti-terrorist unit on Friday staged a raid for
journalists on an abandoned house. Black-clad and masked, they
burst through a window and blew out doors, shooting dead their
supposed opponents with ruthless efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Built up in the last two years by Djukanovic's government, the
Montenegrin special police are the talk of this small capital, and
the republic's best hope for defense should it come to conflict
with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone tries to discipline Montenegro by force, we will
prevent him by all means,'' said the commander of the Special
Police, Veselin Veljovic. He supports the government line that
every effort must be made to avoid a conflict with Serbia, but
warns that Montenegro may not be able to control events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a balance of fear will preserve peace. The moment
Belgrade thinks we are weak they will take steps. We know they are
planning that. We will show that we are neither weak, nor
defenseless,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is already a standoff between the Montenegrin police and
the Yugoslav army, the main protagonists in the growing divide
between Montenegro and Serbia. They circle each other warily and
monitor each other's activities across the republic. Numerically
the police have the upper hand, but the army is far superior when
it comes to firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders of the 2nd Army, which is based in Podgorica, do not
appear to relish the idea of conflict against Montenegrins. ``We
are trying to keep out of politics, but the politicians are
dragging us in,'' said a spokesman for the 2nd Army.
</P>
<P>
   The government says that a recent agreement with the army for
joint border controls has reduced the tension and put the
relationship between the police and military on a clearer footing.
Yet the busy activity of the special police tells another tale.
Police officials say the government has not let on just how tense
relations are, and how close to a clash the two have come on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslims in Bijelo Polje look forlorn when asked if they
think the police could prevent a conflict. ``It has never been so
bad, but I have never seen the people so calm,'' said Daco.
``Perhaps after 10 years of war and troubles they have become
deadened, like a piece of wood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
