<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES02-COX     04-01 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will any team be able to stop the Yankees?
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yankee-hating, a noble pursuit, remains one of
baseball's most time-honored traditions, spawned by decades of
arrogant success, bad movies, arrogant ownership and even more
arrogant fans. Native son Joe Torre couldn't even stand them.
</P>
<P>
   The great philosopher Bill Veeck used to say that when the New
York Yankees failed it was ``one of those exquisite times when life
and art are in perfect conjunction.'' And he was probably
underselling.
</P>
<P>
   But last fall, the baseball universe stopped what it was doing
to behold the Yankees. October, like the October before it and much
like the last half-decade, became another inning-by-inning
verification that this was a special team in the middle of a
special time doing something special.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-1 run through the postseason and a 25th World Series
title. A third World Series Championship in four years. A World
Series win streak of 12 in a row. Eighteen wins in 19 postseason
games, dating back to the 1998 ALCS. Casey Stengel's five
consecutive championship clubs, 1949-53, did not dominate in the
postseason like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mentality is to win games,'' Torre said. ``How much better
do you want it than winning? Being on a world championship team
stays with you forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager is hardly the first to evoke eternal terminology
around his team. If the Yankees keep this up _and only a few more
gray hairs suggest they can't _ they will become the first team in
more than a quarter-century to win three World Series in a row. The
last was the Oakland A's, 1972-74.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Yankees have done it with style and some grace _
and maybe just a little arrogance _ that has left even the
bitterest rivals with a sense of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play the game right, whether you like them or not, their
attitude,'' Boston manager Jimy Williams said. ``They play with
respect for the game. Maybe that's why I admire them so much, the
way they play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They did everything right that series,'' Red Sox catcher Jason
Varitek said, referring to New York's ALCS victory. ``They played
pretty much perfect baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why Las Vegas likes them to do it again. The
roster has been disturbed slightly; the missing include reserve
outfielder Chad Curtis (traded to Texas), fifth starter Hideki
Irabu (traded to Montreal), designated hitter Chili Davis
(retired), catcher Joe Girardi (signed with Chicago Cubs) and
reserve infielder Luis Sojo (signed with Pittsburgh).
</P>
<P>
   But the engine driving the franchise remains untouched. The
four-man rotation of Orlando Hernandez, who had a wicked spring,
David Cone, Roger Clemens and Andy Pettitte can expect to be the
best in baseball this year. Ricky Ledee, thrust into a starter's
role in left field, responded by leading the team in spring home
runs. Derek Jeter, now just 25, hit .400 nearly the whole
exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Bernie Williams remains the popular vote for
toughest out in the major leagues. Closer Mariano Rivera led the
majors in saves last year (45), dropped his career postseason ERA
to 0.38 and then picked up the World Series MVP trophy.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees' spring record (12-18) so disturbed owner
George Steinbrenner that he held a late-night meeting in Tampa to
root out the problem, rival teams only laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Call it pennant envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to hand it to us because we're the Yankees,''
Cone said. ``We don't have a problem with complacency. If there was
any of that, it would have shown up before. But we've won it three
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee mystique, an ethereal commodity sparked for decades by
the likes of Gary Cooper, William Bendix and Reggie Jackson, might
never be so much in evidence. This weekend, the Yankees flew to
Houston to play the first exhibition games in new Enron Field,
before flying on to San Francisco to do the same for new Pacfic
Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Pirates already are arranging for the Yanks to
play the first games in PNC Park, when it opens in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the name. It's the Yankees,'' said San Francisco's Barry
Bonds, not generally noted for being overappreciative of anything.
``How many people in this world would love to play for the Yankees?
Or have the opportunity to play against them? They won 25 World
Series. That's huge.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25 titles are the most by any team competing in the four
major North American professional sports. The Yankees' share came
over a 78-year period; the Montreal Canadiens won their 24 Stanley
Cups over an 80-year span. Those numbers make the Yankees the
winningest professional team, just as they insist they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in New York when they won five in a row, I remember
that,'' said Torre, who was raised in Brooklyn, the son of a NYC
detective. ``That's probably what kept me from bring a Yankee fan _
to want to pull for someone who was more of a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is that challenge still there, some 50 years later? A
primary advantage is the franchise's wealth. Funded by a monstrous
$50 million broadcast contract, the Yankees are able to do things
other teams can't, an inequity inherent in the baseball business.
Their payroll will approach $94 million _ Williams just signed an
$87.5 million, seven-year deal _ and the club soon will pay bigger
sums to keep Jeter and Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   But spending money is the effect, not the cause. Williams,
Jeter, Rivera, Pettitte, Ledee, catcher Jorge Posada and outfielder
Shane Spencer all were developed within the Yankee farm system. And
the system remains as fully stocked as any in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Middle infielder Alfonso Soriano, third baseman (and Michigan
quarterback) Drew Henson, shortstop D'Angelo Jimenez and first
baseman Nick Johnson could wind up being better as a group than
what is up in the Bronx right now. Right-hander Ryan Bradley
stumbled in his first major-league exposure last summer, just as
left-hander Ed Yarnall stuggled this spring. But both will inherit
major roles with the big club. Jake Westbrook, who came over from
Montreal in the Irabu trade, made a strong impression in his first
major-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got the system set up so they can slowly start moving
guys when they're ready,'' Jeter said. ``They don't have to rush
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they get to New York, they find another dividend _ Torre,
whom Steinbrenner dubbed the best manager he's ever had. Duh.
Chided in the tabloids as ``Clueless Joe'' when hired in 1996,
Torre has an innate talent for handling Steinbrenner, diverting the
New York press, presiding over a calm and professional clubhouse
and then winning the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees respond to him. Missing nearly seven weeks last
season for treatment of prostate cancer, Torre returned to the
dugout on May 18 when the team lost in Boston, dropped to 21-16 and
fell to second place. After a three-week interval, the Yanks simply
took off, playing .623 baseball, fending off Boston and winning 98
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't go to the World Series and lose it; they went to
the World Series and swept it,'' Boston first baseman Mike Stanley
said. ``It's hard to say you've gained ground on a team that has
won back-to-back World Series. And it's not like they've made a
whole lot of changes, lost a bunch of players.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, this will be an even older team in 2000. Only
three members of the Opening Day lineup will be under 30. The three
mainstays of the rotation average 36 years old, and right fielder
Paul O'Neill is 37. El Duque might be 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really see this as a Chicago Bulls last-hurrah run for
us,'' Cone said. ``We have some great prospects coming up. Paul
O'Neill and I have talked about this. We're getting late in our
careers, and we want to win another title to validate all the other
championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the countryside, they'll really hate to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
