<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4288 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-PITCHING02     04-01 1730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PITCHING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time's gaining on Braves' big three
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLATNA _ John Smoltz had a grin on his face as he walked past
several teammates toward his locker and announced, ``Dead man
walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a couple of days had passed since Smoltz had learned, after
five years of fighting it, that the ligament in his right elbow had
finally given way. The Braves would be without the services of one
of their three Cy Young winners for the entire season for the first
time since the rotation had been assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz is walking evidence of something the Braves and their
fans don't exactly like to think about _ the mortality of their
starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The National League's team of the 1990s enters the 2000 season
wiser and older. Smoltz turns 33 on May 15, Greg Maddux will be 34
on April 14, and Tom Glavine turned 34 on March 25. Smoltz is the
only one who has shown serious signs of slowing down. But Glavine
and Maddux struggled early last season, going a combined 7-9 with a
4.76 ERA in April and May.
</P>
<P>
   Those problems might have had more to do with a shrinking strike
zone than anything else, but they brought up the inevitable
question: How long can they go?
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought if I could pitch until I'm 30 that'd be
great,'' said Maddux, who is signed through 2002. ``After 10 years,
I'm on extra credit.''
</P>
<P>
   So, does he see himself pitching until he's 37? Or 40? How about
300 wins?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really look that far ahead,'' Maddux said. ``I'm going
to do what I can this year, enjoy it. I spent a couple years where
I kept waiting for the end of the year, kept waiting for the season
to start, or waiting for the All-Star break, or waiting for the
playoffs. I forgot to enjoy it along the way, so I stopped doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, whose contract expires after 2001 with an option for
2002, like Maddux is a control pitcher, which means he can feel
good about his chances of pitching for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel like I do right now, I'll go for a long time,''
Glavine said. ``Hopefully, I'll get (to) 200 (wins) this year. The
realistic goal that's out there for me is 250 wins. I'm (63) wins
away from that. Average 14 or 15 a year, that's another five years
or so and I think I can pitch that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, because of a mid-90s fastball and a nasty slider and
their toll on his elbow, doesn't have as good a chance to last, and
he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago my (goal) was to play until I'm 40,'' Smoltz
said. ``I had worked my whole life to do this. I was going to get
the most out of it. But when you realize that it's got you and you
don't have it, that's when my walk with God and my faith changed
me. ... Baseball's not my god anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz's injury actually might prolong his career. Having
ligament transplant surgery could ensure him three or four years
more than he would have had with a weakened elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be forced out because of an injury,'' Smoltz
said. ``I like to think I still have some unfinished work.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching them all has been a former pitcher with a unique
perspective. Braves broadcaster and Hall of Famer Don Sutton
pitched until he was 43. He won 324 games, one of only 20 pitchers
to reach 300 or more victories, and his 5,282 1/3 innings pitched
ranks seventh all-time.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's take on who, what and how long:
</P>
<P>
   ``John Smoltz has the personality to be a reliever,'' Sutton
said. ``In order to get John's attention, it's got to be something
big on the line. I'm not sure he's ever been long-range oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``(What Maddux and Glavine do) from the neck up is going to
decide how long they want to go. They have very uncomplicated,
simple deliveries. Barring some freak injury, they should not get
hurt. ... They've already made the adjustments. They know how to
bum their way through games, how to change speeds, win when they're
not at their best. Glavine learned that about his fourth year in
the big leagues. Maddux knew it as a 13-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one has any guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can predict how long a pitcher will last,'' Braves
orthopedist Joe Chandler said. ``It's a genetic thing. Aside from
that, it's taking care of your body, staying in shape and pacing
yourself, and then there's luck. ... They're smart. They know their
bodies well. (They know how) to play within themselves and maximize
what they do have.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz is the creative one, trying everything from acupuncture
to chiropractic care to massage therapy. The more traditional
Glavine is the one most likely to pass up doughnuts and bacon in
the clubhouse breakfast spread for a bagel with no cream cheese and
some fruit, and to wash down vitamins with his coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's offseason regimen is mostly about resting his arm and
shoulder. While not exactly the picture of health, Maddux said he
has cut down on fast food. ``It's only if you're in a hurry type
thing,'' he said. ``It's not, `Oh, I'm going there because I want
to.'''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Glavine nor Maddux has noticed much of a physical change
so far. Maddux said he's lost a step or two running, but his arm
feels better than it has in years.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine said the same thing. His worst arm problems came in 1992
and 1993, but in the past several years he has thrown harder than
he did early in his career. He noticed a difference in his
conditioning, so he made some changes. He used to take four to six
weeks off from working out in the offseason; now he takes only two
weeks, because it's harder to get back in shape.
</P>
<P>
   As he has gotten older, Glavine has questioned his approach to
hitters. He went to Sutton early last year when he was struggling
despite feeling good physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I worried about,'' Glavine said, ``was, `OK, am
I at a point in my career where I've been doing this long enough
that people are starting to beat me at my game and I need to
change?' Don helped me in easing my thoughts that I wasn't at that
point. ... I'm just saying I haven't gotten there yet from a
physical standpoint. From a game approach, maybe I've gotten there
a little bit, yeah. I've been here for 13 years now, and there's no
secrets as to what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine made a point of pitching inside more and mixing in more
breaking balls. Maddux, meanwhile, hasn't had to make noticeable
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still trust my instincts,'' Maddux said. ``I might not be as
good as I once was, but I can still be good enough. It's about
putting your team in a position to win. You don't have to be pretty
to do that, sometimes. I still feel like I'm capable of getting my
team into the seventh, eighth inning, where we still have a good
chance to win. That's what starting pitching is all about. If you
can do that 30 times a year, your team's going to probably win 25
of them. That's kind of what you're after.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux credits manager Bobby Cox with helping extend his career,
physically and mentally, from the trust he puts in the pitchers to
let him know when they are done, to the way he runs spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do the running with the parachutes on, the underwater
exercises,'' Maddux said. ``We're in more than good enough shape to
go out there and play an 18-inning game by the time the season
starts. So what if we can't do the triathlon next week? That keeps
the game fun, and it keeps you mentally into it. It means a lot,
more than people realize.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's Cox's handling of the pitchers in games. Terry
Mulholland, a newcomer to the Braves last August, was surprised
last year when he was asked if he needed to come out of the game.
He said later he hadn't been asked since he played in Philadelphia
three years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something for winning today, but there's also
something to be said for being right for your next 20 games, as
well,'' Maddux said. ``(Cox is) one of the few that can kind of
blend it in together, where you don't sacrifice on Friday to try to
win on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox and pitching coach Leo Mazzone take a lot of pride in the
longevity of the ``Big Three,'' and both think all three can pitch
into another contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't lose their enthusiasm, No. 1,'' Cox said. ``It
would be easy nowadays to lose some of that. Players are making
good money. Most are set for life after one contract. They love the
game of baseball. That separates them from a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzone said: ``I think Maddux and Glavine can pitch until
they're 40. I think Smoltzie will come back real strong. I think
they're only in the middle of their careers, based on what I know
about them as people, their work ethic, dedication, mental and
physical approach.''
</P>
<P>
   But will they pitch until they're 40?
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, for one, doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll reach a stage where there's too much life out
there,'' Sutton said. ``They'd have to go to another team. They'd
have to take a lesser role. I think when they walk into their kids'
bedrooms and drive carpool, they'll say it's not worth it. ... I
don't think(Glavine or Maddux) needs to (pitch that long) to have
carved their niche in baseball. I'd like to see them both win 300.
God willing, I'd like to be there to shake their hand when they're
inducted into the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, more young pitchers will enter the league
labeled as the next Glavine or Maddux or Smoltz. And that's fine
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great, and I hope it continues for six or seven more
years,'' Glavine said. ``The people that are in the worst spot are
the Braves, because all three of us are getting old together, and
it's going to be tough to replace three guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Good point. The Braves have staggered their contracts by a year,
but at some point there's going to be a serious void in the
rotation. And not even the pitchers have any idea when.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm to the point where I still feel like I have a good chance
to win, but at the same time, I can walk away right now, no
regrets,'' Maddux said. ``The game has given me more than I ever
hoped. I've got my World Series ring. I've accomplished
individually more than I ever thought I would. Financially, it's
been excellent for me. I could walk away now.''
</P>
<P>
   So then why keep coming back?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kicks,'' Maddux said.
</P>
<P>
   And he was dead serious.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
