<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-SCHUERHOLZ02-COX     04-01 3326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SCHUERHOLZ02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The art of the deal: Grading John Schuerholz's big moves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Schuerholz once dreamed that he might save the
world.
</P>
<P>
   A bad case of measles when he was 5 left Schuerholz half-deaf; a
soaring temperature incinerated the nerve system in his right ear.
But he tried to make it work for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always used to visualize, if there was some sort of
tragedy,'' he said, ``where there was some sort of supersonic sound
that was destroying the Earth, I could put one finger in this
(left) ear and go save people with the other hand. I'd have one arm
to work with to pick up people. Everybody else would have both
fingers in their ears. I'd guide them to safety.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not quite work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I used to be like the corner freak,'' Schuerolz said.
``The kids in school, they'd blow bugles in my right ear full
blast. Could not hear a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Half-deaf and six months away from 60, Schuerholz is 34 years
into his career of baseball administration. He calls himself ``a
geezer'' now, having come from an age when a guy could get a
baseball job just by writing to a team, as he did. The World Series
Championship team he constructed in Kansas City was paid less than
$10 million. Greg Maddux will make more than that this season.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of younger general managers, Schuerholz is as stiff as
the junior-high English teacher he once was. His game was all
scouting and development and shrewd intuition, not high finance or
drug tests or agents. Beginning his 10th year with the Braves, the
most successful GM in the game sometimes wonders why he is still
doing this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, I ask myself that question a lot more frequently that I
used to,'' he said. ``And it's a shame, because I love the game
still, and I love being a part of it. I'm proud of it. But maybe
that's a just a reflection of the fact that I'm almost 60 years
old, and that's what geezers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look back on the early days as the golden days, and they
look at the changed environment in which they operate now as not
being as pleasant or enjoyable. Maybe that's true in all walks of
life. I'm probably a living, breathing example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, what would he do without baseball?
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, he was born for this,'' said Herk Robinson, Kansas
City's GM and an old friend.
</P>
<P>
   The job is the fuel for Schuerholz's celebrated ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's even a little cockier now, if that's possible,''
said George Brett, the Hall of Famer whom Schuerholz helped
shepherd through the Royals system.
</P>
<P>
   The job also is what he does best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you've ever been on the inside and worked with him,''
Braves special assistant Paul Snyder said, ``there's no way you can
appreciate the man's baseball intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   And that comes from a man Schuerholz once removed from his job.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the contract of Atlanta's GM was extended through
2003. He says he does not want to leave the impression that he is
bailing out on a team that eventually should stop being a
championship contender every year, as its vaunted pitching rotation
ages.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement would mean something far more grave and sinister.
John Schuerholz no longer would dress for work, and for a slave to
fashion, life is unimaginable without linen slacks and Italian
suits and yellow socks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be casual attire,'' he says wistfully. ``So I'll go to
counseling, I guess, for that. Maybe there's some Good Dressers
Anonymous or something, where we can put on suspenders and ties and
go talk. `Hi, I'm John. I used to dress up. And I miss it.'''
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING AROUND PITCHING
</P>
<P>
   What Schuerholz has demonstrated to contemporary management is
how to spend, where to spend it and when to stop. Tom Glavine, Greg
Maddux and John Smoltz remain the team's unofficial logo, but
Schuerholz's dexterity has been in re-creating what goes around
them. Only two position players from the 1997 Opening Day lineup
are still with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the model I look to,'' Houston GM Gerry Hunsicker
said. ``Nobody's been any more effective or efficient than the
Braves over the past decade. Yes, they've had resources available
to them, but it's being able to use those resources wisely and also
not to be afraid to make changes to a successful nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at the bigger picture,'' Hunsicker said. ``A
mistake a lot of teams make is, when they have found a successful
nucleus, they let them grow old together, and then they look up and
wonder why they're 20 games out of first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Since coming to Atlanta in the fall of 1990, Schuerholz's teams
have a .618 winning percentage. The Braves have won 76 more games
that the New York Yankees, their closest competitors. Only three
other teams in history have matched Atlanta's current streak of
three consecutive 100-win seasons _ the 1929-31 Philadelphia A's,
the 1942-44 St. Louis Cardinals and the 1969-71 Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The streak of eight division titles in a row is unprecedented.
The Hall of Fame has admitted just 12 club executives through the
years, and it is no stretch to imagine Schuerholz joining that
short list one day. His opinions are highly valued within his
industry.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Braves' inability to win more than one World Series
is a qualifier to Schuerholz's reign. It might have been different
had Lonnie Smith glanced at his third-base coach instead of
stopping at second in 1991 or had Mark Wohlers thrown another
fastball in 1996 rather than the fated hanging slider.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not reality. It's also a reason for Schuerholz to come
to work every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been disappointed for him,'' Cleveland GM John Hart
said. ``With the great organization he's put together, the fact is
that they've never had that three or four (championships) that they
very easily could have. He may still get that.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz enjoys a popularity uncommon to the front office. He
often is asked for his autograph, and when introduced for the
occasional on-field ceremony at Turner Field, his name draws
ovations.
</P>
<P>
   He never could save the world, but for many people, he saved
baseball in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For such a public person, his adopted city knows little about
him, beyond the threads and the articulated sound bites. He rarely
wields his wicked sense of humor unless around friends. He carries
a 10 handicap at the Cherokee Town and Country Club. He works out
with weights regularly, appreciates fine wines and does not dye his
hair, which is still almost exclusively jet black. He returns
telephone calls faithfully but does not share a confidence often or
suffer fools gladly.
</P>
<P>
   He is a painter and still writes poetry on occasion. When his
father died of colon cancer in 1994, Schuerholz wrote a poem (``A
kind and gentle man has left this world too soon ...'') that his
brother Jerry still cannot read aloud without choking up.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz still bears a ``frustration ... that will go with me
to my grave'' over never being offered a professional baseball
contract, even though he was the best high school second baseman in
Baltimore in 1958 and hit .420 his senior season at Towson State
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he comes off with his first impression as being
somewhat intimidating to people,'' pitcher Tom Glavine said. ``I
got the sense I needed to respect this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL IN HIS BLOOD
</P>
<P>
   The Schuerholzes left Germany before World War I and wound up in
south Baltimore, ``because I guess that's where the boat landed,''
he says. He and two younger brothers were born into a family
already celebrated for athletics.
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather, William, is in the Maryland State Hall of Fame
for basketball. His uncle Gilbert was an Olympic soccer player. And
Schuerholz's father, John, was a promising second baseman in the
Philadelphia A's organization, but three years into his career he
suffered a severely broken leg while playing for the Wilson (N.C.)
Tobs, effectively ending his future in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1940. Schuerholz was born later that year, and it
became almost a genetic duty to compete fiercely with his brothers
as soon as they were old enough to take their floggings. Any game,
anywhere. Even ping-pong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you had to watch for the paddle coming back across the
table,'' brother Jerry said.
</P>
<P>
   They came of age in a Baltimore depicted in the Sam Levinson
film ``Diner,'' a small-town city where kids cracked wise and daily
life circulated around the Colts and Orioles. His high school,
Baltimore City College High, was a castlelike structure across the
street from Memorial Stadium, and some nights the Schuerholz boys
sneaked into the park to play out their baseball fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   His life came down to three primary pursuits: baseball, clothes
and music. His fascination with clothes dates to a pair of pants
given him by an uncle for an elementary-school graduation gift.
They were ``kind of electric blue, and they had the saddle
stitching down the side, a matching belt,'' Schuerholz says. ``Now,
that's not my style any longer. But I was captivated then, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   He still vividly recalls buying his first record _ Bill Haley
and the Comets' ``Rock Around The Clock'' _ and to this day remains
a '50s music aficionado.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest song ever written by a human being is `Come Go
With Me' by the Del-Vikings,'' Schuerholz said. ``My apologies to
Beethoven.''
</P>
<P>
   But baseball was always the family's primary passion, and
Schuerholz followed in his father's footsteps at second base. He
was an all-conference player at Towson and voted athlete of the
year his senior season, but scouts could not overlook two
statistics: The prospect was 5 feet 9 1/2 and weighed just 155
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a scouting combine, I'd be a good 5-10,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His final at-bats came against Johns Hopkins and Schuerholz went
4-for-5 against Don Lenhardt, who later kicked around the majors
for five years. Schuerholz still cites the episode proudly.
</P>
<P>
   But then he went cold turkey. Within two years, he embraced his
second calling, education. He was teaching by day at North Point
Junior High in Dundalk while pursuing a master's degree in
education by night at Loyola University. He was newly married and
sold on the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ultimately saw myself teaching at the collegiate level and
would often visualize myself in a cardigan sweater, smoking a pipe,
walking down some ivy-covered pathway toward a classroom,''
Schuerholz said. ``I would teach to try to make people
better-prepared for life.''
</P>
<P>
   But four years at North Point did not extinguish what he felt
for baseball. So, in 1966 he wrote a letter to the Orioles'
chairman, Jerold Hoffberger, which set off a remarkable sequence of
events. The letter wound up on the desk of President Frank Cashen,
who had a policy of personally replying to every letter he
received. He was also a former sportswriter for the Baltimore Sun
and recalled the Schuerholz family name. The connection led to an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always serious-minded,'' said Cashen, now a vice
president with the New York Mets. ``And I can give you a codicil to
that. He was also always well-dressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz struck it off with Lou Gorman, the Orioles' energized
director of player development, and was offered a job as his
personal assistant. Schuerholz became one of the only people in the
universe to quit a teaching job and take a pay cut, from $6,800 to
$4,700.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first day I started in that job, my goal was to
become a general manager of a major-league baseball team,''
Schuerholz said. ``I gave myself five years, after which I would
assess where I was in my career. Because I felt I could always go
back to teaching if I didn't succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   In five years, he was still Gorman's assistant after he had
moved on to help grow the expansion Kansas City franchise. But his
reputation rose, as did the Royals', into the IBM of baseball.
Rising to the position of farm director, Schuerholz oversaw the
drafting and developing of George Brett, Frank White, Willie Wilson
and Dan Quisenberry, who became a backbone for six divisional title
teams.
</P>
<P>
   At 41, Schuerholz finally became a GM in 1981. It had cost him a
first marriage and would introduce him to a host of troubles _ the
notorious Royals drug cases of 1983 and a palace intrigue that soon
engulfed ownership _ that he had not been prepared for. And
compared with flamboyant club President Joe Burke, Schuerholz was
seen by some as a secondary character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maryland, Ivy-Leaguer type, preppy,'' said a smiling Jamie
Quirk, one of Schuerholz's first-round draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that John received the credit that he should have
received,'' said K.C.'s Richardson, who had staffed the farm office
with Schuerholz. ``It may have been perhaps because some people
maybe took John for granted, because he had been there for a long
time. He didn't come in to save the world. He was there and part of
a process.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz was voted executive of the year by The Sporting News
after the 1985 World Series victory. But the club soon divided
against itself, as co-owners Ewing Kauffman and Avron Fogelman
clashed. Fogelman enlisted his GM's support. Everyone else sided
with Kauffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sort of in the middle, and I didn't feel like I had a
lot of support from either side,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Around that time in the summer of 1990, he and Stan Kasten, the
Braves president, shared a limousine ride in New York. Kasten asked
for Schuerholz's suggestions for a GM, now that Bobby Cox had moved
from the front office back into the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz said he would come up with some names, but when he
called Kasten back a few weeks later, he could think of only one _
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took this job, I got calls from my friends in the
business who thought I had lost my mind,'' Schuerholz said. ``When
I stepped out on the field at the instructional league in the
winter of 1990, a general manager stepped up to me and said, `Do
you realize what the circumstances are in the organization you just
took over?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Yes, I do.'''
</P>
<P>
   NOT ALL DEALS ARE GOLDEN
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with Schuerholz over a proposed trade is as might be
expected _ straight-forward, no junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably some misconceptions about John but he's
great to work with on a deal,'' Cleveland's Hart said. ``He's
matter of fact. He knows what he wants. He's always prepared, and
he doesn't mince words.''
</P>
<P>
   Some decisions he made _ fetching Terry Pendleton off the junk
heap, the Fred McGriff steal _ changed the course of the franchise.
But no one in authority is immune from error. Schuerholz has had
his share.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better get him in the right mood if you're going to joke
about the David Cone thing,'' Richardson said, ``because he doesn't
turn loose of those things easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz traded away a future Cy Young winner in 1987 to the
New York Mets for a catcher, Ed Hearn, who had a damaged shoulder,
pitcher Rick Anderson, who would appear in just 13 Royals games,
and pitcher Mauro Gozzo, who never made K.C.'s major-league roster.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on minor-league coaches' opinions that Cone's off-field
conduct could be ``untoward'' _ a conviction later born out in
several New York incidents _ Schuerholz triggered one of the worst
deals in this half of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Ed Hearn had been healthy as a horse, it would have
been a bad deal,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   The move only exacerbated public opinion in some parts of Kansas
City that Schuerholz was overmatched. While serving as the Royals'
director of player procurement and development in 1976, he signed
free-agent infielder Jerry Terrell, an uncommon move for the
farm-conscious franchise, while Burke, the club president, was
vacationing on a cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The Wichita Eagle did not approve, running a column and cartoon
that said, ``Leaving John Schuerholz in charge of the Royals is
like Jimmy Carter leaving Amy in charge of the White House.'' A
quarter-century later, Schuerholz still grimaces at the episode.
</P>
<P>
   For every right move he has made in Atlanta, his 1997 decision
to send away Marquis Grissom and David Justice, after they had been
so instrumental to a pair of World Series teams, to Cleveland for
Kenny Lofton and Alan Embree remains controversial. The deal was
packaged as a salary-saver, that the club was then able to
negotiate the combined $91 million contracts that Greg Maddux and
Glavine are still tied to.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably one that I think guys questioned because
we're so big on the clubhouse and chemistry and all that stuff, and
the two guys who went in that deal, they were Braves,'' Glavine
said. ``It's tough taking that kind of soul out of your club.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice charged that Schuerholz had deceived him, that he had
told him a few weeks before that he would trade ``my house and
family'' before he would deal Justice. The interceding three years
have brought stoicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what? People get deceived every day,'' Justice said. ``That
man doesn't owe me anything. I've got nothing against John
Schuerholz. The man just told me one lie. It was a big lie, but
that's all he ever did to me.''
</P>
<P>
   CONSISTENTLY GOOD
</P>
<P>
   ``So actually, there are people out there saying that when
Glavine and Maddux retire, I'm going to retire? That that will be
the prompt for me to go?''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got three more years to go on my contract and perhaps
even more than that, if the club so chooses,'' he says. ``But I'll
be in my 60s then, and I don't know how much longer I intend to
work beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some see a change in him already. He and wife, Karen, have a
second home in Cashiers, N.C., which they use for quick getaways.
Schuerholz also has shocked some associates with a newfound
interest in hunting, seemingly unthinkable for a man so
buttoned-down in professional life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so uptight and so conservative,'' Kasten said. ``His
family will tell you all this has done him a world of good. I mean,
now it's hunting? I believe he's a member of Ducks Unlimited. I'm
sure he subscribes to things like Guns &AMP; Quail magazine. I mean,
that's like me getting Blacktop &AMP; Asphalt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schuerholzes' son, Jonathan, has become a proud diversion;
he is the starting shortstop in his freshman year at Auburn. A
middle infielder, as his father and grandfather were, Jonathan will
play in the Coastal Carolina summer college league this year, which
uses as one of its parks Fleming Field in Wilson, N.C., where his
grandfather played in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Life after baseball appeals to Schuerholz, but the 2000 season
is screaming at him. The John Rocker affair, which Schuerholz
likens to the Royals' drug case as ``an organizational kick to the
groin,'' will bear his close scrutiny all year, and a feeling
exists in the clubhouse that Schuerholz will acquire help for the
end of the rotation. A ninth division title will come harder than
the past five.
</P>
<P>
   Old North Point Junior High was used briefly as a police academy
and then closed down. Three of the stadiums Schuerholz called home
_ Memorial, K.C.'s old Municipal and Atlanta-Fulton County _ have
been closed or blown up. The baseball men who trained Schuerholz
have mostly retired or died.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he remains, shaking a fist at his critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be a one-shot wonder,'' he said. ``In '91, we go from
last to first, like Minnesota. Like the Toronto club we played in
'92. Like the Pirates, who we played for three years and then
diminished. The consistency of our success is a great source of
pride for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will say, `Well, anybody could do it once. Ah, anybody
could do it twice. Well, if you're lucky, three out of five.'''
</P>
<P>
   John Schuerholz simply plots a course for a ninth October. No
one's blown a bugle at him in years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
