<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4291 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-SELIG02-COX     04-01 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SELIG02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commish steers game into brave new century
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bud Selig trades in snake oil.
</P>
<P>
   With a fleet of young stars, a pile of new TV money to be
collected, a string of gleaming new parks and a host of richer,
hipper owners, the baseball commissioner can afford to look the
camera in the eye and foretell a new dawn for a game that just five
years ago lay bleeding in the street.
</P>
<P>
   And Selig will tell you exactly that. But as the game's most
incidental commissioner steers baseball into the 21st century,
empowered as no major-league executive before him, he also knows
better.
</P>
<P>
   The game wants to think it no longer walks with a limp from the
last strike. Bud Selig knows better, and he also knows that the
fans know it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of where we were in '94 and '95 and think of where we
are today and as we head into 2000. It's spectacular,'' Selig said.
``But we're not fooling anybody. In the midst of this incredible
renaissance, we have a paradox of disparity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I could sit here and deny and say we're in this great
renaissance and we have some minor problems. But I can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is the world's only professional sport that, before the
games ever start, eliminates half the teams because they're too
poor, or too cheap, to pay for enough talent to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings, up against more aggressively marketed
leagues, plummeted 10 percent last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Worst, the basic working agreement must be readdressed within
two years. Disputes over the document have caused eight work
stoppages over the past 24 years. The sport cannot withstand
another, and both sides are reluctant even to evaluate their
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get locked out or something, I will walk away from the
game,'' St. Louis slugger Mark McGwire said. ``I would be
embarrassed to be a baseball player. We're making way too much
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the 1994-95 strike and whatever lies ahead, however,
Selig is enjoying remarkably good PR. He just negotiated a new $800
million cable deal with ESPN, when it seemed both sides were headed
to federal court over the last contract. Prospects for the next
network contract are glowing. He broke the umpires' union and now
more closely controls umps from both leagues under one umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, in a unanimous vote by the owners, he was granted
newly stated powers to block trades, punish teams and intercede in
the best interests of the game to maintain competitive balance. He
won that clout from a roomful of owners who for decades couldn't
even agree on what to order for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gained control of their house, where he has the ability to
sanction ownership for conduct more readily,'' power agent Scott
Boras said. ``There is more ability for the commissioner to gain
plurality. So from the House of Lords standpoint, he certainly has
more ability to get matters completed more efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I agree he hasn't done anything yet,'' Pittsburgh
general manager Cam Bonifay said. ``But there's a basis for
productivity that could be very positive for our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig stepped down as owner of the Milwaukee Brewers to become
interim commissioner in 1992, mostly because fellow owners were too
battle-worn to break in another outsider. But he also fit the role
well because, as baseball historian Jerome Holtzman writes in ``The
Commissioners,'' he had been ``on the phone for 23 years,
canvassing every square foot of baseball's problems, particularly
at the executive level. He has been the quintessential insider.''
</P>
<P>
   His first big moves _ hiring ex-Toronto CEO Paul Beeston and
ex-Oakland GM Sandy Alderson _ drew high marks. Beeston, chief
operating officer for Major League Baseball, put a likable
personality in control of daily operations.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson, a Princeton-educated lawyer, became his executive VP
and took on the hard cases, the umpires fight and the investigation
of the Aldrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   Then late last summer, Selig moved to eliminate the NL and AL
offices, an often-misunderstood move that was devised not to ruin
tradition but to consolidate umpire control and administration.
Club execs view the current set-up to be like the NFL, where the
AFC and NFC act in separate spheres but have no separate offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of going through the league presidents, we're
initially getting through to the commissioner's office,'' Braves
assistant GM Frank Wren said. ``It kind of eliminates middle
management.''
</P>
<P>
   But those were procedural matters that gave ownership the
sympathetic ear of an ex-team executive in MLB's headquarters.
Selig's real agenda remains to be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   He has pushed baseball internationally and envisions not only a
baseball World Cup but a global marketing endeavor similar to the
NBA's.
</P>
<P>
   He has received a report from a blue-ribbon committee for
restoring competitive balance _ read: sharing the money. As a
former small-market owner, he has lived with the problem as it grew
during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm more aggressive as a commissioner (than as an
owner), but they know what I want to do, because I've told them,''
Selig said. ``There are no hidden agendas here, nothing else. They
know the economic system needs reformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that, the owners can address themselves, by sharing more
revenue, specifically local TV-radio proceeds. But Selig's first
crisis will come after the 2001 season, with the next opening of
the basic working agreement. Baseball has changed since the last
strike. The game has 13 new owners, most of them moderate
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball does not have the growing confrontation that was in the
air in the early 1980s. Beeston enjoys a friendly relationship with
union executive director Donald Fehr. They should find negotiating
room; for example, how many players enjoy playing for teams that
can't compete? The previous administration had only rising blood
for fighting the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had had success, I would have been able to talk (the
owners) out of that,'' former Commissioner Fay Vincent said. ``In
that sense, I failed as commissioner.''
</P>
<P>
   As an interim, Selig already had surpassed Vincent in bringing
change to the game. He oversaw the shift to three divisions, the
advent of the wild-card entry in the postseason, interleague play
and the first attempt at revenue-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that stands as a mere first act if Selig is to reform
the game's economic structure. As that fight and the next union
clash draw closer, the commissioner carries the highest approval
rating he has had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that time tells that, (for) the commissioner who has
been given this authority, the enemy is always increased rather
than decreased,'' Boras said. ``The commissioner's office is a
place that the top 10 clubs always view as the most restrictive.
They're the one who have the liberalness, economically, to get
different things done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time always comes when the honeymoon will end.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
