<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GIVERS02-COX     04-01 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIVERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small-time philanthropists make big difference
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ When George Domet first heard the plight
of an elderly woman about to be evicted from her trailer, he knew
he had to do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a heartbreaking woman and some unfortunate things have
happened to her,'' says Domet, 68, who moved to Grand Junction from
Los Angeles with his wife, Valerie, five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is almost totally blind, she has a disabled hip and walks
with a decided limp and a cane, and her right arm is in a sling.''
</P>
<P>
   Domet was initially contacted by St. Mary's Hospital who told
him an IRS snafu caused the woman to lose her federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had taken time to teach blind children to read Braille,''
explains Domet, president of Ironwood Construction, a construction
management firm. ``It wasn't for very long, two or three months,
and someone from the IRS caught this when she filed her tax return
and said if you can work, we're taking you off the rolls.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Domet stepped in to help, the woman was three months
behind on her mortgage and trailer-space rent and was in the
process of being evicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have taken her under my wing,'' Domet says. ``It makes me
feel good inside when I extend myself to help somebody else. Some
people think I'm crazy and that I shouldn't be doing this.
</P>
<P>
   I have a guardian angel that sits right here, he's on my left
shoulder. When I do something right, he pats me on the back and
kisses me on the cheek. When I do something wrong, he kicks me in
the butt. I've probably gotten a 50-50 split on the butt-kicking
and the kissing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Doris Horton found out the kids in her Gateway community
weren't reading because they didn't have library cards, she waged a
campaign to improve an existing reading program by offering toys to
kids who read.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop was Toys-R-Us where she shopped the bargain bins
in search of toys to give away as prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with garbage bags overflowing with toys, she went to the
Gateway Library and presented them with her finds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be wealthy,'' says Horton, 57, a landscape
designer. ``You don't have to do anything big. Just pick your own
spot and make it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Long reviews books on tape for AudioFile magazine and then
donates the tapes to the Mesa County Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``They send the books at no cost to me,'' says Long, 48, owner
of Montessori School of Grand Junction. ``I listen to four or six
every couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Long estimates she donates about 40 books per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rarely listen to a book twice,'' says Long. ``I listen to
them, pass them on and I'm happy to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Small-time philanthropists make up an increasingly large portion
of the giving picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where we build our base,'' says Cheryl Collins,
executive director of the United Way of Mesa County. ``You cannot
cookie-cut people who give money away. Everyone has their own
specific reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, an independent survey found that people in the
lowest income brackets tend to donate as much or more than their
higher-wage counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The average American household donates about 2 percent of its
annual income.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find ironic is the people who really can't afford to
give always find a way to give,'' says Collins. ``I would like to
feel in my own heart that people give because they want to, not for
any reason other than you get a good feeling when you do it and
it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins says when the economy is good, people feel good about
giving and are typically more generous.
</P>
<P>
   Churches top the list when it comes to receiving. Other
recipients include colleges and universities, arts organizations
and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Being a philanthropist doesn't mean you have to have to be rich
or have an abundance of time.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the simple things mean the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn your television set off for an hour and go say `hi' to
your neighbor,'' says Collins. ``When you go to the grocery store,
buy an extra can of food for the food drive. Instead of buying
pizza for yourself, take that $15 or the pizza and give it to
someone who might not be able to afford it or buy a gift
certificate and give it to a single parent who might need some
help. Sometimes you just have to stop and say, `What can I do to
help someone today?'''
</P>
<P>
   A DOZEN LITTLE THINGS THAT CAN MAKE A BIG DIFFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   _ Take your newspapers to the recycling bins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Volunteer to be a master gardener at in Girl Scout program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sponsor a student/tutor pair to learn to read at your local
library.
</P>
<P>
   _ Donate a book to your local library.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay back your college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   _ Donate food to the food bank.
</P>
<P>
   _ Volunteer for a charity fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy a pizza or a gift certificate and take it to a family who
otherwise couldn't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offer to do home repairs for elderly or handicapped neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take a blind or visually impaired person to the park.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish a scholarship fund.
</P>
<P>
   TAX BREAKS FOR PEOPLE WHO DONATE TO CHARITY
</P>
<P>
   _ General Rule: Gifts of cash or check to qualified charity
(organization described as 501 C3 organization) are deductible if
you itemize for individual returns. There is a limitation on amount
of deductions each year amounting to 50 percent of income.
</P>
<P>
   _ Biggest exception to the general rule: in capital gains
property (i.e.: stocks and bonds), the deduction is the fair market
value of property. If it's appreciated in value, you avoid paying
tax on gain by giving it away.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limitation rule on that type of property: general rule limited
to 30 percent of income.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you make a significant gift of appreciated property (other
than cash or publicly traded securities) you need a qualified
appraisal if amount is over $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you donate out-of-pocket expenses to charity (i.e. driving
for charities) you can take deduction for gas and oil or standard
14 cents per mile in lieu of using actual out of-pocket-costs.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you give a gift of more than $250, a cancelled check is not
sufficient. You need a statement from the organization saying you
gave this amount and weren't compensated for it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Self-created property: For example, if an artist painted a
painting and sold it for $1,000 and the cost of canvas and paints
were only $100, you can only deduct cost of paints and other
out-of-pocket expenses. Self-created property cannot take deduction
for sale price.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you go to a charity ball, you can only deduct the
difference between the value of the meal and the ticket price. You
cannot deduct the full ticket price.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Dalby Wendland &AMP; Company PC
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
