<SLUG> BC-BBN-BOWDEN-BIO02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The facts for Jim Bowden
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   Age: 38
</P>
<P>
   Born: Weston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Resides: Anderson Township, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Made baseball history Oct. 16, 1992, at age 31 when he became
the youngest general manager in major-league history. Among GMs
since then, his 554 victories with the Reds rank second only to the
668 over which Atlanta's John Schuerholz has presided. Made history
again Feb. 10, 2000, by engineering trade for 10-time All-Star
outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. Never shy about pulling the trigger on a
big deal at any time, Bowden has built his reputation by making key
moves down the stretch to help the Reds. Was named Executive of the
Year by several organizations after putting together a team that
won 96 games last season and lost a one-game wild-card playoff to
the New York Mets. Bowden and wife Amy have five children and two
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
