<HEADER>
A4295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ANDRUW02-C     04-01 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ANDRUW02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A natural swagger
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Andruw Jones might not look 22 years old on a baseball
field, but he certainly can in a clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   All 185 pounds of the Braves' Gold Glove center fielder,
scrunched up in a laundry cart, arms and legs dangling over the
sides, talking to his teammates, never cracking a smile. Or eyes
glued to a television and a video-game version of himself _ the one
Jones admits is a better player than the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   Does it bother him?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because I want to win the video games,'' Jones says with a
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   So he says. But this spring training, Jones' actions have spoken
louder than those words, and the Braves, who have just made Jones a
millionaire, are hoping his efforts translate into a breakout year
for $3.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   After three full seasons in the majors, Jones has left little
doubt that he is the game's best defensive center fielder _ and
maybe one of the best in history. But in November, he was reminded
about his unfulfilled offensive potential, right about the time Ken
Griffey Jr. asked for a trade and Atlanta was mentioned as a
possible destination _ with Jones speculated to be part of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, three years into his major-league career, Jones' numbers
actually are better than Griffey's were at the same point. But it
didn't exactly reassure Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't let anything bother me, but it was kind of hard,''
Jones said. ``If they call and tell you you're in a situation that
we might trade you, you get shocked. But nobody called me.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until he ran into manager Bobby Cox at Turner Field
during the offseason that Jones breathed a little easier. ``Bobby
told me we didn't even talk about that, so don't worry,'' Jones
said. And then he went back to work.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks earlier than usual, Jones started hitting soft
toss with George Lombard, his alter outfielder _ Jones, the natural
who made heads spin as he moved through the minors so fast, and
Lombard, the project who has had to work so hard at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most talented player I've ever played with for any
amount of time,'' said Lombard, who said he didn't notice much
difference in Jones this offseason. ``Same old Andruw that always
makes you laugh, whether he's striking out or hitting a home run.
He always makes it look like he's having a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ozzie Guillen, who was released Friday but was one of Jones'
closest friends on the team, has noticed a change in Jones the past
couple of years. It started July 21, 1998, the day Jones came to
him after Cox pulled Jones in the middle of a game for not hustling
to catch a fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if Bobby was being a jerk,'' Guillen said. ``I
told him, `He did it because he wants you to be the best player you
can be.' From when I got here (in 1998), he's a 100 percent better
player. Not the talent part.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones used to be one of the stragglers, Guillen said. Now he's
among the first to the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here, I told him, `You're cocky; you're walking
around here like you're Willie Mays,''' Guillen said. ``He's lucky
to grow up in the Braves organization. Bobby Cox has a great way of
doing things. He uses a lot of discipline. If Andruw grew up in
another organization, he might be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is one of the few who exhibits what new teammate Bobby
Bonilla calls ``the Atlanta swagger.'' He has a sarcastic sense of
humor and outwardly he can appear aloof, including toward teammates
and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   New Braves hitting coach Merv Rettenmund is taking his first
stab at teaching Jones the same thing. He's no stranger to trying
to reach a headstrong young player. He spent the past several
seasons working with Ruben Rivera in San Diego and didn't have much
success. But Rettenmund knows it's not just up to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jones) could make a hell of a difference,'' Rettenmund said.
``But he has to want to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The two have spent early mornings in the indoor batting cages
and are constantly gabbing by the cage in batting practice.
Rettenmund isn't convinced that Jones has caught on to his ideas
about hitting the ball to center and right field when the pitch is
away and getting his hands into motion quicker.
</P>
<P>
   He is trying to help Jones understand why teams, including the
Padres, jam him inside and then come back with offspeed pitches
away, and why he was an easy target in the postseason, when he hit
only .185.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I had my hands too far up on my body and when they throw
the ball in I have no movement, no nothing,'' Jones said. ``That's
why I got jammed. ... I think in my mind maybe I was tired. I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be an overnight change. But whether it's because of the
Griffey talk or because he watched Chipper Jones win an MVP award
or because he wants more than a .275 average to go along with his
good but not outstanding run production, Jones seems to be
listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're waiting for me to have a great, great, great
season with my bat,'' Jones said. ``But it's not that easy. ... I
can hit. I just need to make my adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones showed some improvement in patience last year, drawing 76
walks, up from 40 in 1998, and lowered his strikeouts to 103, down
from 129. His homers dropped from 31 to 26 last year and his RBIs
dropped from 90 to 84, but the Braves weren't exactly complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much of a slump he may be in, if you are as good
as he is in center field, you're still going to be in the lineup,''
Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   When Greg Maddux first heard Griffey might want to come to
Atlanta, he said he assumed the Braves would leave Jones in center
and make Griffey the best left fielder in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andruw's willing to do the little things to help a team win,''
Maddux said. ``Anybody who can play the game like that will be
welcome wherever. He plays like Mark Lemke did. Lemke rarely hit
over .240, but we were a better team when he was on it. Andruw
plays the game the same way, only better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
