NYT-04-01-00 1416EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-CHIPPER02-     04-01 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CHIPPER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    C. Jones' best, toughest season
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From National League ballparks to the Jones kitchen
table in Pierson, Fla., Chipper Jones has managed to amaze.
</P>
<P>
   He was eating supper with his parents _ Lynne and Larry Jones
Sr. _ one night during spring training when the topic of last
season came up. It prompted Lynne to look over at her reigning
National League MVP son and say, ``I can't believe you're my kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while, you wake up and go, that's our kid out
there,'' Lynne said. ``You're going along, and all of a sudden
somebody will be interviewing him on TV, and it hits you. My
goodness, this was a kid from Pierson, Fla. The munchkin monster.''
</P>
<P>
   The munchkin monster who grew into everybody's All-American
baseball hero. But the year that he won his first MVP award began
as one of the worst years of his life. He was only months removed
from having admitted publicly to cheating on his now-former wife
Karin and having a child out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   In a year's time, Jones has gone from tarnished superstar to
National League MVP. Along the way, he has embraced his new role as
father. This past offseason, Matthew and his mother, Jennifer
Rutledge, moved to Atlanta, allowing Jones easier access and more
time to spend with his son, who turned 2 in March.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also has another son on the way. Chipper and his live-in
girlfriend, Sharon Logonov, got married last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As for the details of his new marriage, Jones doesn't feel the
need to address them. Unlike his very public divorce with Karin, he
prefers to keep his personal life more private now. If last year
taught him anything, it was the benefit of putting his troubles
behind him and moving on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to the point where the whole situation was kind of
consuming me. I'd be out there on the field thinking about it, and
that wasn't good,'' Jones said. ``I finally came to the point where
I just said, `You know, I can't control this anymore, so I'm not
going to try. I'm just going to move on.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've dealt with it,'' he said. ``I'm tired of dealing with it.
I'm just going to get on with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The former No. 1 draft pick managed to turn a season golden in
which he was primed in many ways to fail. He carried the Braves
through the losses of Andres Galarraga and Javy Lopez, and he did
it best when he finally let go of the burden of his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what he was going through emotionally, all the turmoil
behind the scenes,'' Lynne said. ``For him to go on the field and
turn it all off and not only produce but produce as well as he did
with Andres going down, and Javy going down, was stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   His season began to change not long after a conversation he had
with his mother in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had told him, 'You're going to make yourself sick,''' Lynne
said. ```It happened. It was wrong, but it's over with. You've got
to live with the consequences, but that means living with the
consequences. It doesn't mean tearing yourself up about it day
after day.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jones responded with his best month of the season. He hit .413
in July with 11 home runs. And by the end of September, he was
unstoppable. He virtually assured himself the MVP award by hitting
four home runs in a three-game sweep of the Mets that all but won
the pennant for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   By then the cheers were pretty well wiping out the jeers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones still hears in fans' taunts the Hooters comments, in
reference to where he met Rutledge. Sometimes, if they say it to
his face, Jones can laugh about it. And he no longer looks at that
situation as one huge mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Matthew just as that, my son,'' Jones said. ``I don't
see the story behind Matthew. If you spend any time with Matthew,
Matthew will make you forget about everything, including baseball.
Now he consumes me. I'm so happy, so proud of him, that you can't
even really look at what happened a couple years ago as being a
mistake, because he's brought so much joy to me and my family
already, and I've only really known him a year. Shoot, I wouldn't
trade it for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the compliments Jones heard last year from coaches and
managers, teammates, opponents, members of the media, family and
friends, the most meaningful ones to him came from fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a parent come up and say to you that their son or their
kids idolize me, they still enjoy coming to the game to watch me
play _ that's the biggest compliment,'' Jones said. ``I understand
that a lot of people don't think much of professional athletes, and
with all that's been on the news, probably they've got pretty good
reason not to, but most of us are good guys. We work hard. We try
our best to entertain the fans the best we can. It's nice to be
given credit for doing that....
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a stretch where I didn't know if I was going to
hear it anymore,'' he said. ``I didn't know if I was going to get
booed every time I came to the plate, so it's comforting to know
that, at least in most people's eyes, I've been forgiven, (that)
the mistakes that I made haven't soured too many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Jones watched Chipper hit 45 homers and 41 doubles, bat
.319, score 116 runs and knock in 110. She also watched her son
grow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys who are drafted out of high school never have a
chance to grow up; it's mom's house one day, a millionaire the
next,'' Lynne said. ``From the time they're drafted, major-league
ballplayers have a lot of things done for them. They get used to
leaning on other people. He found out the only one who could stand
on his two feet is him. He's grown up a lot. I hope he'll be a
better man for it. It's a horrible way to have to learn a lesson. I
wouldn't wish it on anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is looking ahead now, to putting up another good year and
also signing a new contract. He is in position to become the
highest-paid player in baseball, more than $15.5 million a year. In
the meantime, he's got the MVP label for life.
</P>
<P>
   The actual MVP award has made the rounds to award ceremonies and
photo shoots, and it probably will spend a year in the Braves
Museum at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, it will settle back in his parents' house in
Pierson, not far from that kitchen table. Lynne has a spot picked
out in the family room, above his framed 1995 World Series jersey.
</P>
<P>
   And it will serve as a reminder of just how far Jones had to
come, from the days he collected Little League awards to the
heights of the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistakes he made and the consequences brought him down to
earth really hard,'' Lynne said. ``Sometimes they say you have to
bottom out before you get back up. He came pretty close. For a
while (the fun of playing) was gone, and it was tough to watch. The
kid has wanted nothing more than to play baseball since he was 4
years old _ totally, singularly focused....
</P>
<P>
   ``To see him enjoy the game again and thrive on competition,
that was so wonderful,'' his mother said. ``It made me know he was
healing inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
