<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS02-COX     04-01 2054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets vs. Braves can get heated, but it's not hate
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Theirs is not a loathe-hate relationship. The Braves
don't loathe the Mets _ manager Bobby Valentine excluded, of
course. And no, the Mets don't hate the Braves. ``Why?'' Mets
pitcher Bill Pulsipher asked. ``Are we supposed to hate them?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no. It is neither clean, new-fashioned hate nor sneer and
loathing on the National League campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Mets would rather beat the Braves than anyone else.
Because they're there, up there atop their division for what Mets
reliever Dennis Cook says ``seems like 100 years in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Braves have no one _ not Arizona or old nemesis Los
Angeles, not Ken Griffey Jr. and the Reds or the rest of the NL's
Central Blasting _ that they would rather keep under their thumb
than the Mets. Because after a compelling 1999 season that climaxed
with the most riveting NLCS in years, the Braves and Mets have
become the best of rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the best rivalry we have right now,'' pitcher
Tom Glavine said. ``It's replaced the rivalry we had with the
Dodgers. And after meeting one another in the playoffs last year,
it should add a new dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   The old dementia remains. Listen and you can still hear the Shea
denizens serenading Chipper Jones: ``LAR-ry! LAR-ry!'' And worse.
And more profane for John Rocker, whose rantings and WCW shtick
prompted police snipers to be positioned around Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Add Valentine: ``The polar opposite of Bobby (Cox),'' one Brave
said. ``He thinks he's smarter than everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, the Mets and Braves have the 1999 NLCS. Five one-run
games in a row, concluding with the fall classics: Games 5 and 6,
which lasted 26 innings, took 10 hours and 11 minutes and ended in
the most improbable manner. A bases-loaded, bottom-of-the-11th walk
by Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never going to have another one like that again,''
Brian Jordan said. ``Ever. That was the best playoff series ever in
baseball. I mean, the intensity, the emotion, the length of the
games. The only way it could've gotten better would've been if it
went to Game 7. I'd probably have pulled out my hair.''
</P>
<P>
   His hair intact, Jordan's sense of the rivalry is stronger than
ever, even after just one season as a Brave. ``It's almost like
bragging rights now,'' he said. ``The team you want to beat is the
Mets. Just the division rivalry.'' RESPECT FROM THE METS
</P>
<P>
   Things change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like we're in a rivalry with somebody different
every year,'' said Greg Maddux, a Brave since '93. ``We've never
really had a (prolonged) rivalry since I've been here. It was just
starting to happen with the Dodgers, then the league switched (with
the Braves moving to the NL East). So we kind of create one every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   It was L.A. in '91, the Reds in '92, the Pirates in both of
those playoff series. In '93, it was the Giants, in the last great
pennant race before realignment. The strike struck the '94 Expos.
The '97 Marlins dominated the Braves during the season, took the
NLCS, then were disassembled faster than umpire Eric Gregg could
cry, ``Strike three!''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets fit the profile of a rival. ``Two winning teams,
that's what makes a rivalry,'' Maddux said. ``Nothing else. A
winning team and a losing team, who cares? Unless it's the Cubs and
Cardinals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just teams that you like to beat,'' Glavine said. ``You have
an added emotion to want to beat 'em, whether it's players or
whatever on the other team you don't like. Or that team has had a
lot of success and you're sick of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you're two good teams in the same division fighting for
the division, that's the biggest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, Braves-Mets. ``No. 1, it's the Mets, and they're from New
York, and New York's a big town,'' Glavine said. ``Teams that come
from bigger cities, it's easier to have a rivalry, because people
tend not to like them. The Mets, Yankees, Boston. And going into
New York, their fans are what they are. You're gonna take abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their fans hate us,'' Javy Lopez said, smiling. ``Ninety-nine
percent want to kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets management, meanwhile, takes a businesslike approach. ``The
Mets are really spending a lot of money on players, trying to get
us off the throne,'' Lopez said. ``Not having done that, I guess
that makes them mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons ago, it meant trading for catcher Mike Piazza in
midseason, then signing him to a seven-year, $91 million contract.
Then, third baseman Robin Ventura arrived. During the winter, the
Mets signed free agent Todd Zeile and acquired from Houston
outfielder Derek Bell and left-hander Mike Hampton, who was
runner-up in the Cy Young voting. ``I feel that's the reason they
got me over here _ to get over that hump,'' Hampton said. ``Me and
Derek. I think everybody in this clubhouse feels we're going to
have to go through the Braves eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   But can they? ``I think so, I really do,'' he said. ``I think we
have a legitimate chance at (being) a World Series team here. I saw
it last year, not only the talent and attitude, but the heart to
battle back.'' Hampton doesn't hate the Braves. ``They're trying to
do what everybody else is, and that's win,'' he said. ``You can't
hate a team because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. A Mets clubhouse sampler:
</P>
<P>
   Cook: ``I wouldn't call it a rivalry. We seem to always be
chasing them. They have nothing to prove. They've won the division
for what seems like 100 years in a row. We have something to prove.
And I don't have a problem with the way they carry themselves. As
long as you win, you can carry yourself any way you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura: ``They've always seemed very professional. And it's a
good rivalry. The NLCS, that's stuff that makes rivalries, back and
forth, both teams coming back. If they were crushing us every game,
it wouldn't be a rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Turk Wendell: ``They're not cocky. It's confidence, is
what it is. There's a fine line. If they wanted to be cocky, they'd
have every right to be. Now, some of the smack Chipper talked in
the papers, and the whole Rocker thing, (that) gets guys fired up.
Rocker dug himself a hole to dig out of. Which he did. We got him
once (in Game 4), but he got us, too. Everything he got, he
deserved. You say that stuff in the papers, you've gotta be smarter
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a Mets newcomer like Zeile has a feel for the rivalry: ``I
certainly get a sense of the intensity by the way people discuss
the (NLCS) or how we'll match up this year. What guys are saying
more than anything is that they're anxious for another crack at
them, because we didn't fare as well as we could've at the end of
the regular season and in the playoffs. It's a more anxious
intensity to get back on the playing field against them. Even if
you're one of those guys that loves to hate the Braves or wants to,
you have to respect them because of how they've done it over
time.'' TALK, TALK, TALK
</P>
<P>
   In February, Chipper Jones sat beside Piazza at the ESPYs. ``We
talked just like we're teammates,'' said Jones, who also saw Piazza
at the Players Choice Awards. When Glavine comes to bat, he always
says something to Piazza. Lopez is one of Atlanta's several Latin
players who are friendly with Mets infielders Rey Ordonez and
Edgardo Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets players are good people, nice people, friendly,''
Lopez said. ``The fans will change everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of their guys are fine,'' Glavine said. ``To be honest
with you, there's teams you play you don't like because you don't
like some of their players. The Mets are fine. They play hard. I
think all their guys are pretty cool. If I was going to go in the
(ballpark) weight room and work out, there's nobody on that team
that I'd say, `Oh, this guy's in there. I don't want to be in
there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there's some guys on their team that don't like us,''
Glavine said. ``Some guys last year had a big emotional tie to beat
us because we knocked them out of the playoffs in '98. I'm sure
there are a lot of guys (on several teams) who'd love to beat us
and can't stand us because they think we're cocky. If they come
here, they find out we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, the last game before the All-Star break, Michael
Tucker went in on Piazza with spikes high to beat the Mets. That
enraged Piazza and Valentine. In September, Atlanta swept the Mets
to end the regular season and eliminate New York from the wild-card
race.
</P>
<P>
   Many baseball people don't like Valentine. ``Bobby don't bother
me,'' said Ozzie Guillen, who nevertheless tried to beat him when
he played for the White Sox and Valentine managed Texas. ``A lot of
people don't like his style. He likes to be known, to be seen. He's
not a typical manager, (who will) sit back and manage the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He always says stuff,'' said Eddie Perez, MVP of the 1999
NLCS. ``Players are tired of that. I don't know if he's trying to
intimidate us or say stuff about us. But that hurts. I play so hard
against them because of the way they talk, especially Valentine,
and the things they said about Chipper.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, in September in Atlanta, the Braves swept a
three-game series from the Mets and Jones smacked four homers.
After leaving town, the Mets suspected that Jones was being tipped
which pitch would be thrown to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a player (accusation), I can tell you that,'' said
Bobby Bonilla, then a Met, now a Brave. ``We were still trying to
figure out, `Why are we still pitching to him?' We kind of locked
up the MVP for him, didn't we?''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said: ``Obviously, they didn't have any proof about that.
I write it off as something said in the heat of battle. I've never
been tipped on pitches. I think what frustrated me right there was,
whatever happened to giving a guy credit when he's swinging the bat
well? If Piazza had done that, we'd never had said he's getting
signs. Besides, you've still got to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later at Shea, after Atlanta took two of three from the
Mets and seemingly knocked them out of the playoffs, Jones said,
``Now the Met fans can put on their Yankee stuff.'' Bad move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret saying it, in that the Mets took it the wrong way,''
Jones says now. ``That was directed at five fans sitting over the
dugout in Mets jerseys and they're talking about the Yankees in the
World Series and the Mets were not even out of it. I remember
learning a pretty valuable lesson: That place was chaotic enough
without giving them bulletin-board material.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine supplied some when the Mets arrived in Atlanta for the
NLCS, crowing, ``We're here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a loser,'' Perez said about Valentine. ``I think
they had a better team than us last year (in the NLCS), with Javy
hurt and Big Cat (Andres Galarraga) out.''
</P>
<P>
   Duly inspired, Perez homered to win Game 2, after which Rocker
declared, ``To hell with New York fans.'' Then he taunted Mets fans
at Shea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people say, when you're beating somebody, let sleeping
dogs lie,'' Glavine said. ``They already had 100 reasons to kick
our butts; now they had a few more.''
</P>
<P>
   They nearly did. Now it's 2000. The Mets have revamped their
roster, again. Atlanta has, too. One thing hasn't changed:
Braves-Mets. With baseball again considering realignment, this
could be their last season as division rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``By us coming back and winning (Games) 4 and 5, it changed our
view a little bit that, `Wow, we hung tough and made a series of
it,''' Mets left-hander Al Leiter said. ``I think our confidence is
better because our team is better. I don't think it _ I know it.
Each year (general manager) Steve Phillips has put pieces together
to be where we are _ to compete for the National League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say you still have to give the Braves the upper hand, that
we have to beat them,'' Leiter said. ``It'd be ignorant for me to
say we have the upper hand, because we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be the same way, a good season for both teams,''
Jones said. ``We're two of the best teams in the National League.
Both teams know it. So you've got a lot at stake and tensions are
going to be high. And whoever wins, wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
