<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-GRIFFEY-TRADE02-C     04-01 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GRIFFEY-TRADE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Griffey trade considered a benchmark in baseball
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Call it the BKG trade, the Before Ken Griffey
trade. Until Feb. 10, 2000, the BKG deal was acknowledged as not
only one of the best trades ever concocted by the Cincinnati Reds,
it was considered a benchmark in Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It was the baseball diamond heist of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May was an important cog in The Big Red Machine. In fact, he
was the one who came up with that nickname. He was a hard-hitting
first baseman and a funny man in the clubhouse, a leader with a
verbal knife that cut deep.
</P>
<P>
   So, when general manager Bob Howsam included May in a trade with
the Houston Astros on Nov. 29, 1971, fans in Cincinnati howled.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Howsam give up the popular May, he tossed in very
popular second baseman Tommy Helms and outfielder Jimmy Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   And what did Howsam get for this tidy bundle of talent?
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Denis Menke. Who? Outfielder Ed Armbrister. Who?
Pitcher Jack Billingham? Who? Outfielder Cesar Geronimo. Who? And
second baseman Joe Morgan. Who?
</P>
<P>
   The Reds were in the 1970 World Series, losing to the Baltimore
Orioles and the magnetic glove of third baseman Brooks Robinson,
four games to one.
</P>
<P>
   Howsam realized the club was a few pieces short of taking the
final step. He acted quickly and boldly and if the public didn't
feel the same way, well, wait until the results were in.
</P>
<P>
   The results were staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Billingham became a regular in the rotation. Geronimo became a
wizard in center field and developed into a steady No. 8 hitter.
And Morgan? Well, he has a plaque in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   The trade became known as one of the best and most one-sided in
the history of baseball. It pushed the Reds over the top, put The
Big Red Machine in high gear and led to World Series championships
in 1975 and 1976.
</P>
<P>
   What is generally forgotten is that Howsam made another
significant trade that same year _ May 29, 1971. He dealt shortstop
Frank Duffy and pitcher Vern Geishert to the San Francisco Giants
for outfielder George Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy and Geishert never were heard from outside their family
circles, but Foster was as significant as Tony Perez, Joe Morgan,
Pete Rose and Dave Concepcion to The Big Red Machine. Until two
months ago, those two trades were the most significant in Reds
history.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 10, general manager Jim Bowden, after holding his ground
against trading talent like second baseman Pokey Reese, first
baseman Sean Casey, outfielder Dmitri Young and pitcher Scott
Williamson, obtained baseball's marquee player, Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it at a low, low cost.
</P>
<P>
   The best player the Reds lost was young outfielder Mike Cameron,
who may some day shine. But his star never will shine with the glow
of Griffey's. Bowden tossed in malcontent pitcher Brett Tomko and a
couple Class A minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Bowden had the Seattle Mariners against a wall,
unarmed and with their hands up. They could do nothing but trade
Griffey to the Reds for whatever they could get.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, as a 10-and-5 player (10 years in the majors, five with
the same team), could refuse any trade. He told the Mariners,
``Cincinnati and Cincinnati only.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Mariners didn't trade him, Griffey would have become a
free agent after this season and signed with the Reds anyway.
Seattle would have gotten nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the Mariners got nothing anyway. But it figures to
supercede anything Howsam did ... maybe. The verdict won't come
until a few years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Will Griffey help the Reds win two world championships? After
all, even though Bowden obtained baseball's best player, he
obtained only one player.
</P>
<P>
   Howsam pried five away from the Astros and four figured
prominently in Reds history _ Morgan, Billingham, Geronimo and
Armbrister, who had a big moment in the 1975 World Series against
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's more difficult for one player to make a difference than
five, but if anybody can, it's Junior Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
