<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-GRIFFEY-IMPACT02-     04-01 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GRIFFEY-IMPACT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Griffey a great catch, but rest of Reds must contribute
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Ken Griffey Jr. is many things to many people,
depending on what vantage point one views him.
</P>
<P>
   To fans, he is the icon of sports, the man who replaced Michael
Jordan as the most recognizable person in sports.
</P>
<P>
   To opposing pitchers, he is a menace with mayhem in mind as he
stands at home plate waving his black double-lacquered Louisville
Slugger.
</P>
<P>
   To his teammates, he is hits, home runs, RBIs and superlative
defensive exploits, along with a few laughs in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   To the Cincinnati Reds, he is tickets sold, memorabilia and
trinkets sold and guaranteed attention from the national media.
</P>
<P>
   All that is pabulum. The big question is, ``Will Junior
translate into victories and championships?''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Jim Bowden, the man who worked the miracle that
brought the 30-year-old Griffey to Cincinnati, is wise enough to
realize baseball games are not won by one player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he is the best player in the game,'' Bowden said. ``But
baseball isn't like basketball, where a Michael Jordan can control
the ball and control the game. In baseball, you can't control the
ball. Griffey comes to bat once every nine at-bats. He'll catch
every ball hit near him, but he can't control when it is hit to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   So other parts must be in place and that, of course, falls into
the hands of the one player on a baseball field who does control
the ball ... the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   As Bowden says daily, ``You can never get enough pitching. We'll
only go as far as our pitching takes us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Bowden, with 30 teams in the majors leagues,
pitching is diluted. Teams with more than two outstanding starters
are rare.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees win because of pitching, not hitting. The
Atlanta Braves win because of pitching, not hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Reds have enough to make adding Griffey into the mix
worth it?
</P>
<P>
   Opening Day starter Pete Harnisch is as solid as granite. Denny
Neagle should be dazzling after going 6-0 in his last seven starts
last season, but he was wobbly all spring. Steve Parris and Ron
Villone didn't figure into the starting mix at all last spring, but
were sterling citizens once they were plugged into last year's
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Can they do it again? They have no history other than last
season for comparison, so it is a cross your fingers and hold your
breath situation.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth starter? Before the season is over, that spot could be
occupied by a half-dozen suspects, unless Bowden can coax a decent
starter from another team in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen is nearly intact, missing only seldom-used Stan
Belinda from last year, but returning Dennys Reyes, Gabe White,
Scott Sullivan, Scott Williamson and Danny Graves. The law of
averages says they all can't repeat, and rookie of the year
Williamson was injured the last month of last season and spent most
of the spring trying to find the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, with the addition of Griffey and Dante Bichette
into an already potent lineup, runs shouldn't be difficult to
accumulate daily. Teams, though, can only outscore the opposition
10-9 so many times. Just ask the Cleveland Indians, who survive
because they are in a watery division.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are in what many believe the toughest division in
baseball. St. Louis will score runs and pitch. Houston will score
runs and pitch. Chicago will score runs. Pittsburgh will pitch.
Milwaukee will neither score runs nor pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The defense up the middle is noteworthy, except for catcher
Eddie Taubensee, who hits with a passion but throws with a prayer.
Taubensee threw out only 15 of 106 base-stealers. But the team was
68-42 when he caught and the team earned run average was 3.78,
while it was 4.93 when Jason LaRue caught and 3.81 when Brian
Johnson caught.
</P>
<P>
   The double play combination of shortstop Larkin and second
baseman Reese is not only good, but flashy. Reese fields everything
on the continent and Larkin remains one of the game's best
shortstops. Griffey has enough Gold Gloves to stock Fort Knox and
catches everything from left-center to right-center and as outfield
coach Dave Collins says, ``He does it so easily he turns difficult
catches into what looks to be routine.''
</P>
<P>
   On the corners is where the defense is suspect. Aaron Boone is
only average with less-than-average range at third base, but
finished last season with a 41-game errorless streak. Sean Casey
has limited range at first base, but catches everything he touches
and made only six errors all season and went the final 48 games
without an error.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Dmitri Young and right fielder Dante Bichette never
will be known for their leather. They make up for it with their
wood. Both should have a two-word phrase in their vocabulary when a
fly ball heads for the outfield: ``Yours, Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bowden and manager Jack McKeon cite pitching as the key,
starter Harnisch says, ``We'll get the pitching, just as we did
last year. Before last season I said, 'If we catch the ball, we'll
win.' We caught the ball and we won. It's the same thing this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is an excellent accoutrement, an attention-grabbing
bauble. He will do his thing. The rest of the Reds, especially the
pitchers, must do more than their thing for Griffey to get that
World Series ring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1417EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
