</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCKEON-GRIFFEY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jack: Junior talks with bat, glove
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ During more than 50 years in professional
baseball, Cincinnati Reds manager Jack McKeon has learned a lot
more about the game than how to fill out a lineup card, the nuances
of the double switch and the proper way to snip a premium cigar.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important duties of a manager is how to handle
and how to relate to his players _ which ones need kind and
soothing words and which ones need swift kicks in the posterior.
</P>
<P>
   In that facet of his job, McKeon is a master. His
fatherly/grandfatherly approach is perfect for a talent-laden team.
His style is, ``To play and let play.''
</P>
<P>
   His credo is for his team to have fun and the best way to have
fun is to win. Show up on time, play the game right, play the game
hard, have fun and McKeon will be no more than a puff of cigar
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   That is the main reason he and Junior Griffey will get along
famously. Griffey plays the way McKeon wants the game played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably didn't speak more than 100 words all spring,''
McKeon said. ``Once you've said, `Good morning, how are you?' What
else is there to say to him? He is the best player in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the way he is with Barry Larkin, the way he was last year
with Greg Vaughn, the way he is with Sean Casey and Pokey Reese. He
is a hands-off, let-'em-play manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Griffey slid right into our clubhouse, no problems, no muss,
no fuss,'' McKeon said. ``He has a lot of close friends on this
team, especially Larkin. And having his father (Ken Griffey Sr.)
here as a coach certainly helps. He blended in real fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to the right club,'' McKeon added. ``We want them to
have fun, enjoy themselves. There is no pressure or drudgery
associated with this team. Everybody knows they won't be shot or
shipped out if they make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Junior came here and right away saw guys like Sean
Casey, Pokey Reese and Larkin having a lot of fun while they work
and play,'' he said. ``He saw that good rapport and camaraderie we
have on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey laughs and agrees with McKeon's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our longest conversation all spring was, `Hi, how are you?,'''
and, `Here is your day-off schedule,''' Griffey said. ``I think we
had one five-minute conversation about a commercial I was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows I don't say much to anybody,'' Griffey added. ``I
joke around with the guys and say some off-the-wall things, but I
don't yell at people because they messed up. That's not me and the
manager doesn't have to worry about me trying to run things.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one ominous factor that confronts McKeon and Griffey
nearly every day, especially from out-of-town writers. They wonder
not if, but how soon, will Griffey Sr. replace McKeon as manager
... and wasn't that part of the deal to get Junior to come to
Cincinnati?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's insulting to us,'' general manager Jim Bowden says.
``Jack McKeon is our manager ... period. If we had plans to make
Ken Griffey Sr. our manager right away, would we have given him
permission to interview for three or four other managerial openings
last year?''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey Sr. coached in Seattle when Junior played for the
Mariners, but there was no talk at the time of Senior replacing Lou
Piniella as manager to keep Junior in town.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Griffey Sr. wants to manage. And yes, Junior wants to play
for him. Junior, though, is signed for the next decade to play for
the Reds and, yes, Senior could eventually manage the Reds down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad wants to manage and I'd like to play for him, sure,''
Junior said. ``But if he has an opportunity somewhere else soon, I
sure hope he takes it. There is no agreement here that he has to
manage me with the Reds.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
