<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-BOWDEN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowden always ready to deal
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Shortly before the Cincinnati Reds took the
field for another Grapefruit League game this spring, their general
manager could be found prowling the grounds, a cell phone to his
ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talkin' trade?'' someone asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope so,'' Jim Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   With Bowden around, the roster is always in a state of flux. And
now, given increased financial flexibility as a result of Carl
Lindner's ownership group taking control, he is that much busier.
Checking. Always checking. Have the Minnesota Twins reconsidered?
Will they listen to offers for Brad Radke now? Is there really a
market out there for Dmitri Young? Where can that missing pitcher
be found?
</P>
<P>
   Think blockbuster. Bowden does. And sometimes his patience with
the cards he's holding wears thin. Asked recently about a pitcher
on the bubble and whether he would make it through the weekend,
Bowden said, ``I couldn't tell you that about any of our players
except for Griffey and Larkin. I may get mad and trade them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden lives to trade, loves to trade. Acquiring Ken Griffey Jr.
on Feb. 10 without dismantling the team will go down as his
crowning achievement no matter what else he does, no matter how it
plays out. And nary a day went by this spring without someone,
whether fan or media member, patting him on the back,
congratulating him.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, he should have worn a mask if he intended to pull off
such a heist. Mike Cameron, Bret Tomko and two minor leaguers for a
10-time All-Star? Can you say Executive of the Year? Again?
</P>
<P>
   The Griffey trade brought out the little kid in Bowden, who
turns 39 in May. It had been his dream to reunite the best player
in baseball with his hometown, and he made it happen, shrewdly
outfoxing Seattle Mariners counterpart Pat Gillick in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball establishment even seems to have forgiven Bowden
for later boasting in a national publication about how he pulled it
off, how he waited and waited until Gillick finally ran out of time
and the asking price began to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Griffey engineered his way out of Seattle. Sure, he would
not be wearing a Reds uniform had it not been his intention.
Bowden, however, can rightly take credit for creating an atmosphere
to which such a superstar of Griffey's caliber would be attracted.
Not lost on Griffey were the Reds' 96 wins last season.
</P>
<P>
   Not lost on Griffey was the type of team Bowden had been
assembling and how, amazingly, shortstop and team captain Barry
Larkin was still its driving force after several years of trade
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Reds been viewed as a team going nowhere, what chance
would they have had to lure Griffey, who had expressed the desire
to play for a contender, but easily could have stayed in Seattle
another year and then tested the free-agent market? Bowden knew
this, of course, and had the foresight to put a winner on the field
before the game's most celebrated star became available.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden seems to do his best work when backed into a corner.
After losing slugger Greg Vaughn to free agency over the winter, he
talked the Colorado Rockies into taking reliever Stan Belinda and
outfielder Jeffrey Hammonds for Dante Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what Jim's going to do,'' Reds manager Jack
McKeon said, meaning that as a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   For Reds fans, the best news about Bowden is that in 1998 he
signed a contract extension that commits him and his cell phone to
Cincinnati through the 2003 season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
