<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-LINEUP02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key to run-producing offense is Mayhem Row
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It isn't Murderer's Row down in the depths of the
Cincinnati Reds batting order _ sixth, seventh and eighth. Maybe
it's Assailant's Row or Perpetrator's Row. It definitely is not the
soft underbelly of the batting order, as it is with many teams.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Young will bat sixth. In the past two seasons, D.Y. has
batted .310 and .317. He has hit 14 home runs both seasons. He has
driven in 83 and 56 runs. He has 48 and 30 doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Taubensee will bat seventh. Last season, E.T. phoned home
with a career-best .311 batting average, a career-best 21 homers
and a career-best 87 RBIs. Aaron Boone will bat eighth. Last
season, A.B. was a positive force with a .280 batting average, 14
homers and 72 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that isn't the most potent lower third of a batting order
in baseball, I challenge somebody to find it,'' general manager Jim
Bowden said. It is fact that the combined 35 homers and 159 RBIs by
Taubensee and Boone are the best numbers for hitters No. 7 and No.
8 in any major-league batting order. The mayhem, though, comes from
above, which is why manager Jack McKeon can put such potency at the
bottom of his lineup card, and smile broadly as he does it.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with Pokey Reese, who began last season as the leadoff
hitter, but got hurt. His replacement at No. 1 was Mike Cameron,
who did so well that McKeon left him there and plopped Reese in the
No. 8 hole when Reese returned to the lineup. With Cameron gone as
part of the Ken Griffey Jr. trade, Reese is back on top of the heap
of hitters. He hit .285 last season, which is A-1. But he drew only
35 walks in 585 at-bats and had only a .330 on-base percentage.
That isn't good enough. A strong leadoff hitter should have an
on-base percentage of .400 or better.
</P>
<P>
   Reese plans to work on it, be more selective. ``I hate to get
behind in the count and I hate to watch good pitches go by,'' Reese
said. ``But I know I have to do it. I have to get on base whatever
way possible for those guys behind me. It is an incentive for me
because I know if I get on base I can score 130 runs this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Reese is the Reds' version of Mayhem Row _ Barry
Larkin, Junior Griffey, Dante Bichette and Sean Casey. Larkin is
the perfect No. 2 hitter, a guy who gives himself up without a
whimper. If Reese gets on base, Larkin will hit the ball behind
him, go to right field, anything to move Reese to second on a
ground ball or to third with a base hit to right.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the juice ... Griffey and Bichette. Griffey's numbers
the past four years are Ruthian. He has averaged 52 homers, hitting
56 in both 1997 and 1998. He has averaged 142 runs batted in,
driving in 147 in 1997 and 146 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As the Chicago Cubs' new manager, Don Baylor, said during spring
training, ``Griffey will be pitched around a lot. There are guys on
every team you don't want to beat you, and he is the guy on that
team.''
</P>
<P>
   That often should leave the bases densely populated for
Bichette, and he is accustomed to watching teams pitch around the
hitter in front of him to take their chances with him. ``Happened
to me all the time in Colorado,'' he said. ``They would pitch
around Larry Walker to face me. Hey, I understand that. I'd pitch
around Griffey and Walker to pitch to me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bichette, though, makes them pay and pay and pay. In his last
seven seasons with the Rockies, he hit .317 with an average of 29
home runs and 118 RBIs. Pick your poison, men.
</P>
<P>
   Casey hit .332 last season and astounded those who said he
wouldn't hit for power by jolting 25 homers and compiling 99 RBIs.
But he's giving up the No. 3 spot in the order to Junior, dropping
to No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   It is an offense that should score runs in the same abundance
scored by their Ohio brethren to the north, the American League's
Cleveland Indians. The Tribe, which gets the added plus of the
designated hitter, scored an amazing 1,009 runs last season. The
Reds, without Griffey and without Bichette, scored 865. ``Don't see
any reason why we can't score 1,000 ... or more,'' Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
