<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-DAY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deadline two weeks away, with extra time this year
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The great American game may be procrastination, not
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain the millions of Americans who put off
their income tax preparations until the very last hour?
</P>
<P>
   We get two extra days this year, because the traditional
deadline, April 15, falls on a Saturday. You can bet that millions
of Americans will mosey through that extra weekend, confident that
they can stall just one more day.
</P>
<P>
   That's a mistake. In fact, stalling past today is an invitation
to unforeseen and unnecessary problems.
</P>
<P>
   The closer we get to the deadline, the harder it will be to find
help, professional or volunteer. You may have more problems
locating copies of any missing forms and instructions. Even on the
Internet, which has greatly simplified the process, you can't be
surprised if last-minute traffic jams develop.
</P>
<P>
   Want to start now? Here are some steps you can take:
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for freebies. There are locations where professionals or
trained volunteers will prepare your returns for free. No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service is providing help because it wants
to stop being seen as the enemy of taxpayers. Kroger stores are
involved because it's a community service _ one that brings people
into the stores. You'll find IRS employes at selected IRS offices
and Kroger stores.
</P>
<P>
   The senior advocacy group AARP just wants to help.
</P>
<P>
   The service is available to anyone who walks in the door. ``We
will help anybody with low to moderate income,'' said Billy
Phillips of Thomaston, coordinator of the AARP program. The
IRS-staffed sites have no income limitations.
</P>
<P>
   People with particularly complex tax situations are probably
better off doing it for themselves or hiring a professional. That's
just plain good sense if a lot of money is at stake. At the AARP
sites, volunteers will not tackle questions for which they are not
trained.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you bring with you last year's federal and state
returns, along with all forms for the current tax year. That
includes W-2s, 1099s and other papers that show tax-related income
and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pick a professional, and do it right now. Remember that more
than half of America's individual taxpayers already use CPAs,
enrolled agents or other paid preparers. The best of them may
already be booked solid.
</P>
<P>
   The resource list gives contacts for professional associations
that make referrals. Remember that the best referral always is a
word-of-mouth recommendation from someone you know and trust.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to go with full-time, year-round tax preparers, and to
ask how they keep up with changes in the law.
</P>
<P>
   You should avoid people who advertise that they will get you the
biggest deductions. They might also get you the biggest headaches
with the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Ask upfront how much the service will cost, and ask if the
preparer will stick with you in case of an audit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use your computer. Store-bought software is an established
option, and this year many taxpayers are preparing their returns by
using software on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's TaxCut, Quicken TurboTax and MacInTax are the
established packages available in stores. All of them get high
ratings from reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   They are also available online. For Kiplinger software, go to
www.taxcut.com or www.HRBlock.com. The Quicken versions are at
www.turbotax.com or www
</P>
<P>
   .macintax.com.
</P>
<P>
   You can find do-it-yourself software at hundreds of other Web
sites maintained by banks, mutual funds and brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   The buzzword for all these options is ``e-filing.'' Roughly one
of every four individual taxpayers will file electronically this
year, and the IRS would like to see a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   The government likes e-filing for reasons that should also
appeal to taxpayers: fewer mathematical mistakes, legible returns
and easier processing.
</P>
<P>
   There's one other advantage for consumers: The software's
interview format, asking one logical question after another,
reduces the fear that you will miss crucial instructions or
misunderstand what you're supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that factor alone will encourage more people to file their
returns before the last minute, this year and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
