<HEADER>
A4304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-NLPREVIEW-COX     04-01 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLPREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds feeling confident with Griffey in the fold
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before they get started, Barry Larkin, captain of the
Cincinnati Reds and a forthright fellow, wants the rest of the
National League to know something.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a matter of whether we will win the division,''
Larkin said. ``It is a matter of by how many games.''
</P>
<P>
   But wait. There's more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that,'' Larkin said. ``That's the attitude we have
here. The atmosphere here still presents itself that we had last
year. We are confident. Guys can have fun when they're confident.
We'll have a good time, have fun on the field, because it is always
fun when you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Having Ken Griffey Jr. in your dugout can encourage such talk.
But around the league, the Reds have shown enough power and
pitching to make a quick bunch of believers. The old NL ``Comedy''
Central has become the most formidible division in the league, and
perhaps in the majors, and Cincinnati is presenting itself as a
team to be beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be, with the club they had, and you throw in
Griffey,'' St. Louis general manager Walt Jocketty said. ``They won
96 games (in 1999). We're not ready to throw in the towel, but it
certainly is going to make it tougher to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will have plenty to say about it. Replacing the
injured John Smoltz will be nearly impossible, and the New York
Mets made offseason improvements. But the Braves field what might
be their most complete offensive team of any of their eight
division-winning rosters of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like our team,'' left-hander Tom Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   NL West champion Arizona likes its team, too, so much that the
Diamondbacks hardly touched the roster over the winter after a
100-win season. That inactivity raised hopes in San Francisco and
Los Angeles, which improved their clubhouses. Four teams have won
this division over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The NL wild card becomes harder to call than the division
favorites. Although the Mets will miss first baseman John Olerud,
the addition of Mike Hampton fixes a bigger problem. St. Louis
improved its pitching. Houston retains a strong core from the group
that won the NL Central three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   And as for a dark horse, Philadelphia has an opinion. ``The
future is here now,'' right-hander Curt Schilling said. ``No doubt
about it. We legitimately have a chance to go the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL LEAGUE PREDICTIONS
</P>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   1. Atlanta: Reduced pitching staff might require five runs a
night to win, but this roster can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   2. New York: Hampton enhances a team that made strong fall run,
but a poor start will renew the feuding.
</P>
<P>
   3. Philadelphia: Only one winning season in 13 years but the
Phils think they're ready; they must avoid typical late swoon.
</P>
<P>
   4. Montreal: Felipe Alou proclaims Expos' ``crisis'' over, but
someone better teach them to field first.
</P>
<P>
   5. Florida: Targeted contending date: 2002. Until then, these
fish continue some serious bottom-feeding.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   1. Cincinnati: One winning season in the past four, but this
roster is seamless, and Griffey stirs the drink.
</P>
<P>
   2. St. Louis: Pitching still not great yet, but it is improved
enough to take advantage of Big Mac run-support.
</P>
<P>
   3. Houston: New park, new uniforms, but star has slipped; could
see October but not with another Central title.
</P>
<P>
   4. Pittsburgh: Pirates finally might be on to something with
rebuilt talent base. The Central is just too deep.
</P>
<P>
   5. Chicago: HRs rain on Waveland, and Cubbie pitchers serve up
most of them; Baylor earns his money.
</P>
<P>
   6. Milwaukee: What foul cheese be this? Good news: Roster is
revamped. Bad news: New players won't help.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   1. Arizona: 1999 was no mirage. The D-backs are skilled
everywhere and are smart enough to learn what last year required.
</P>
<P>
   2. Los Angeles: Better vibes with Mondesi gone, Green in. Better
yet, who gagged big-mouth GM Malone?
</P>
<P>
   3. San Fran: Bonds waited so long to play in this new park; now
that it's built, can his 35-year-body make it?
</P>
<P>
   4. Colorado: Managers leave Denver the way baseballs leave
Coors. Buddy Bell ponders the uselessness of the six-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   5. San Diego: Padres swear they aren't the Marlins of 1997, but
the roster atrophies as Gwynn's tummy swells.
</P>
<P>
   POSTSEASON
</P>
<P>
   Wild-card team: Mets
</P>
<P>
   First round: Braves over Diamondbacks; Reds over Mets.
</P>
<P>
   NLCS: Braves over Reds.
</P>
<P>
   World Series: Braves over Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Favorite: Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Team to watch: New York.
</P>
<P>
   Team not to watch: Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeper: Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Manager on the hot seat: Terry Francona, Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Player on the spot: Tom Glavine, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Player who will thrive with new team: Mike Hampton, New York.
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Favorite: Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Team to watch: Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Team not to watch: Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeper: Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Manager on the hot seat: Gene Lamont, Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Player on the spot: Jose Lima, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Player who will thrive with new team: Ken Griffey Jr.,
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Favorite: Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Team to watch: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Team not to watch: San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeper: Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Manager on the hot seat: Davey Johnson, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Player on the spot: Al Martin, San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Player who will thrive with new team: Jeff Cirillo, Colorado.
</P>
