<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-470&AMP;ADD-NYT     04-01 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL SEEMS CALM, FOR NOW, IN BATTLE OVER CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ If there could be such a thing as a quiet day in the
tumultuous story of Elian Gonzalez, it was Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After a tense week filled with defiant speeches against the
federal government by local politicians, accusations by family
members that Elian's father has been verbally abusive to the boy in
telephone calls, and an unexpected show of support for the Miami
relatives by Vice President Al Gore, a comparative calm settled
over Little Havana on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Even the demonstrators _ a few dozen have kept vigil around the
clock there _ were mostly quiet outside the house where the
6-year-old boy lives with his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, and
other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Last week angry demonstrators clashed with and routed a small
group of counterdemonstrators who said they believed Elian should
go back to his father in Cuba, and yelled ``comunista'' at
reporters. But on Saturday an elderly man _ retirees have made up a
large part of the weekday force of demonstrators outside the home _
waved pleasantly to a passing reporter.
</P>
<P>
   But then the crisis itself seemed on hold for the weekend, after
Lazaro Gonzalez and federal government officials agreed to suspend
their long-running negotiations over how, and whether, the boy
would be handed over to his father or federal authorities. That
seeming calm, say people who have been following the case, will
evaporate this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think if they make enough noise, the U.S. government will
listen,'' said Lisandro Perez, director of the Cuban Research
Institute at Florida International University.
</P>
<P>
   But the government, despite Gore's defection from his
administration's position on the Elian situation, seems to be
holding to Attorney General Janet Reno's resolve to reunite the boy
with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials said that if the family lost its appeal
for custody of Elian in the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in
Atlanta, and if his great-uncle still refused to sign an agreement
to peacefully hand the boy over, they would on Tuesday revoke the
boy's right to remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials are afraid of violence, as well as trauma
for Elian, if federal officials do not have the cooperation of
Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Coffey, a lawyer for the boy's Miami relatives, said the
family had never said it would resist if federal authorities went
to the house to take the child. Lazaro Gonzalez has said he would
not, however, deliver the boy to them.
</P>
<P>
   It has all led to an unusually ugly confrontation between the
federal government and Cuban exiles here, and one that grew
steadily hotter as the week progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are destroying justice because we are Cubans,'' said
Dulce Gonzalez, a retired teacher who arrived from Cuba 30 years
ago and kept vigil at the house all week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was, for everyone associated, a dizzying week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Lazaro Gonzalez refused to sign the government's
agreement, while in the streets of Little Havana exile leaders
continued to drill a small army of demonstrators in protest
tactics, including a ``human chain'' intended to prevent federal
officials from taking Elian.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, President Fidel Castro surprised many when he said
that the boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, was ready to go to the
United States to reclaim his son, and would be accompanied by an
entourage that would include his family in Cuba, Cuban officials, a
teacher, classmates of Elian, psychiatrists and others.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official told The Associated Press later in
the week that the boy's father would most likely be given custody
of Elian if he traveled to the United States, though it is
uncertain when that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, 20 elected officials in Miami said they would not lend
their resources to federal officials if they arrived to retrieve
the boy, and warned that violence could break out.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gore broke with President Clinton and Attorney
General Janet Reno, saying the boy should be allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, lawyers for Elian's relatives in Miami said that
the boy's father was verbally abusive to the boy on the telephone,
and that he told Elian his mother was still alive in Cuba. The
boy's mother drowned when the boat that was bringing her, the boy
and others to Florida capsized in the Florida Straits.
</P>
<P>
   This week is likely to bring more of the same furor. Federal
officials have said they will not go in and immediately take the
child if Lazaro Gonzalez does not sign the paper, but that they
would revoke the boy's immigration status, clearing the way for his
removal from the home.
</P>
<P>
   But in the streets, demonstrators say they are ready, at a
moment's notice, to block that effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
