A4313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-DISSENT-NYT &LR;      04-01 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA KEEPS HERO'S WIDOW FROM VISITING CRITIC OF ARMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The widow of Edgar Snow, the American journalist who
was celebrated here as a ``friend of China'' for his sympathetic
portraits of the Communist revolution, was prevented by police
Saturday from meeting a prominent critic of the 1989 army crackdown
on student democracy demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by at least two dozen plainclothes officers, several
of them carrying ill-concealed video cameras in book bags, Lois
Wheeler Snow, 79, and her 50-year-old son, Christopher Snow, were
halted at the gate of People's University Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   They had hoped to meet with the critic, Ding Zilin, at her
apartment inside the campus, where she is a professor, and to
support her efforts to provide money and consolation to relatives
of those killed by the army in the Tiananmen Square crackdown in
June 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Ding's own 17-year-old son was among the dead. Since then, she
has risked arrest by demanding that top officials be held
accountable for the shooting of unarmed demonstrators, and she has
been a key organizer of bereaved families, many of whom have
suffered financially.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the authorities felt compelled to keep apart these
two women _ one who for years was described here as a great friend
of the nation, but was sickened by the 1989 crackdown, and one who
lost her son _ was a renewed reminder of the sensitivity in the
Communist Party about the Tiananmen Square demonstrations and their
violent suppression.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, authorities have tried to prevent Ding's
family group from receiving donations, and she has often been kept
under virtual house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a just a friendly visit from a mother with a son to a
mother who has lost a son _ to many mothers who have lost sons,''
Snow said as she was stopped from entering the campus by its chief
of security. ``I just want them to let her receive donations and
distribute them to the victims' families.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, Ding's apartment was also surrounded by
plainclothes officers and she was not allowed to leave home.
Several foreign journalists nearby were temporarily detained.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Ding's, Su Bingxian, whose son was also killed in
the 1989 crackdown, emerged to meet the visitors and relay Ding's
regrets. Snow, clearly moved, gave the friend a book of her late
husband's writings and what she described as a symbolic
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Snow, Edgar Snow's second wife, was married to him from
1949 until his death in 1972. She lives in Switzerland, where they
moved in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every year from 1972 to 1987, Snow said in an interview,
she returned to Beijing and was honored by high officials. But in
1989, she publicly condemned the crackdown and did not return again
until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had been touched by press accounts of Ding's
efforts on behalf of victims' families, and last summer had tried
to send her a letter and a small contribution. ``The letter was
confiscated and she was not allowed to receive the money,'' Snow
said. ``So I decided it was time to act.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, Snow became the first Western journalist to spend time
with Mao Tse-tung, when his bedraggled army was holed up in the
mountains. Snow's 1937 book on the rise of the Communists, ``Red
Star Over China,'' became a classic.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, he was one of the few Americans allowed to enter
China, but his books and magazine articles played down or missed
some of the darker aspects of Mao's revolution, including a famine
at the beginning of that decade.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, when Mao and Prime Minister Chou En-lai wanted to
signal a willingness to reopen ties with Washington, Snow and his
wife were invited to sit on the rostrum with Mao and other leaders
during the National Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   When Snow died two years later, his wife returned with a portion
of his ashes, which are interred in a monument at Beijing
University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
