<HEADER>
A4315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-GAS-PRICES-ART-     04-01 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GAS-PRICES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH GAS PRICES SPUR LIFE CHANGES FOR CALIFORNIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Alaska)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gas prices may have risen across the nation in
recent months, as a tight oil supply has driven up the cost of
crude oil. But nowhere in the country are the increases more
astounding than in California, where they have even become
noticeable to people not accustomed to worrying about such things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can barely even fill it up, it's just so expensive,'' said
Katherine Butler, 30, an actress (30 is her real age, she noted
with pride), as she gassed her black BMW convertible at a Sunset
Boulevard station.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Butler said, it costs up to $30 to fill the tank, so
``I'm always just getting enough to get to the next place.''
</P>
<P>
   The vastness of the West has generally made development
horizontal rather than vertical, and in decades past California has
invested heavily in highways. Cars here are more than a privilege
or a convenience; they are a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of OPEC's decision last week to increase production of
crude oil, gasoline here has reached nearly $1.79 a gallon, 28
cents higher on average than in the rest of the nation. In some
places it has exceeded $2.
</P>
<P>
   California has an unusual system: it requires a cleaner-burning
formula than the rest of the country and buys gasoline from
different sources. Most of the state's gas comes from Alaska and
California, and 90 percent of the market is controlled by five
companies, according to state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Cars are still the vehicle of choice in Los Angeles; ridership
on buses and subways is actually down slightly in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   But a few who have made the change to public transportation say
that the gas price increases have profoundly altered how they live.
They have gotten out of their cars, come into contact with other
Angelenos on the subway, enjoyed the camaraderie and passed their
time talking, embroidering or reading, instead of steaming in that
other Los Angeles icon, the traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the encounters have been a bit otherworldly. Heather
Stevens, 31, a Web site editor who takes two subway trains and a
bus to get from her home in Long Beach to her job in midtown Los
Angeles, said she recently sat next to a woman who asked her if she
was going to Houston. When she replied no, the woman said: ``I need
to go to Houston. I'm from the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Evon Gray, a 44-year-old health care customer service
representative, said she rode the subway because ``I was
budgeted.'' The transportation stipend Gray receives from her
employer covers less and less of her gas costs, she said, and ``I
figured it was cheaper for me to take the subway than keep buying
gas.''
</P>
<P>
   State legislators are backing competing proposals to alleviate
the crunch. Republicans favor eliminating the gas tax, which adds
19 cents a gallon. Democrats say that would not stop oil companies
from raising prices further and have proposed a measure to impose a
100 percent tax on oil companies' ``excess profits'' and return the
money to residents. The proposal is short on details and has been
met with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, public outcry has been more muted than it
was a year ago, when the price of regular unleaded rose to what now
seems a modest $1.58 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the high prices, many in Los Angeles do not consider
public transportation an option _ because their homes are not close
enough to bus or subway stops, because it would be too
time-consuming or because they fear it would be unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   And the subway has not won over all of its new patrons. The high
gas prices are not enough to keep some from going back to their
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not me,'' said Trevon Blaylock, 30, a Mobil gasoline tank
driver who has been riding the subway for two months since his car
broke down. ``I'm buying a car tomorrow. I'm about tired of this,
this subway. It's more convenient to drive a car. In L.A., you have
to have a car.''
</P>
<P>
   For Eugene Negri, a 48-year-old private chef from the Hollywood
Hills, the cost of filling his pickup truck has risen to about $30
a week. But is he doing anything different to save money?
</P>
<P>
   ``No change,'' Negri said, as he finished filling his truck.
``Just endure the pain. At least we have good weather.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
