<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCIDENTS RENEW RANCH'S BORDER PATROL BAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (jw) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARITA, Texas _ After government vehicles ran over and injured
illegal immigrants on a vast cattle ranch here twice in the past
month, the ranch's owners notified the U.S. Border Patrol that its
agents could no longer pursue their quarry on ranch property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a hard situation,'' said Richard Leshin, a lawyer for
the John G. and Marie Stella Kenedy Memorial Foundation, a
charitable organization that owns the Kenedy Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which has strong ties to the Roman Catholic
Church, made its decision because it believes that the Border
Patrol has been violating immigrants' human rights.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Leshin said, ``The government has told us that they
have the authority to seize the ranch because we are in violation
of federal law, and that's a major concern for the foundation's
directors.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Border Patrol officials say that while they have
the right to seize the ranch, they do not plan to. But they say
they expect the foundation to allow agents to patrol the area
freely, which, they say, is necessary to control illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Each month, several thousand undocumented immigrants try to slip
past the Border Patrol's K-24 checkpoint in the middle of ranch
property on Highway 77, just south of Sarita, the Border Patrol
said. Many of the immigrants enter the largely uninhabited
235,000-acre ranch, one of the largest in Texas, in hopes of
escaping north.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by rolling plains of scrub chaparral and mesquite
trees, the checkpoint and the 90 agents who operate it are like a
dike against the human river of illegal immigrants, said Fred
Borrego, a Border Patrol supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are poor, they're hungry, they're desperate, and
they'll do anything to keep from being caught,'' Borrego said.
``But it's our job to stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents, he said, capture 1,800 to 2,200 undocumented immigrants
near the checkpoint every month, about half the total he estimates
moves through the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we can see dozens of suspected illegals from the
checkpoint and can't do anything about it if we can't get on to
Kenedy Ranch property,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The checkpoint has been controversial for years. A University of
Houston study found that in 1996, 19 immigrants died of heat stroke
and other exposure-related causes while trying to evade the
checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Because of ongoing internal investigations by the Border Patrol,
Borrego would not discuss details of what he called the
``unfortunate accidents'' in which the immigrants were recently
injured.
</P>
<P>
   On March 2, agents working west of K-24 ran over the right arm
of Victor Manuel, 25, while pursuing about 25 people suspected of
being undocumented immigrants; on March 7, another vehicle struck
Armando Leal, who was hiding in high grass, Border Patrol incident
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Leal suffered major injuries to his back and pelvis that
required surgery. He was released on March 17 from Christus Spohn
Memorial Hospital in Corpus Christi, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenedy Foundation banned agents once before, in 1995, when
vehicles operating off the ranch's paved roads ignited grass fires
and agents damaged gates and fences, Leshin said. Border Patrol
agents also fished and hunted on ranch property without permission,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, Leshin said, the FBI warned the Kenedy
Foundation that the government was considering seizing the ranch
because of the ban, and a settlement was signed in September 1999
that required federal officials to notify the foundation before
they pursued immigrants beyond paved roads on ranch property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidents in which the two immigrants were injured broke
that agreement, and the foundation's board voted March 17 to ban
federal agents from its property,'' Leshin said.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch is used primarily for cattle and oil operations but
also allows nature tourists to prowl its coastal prairies and sand
dunes in search of the 200 species of migratory birds present in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, agents have the right to enter any property
within 25 miles of U.S. boundaries. Although the Kenedy Ranch is
nearly 100 miles from the Mexican border, its land extends almost
to the Gulf of Mexico, which officials say is an international
boundary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has the authority to seize the ranch, but I
don't know that there is any current talk of doing that,'' said
Perry Cronin, a spokesman for the Border Patrol's regional district
office in McAllen, Texas. ``We're still in the talking stages, and
no agreements have been reached.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Cronin and Nancy Cohen, with the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Washington, said they were unaware of any
case in which the government had seized private property in such
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for immigrants in El Paso, Houston and the Lower Rio
Grande Valley say disputes with the Border Patrol over access to
private property and injuries caused by agents pursuing immigrants
have increased along the border in recent years as enforcement
efforts have intensified.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should have the right to seek jobs across borders
without being herded and hunted like animals,'' said Nathan Selzer
of Proyecto Libertad, an immigrant legal aid organization based in
Harlingen, Texas. ``It's an affront to human dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Jimenez of the American Friends Service Committee in
Houston said that, increasingly, residents along the border were
``beginning to object to the numbers of Border Patrol agents coming
onto their property.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``We're hearing many more complaints in recent years
about their tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez said those problems included at least two or three cases
a year of what she called ``rundowns'' by agents chasing immigrants
with vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1456EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-LENDER-CRACKDOWN-2TAK     04-01 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENDER-CRACKDOWN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE MOUNTS FOR CRACKDOWN ON DECEPTIVE LENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.C., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After several years of inaction, pressure is building in
Washington to impose tighter rules on banks and finance companies
that specialize in lending money to homeowners with blemished
credit records.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, chairman of the House Banking Committee,
said last week that his committee would be pressing for more
vigorous enforcement of a law adopted in 1994 to combat deceptive
lending practices, and may do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, do we need stronger legislation, more
aggressive regulatory oversight, or both?'' Leach said in an
interview. ``I am increasingly thinking we need both.''
</P>
<P>
   The consumer finance industry, which is regulated by state
governments, has been sharply criticized in recent years for the
actions of certain aggressive lenders who mislead borrowers into
taking out home equity loans with excessively high fees and
interest rates. Some borrowers have lost their homes, and others
are struggling to meet escalating monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Congress enacted a law intended to curb those
practices, but more than two years ago, the Federal Reserve Board
and the Department of Housing and Urban Development warned that the
law had failed to stem a tide of deceptive lending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abusive practices continue to exist'' and would continue
unless Congress drafted new ``substantive protections'' of
consumers, the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Little action resulted, even as the industry continued to expand
its lending with billions of dollars raised by leading Wall Street
investment banks. Neither the Fed nor HUD followed up with a formal
legislative proposal, congressional aides said. And the Republican
leadership in Congress, which believed that the 1994 law gave
regulators broad authority to attack the problem on their own, was
distracted by presidential impeachment, a global financial crisis
and a prolonged fight over Depression-era laws governing banks and
brokerage houses.
</P>
<P>
   That all may be about be change.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Leach's blunt call for stronger steps by regulators,
all four federal banking regulators _ including Alan Greenspan,
chairman of the Federal Reserve _ had spoken out against deceptive
lending practices, and some are beginning to develop new
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a large and influential corporate player in the
nation's mortgage markets, Fannie Mae, has decided to put its
considerable influence to work to establish enforceable industry
standards.
</P>
<P>
   And with state lawmakers taking matters into their own hands _
North Carolina has already adopted the toughest law in the country,
and other states are considering action _ some segments of the
industry are becoming more willing to consider a federal law that
could head off 50 state laws restricting their business.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about unfair and deceptive loan practices have
intensified since 1994, when Wall Street began to pump substantial
amounts of money into the industry through the sale of securities
backed by home equity loans to so-called ``subprime'' borrowers,
those with less-than-perfect credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The industry insists that deceptive practices are rare and that
subprime lenders make credit more available, and more affordable,
for people who once had few options beyond the local pawnshop.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates and regulators _ and lately, a few
mortgage industry leaders _ say that even some of the largest
subprime lenders engage in predatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem is getting worse because it's getting more
brazen,'' said Franklin D. Raines, the chief executive of Fannie
Mae, a government-chartered corporation that finances most of
America's home mortgages through the purchase of loans from banks
and other original lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many legitimate lenders are being tempted to get into this
because of its profits,'' Raines said. ``And if this goes
mainstream, we've really got a very serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines' company and another federally chartered loan financing
corporation, Freddie Mac, are already taking steps to ensure that
their own loan purchases do not encourage predatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   But Raines, in a recent interview, disclosed that he also
intended to lead an industrywide campaign _ fashioned after an
earlier nationwide effort to discourage investment in South Africa
_ that could deny abusive lenders access to Wall Street capital.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His approach is modeled after the Sullivan Principles, named
after the Rev. Leon H. Sullivan, the Philadelphia civil rights
leader who in 1977 developed a widely followed code of conduct for
companies doing business in South Africa. His efforts have been
cited for helping to end apartheid in that nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard for Wall Street to know, from where it sits,
which loans are predatory,'' Raines said. But once
``Sullivan-like'' principles are in place and adequately monitored,
he said, Wall Street could refuse to finance any lender that did
not subscribe to those principles.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, where Fannie Mae is a formidable voice, is also
sensitive to the views of Greenspan. And he, too, recently
condemned predatory lending practices.
</P>
<P>
   Although markets have ``vastly expanded credit to virtually all
income classes,'' Greenspan said in a speech on March 22, he was
concerned about ``abusive lending practices that target specific
neighborhoods or vulnerable segments of the population.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has formed a multi-agency study group to explore ways to
address predatory lending, aides to Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's remarks echoed warnings by John D. Hawke Jr., the
comptroller of the currency; Donna Tanoue, chairman of the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., and Ellen Seidman, chairman of the Office
of Thrift Supervision.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Seidman will call for public comments on the
problem, the first step in developing new rules.
</P>
<P>
   As for new legislation, Rep. John J. LaFalce, D-N.Y., the
ranking minority member of Leach's committee, is preparing to
submit an anti-predatory lending bill. Leach did not openly support
that effort, but his interest in the issue was encouraging,
consumer advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   The report that the Fed and HUD made to Congress nearly two
years ago provided a road map for new legislation. Its
recommendations included providing clearer and earlier disclosure
of loan fees and loan amounts; prohibiting certain loan terms, like
large balloon payments that force borrowers to refinance their
mortgages; and establishing minimum standards for foreclosures,
which are now governed by state law.
</P>
<P>
   Like Leach, the report called for more active enforcement, but
it also recommended tougher penalties for violating fair-lending
laws, and called for steps to make it easier for consumers to sue
deceptive lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Enforcement of all federal fair-lending laws falls largely on
the Federal Trade Commission, which has recently made lending cases
a top priority, said David Medine, associate director of the
commission's division of consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   The National Home Equity Mortgage Association, which represents
subprime lenders, has spent at least $300,000 in the last three
years on lobbying efforts in Washington, according to records
assembled by the Center for Responsive Politics. Its allies in the
fight against new anti-predatory lending laws include the Consumer
Mortgage Coalition, representing many large mortgage lenders, which
has spent more than $2.2 million on lobbying since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Both organizations _ and some consumer advocates _ adamantly
oppose Fannie Mae's involvement in the subprime market. Raines says
that such opposition ``only invigorates us,'' but industry
opposition nevertheless could distract Congress from taking
meaningful action.
</P>
<P>
   Even here, though, there are signs of a thaw in the industry's
views.
</P>
<P>
   People in Congress who have recently tested industry sentiment
say they found less uniform resistance in recent weeks. ``They're
divided _ there is some support for a federal law, and there are
others who just aren't decided yet,'' one congressional aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Action would become far more likely, of course, if the mortgage
industry determines that federal legislation is preferable to a
proliferation of strong state laws addressing predatory lending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1504EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
