<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4322 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-MELTINGPOT0402-CO     04-01 2261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MELTINGPOT0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spring training includes lessons in cultural diversity
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the Atlanta Braves, spring training 2000 was as
much about preparing to beat opposing teams as it was about
learning to respect them.
</P>
<P>
   In group sessions and in one-on-one discussions, the defending
National League champions sat down with a Maryland consultant to
discuss such topics as racism, stereotypes, the O.J. Simpson trial
and what it's like to be a minority in America.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the ground-breaking classes, of course, was John
Rocker, the Atlanta relief pitcher who offended the planet last
December when he disparaged whites, minorities and gays in an
interview with ``Sports Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, other teams are tinkering with the idea of making the
so-called ``cultural diversity training'' sessions as much a part
of spring training as batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably something that, for everybody, has long been
overdue,'' said Braves pitcher Tom Glavine, because ``the face of
baseball has changed a lot in the last 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The face of baseball has changed so much that America's national
pastime can be more accurately called the pastime of the Americas
or the pastime of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that in 1950 _ three years after Jackie Robinson became
the first man of color to break into the all-white sport _ roughly
one in 25 major league players on baseball's 16 teams was born
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 30 teams. And slightly more than one in every
five players on those rosters is from somewhere other than the
United States. In fact, there are 178 players representing 16
foreign countries and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   All of them bring a myriad of cultures, languages and values
that make each major league clubhouse its own melting pot. While
players share the common language of baseball, the mix of whites,
blacks, Latinos and Asians is producing challenges and problems
both on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams have recognized the cultural changes and have taken
measures over the years to address them. These are some of the
changes that have taken place:
</P>
<P>
   _ Interpreters, ``player development coordinators'' and
bilingual staff members are increasingly becoming the most valuable
members of a team. Chief among their duties is easing the culture
shock that often scares young minor-league players into leaving
camp, sometimes forcing teams to report the AWOL athletes to the
INS and Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clubs and players are being marketed to fans outside U.S.
borders. Teams have Spanish flagship radio stations to reach
Spanish-speaking listeners, and baseball writers are taking
language classes in an effort to communicate with players.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Braves may extend the cultural diversity sessions to next
season. And managers and executives with several teams, including
the Florida Marlins, one of baseball's most culturally diverse
franchises, say it wouldn't be a bad idea if the classes are
incorporated into their training camps.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees with the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Rocker is not the voice of major league baseball,'' said
first baseman Eric Karros of the Los Angeles Dodgers. ``I think
what's unfair is (that) because one person says that, that doesn't
mean that's what major league baseball players in general feel.
That right there is being stereotypical, which is the basis for
racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it fair for the whole team (to take the classes)? No. One
person made the statements so why does Chipper Jones have to sit
through that. Or (Andres) Galarragas or Brian Jordan?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Jordan, Jones and Galarragas are among the Braves
players who said they were glad they sat through the two-hour
sessions, taught by the Cook Ross consulting firm, whose clients
include the American Red Cross and the Geico insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it. I found it educational. It caught my ears,''
said pitcher Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL'S CHANGING IDENTITY
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move into the next 10 to 20 years, you're going to see
world baseball. You'll see major league teams in Japan, the
Dominican Republic, Venezuela, Mexico. We are moving in that
direction,'' said General Manager Kevin Malone of the Dodgers, who
have two Russian pitchers in their minor-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to not only develop players coming into our
organization but also develop our players to understand those
people. It's really something needed and called for.''
</P>
<P>
   And against that backdrop, this much is certain: John Rocker
might not, as Karros contends, represent the voice of major league
baseball, but he just might represent the voice of a silent
minority around the leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any job there are people with prejudices against people,''
said Marlins third baseman Mike Lowell. ``That's life, society.
Just because we play baseball doesn't mean everyone has nice things
to say about everyone. John Rocker was just willing to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   One expert says baseball isn't doing enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are programs in pockets of teams through their
intervention of Latin America and their baseball academies,'' said
Jose Masso of the Northeastern University's Center for the Study of
Sport in Society. ``But is it enough? No. Should we expand it? Yes.
It would avoid a lot of misinformation and miscommunication in the
world of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk into a clubhouse and you'll often see white players hanging
out with whites, and Latinos talking with Latinos. But that often
is a reflection of common values as opposed to ethnic
fractionalization.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican-born slugger Juan Gonzalez of the Detroit Tigers
had plenty to say last month when he accused his former team, the
Texas Rangers, of not treating Latin players well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people working there in Texas don't have good relations
with our cultures, people from different countries, in my
opinion,'' Gonzalez told the Dallas Morning News. Other Latin
players on the Rangers disagreed with Gonzalez's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Even baseball fans have been struggling with the sport's
changing identity _ from the racial slurs screamed at Robinson in
April 1947 to the person who called the sports desk of the
``Arizona Republic'' newspaper during the 1998 Mark McGwire-Sammy
Sosa home-run race to say: ``Allow me to point out, sir, that the
most home-runs-in-a-season title has always been a white man's
title.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's pursuit of Roger Maris' home-run record turned into a
forum for racial identity when the Domincan-born Sosa closed in on
McGwire late that summer.
</P>
<P>
   Whites accused Latino pitchers such as Jose Lima of grooving
pitches to Sosa. Latin fans took note of how the league stopped the
game to celebrate McGwire's 62nd home run but not for Sosa's five
days later.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997, some 8,000 Dominican-Americans marched in
Miami to honor Moises Alou, the Dominican-born outfielder for the
Florida Marlins who many thought should have been named the World
Series MVP. That award was given to Cuban-born pitcher Livan
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Alou recently downplayed the controversy, which some observers
saw as a Dominican-vs-Cuban debate. But Alou owns a 2-year-old race
horse named ``The Real MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlins manager John Boles, a player development guru for more
than a decade, says he has worked with players from enough
different backgrounds to know that ``certain cultures look down on
other cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any difficulties right now, knock on wood,''
said Boles, who would like to see the Marlins offer
cultural-diversity classes. ``What you have to do is really be
aware of people's feelings and if you're a good person, people will
see that and respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE SHOCK
</P>
<P>
   Among the most important people within the Marlins organization
is Laurie Soltman, whose title is ``player program development
coordinator.'' Her duties include the underlying charge of helping
minor league players from all over the world make the transition to
the disciplined rigors of professional baseball life. That includes
everything from meeting players at the airport upon their arrival
to teaching English classes after practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've showed them how to turn on the shower, how to use the
commode. If a kid doesn't understand how something works, you show
them. Everything is brand new for some guys,'' Soltman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys show up and they have a duffle bag and they have a
Bible and they have a picture of their mother inside the Bible. And
that's what they bring with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge to every foreign player is the culture
shock _ adjusting to the language, food and lifestyle of another
country. And not all players survive it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of so many young guys,'' Soltman said. ``Did they
have the on-field ability? You know what? We didn't even find out
because it was hard to keep them here. They were crazy homesick,
which a lot of guys are. It's really difficult because they don't
feel like there a lot of guys they can really connect with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the hardest thing for me,'' said Cardinals shortstop
Edgar Renteria, a Columbian who broke in with the Marlins.
``Playing baseball is hard, too, but I know how to play baseball. I
didn't know how to speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, who was born in Puerto Rico and is bilingual, said many
of his minor-league teammates turned to him for help. ``They didn't
know how the American way of things was done. Like paying your
phone bill on time. They didn't understand why it would get shut
off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said many young Latin players are ``the breadwinners of their
families.'' Many are satisfied just to earn a minor-league salary
because it often pays for a year of the family's expenses back
home. ``Sometimes that drive really isn't there to make it to the
big leagues because they are making money.''
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE BARRIER
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Lara, a 21-year-old pitcher in the Marlins organization,
laughs when talking about his first year in the Gulf Coast League
when he first left home in the Dominican Republic at the age of 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hungry so I walked to Wendy's behind the (team) hotel. I
saw all the pictures of all the burgers (on the wall menu) and I
said to the girl, 'Can I have number one?' and she said, 'Anything
else?' And I had no idea what she was saying, so I threw my arms up
like I forgot my wallet and I walked back to the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, while shopping at the Indian River Mall, he would repeat to
himself as he carried his purchases to the cashier: ``Oh, please,
God, don't let her ask any questions. Just take my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Boles said he advocates hiring as many bilingual staff members
as possible. Lean against the batting cage while Venezuelan
shortstop Alex Gonzalez take his cuts and you can hear Marlins
hitting coach Jack Maloof, a Californian, repeat after each swing,
``Bueno! Bueno!''
</P>
<P>
   The most valuable person on the Montreal Expos pitching staff
might be 22-year-old Go Ikeda, an amateur player hired to serve as
the interpreter, roommate and team liaison for Japanese pitcher
Hideki Irabu, a 11-game winner with Yankees last year who will
start third in Montreal's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without (an) interpreter,'' Irabu said, ``I don't play
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   And without interpreters, many players might just be nameless
faces to fans _ because many baseball writers don't speak a second
language.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball columnist Pedro Gomez of the ``Arizona Republic'' says
that much of the success and popularity of Latin superstars Pedro
Martinez and Sosa can be attributed to their ability to communicate
with American writers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gomez added, players with little grasp of the language
``certainly are not afforded the same courtesy that U.S.-born
players are. I wouldn't say Latins are mistreated but the majority
of the American ballwriters do little to try and learn even a
little about them _ their background, how they grew up, family
situations. Things that really shape the personality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins are among a growing number of teams that market
themselves to fans from other countries, primarily Hispanics. They
opened Marlins En Miami, a ticket office and merchandise store, in
Miami's Little Havana, and there are weekly Marlins shows on
Spanish television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres market the team to Mexico, sponsoring bus
caravans from Tijuana. Like the Marlins and Padres, the Arizona
Diamondbacks host weekly pregame festivals at the ballpark geared
toward Latin fans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some observers watching the major leagues enter the
new millennium would like the sport to take its cultural awareness
measures a step further, eliminating ethnically sensitive names and
images associated with baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The National Coalition on Racism in Sports and the Media is
planning a protest outside Jacobs Field this week against the use
of the team's longtime mascot, Chief Wahoo.
</P>
<P>
   The group would like to eliminate nicknames like the Indians and
Braves. Teams change their uniforms for marketing purposes, the
group says, so why not adopt a more sensitive nickname, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a connection with what John Rocker said and the fact
that he plays for a franchise that actively promotes the tomahawk
chop,'' said Ellen Staurowsky, an associate professor of sports
sociology at Ithaca College.
</P>
<P>
   But she said none of the controversy is necessarily Rocker's
fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Rocker is a product of the society that educated him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
