<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-01 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A DIRTY BUSINESS, BUT A BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Had Stephon Marbury remained at Georgia Tech for four long years
and helped keep the departing Bobby Cremins' program afloat, he
would be a rookie now in the National Basketball Association,
greener all over except in the wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets' best player was at his dressing stall one
night last week when he was asked if at any time as a millionaire
professional he had found himself sighing, thinking that maybe he'd
moved on too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not once?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not once.''
</P>
<P>
   Much ado _ about nothing _ was made when Marbury, before his
first college game, told a reporter that he might leave college
after his freshman season. Out of the projects in Coney Island,
Marbury has always spoken about the business of basketball with a
no-frills frankness, compared with the intellectual nonsense that
spills from the mouths of university administrators and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I signed to go to Georgia Tech, we were on ESPN 20 times,
instantly,'' Marbury said. ``When you make the tournament, they
just give you money. And then they say a coach can't buy you a
winter coat, even if you grew up in the 'hood and you don't have
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The same stories that are written now about another New York
City point guard, Erick Barkley, formerly of St. John's, were
always whispered about Marbury. He was always said to be getting
one thing, taking another. Cremins once told me that mysterious
characters from Chicago, supposedly part of the crowd that helped
steer Kevin Garnett to the pros, would show up on campus,
unannounced and unwanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who the hell are these guys?'' Cremins said he once asked
Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends of mine,'' Marbury said, leaving the coach nowhere to
go.
</P>
<P>
   The day at Junior's Restaurant in downtown Brooklyn, when
Marbury announced he was turning pro, the agent Eric Fleisher was
already attached to his hip. Fleisher had not long before split
from his brother, Marc, in a litigious feud that fractured a family
made famous in basketball circles by their late father, Larry, the
Marvin Miller of hoops.
</P>
<P>
   Marc and Eric had a nice business going, and then Willis Reed
called one day to recommend a young man who had been a Nets intern
and wanted to learn the agent game. His name was Andy Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The Fleishers took him on, and a couple of years later, Eric
Fleisher was off on his own, Miller tagging along, until Miller
eventually made off with all their clients, creating for Fleisher
another ex-partner to sue.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Marbury was enlisted with David Falk, unofficial
co-commissioner of the NBA. Marbury remembers Miller, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good guy or bad guy?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, he's OK,'' Marbury said, sounding like an Al Gore sound
bite on the character of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury was asked about the telephone calls that Miller
reportedly made to various college players, apparently fished out
of the records of the Eric Fleisher lawsuit against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, that goes on every day,'' Marbury snorted, suggesting
these discoveries were the journalism equivalent of fool's gold.
</P>
<P>
   Miller may have foolishly run afoul of Florida law, but even the
few respectable agents will tell you that contacting players who
are still in college is not only permissible (except in those
states that prohibit it by law) but is standard and mandatory
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The college coaches rail against the agents, but they are such
hypocrites. They have often been accessories to the so-called
crime, steering players to the agent they do personal business
with, and not allowing other agents a chance to sell themselves
when the player decides to turn pro. Is it coincidence that every
John Thompson player of note has left Georgetown with Falk's hand
under his elbow?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd write the coach and ask for a meeting with the player,''
one agent said the other day. ``They'd say, `You'll get one,' and
then the kid comes out and he's with the agent the coach gets
something from. The agents figure, `If I'm going to speak to this
kid, I'll have to do it myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   So they call, and once they get access, here comes the so-called
financial adviser, who is not governed by the union's agent rules.
Here comes the promise of a prodigious line of credit.
</P>
<P>
   The business is rife with such self-interest and adult-driven
greed, and the student-athlete doesn't have to be dean's list to
know a scam when he sees one. Starting with that $6 billion
television deal in the NCAA's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they paid the players, they'd stay in school,'' Marbury
said flatly, but that has become a cliche, an unworkable fantasy.
Regardless of what restructuring the NCAA is proposing, the next
significant evolutionary step will be the NBA developmental league.
The industry buzz has David Stern contemplating the two-man game
with Clear Channel, whose sports division is run by Falk, often
referred to by Stern as ``a parasite.''
</P>
<P>
   While a developmental league will certainly lighten the
hypocrisy load, this will remain a dirty game. The agents, already
crawling around the high schools, will infest them. The colleges
could even get desperate and start bidding, like George
Steinbrenner in free-agent heat.
</P>
<P>
   The players will just continue to do what players do, as long as
they are conditioned by people who want something from them. They
will ask, and rightfully so, what's in it for them. And as long as
he's got NBA game, no one will remember Erick Barkley's collegiate
sins, the way no one cares about Marcus Camby's.
</P>
<P>
   They are young men who took a swim in a cesspool and didn't come
out clean. They are the last ones to blame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1511EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
