<SLUG> BC-BKW-TENNESSEE-UCONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS INEVITABLE: TENNESSEE AND CONNECTICUT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There is an air of inevitability to this national
championship game. And the air is electric, charged by the best
rivalry in women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, the nation's No. 1-ranked team, will play
second-ranked Tennessee for the third time this season. Sunday
night's National Collegiate Athletic Association championship, at
the neutral First Union Center, will be a tie breaker to the
dramatic home-and-home season series the two staged this season.
</P>
<P>
   But on the grand stage, this is the only game that counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that everybody has been waiting for this game,''
Connecticut forward Shea Ralph said, moments after the Huskies
dispatched Penn State, 89-67, in the national semifinals Friday
night. In the earlier semifinal, Tennessee had already defeated
Rutgers, 64-54.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you ask anybody who watches women's basketball,''
Ralph said, ``they probably would have said or put down in their
pocket that UConn and Tennessee would have met in the final game.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not? It was not just the safe pick, but the sentimental
one, too. The rivalry is rather new, yet in just six years, and 10
games, every game in the series has become a showdown, and a
showcase, on national television. If not deciding rankings, the
game has broken home-court winning streaks or determined national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   This season each team stole victory on the other's home court.
Connecticut spoiled Tennessee's home advantage Jan. 8, dominating
the entire game in Knoxville. Then on Groundhog Day, Feb. 2,
Tennessee spoiled Connecticut's perfect season, ending the
back-and-forth thriller with a jumper in the final 4.4. seconds in
Gampel Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the teams have met three previous times in the
tournament, the Huskies will play Tennessee in the championship for
the first time since 1995. That year, in Minneapolis, Connecticut
downed the Lady Vols, 70-64, to cap a perfect season and win its
first national title.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' undefeated run that year, with their personable
star forward, Rebecca Lobo, and gritty point guard Jennifer
Rizzotti, ignited new interest in the women's game, arguably
changing it forever.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, Tennessee downed Connecticut in the national
semifinal game, 88-83 in overtime, in one of the most dramatic
games in Final Four history. The Lady Vols went on to win the
title, their first of three led by the superstar forward Chamique
Holdsclaw, who helped Tennessee go undefeated in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, everyone expected the Lady Vols to win their fourth
straight title, but they faltered in the regional final against
Duke. Connecticut, without the freshman point guard Sue Bird, who
was lost to knee surgery after eight games, sputtered in the
regional semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   That loss to Duke has driven the Lady Vols all season. Bird,
back healthy, has done the same for the Huskies. In their Jan. 8
victory in Knoxville, she had a season-high 25 points, causing
Tennessee Coach Pat Summitt to remark, ``Sue Bird was the
difference-maker.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, Bird had 15 points, but Tennessee's junior Semeka
Randall, who averages 21.3 points against Connecticut, hit the
game-winning shots in the final seconds. After the upset, the
Tennessee freshman point guard Kara Lawson mugged for the cameras
and appealed to the poll voters, saying ``We're No. 1,'' while
jabbing her index finger in the air.
</P>
<P>
   But while Tennessee rose from fourth to second in the rankings,
Connecticut never dropped from its No. 1 perch, setting up the
drama for the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Lawson and Bird each scored 19 points and had
no turnovers to lead their teams into the final. Both are crucial
to Sunday's outcome, directing their teams' powerful inside games.
Tennessee boasts the national player of the year, the 6-foot-3-inch
junior forward Tamika Catchings, and the 6-5 sophomore Michelle
Snow, while Connecticut counters with its revolving door in the
post: sophomores Tamika Williams, Asjha Jones and Swin Cash.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's roster boasts eight players who were first-team
All-Americans in high school, one player who was All-Canada,
another who was All-Russia. Tennessee has seven first-team
All-Americans from high school.
</P>
<P>
   This national championship features some of the greatest talent
assembled on one court since Michael Jordan practiced alone.
</P>
<P>
   On the sidelines, the teams are led by two of the most visible
and most successful coaches in the country. Tennessee's Pat Summitt
has two best-selling books and six national championships. This
year, Connecticut's Geno Auriemma was the consensus national coach
of the year, winning the honor from the Associated Press on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut (35-1) has won its games more convincingly this
season than Tennessee (33-3), but records may not be consequential
in this series, even at five games apiece. Perhaps there are other
factors.
</P>
<P>
   The game is the same day, April 2, on which UConn won its first
and only championship five years ago. ``It's definitely fate,''
Ralph said. ``It's going to be a big battle. We're prepared, we've
worked hard and we're ready for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
