<SLUG> BC-PSYCHO-INVEST0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Studying investor psychology can keep you a jump ahead
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Investors are people, too. Theoretically, that
suggests that understanding investor psychology can give you a
better understanding of market trends.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it can, according to David Hirshleifer of Ohio State
University, whose specialties include investor psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, it seems, suffer human foibles, according to
Hirshleifer. One is that they tend to be overconfident about their
own ability to pick winning stocks. Another is that their
confidence increases more sharply when news supports their thinking
than it decreases when the news is contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   The first human fault helps explain why investors have made the
sky the limit for some technology stocks, says Hirshleifer, who
holds the Ralph Kurtz Chair in Finance in the Fisher College of
Business.
</P>
<P>
   ``People put too much weight on their own analysis,'' he
explained. ``In general, they can either undervalue or overvalue a
stock. People who undervalue may stay away from the stock. People
who overvalue may drive the price to excessive levels.''
</P>
<P>
   That tendency to be too confident _ and overvalue stocks _ can
build on itself because of the second fault, according to
Hirshleifer. ``If people get some good news on a stock, they
overreact. If they get some more news, they overreact even more.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, people tend to downplay news that runs
counter to their thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some disconfirming news comes in, people say that was
`random noise,''' Hirshleifer said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the weight of contradictory news overcomes the hubris
and a stock should return to a price level commensurate with
available information, or so the theory goes. Before that happens,
investors can take advantage of human nature, Hirshleifer thinks.
One way, he said, ``is to play the momentum game.''
</P>
<P>
   Momentum investing involves buying stocks that are rising, not
because of any fundamentals behind the stocks but simply because
they are going up. The idea that stock prices swing too much one
way or the other because of overconfidence on the part of investors
suggests stocks that are going up should continue to rise for some
period, presenting an investment opportunity. But how does an
investor figure when to cash out?
</P>
<P>
   No one can make that call. But there are a couple of things to
keep in mind, Hirshleifer says. ``If a stock has been going up, the
more it's been overvalued, and the longer, the riskier the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sign to watch for is a slowing of momentum, he added.
``If you see the stock flattening out, that's a good hint you might
want to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another option is to take a contrarian view and go against
the grain.
</P>
<P>
   One way is to watch the short interest in stocks, Hirshleifer
proposes. Short interest is the proportion of shares that have been
borrowed and then sold, with the expectation that a stock will
decline. If the stock falls, the short seller can replace the
borrowed stock at a lower price than for what it was sold and
pocket the difference.
</P>
<P>
   If overconfidence can send stocks too high, it also can send
stocks too low, according to a theory, proposed in 1998 by
Hirshleifer, Kent Daniel of Northwestern University and Avanidhar
Subrahmanyam of UCLA, that stocks with high short interest may get
beaten down too much.
</P>
<P>
   The three suggested that small stocks, in terms of market value,
are good models for testing their theory, since there's less
outside information to contradict the thinking of overconfident
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks that are low in market value are probably stocks that
overconfident investors have become pessimistic about,'' said
Hirshleifer, ``which may create an opening for contrarians to
benefit from an upward correction.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
