<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-IRS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE GOP RENEWS CALL FOR MEASURE TO OVERHAUL TAX SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)  (jw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in the House proposed legislation
Saturday to help taxpayers in their dealings with the Internal
Revenue Service, and called for hearings this month on developing
an entirely new tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said the proposed legislation was intended to build on
changes made in 1998, when Congress granted taxpayers broad new
protections in their dealings with the tax service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our new Taxpayer Bill of Rights will help protect taxpayer
privacy, level the playing field between taxpayers and the IRS, and
take at least some small steps to help simplify the process of
paying taxes,'' Archer said in the weekly Republican radio address.
</P>
<P>
   To help assure the confidentiality of taxpayer records, the
legislation would require states with access to federal tax
information to do more to protect their computer systems against
unauthorized access, and would require the IRS to notify taxpayers
immediately if their tax information is obtained illegally by a
third party.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would bar the IRS from imposing taxes on interest
payments it makes to taxpayers, and would stop the tax agency from
imposing interest charges as penalties in cases where the IRS had
made a mistake or caused an unreasonable delay. It would provide a
way for taxpayers to avoid a rapid buildup of interest charges in
disputes with the tax service.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also includes provisions to ensure that banks
and other lenders keep confidential any tax information they
receive in verifying a customer's credit worthiness, to simplify
estimated tax calculations and to speed decisions about
organizations seeking tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   Archer did not provide an estimate on the cost of the changes,
but his aides said it would run into billions of dollars over a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials gave Archer's proposals a muted
welcome. ``While we have concerns about some of Chairman Archer's
suggestions, we agree with many of them,'' Secretary of the
Treasury Lawrence Summers said in a statement. ``We are committed
to strengthening taxpayer rights and we will continue to work with
Congress and the IRS to ensure that taxpayers receive the best
service possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican initiative was timed to coincide with the season
in which voters are most involved in preparing their tax returns,
and to broaden the political debate over taxes, in Washington and
in the presidential campaign, to include the very nature of the tax
system, not just whether the nation wants a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax code is too complicated and confusing, and we'd like
to get the IRS out of the lives of American taxpayers,'' Archer
said.
</P>
<P>
   He has long been a proponent of scrapping the progressive income
tax system and replacing it with an alternative, like a national
sales or consumption tax, or a single-rate flat tax on income.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is popular among many Republicans in Congress, and
among many grass-roots conservatives. But it has never gained much
traction in Washington, in part because such a change would be
costly, technically difficult and certain to bring protest from
groups that would lose tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   To generate some interest in the subject, Archer said he would
hold hearings this month to examine proposals for a national sales
tax, a flat tax and other ideas.
</P>
</TEXT>
