<HEADLINE>
PENNSYLVANIA RACE SPUTTERS TO A CLOSE  
 PRO-BUSH GOVERNOR WANTS TO LEAD MCCAIN'S DELEGATES  
 NADER KEEPS BEING NADER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Ohio, Mass.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way Pennsylvania Democrats figure it, Sen. Rick Santorum, a
freshman Republican up for re-election this fall, is vulnerable,
perhaps as vulnerable as any Republican senator running. They see
him as too conservative for Pennsylvania and too brash to be a good
fit in the staid U.S. Senate, and they always point out that he was
elected in 1994 by a wispy margin of just 2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats have a problem of their own in this contest.
</P>
<P>
   Their best prospects for taking on Santorum _ among them Edward
G. Rendell, the former Philadelphia mayor, and Bob Casey Jr., the
state auditor _ took a pass, leaving six lesser-known Democrats to
duke it out for the party's nomination. The primary is on Tuesday,
and by just about any measure the campaign, even though capped with
a series of debates, has hardly been the riveting kind needed to
give the eventual nominee a running start at Santorum.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the final weekend of campaigning, polls indicated two
of every five voters had not decided how they were going to vote,
an unusually high number. Further, only one of every three voters
felt that Santorum, who has moderated both his conservatism and
brashness, should be replaced in November.
</P>
<P>
   So come Tuesday, who is likely to win the nod to take on the
senator?
</P>
<P>
   The polls found three of the six candidates totally out of the
running, pulling less than 10 percent of the vote combined. The
remaining three _ Rep. Ron Klink, state Sen. Allyson Schwartz and
Tom Foley, a former state labor secretary _ were locked in a tight
contest, with Klink holding a slight edge.
</P>
<P>
   None of the candidates has been able to raise the money needed
to blitz the state with television ads (Santorum has raised more
cash, $6 million, than all the Democrats combined). No compelling
issue has dominated the campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Klink is from the 4th Congressional District in western
Pennsylvania, a part of the state that usually has a heavier
turnout than elsewhere, and he has significant backing from labor
and fellow Pennsylvania Democrats in Congress. Schwartz comes from
Philadelphia, which also has a big vote, and she has the backing of
a number of women's organizations. Foley comes from the Harrisburg
area and, having been state labor secretary, is competing hard with
Klink for the labor vote.
</P>
<P>
   Best bet, as the political pros see things: a tossup on Tuesday,
a slight lean toward Republican in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush Loyalist in McCain Country
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Dee Hull of Arizona raised some eyebrows, and hackles,
early in the presidential primary season when she sided with Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas rather than her fellow Arizonan, Sen. John
McCain. She even volunteered to run Bush's primary campaign in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won easily and therefore ``owns'' all 30 of the state's
delegates to the national convention in Philadelphia. But Hull says
she nevertheless wants the state Republican Party to pick her to
lead the delegation to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   That is the ``standard role'' all governors play at conventions,
she argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very definitely I would want to be the chairman,'' she told
The Arizona Republic last week. ``My feeling is that's the way we
proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   She insisted that she was not looking for a fight with McCain
and would probably defer if he or other party leaders strongly
objected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, The Republic reported that behind the scenes, the
governor was ``assiduously cultivating allies.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a politician with a tit-for-tat reputation, deserved or
not, did not have any immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Nader Keeps Running
</P>
<P>
   Since he came on the national scene in the 1960s as a critic of
the auto industry, Ralph Nader has tried ceaselessly to elevate the
consciousness of corporate America. And as he enters the second
month of his second run for president under the Green Party banner,
he is still trying _ making no more progress now, it appears, than
in 1994 (1 percent of the vote) but laying down vintage Nader stuff
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   In Toledo, Ohio, last week, he went after DaimlerChrysler and
city officials for striking a deal that, as he darkly saw it,
resulted in the use of hard-earned tax dollars to roust scores of
helpless citizens from their humble homes so that room could be
made to build a Jeep plant.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, Nader charged, was ``one of the most extreme,
one-sided deals ever given to a gluttonous corporation'' _ a charge
that led Mayor Carleton S. Finkbeiner to call him an untruthful
``demagogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon Nader countered that somebody should get a bar of soap
and wash out ``the mayoral mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days earlier, while in Boston, Nader threw all
rational political caution out the window and went after two sacred
Beantown icons: the Red Sox and Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The ballclub, he said, should renovate venerable Fenway and its
Green Monster wall with private money and stop pressuring the state
and city to invest $600 million in a new park.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win a World Series,'' he said of the hapless Sox, ``they
don't need new sky boxes populated by gluttonous financiers
freeloading on the backs of hard-working taxpayers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
