<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-CAPSULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSAGES FROM THE DIM PAST TO THE HAZY FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH HADLEY, Mass. _ Over the century, the box sat quietly in
the Mount Holyoke College library, then in the comptroller's
office, then on a shelf in the school archives, and finally on the
dorm room floor of Sara Hines, president of the class of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Hines had little idea what was in the oak box, which measured a
little more than a foot on each side. A plaque on the top described
it as a legacy from the class of 1900 to its sisters in the class
of 2000. As she prepared the box for the cracking-open ceremony on
Friday night, Hines said that it did not much matter what was in
the box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the class of 2000 feels special that a group of
women 100 years ago were waiting for us and anticipating our
arrival,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to time capsules, it is the thought that counts.
The term ``time capsule'' did not exist in 1900, and sealing up
mementos for future generations was not as commonplace as it is
today, and the box avoided the fate of most time capsules: stolen,
misplaced or just plain forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a list of human frailty,'' said Paul Hudson,
co-founder of the International Time Capsule Society at Oglethorpe
University in Atlanta. ``People are so excited about it as they do
it, but they forget about it almost the day after it's sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   To be accurate, the Mount Holyoke box was lost, or at least
overlooked, for about 20 years, after the college remodeled the
library in the 1960s. An employee in the comptroller's office
stumbled across it in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called me from the college and said, `What's this?'''
said Ruth Craig Morales, a Mount Holyoke alumna from Northampton,
Mass. ``It has your name on it.''
</P>
<P>
   She and two of her classmates were named trustees of the capsule
at their graduation in 1950. The phone call reminded her of that
forgotten responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   She was on hand for the ceremony on Friday, as was Peter Carini,
Mount Holyoke's archives director, who was taking all the
excitement over the box with reservation. After all, squirreling
away historical mementos goes against his professional creed. ``The
problem with time capsules is that they are inaccessible for
hundreds of years, so they sort of defeat the purpose of
archivers,'' Carini said.
</P>
<P>
   He joked that opening the box would free space on his shelves,
but deep down he was impressed. In 1896, two weeks into their
freshman year, the class of 1900 saw the main building on campus
destroyed by fire. ``They had the idea that this oak box would last
100 years, and yet they had seen the college burn to the ground in
their lifetime,'' Carini said. If nothing else, they were an
optimistic lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think about the class of 2000, a group of women they were
never going to meet, a group of women they had no connection to, I
find that really interesting. That intrigues me much more than even
the contents.''
</P>
<P>
   A time capsule is not the strangest thing the college has handed
down through the years. Only alumnae can understand the ceremony of
Founder's Day, when trustees rise at dawn to serve ice cream to
students at Mary Lyon's gravesite.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Holyoke student life is a calendar of traditions. In the
fall, students take off from classes to experience nature on
Mountain Day, and don white and carry branches for the Laurel
Parade in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful to think that for the last 160 years, women
have been doing these same things,'' Hines said. ``And if they
haven't been doing them for 160 years, people like to think that
they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of students, alumnae and their families turned out for
the opening of the box. Some thought the box would hold letters of
inspiration; others thought it might turn out to be a big April
Fool's joke. But after the speeches, the class officers removed the
wooden lid, they found the one thing none of them expected: another
box, a black metal box that was soldered tight.
</P>
<P>
   So to a century of anticipation was added another 20 minutes,
while people from the audience hammered away at the stubborn box
with a mallet and putty knife. Hines entertained the crowd by
reading headlines from the newspapers that lined the wooden box,
among them: the birth of the czarina's fourth daughter and the
recovery of Ida McKinley, the first lady, from a recent illness.
</P>
<P>
   The foremothers had enclosed, among other bits of nostalgia, a
beret with the school name, a ticket from a school play and a faded
paper blue book used for ``examinatories,'' the kind that brought
groans of familiarity from the students. There was also a class
photo with the assertion, ``We are really much better looking than
it will give you reason to suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   A letter read: ``We believe that some of the many reforms seen
by us only in the hazy future of the world, and longed for with the
force of a somewhat impatient optimism, will be records of history
to you.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's graduating class plans to use the box for its own
time capsule, to be opened in 2100.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
