<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE PROTESTERS BEATEN BY GOVERNMENT SUPPORTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ A peaceful anti-government march in
Harare, the capital of Zimbabwe, erupted in violence Saturday as a
group of armed men wielding machetes and clubs attacked the crowd
of several thousand marchers, leaving several people seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 men, who were described by witnesses as supporters of
President Robert Mugabe, hurled bricks and stones and beat several
protesters bloody until riot policemen intervened with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine people were hospitalized, according to a spokesman
for the National Constitutional Assembly, an umbrella group of
civic organizations, which organized the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers, some of whom wore T-shirts bearing the name of
Mugabe's governing party, seemed determined to go after the handful
of whites in the overwhelmingly black crowd, marchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were wielding machetes, stones, sticks, and they just
charged at the peaceful marchers,'' said Brian Kagoro, the
spokesman for the NCA, who witnessed the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was screaming,'' Kagoro said in a telephone interview
from Harare. ``Some people were too old to run. Some had crutches.
It was mayhem. It was absolute chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   The clash between Mugabe supporters and opponents came as
Zimbabwe braces for its most heated election since independence in
1980. Mugabe's party, known as ZANU-PF, has governed for 20 years,
but faces its most serious challenge ever in the parliamentary
election, now scheduled for May.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, scattered incidents of political violence have
been reported around the country. Last Sunday, one opposition party
member was killed by armed men after a political rally in the town
of Bindura, opposition party officials say.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, fights between opposition party members and
supporters of Mugabe left 16 people injured in the town of Kwekwe,
according to Zimbabwe's state-controlled newspaper, The Herald.
Twenty opposition members were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's march was organized to call for peace in the country
and to protest the recent invasions of white-owned farms by black
squatters.
</P>
<P>
   About 800 white-owned farms have been invaded and occupied in
recent weeks. The invasions follow the stunning rejection last
month of a draft constitution that would have allowed Mugabe to
seize white-owned land without compensation. About 4,000 white
farmers own more than half of Zimbabwe's most fertile land.
</P>
<P>
   The police had tried to prevent Saturday's march from taking
place, organizers said. But the demonstrators obtained a court
order on Friday barring the police from interfering with the
protest. And several thousand people showed up to voice their
dissatisfaction with the government.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The marchers, who walked peacefully through downtown Harare on
Saturday morning, carried posters and signs that read ``Peace
Now.''
</P>
<P>
   The police had set up cordons to separate the marchers from
Mugabe's supporters, but the latter managed to get through, Kagoro
said. He said the police had taken no action to prevent the armed
men from approaching the demonstrators until the violence occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own thought is that Mugabe was trying to create chaos,'' he
said. ``He wants an excuse to move in against his opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Mugabe denied that the government had
orchestrated the attacks. The spokesman, George Charamba, said the
demonstrators knew violence might erupt because veterans of the
1970s independence war were in town. Kagoro and other marchers
described the assailants as war veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why the police were very reluctant to allow the
march,'' Charamba said in a telephone interview from Harare. ``When
the NCA organizes a public march, they are responsible for an
orderly outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe's second city, Bulawayo, a march of about 4,000
people passed without incident.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the last rally organized by the National
Constitutional Assembly _ in support of the ``no'' vote against the
proposed constitution _ was broken up by riot policemen using tear
gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
