<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4340 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-SCANDAL0402-COX     04-01 1976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SCANDAL0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP targets Gore fund-raising
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a hastily called news conference on March 3,
1997, Vice President Al Gore uttered words that have come back to
haunt him repeatedly in the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to news reports that he solicited campaign
contributions from his White House office, Gore said, ``My counsel
advises me _ let me repeat _ that there is no controlling legal
authority that says that any of these activities violated any
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) jumped on the
legalistic response and incorporated it into this presidential
stump speech. ``I'm going to give Al Gore controlling legal
authority,'' McCain told audiences. ``And then I'm going to beat
him like a drum and send him back to Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas also has picked up on the phrase in
his speeches and, in the same breath, drops in a mention of
``Buddhist temples,'' a reference to the controversial fund-raiser
Gore attended in California in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's ``no controlling legal authority'' response and the
Buddhist temple event are sure to find their way into television
commercials this fall. The Republican National Committee already
provides visitors to its Web site (www.rnc.org) streaming video of
the temple fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   To the singsong cadence of Asian music, viewers can watch Gore
glide past robed monks in the regal courtyard of the Hsi Lai Temple
in Hacienda Heights, Calif., and accept a small Buddha statue from
the temple's grandmaster.
</P>
<P>
   The RNC site also has a ``photo album'' of Gore with Maria Hsia,
who helped Gore raise money for his 1990 Senate campaign and
organized the temple fund-raising event. Hsia was recently
convicted of campaign fraud in connection with some $100,000 given
to the Democratic National Committee and Democratic candidates from
temple monks and nuns, who were illegally reimbursed for their
donations.
</P>
<P>
   But while the pictures may make for damaging political
advertising, the facts surrounding the temple fund-raiser and
Gore's White House fund-raising calls escape easy packaging. No
one, for example, has suggested that Gore himself knew that Hsia, a
Los Angeles immigration consultant, was hitting up Buddhist
monastics for illegal contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's most serious brush with the law had nothing to do with
the temple, but rather concerned 45 phone calls that he made from
his office to big Democratic donors. Those calls risked running
afoul of a 19th-century law, updated in 1980, that prohibits
federal officials from soliciting campaign contributions inside
federal buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Gore exposed himself to further problems when the Justice
Department launched a subsequent inquiry into whether he had been
truthful in telling investigators what he knew about the phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Both the phone calls and the temple fund-raiser fit into a much
larger story of the 1996 elections. Gore, an active participant in
his own re-election, was an enthusiastic participant in the
Democratic Party's no-holds-barred effort to raise millions for the
1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing his vulnerability, Gore last week pledged to make
campaign finance reform his top priority. He told voters in
Milwaukee that a ban on unregulated soft money contributions to the
political parties, the type of money he sought in 1996 and
continues to raise in 2000, would be his first piece of domestic
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know firsthand what is wrong with the way we fund political
campaigns,'' Gore said. ``My commitment to changing America's
campaign finance laws is both personal and profound.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Gore had attended an event at a tax-exempt
religious institution first made news three weeks before the 1996
elections. Republican nominee Bob Dole picked up on the report,
accusing Clinton and the Democrats of cycling contributions through
their own ``Laundromat.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the details surrounding the fund-raiser, however, did
not emerge until the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, chaired
by Sen. Fred Thompson (R-Tenn.), began investigating campaign
finance abuses in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser was organized by Hsia and John Huang, a former
DNC fund-raiser who since has pleaded guilty to a federal
conspiracy charge. Gore was invited to the temple by its
grandmaster, Hsing Yun, whom he had met on a visit to Taiwan in
1989. Gore traveled to Taiwan at the invitation of Hsia, who was
helping Gore raise money for his 1990 Senate campaign, and a group
of Asian-Americans with ties to the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia remained active in raising money for the Democrats and
arranged for Hsing Yun to meet briefly with Gore at the White House
on March 15, 1996. At that meeting, Hsing Yun invited Gore to visit
the Hsi Lai Temple, the largest Buddhist temple in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia and Huang later said that they planned to hold the
fund-raiser at a separate location, and that Gore would visit the
temple afterward. But because of scheduling, they combined the two
events.
</P>
<P>
   Senate investigators never found substantial evidence to support
the claim that the events were to have been separate.
</P>
<P>
   MONASTICS WERE SHAM DONORS
</P>
<P>
   Gore arrived at the temple shortly after noon on April 29. A
local school band played in the courtyard as Gore, wearing a flower
necklace, passed by scores of monks and nuns clad in saffron robes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore met privately with Hsing Yun before having lunch with about
120 people, some from the temple and some local business people who
had received invitations from Hsia and Huang. Gore spoke briefly.
He did not thank anyone for contributions, as he typically would
have done at a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the crimes committed at the temple occurred after Gore
left. When DNC fund-raisers in Washington expressed disappointment
that the luncheon had raised only $45,000, Hsia and Huang set out
to make up the shortfall, according to Senate investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Using her contacts at the temple, where she often helped
devotees with immigration problems, Hsia persuaded monks and nuns
to make additional contributions totaling $55,000. Those
contributions later were reimbursed from the temple's general fund,
breaking campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   In investigating the temple, investigators found other
fund-raisers at which the temple's monastics had made illegal
contributions to the DNC, the Clinton-Gore campaign and the
campaigns of other prominent Democrats, including Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy (D-Mass.).
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors ultimately declined to prosecute the monks
and nuns themselves, saying they were unwitting pawns, and instead
focused on Hsia. Hsia was convicted March 2 of five counts of
causing the DNC to file false contribution reports with the Federal
Election Commission. The federal judge presiding over the case,
however, still has reserved the right to dismiss the charges and
has not yet entered the conviction into the court record.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the biggest unanswered question about the
event is what Gore knew about it beforehand. Gore at first said he
thought it was ``community outreach,'' but later admitted he knew
it was ``finance-related.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate investigators, however, uncovered batches of internal
correspondence in the files of Gore's senior staff that referred to
the event as a ``fund-raiser.'' Don Fowler, then chairman of the
DNC, also attended the event, as well as Hsia and Huang, who were
known to Gore as fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite his various denials, the vice president was well aware
that the event was one designed to raise money for his party,''
Senate investigators concluded in their lengthy summary of the
affair.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising phone calls Gore made from his White House
office, raising about $795,000 for the DNC, were far more
problematic for the vice president because of the 117-year-old law
prohibiting federal employees from soliciting campaign
contributions from federal property.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Gore said he did not believe the law applied to him
or the president because they were candidates. But the case turned
on the arcane details of federal campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno declined to pursue an investigation
into the calls on the grounds that Gore was raising unregulated
``soft money,'' not ``hard money'' governed by federal election
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, investigators found that donations from five
people called by Gore were deposited into hard money accounts. The
DNC explained that its procedure was to deposit the first $20,000
of every soft money contribution into a hard money account if the
donor had not already reached the $20,000 hard money limit set by
law.
</P>
<P>
   After Reno opened a preliminary inquiry, Gore told investigators
he was ignorant of the DNC's method of splitting contributions and
said he believed he was raising only soft money. Reno declined to
appoint an independent counsel in December 1997, saying there was
nothing to suggest that Gore would have known about the split
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The matter might have ended there, but a memo from one of Gore's
senior aides surfaced in the summer of 1998. Handwritten notes by
David Strauss, then Gore's deputy chief of staff, described a Nov.
21, 1995, meeting attended by Gore during which the practice of
splitting contributions was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   The memo was also significant because it portrayed Gore as an
enthusiastic participant in the DNC's overall fund-raising program
of wooing donors with White House coffees and special access to the
administration. At the meeting, Gore volunteered to make more
fund-raising calls than the DNC proposed and was quoted as saying,
``Count me in on the calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on Strauss' memo, Reno opened a second inquiry into
whether Gore had been truthful about what he knew. Investigators
quizzed Gore closely about the 1995 meeting. Gore said he could not
recall what was said. He noted that he usually sat next to Clinton
during such meetings and that the two frequently talked among
themselves while the meeting was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also volunteered that he drank lots of iced tea,
necessitating frequent bathroom breaks. Republican operatives have
seized on this aspect of his testimony and dubbed it the ``tinkle
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   RENO: INSUFFICIENT EVIDENCE
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, Reno concluded that there was insufficient
evidence to conclude that Gore lied about the fund-raising calls,
closing the case.
</P>
<P>
   Still more information exists, however, that could prove
damaging to Gore this year. FBI Director Louis Freeh urged Reno in
a memo to name an independent counsel. Congressional Republicans
are pressing Reno to release the memo.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, parts of a memo written by Charles LaBella, who for
a time headed the Justice Department's campaign finance task force,
were leaked to the Los Angeles Times. LaBella's memo, also
addressed to Reno, criticized career Justice Department lawyers for
not holding Gore and other senior White House officials to a higher
standard.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also expressed skepticism about Gore's contention that
he did not know what kind of money he was raising in his White
House fund-raising calls. Justice department officials vigorously
disputed LaBella's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore's campaign labels the temple fund-raiser and the
fund-raising calls ``old news,'' Gore himself addressed the
subjects in an interview in the New York Times on March 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake going to that Buddhist temple,'' Gore said.
``I made a mistake in making telephone calls from my office. And I
have learned from those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
