<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.J.-COLUMN-JOKES-NYT     04-01 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.J.-COLUMN-JOKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. COLUMN: CANDIDATE LEARNS THE PERILS OF AD-LIBBING THE
ONE-LINERS 
</HEADLINE>
 -NYT  (jw) 
 By MATT PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Jon S. Corzine, the former chairman of Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co., entered the race for the U.S. Senate from New Jersey
with the best campaign money could buy. Generous contributions
endeared him to local politicians. Big checks bought him more
advertising than Priceline.com. He hired President Clinton's
pollsters. Ted Kennedy's media adviser. Two campaign managers. A
squad of consultants and aides.
</P>
<P>
   If only he had hired a joke writer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Corzine left spontaneity to chance, handling the
unscripted moments himself. Now he's paying the price.
</P>
<P>
   Two jokes have returned to haunt him. A small Italian-American
anti-defamation group revealed Wednesday that in a meeting last
summer Corzine joked to some Italian-American leaders sitting with
a Jewish lawyer that the lawyer must be there to get them out of
jail. He recently quipped about making cement shoes to an
Italian-American contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly last week, Corzine, 53, had become what he had said he
wasn't. A politician. Whatever he had been before _ Midwest farm
boy, Wall Street executive _ he was now a New Jersey politician,
sitting at a news conference in a crammed union hall in Hudson
County, and people were shouting.
</P>
<P>
   Did he say those things? reporters demanded. ``Propaganda!''
spat a Corzine supporter. Corzine was contrite: ``I never intended
to offend.''
</P>
<P>
   Since beginning his campaign, he intended to move from corporate
boardroom to Senate cloakroom. Many party leaders saw Jon Corzine,
the nonpolitician, as the perfect foil to Jim Florio, the
recidivist politician.
</P>
<P>
   With the two men competing in the June Democratic primary,
Corzine's Italian-American backers accused Florio of inflating
off-hand remarks just as Corzine's poll numbers improved. Offended,
the former governor denied it, saying his opponent's money was
making the election into ``an auction.''
</P>
<P>
   It is more like a summer stock casting call, with Florio trying
to revive his act and Corzine honing his on stage.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Corzine still resembles a tourist in politics. ``I
think on balance, the political life has been a positive, terrific
experience,'' he said in an interview on Friday. ``I have seen
things from new perspectives and had the opportunity to embrace the
diversity of life.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his understated way, he also sounds hardened after last
week: ``It's a competitive business and I'm going to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio remains popular with Democratic voters. But many party
leaders, particularly in central and northern New Jersey, are still
seething over his $2.8 billion tax increase as governor that led
Democrats to slaughter a decade ago. They haven't controlled
Trenton since, making campaign funds sparse.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they're pinching themselves over Corzine. With an
estimated $300 million of his own and access to big donors, he is
helping to sprinkle cash on parched Democrats around the state.
``He's bringing in new people to the Democratic Party who are
making substantial contributions,'' said Raymond Lesniak, a
Democratic state senator.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, party leaders also like Corzine's politics. He's for
universal everything _ preschool, gun registration, access to
health care. He wants to spread the opportunities he had _ to
attend college with government aid and to succeed financially. ``I
have had people help me from the day I hit the ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He proposes urban investment banks, ``recharging'' affirmative
action and two years' free tuition at a state college for B
students.
</P>
<P>
   With his left-leaning platform, graying beard and rimless
glasses, Corzine, who is married with three children, seems like a
member of the used Volvo set. It's hard to imagine him running an
investment firm. Or cracking tired ethnic jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the jokes surfaced, Corzine simply apologized. Career
politicians supporting him were left to explain. ``We found out
that Jon Corzine is not Superman and not God,'' Lesniak said,
targeting the sinner vote. Stephen Adubato, a community leader in
Newark's North Ward, said Corzine's raw honesty shone through since
``the politicians I know would have denied that they said it.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, drawn into the political fray, tried his hand at
spinning reporters. He said his family had argued for years about
whether they were Italian or French. He had decided. ``For certain,
I am Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   You could almost hear the French vote fleeing. Will he never
learn?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
