<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BIKE-ULLRICH-NYT &LR;      04-01 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-ULLRICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULLRICH MISSES A RACE AND HIS CONDITION IS SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Germany)  (mk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Spring had come to the French Basque coast. The sky was
cloudless, the breeze off the Atlantic soft and briny, the dark
hillside leading down to the French town of St. Jean de Luz flecked
with suspicions of green.
</P>
<P>
   On such a lovely day last weekend, Rudy Pevenage was friendly,
even genial, but his eyes were wary. Definitely wary. For the last
three years, spring has not been his favorite season.
</P>
<P>
   Pevenage, a 45-year-old Belgian who is coach for the Telekom
bicycle team from Germany, knew that anybody approaching with a
notebook or tape recorder did not want to ask about the explosion
of forsythia in the southwestern town, nor about the crocus pushing
up in every garden. What people wanted to talk about for the third
successive spring was the suspect condition of his protege, Jan
Ullrich, now and then a dominant racer.
</P>
<P>
   Spring is not one of those times for Ullrich, the 26-year-old
German.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he celebrated his victory the previous year in the Tour
de France by showing up for the start of the season in February at
least 20 pounds overweight (some said 30). Not until July, when he
finished second in the Tour, did the scales balance at his usual
160 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after Pevenage kept a closer eye on his star's
off-season eating habits, the problem was injury and illness. His
spring was marked by a stomach virus, the flu and problems with a
wisdom tooth, all of which caused Ullrich to skip many of the races
he needs to reach top condition for the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the end of May, he crashed in the Tour of Germany,
injuring his head and a knee. The headache went away but the knee
injury worsened, forcing Ullrich to miss the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Both springs, Pevenage was kept busy fielding questions and
dodging answers. Now, as the songbirds returned to their accustomed
trees, he was being peppered again: Why did Ullrich drop out of the
Tirreno-Adriatico race in Italy three weeks ago? Why did he not
start the Milan-San Remo classic, as scheduled, on March 18? Why
did he not show up for the Catalan Week in Spain, as scheduled,
last week?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, why was he missing when the Criterium International
started its two-day run in St. Jean de Luz last Saturday? There, in
the printed program, was Ullrich's name, with No. 31 after it, but
there, at the starting line, the numbers on the Telekom team's
jerseys began at No. 32.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a week, Ullrich had disappointed race organizers
and fans in Italy, Spain and France, while raising the standard
questions about his weight and condition.
</P>
<P>
   Once again those questions were irritating Pevenage, and so the
best approach in stalking him was a general comment about how well
his team is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Zabel, Telekom's star sprinter, has already won eight
races, including Milan-San Remo for the third time. ``A very good
victory for him,'' Pevenage agreed. ``Also very important for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreas Kloeden, a hitherto unheralded young German, won the
Paris-Nice weeklong race with a smooth victory in the decisive
uphill time trial. ``I knew how good he is,'' Pevenage said. ``Now
everybody knows. I wasn't surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandre Vinokourov, a Kazakh who was lured with a big contract
from a French team, was among the favorites in the Criterium
International.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team is doing very well,'' Pevenage said. ``It
cannot be better. Everything's OK. It cannot be better.''
</P>
<P>
   His rote answers, his off-guard look, his relaxed body language
_ all proclaimed a time to strike.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be better? What about Ullrich?
</P>
<P>
   Pevenage rummaged through his memories. ``Jan,'' he finally
said. ``He's home; everything's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it be better?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe better. Everything will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Last question: When is Ullrich's next race?
</P>
<P>
   ``Next week,'' Pevenage said. ``Probably.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not look happy. He looked, in fact, like a man thinking:
There goes another spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
