<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-FURCAL0402     04-01 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-FURCAL0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `He can play the game'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rafael Furcal spent his first major-league spring camp
giving the Braves a lot to think about, and a lot to look forward
to.
</P>
<P>
   Rated the eighth-best prospect in baseball by Baseball America,
the 19-year-old from the Dominican Republic did nothing but enhance
his status as the Braves' shortstop of the future _ the very near
future.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal made the team as a backup infielder by hitting .283 with
seven stolen bases, displaying a golden right arm and showing his
lack of fear of anything major-league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's exactly what we heard,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``He's a
good infielder. He's got the best arm in baseball, maybe, as an
infielder right now. He's always hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves made room for Furcal by releasing veteran Ozzie
Guillen on Friday. Furcal will see action spelling Walt Weiss at
shortstop and Quilvio Veras at second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready,'' said outfielder Andruw Jones, who also made the
majors at 19. ``He can play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones knows what it feels like to itch for the big-league
opportunity. He offered Furcal this advice: ``Keep playing the same
way you've been playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Furcal has a reputation for being a hard worker with a good
attitude, and he displayed it in camp. ``I'm working hard every
day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His first couple of years in the Braves system were good, but he
underscored his label as a top prospect in his first full season in
the minors last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal led all minor-leaguers with 96 stolen bases. He hit .337
and stole 73 bases in 83 games for Class A Macon. In late July, he
was promoted to Myrtle Beach, in the more advanced Class A Carolina
League, and hit .293 with 23 steals in 43 games.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal played second base but was moved to his natural shortstop
position last season. Paul Snyder, the Braves' former director of
scouting and player development, said the organization wasn't sure
which side of second he would play on, but it wanted to keep his
arm in shortstop shape.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal had 34 errors in 86 games last year as he made the
adjustment. He has been a little shaky with his glove this spring,
but he has the arm strength to make up for a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only criticism now is he rushes a lot,'' said Dick
Balderson, Braves director of player development. ``As he gains
experience, it becomes a non-factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Treadway, the former Braves second baseman who managed the
Macon Braves last year, worked with Furcal on his defense. Furcal
was named the South Atlantic League's top prospect, and from
Treadway's perspective it wasn't even close.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't anybody even close to having that kind of
ability,'' Treadway said. ``He's got major-league tools. Throwing
arm, foot speed, hitting ability and makeup _ his personality, his
approach to the game, his intensity. He has the instincts it takes
to play the game. He exudes it.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment has been echoed all over the major-league camp as
he went about his work eagerly and confidently.
</P>
<P>
   In one of Furcal's first at-bats with the major-league club,
against the Blue Jays, he fell behind 0-2 in the count, but worked
it full and then slapped an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   Another at-bat, he faced a 3-0 count with a runner at second and
a veteran bat coming up behind him. He swung at the next pitch to
drive a single up the middle and score the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has one thing it's tough to have, (and) that's a ton of
confidence in himself,'' Braves hitting coach Merv Rettenmund said.
``He has no doubt he can play ball and hit anybody. He has fun
playing. He believes in himself.
</P>
<P>
   Balderson said: ``He looks like he belongs. He's not
intimidated, not back on his heels, defensive, because he's scared
to make a mistake. He's got a chance to be a special player.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
