<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-NFLDRAFT0402-COX     04-01 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NFLDRAFT0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warrick both draws praise, loses ground
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Washington Redskins coach Norv Turner calls Peter
Warrick, ``the best player in college football the past three
years.'' Cleveland Browns coach Chris Palmer says the Florida State
receiver is ``exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the first three choices are made in next month's NFL
Draft, Warrick might not be among them. Once regarded as the top
player available, Warrick could go as low as fourth to the
Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick and Alabama offensive tackle Chris Samuels are
considered the best offensive players in this year's draft. The
class is especially deep at wide receiver, running back and the
offensive line, but the NFL might take just one quarterback _
Marshall's Chad Pennington _ in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said this past week that the Browns are leaning toward
drafting one of two Penn State players with the top pick in the
draft. The Browns are thought to be favoring Nittany Lions
defensive end Courtney Brown, who dazzled scouts with a workout
earlier this month. Cleveland also is considering linebacker LaVar
Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Brown and Arrington) are rare and Warrick is
exceptional,'' Palmer said. ``Clearly, those three players are
worthy of the No. 1 pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick once seemed like a perfect fit for the Browns,
especially after the team signed free-agent defensive ends Orpheus
Roye of the Steelers and Keith McKenzie of the Packers. Browns
quarterback Tim Couch, the No. 1 pick in last year's draft, has
lobbied Palmer and other Cleveland officials to select Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a horse race, and Warrick came out of the gates very,
very quickly,'' Palmer said. ``It was very easy to evaluate him.
All you had to do was turn on the TV and watch him make plays. But
once we got a chance to evaluate the defensive players, they jumped
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we go around the turn, I'd say Arrington and Brown are neck
and neck, with Warrick closing fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said a final decision might not be made until a few days
before the April 15-16 draft. The Browns would like to have their
first choice signed to a contract before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins have the second and third picks, and are thought to
be favoring Arrington and Samuels. That would leave Warrick for the
Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going into this very open,'' Turner said. ``I
think in those first four or five picks everyone is going to get a
great football player. We're going to definitely get two good
football players.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's stock started to fall after his first individual
workout, in which he ran the 40-yard dash in only 4.54 seconds on a
slick gym floor at Florida State. He was faster in a second
workout, but some scouts also seem concerned about his size. At 5
feet 10 1/2, 190 pounds, Warrick has only average size for an NFL
receiver. But Turner says teams can't ignore Warrick's
explosiveness and open-field moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the whole key to evaluating players,'' Turner
said. ``You've got to go look at what the guy did the last three
years. He's probably the best player in college football the past
three years. All you have to do is turn on the tape and watch him
make people miss.''
</P>
<P>
   What might hurt Warrick is the deep receiver corps in this
year's draft. As many as six could be taken in the first round,
including Michigan State's Plaxico Burress, Georgia Tech's Dez
White, Florida's Travis Taylor and West Virginia's Jerry Porter.
The Browns, who also have the first pick in the second round,
figure that a good receiver might be available at the No. 32 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen so many good, tall receivers,'' said Mark
Hatley, Bears vice president of player personnel. ``It's the
darnedest thing I've ever seen. And there are a lot more juniors
and sophomores coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the NFL initiated the draft in 1936, only five receivers
have been taken with the No. 1 pick, most recently in 1996 when the
Jets selected Keyshawn Johnson from Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Warrick) would be fun to have and work with,'' Bengals
president Mike Brown said. ``It's what he does after he catches the
ball. In that regard, he may be as fine a wide receiver as any
coming out of the draft in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
