<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOTCOM-RENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR UPSTARTS OF CYBERSPACE, A SCRAMBLE FOR RENTAL SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Colo.)  (jw) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How fast is Global Crossing growing?
</P>
<P>
   The two-year-old company, which runs a worldwide fiber-optic
network, recently signed a lease to house its electronic switching
equipment in 205,000 square feet in an old brick factory building
at 636 11th Ave., between 46th and 47th streets.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, it went back to the landlord asking to rent nearly
the entire 600,000-square-foot building .
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. Global Crossing, which is expected to
sign a new lease within days, is also talking to developers about
taking 400,000 square feet in one or another office tower it plans
to build in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, like many other telecommunication and Internet
companies, has a suddenly voracious appetite for space in a city
where large blocks of office space have become rare. In their
quest, the companies are shoving aside industrial tenants on the
West Side of Manhattan, on the Brooklyn waterfront and in Long
Island City, Queens. And they are driving rents up beyond even the
headiest expectations of a landlord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be happening all over town,'' said Scott Latham, a
managing director at CB Richard Ellis. ``It's astounding what this
whole dot-com, telecom industry is doing to real estate. It's the
modern equivalent of the California gold rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, which would not comment, is by no means alone.
Internet and telecommunications companies rented as much space in
the first three months of this year as they did in all of 1999, 2.5
million square feet, according to Cushman &AMP; Wakefield, a commercial
real estate broker. They are gobbling up space in nearly every
neighborhood in Manhattan and chasing manufacturers into
traditional backwaters like the Brooklyn waterfront and industrial
parts of Queens, where rents are low. Industrial tenants in these
neighborhoods who had been paying $8 and $9 a square foot cannot
compete with the technology companies that are willing to pay $30
or $40 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   In the fast shrinking garment district below Times Square,
iVillage took 108,000 square feet at 500-512 Seventh Ave., between
37th and 38th streets, and About.com signed a lease to move its
headquarters into nearby 1440 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' said Adam C. Hochfelder of Max Capital, the
owner of 1440 Broadway. ``One hundred thousand-square-foot blocks
are moving like loaves of bread at a grocery store.''
</P>
<P>
   And printers are getting squeezed out of their longtime home
near the entrance to the Holland Tunnel by newly minted companies
willing to pay three times the old rent.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest Communications International, a multimedia communications
company, took 150,000 square feet at 32 Avenue of the Americas, a
building the Rudin real estate family is developing as a telecom
hotel, in which a building is used to house telecommunications
equipment for a variety of companies. MCI WorldCom leased 105,000
square feet in the same building. At 325 Hudson St., Bell Atlantic
Global Networks, Flag Atlantic USA and Net 2000 have leased large
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Network Plus Corp., a telecommunications carrier that moved into
the Starrett Lehigh Building, at 11th Avenue and 26th Street, has
nearly tripled the size of its space in that industrial building to
90,000 square feet. Last year, Highgate Holdings was planning to
redevelop the 10-story building at 85 10th Ave., between 15th and
16th streets, as a telecom hotel. Instead, Highgate transferred
ownership to Level 3 Communications, a telecommunications network
based in Denver, for a tidy profit.
</P>
<P>
   Highgate is also doing well with 636 11th Ave., despite paying a
small fortune for what is a battered brick structure, still home to
a few remaining printers, lighting shops and storage centers. In
1998, Stephen L. Green signed a contract to buy the old factory for
about $32.5 million, according to real estate executives. But
problems in the capital markets made Green wary. Bidding on the
building resumed last year, with offers of less than $40 million.
Then, real estate brokers said, Highgate won the contest with a bid
of about $43 million.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, Global came calling. Formed in March 1997,
Global acquired Frontier Corp., the fifth-largest telephone
company, in an $11.2 billion deal last year and is in the process
of buying IXnet and its parent company, IPC Communications, for $4
billion. Within the last year, Global's payroll jumped to 12,000
from 148.
</P>
<P>
   Global is taking all the available space in the building at
average rents of about $42 a square foot, said real estate brokers,
well above the single-digit rents paid by the old industrial
tenants. Now, Global, which has hundreds of employees in New
Jersey, and IXnet, which has more than 300 in lower Manhattan, are
looking for a regional headquarters, either in Times Square or
Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire market is adopting the fast pace of the intercom
and telecom companies,'' said Mary Ann Tighe, vice chairman of
Insignia/ESG, a broker. ``Older companies that normally proceed at
a more measured pace are being forced to act quickly, otherwise a
technology upstart will reach in and take the space, or create an
auction atmosphere that drives rents skyward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
