<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRAYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRAYER BEFORE SCHOOL FOOTBALL GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, April 2:
</P>
<P>
   The school prayer issue occasioned a spirited argument at the
Supreme Court Wednesday during which a majority of the justices
expressed a healthy reluctance to permit organized prayer at public
high school football games. Such prayers almost inevitably give an
official endorsement to religious beliefs that may offend some
students and parents.
</P>
<P>
   The case started when a Mormon family and a Roman Catholic
family sued a small school district in Texas, objecting to the
Christian prayers offered by chaplains at school events. Since
then, the district has modified its policies to have a student
chosen in a schoolwide election offer a pregame invocation or
message of his or her own choosing. The district is trying to
persuade the court that prayer led by such an ``independent
speaker'' creates no constitutional problem _ unlike clergy-led
prayer at graduation, which the court outlawed in a principled
decision eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It proved a difficult sell. Five justices suggested that using
an elected student surrogate to deliver the prayer could not mask
the school's role in organizing the religious worship or overcome
the risk of indirect coercion inherent in prayer exercises in
elementary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
   Only Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia
seemed to be probing for a way to distinguish school prayer from
graduation prayer. ``Nobody has to go to a football game,'' the
chief justice observed, glibly ignoring the importance of high
school football to student and community life in Texas and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Justices' comments during oral argument do not always foretell
the court's direction. But to the extent they indicated that a
majority would oppose creating a school sports loophole to the
First Amendment's protection against state establishment of
religion, the direction is sound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1626EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
