<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4361 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-OLAZABAL0402-COX     04-01 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OLAZABAL0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uphill defense
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Augusta _ As a greenskeeper's son playing golf as a youngster in
Fuenterrabia, Spain, Jose Maria Olazabal became a short-game
specialist by necessity. Nobody could outwork Olazabal, who
brandished his first club at age 4, but everyone seemed to outdrive
him. Something needed to be done to keep from falling behind his
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really short,'' Olazabal said. ``I was never a strong
boy. When the rest of the kids were hitting irons to the greens, I
couldn't even reach the green. So, I had to be better with the
short game than they were.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, it's an extra bonus that Olazabal's touch with a
pitching wedge or other chipping club remains among the world's
finest. A few days from defending his second Masters title, it's
about the only part of his game not causing stress.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old Olazabal knows that he can arrive at Augusta
with his driver misbehaving but he won't be there on the weekend if
his putter betrays him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Augusta National, without a doubt, favors the long hitter,''
he said, ``but, at the same time, if you have a good touch on the
greens, you can compensate (for) lack of distance off the tee. I
think that is the beauty of Augusta. You don't need to be a really
great hitter of the ball to score.''
</P>
<P>
   After missing the cut at The Players Championship, Olazabal
arrived at the BellSouth Classic speaking as though he could not
hit a fairway or the hole with consistency. While others were
competing in The Players Championship, Olazabal worked on his tee
shots on the practice range at Sawgrass. On Tuesday, he spent hours
on the practice greens at Sugarloaf, in stiff winds, working on his
putting. He was missing badly on straight, uphill putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a professional, you know these kinds of things are going to
go through your game,'' he said. ``It's just a pity I have to
approach Augusta in these conditions. . . . Last year, it was just
one thing that was not working well. That was the driver. The rest
of the game was pretty solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, you will forgive the rest of the Masters field if they
don't cry over Olazabal's plight. He poor-mouthed his driving last
year, then wound up with a second green jacket. Not only are the
fairways forgiving enough at Augusta National to allow poor drives
_ even with the addition of the ``second cut'' _ Ollie's short game
and it's pre-adolescent origin, have a way of sharpening at the
sight of the first azalea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seve's the best, but Olazabal's quite close,'' Scotland's
Colin Montgomerie said, referring to the latter's fellow Spaniard,
Seve Ballesteros. ``Their short game is second to none, and that's
what's it's all about at Augusta. The emphasis is not so much
driving the ball at the Masters. It's the second shots and in, and
that's where they both score. And that's why they've gotten four
Masters between them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad (Olazabal) doesn't drive it straight,'' Curtis
Strange said. ``He has a wonderful short game, and he always has.
But look who his mentor was. There hasn't been any person better
than Seve chipping the ball that I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Proud of how colleagues regard his chipping, Olazabal insists
that he grinds over each shot more than the results would indicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may look very confident, but I can assure you I don't feel
that comfortable,'' he said. ``Especially when you pass over the
15th green, and the flag is short, and you're seeing the water
behind the shot that you're facing. There's no way you're going to
be feeling comfortable; it doesn't matter how good you are, having
to hit those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal's long-term problem has been the driver. Since the 1999
Masters, he has been missing fairways with troubling regularity. He
was mildly encouraged this winter when instructor John Jacobs
strengthened his grip. But Olazabal has gone back to guessing where
his drives might be heading.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience just tells me that the only way to get something
positive (going) is when you see that ball flying straight to the
middle of the fairway,'' Olazabal said. ``Whenever it goes straight
right or left, in the water or in the trees, that is not good news,
and it's not going to be a good confidence-builder whenever you
have to hit the next tee shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange, for one, always has been surprised by Olazabal's
driving woes, considering how strong an iron player he has been
through the years. ``His left hand is on there so weak, he kind of
hangs on his left side a lot,'' said Strange, a two-time U.S. Open
champion. ``It's kind of like he's catching up all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything's relative, though. Olazabal went nearly two years in
the mid-1990s without competing because of rheumatoid arthritis in
both feet that prevented him from walking. Four years before the
second Augusta victory, Olazabal watched the tournament from his
bed. Last year, after his Masters victory, he was treated like a
hero in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason I really do appreciate it much more now is
just that I was not able to walk at all,'' he said. ``For a while,
I thought I would never play golf again.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Gary Player in a conversation at the Tuesday
Champions Dinner last year, Olazabal made a remarkable
transformation with his game. He came to town admittedly ``not a
happy camper,'' lacking confidence and distrusting his driver, but
``after two days, I looked at the tournament from a different
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   This year could be a tougher challenge. With just one finish
outside the top 10 in the Masters since 1988, Olazabal has had few
opportunities when could not count on his putter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``I'm missing them on both sides of the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
