<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HOUSTON-ATLANTA0402-C     04-01 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-ATLANTA0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Houston flexes
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ You can sense Georgia in the air here lately, and
we're not talking humidity.
</P>
<P>
   In the theater district, beneath downtown's copse of rugged
skyscrapers, the Houston Grand Opera is about to unveil its world
premiere of ``Cold Sassy Tree.'' Published in 1984, the
turn-of-the-century novel by Atlanta newspaper writer Olive Ann
Burns is set in a town modeled on Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Catch this week's Houston Symphony performances, and you can
hear Robert Spano _ the Atlanta Symphony's new music director _
conduct the HSO, an orchestra in the familiar limbo of searching
for a new maestro. Houston is also looking to start funding a new
hall in the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Houston Ballet produced a newly choreographed
and nationally recognized ``Cleopatra,'' featuring the diaphanous
pastel designs of Judanna Lynn, who also did costumes for the
Atlanta Ballet's new ``Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   Drive over to the live oak-lined museum district, and you'll
find the Audrey Jones Beck Building, a mighty $85 million expansion
to the Museum of Fine Arts. High Museum of Art leaders have checked
out its progress as they await plans for their own addition.
</P>
<P>
   Walk through the perfectly placid Menil Collection campus nearby
_ home to heralded surrealist paintings and a Rothko chapel, among
other treasures _ and you'll experience the seductive low-scale
design by Renzo Piano that helped persuade the Woodruff Arts Center
to hire the Italian architect to draw its redesign. The Menil's new
director is Ned Rifkin, who left the High Museum in December.
</P>
<P>
   Houston. Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Regional capitals. Sweaty Sun Belt siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Two major-league cities incorporated in the first half of the
19th century, now a pair of vast, sprawling metro areas with large,
ethnically diverse populations. It's tempting, but tricky, to draw
parallels between them, particularly when evaluating their arts
communities. Yet comparisons can be instructive when considering
the kind of commitment it takes to be recognized as a world-class
cultural capital.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Houston is ahead, perhaps as it should be,
considering that its economic oil gusher started decades ago. The
city has wide philanthropic support, grounded by half a dozen
family foundations, the largest being the Houston Endowment _
founded by Jesse Jones, an oil and newspaper magnate. While Texas'
largest city reached national status in the arts several years
back, Atlanta still has a way to go _ if not because it lacks
talented artists, then perhaps for a lack of broad community
support.
</P>
<P>
   A TALE OF TWO DISTRICTS
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting contradiction that Houston, a city famous
for having no zoning, has two well-organized arts districts. The
downtown theater district includes homes for the opera, ballet,
symphony and major residential theater, within a block or two of
each other. Approximately three miles down Main Street, the museum
district is an oak-canopied refuge that includes the Museum of Fine
Arts, its expansion, a sculpture garden, an art school and the
Contemporary Arts Museum. A city park, with golf course, is across
the street and the Rice University campus a five-minute walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Spend a few days at Houston's stages, and two things strike you:
the number of modern, appropriate venues and the amount of new work
being performed.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's opera and ballet reside in the Wortham Center,
featuring administrative offices, rehearsal space and two
customized theaters, seating 2,200 and 1,100, respectively. The
center, which cost $72 million, was built entirely with private
funds during the economic recession of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   David Gockley, general director of Houston Grand Opera, has
forged an international reputation by producing 24 world premieres,
four of them by Carlisle Floyd, the South Carolina native who
composed ``Cold Sassy Tree.'' His city has an appetite for modern
opera, he says, not having grown up _ as many Atlantans did _ with
yearly visits from New York's Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that Houston has less of a traditional audience,''
Gockley says. ``They have not had opera in their lives for
generation after generation; they're a little less formed in their
mind about what it should be. There's a comparatively small percent
of European-descended population that would want to keep the flame
burning as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   A CITY WITH DEEP POCKETS
</P>
<P>
   Enviable endowments enable Houston institutions, such as the
ballet and the Museum of Fine Arts, to make names for themselves
outside the city. Houston Ballet has an endowment of $37 million,
the largest of any dance company in the United States after New
York City Ballet. The new Audrey Jones Beck Building addition to
the Museum of Fine Arts has raised more than $40 million for its
endowment (to operate the building), after raising $85 million to
build it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about commitment in the fullest sense,'' says
the Atlanta Ballet's director John McFall of Houston's
philanthropy, ``so that everything inside them is supported, so
that the institution is not only able to sustain itself, but to
distinguish itself. Rather than just having a nice regional
cultural institution, they have a passion to create something quite
remarkable in their own neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   But support comes from many quarters. ``I get lots of $55,000,
$60,000 checks (from individuals),'' Peter Marzio, director of the
Museum of Fine Arts, told the Atlanta Journal-Constitution in 1998.
``That's what this place runs on.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta need not cower in comparison (not that this
self-proclaimed ``sports capital of the world'' would). The city's
upside looks too good. The Woodruff Arts Center seems a solid bet
to adopt a new master plan. People who should know say a major High
Museum expansion will happen. The symphony already has a generous
lead gift of $15 million from Home Depot's Arthur Blank slated for
a new hall. The ASO's hiring of the Brooklyn Philharmonic' Spano as
its music director has drawn national attention. Downtown is
building up along the Peachtree Street corridor; it has an energy,
and mass transit infrastructure, that Houston's desolate stretch of
Main Street, between its two arts districts, simply cannot match.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, arts groups are tapping the city's
growing technology market for financial support. Judging from this
past week's economic forum on the arts at the Metro Atlanta Chamber
of Commerce, there's reason to expect good things. Even new
Houstonian Ned Rifkin, the recently departed High Museum director,
says Atlanta has an edge in ``new economy'' resources for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But Houston offers a subtle lesson: It's not enough for a city
to want the arts; it has to need them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
