<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CENSUS-PROBLEMS-NYT &LR;      04-01 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-PROBLEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY CONCERNS THWART CENSUS, DIRECTOR SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The director of the Census Bureau expressed alarm
Saturday that Americans were not adequately cooperating with the
census because they saw the government survey as an intrusion on
their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Kenneth Prewitt, said opinion polls suggested that
public concerns about the privacy of census data had ``sharply
increased.'' About 17 percent of Americans express such concerns,
up from 10 percent three weeks ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said he worried that a ``public backlash'' against the
census, especially the elaborate long form sent to one household in
six, could undermine the quality of data used for a wide variety of
public programs.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the official Census Day, the occasion on which the
government tries once every decade to take a snapshot of the
population. But in a telephone interview with reporters from his
home here, Prewitt said he was ``concerned about the level of
public cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency said that as of Thursday, 50 percent of all
households that had received questionnaires had returned them. It
did not say what percentage of long forms had been returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get a flood of responses in the next couple of
days,'' Prewitt said, ``we will have a huge task ahead of us as we
go into the community to find nonrespondents. A huge task. We have
to express concern about the number of doors that may be slammed,
with people saying this is not that important.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans in Congress, including Sen. Trent Lott,
R-Miss., the majority leader, have told constituents they may skip
questions they see as invading their privacy. But Prewitt
emphasized that Americans were required to answer all questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To signal that the census is not serious, that it is a
pick-and-choose exercise, is to put the response rate at risk,''
Prewitt said. ``I do not believe that's the intent of our political
leadership. But I believe it's a possible consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires Americans to complete census forms, Prewitt
said. ``To tell them not to complete the form is to tell them to
break the law,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the Census Bureau had not anticipated the
``long-form backlash,'' which he attributed to factors beyond the
control of his agency. He said there had been ``a general increase
in dislike of or mistrust of government,'' running from
``Watergate, secret bombing, Pentagon papers, Irangate, right
through the current administration.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``three-decade-long decline in civic responsibility'' has been
aggravated by an increase in privacy concerns, which loom larger
now than in the last three censuses, Prewitt said. ``People
suddenly have a heightened concern about their privacy being
invaded,'' he said. ``Some of that concern is transferred to the
government and the census.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans have always expressed such concerns, but Prewitt
said: ``You now can amplify messages like that much more rapidly
than you used to. Internet sites are out there bashing the
census.''
</P>
<P>
   If a low response rate damages the quality of data, Prewitt
said, the information will be less useful. ``Ask Alan Greenspan if
he'd like to make monetary policy without data on labor force
participation or the Consumer Price Index,'' he said, referring to
the Federal Reserve chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the government would accelerate radio advertising
in parts of the country where response to the census was lagging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
