<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This version contains additional commentary at the end.
 &HT;    Teams gearing up to keep Yankees at bay
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now for Plan J.
</P>
<P>
   The American League for four years has tried anything to escape
the hammerlock that the New York Yankees have maintained almost
unceasingly upon the 13 other teams. This spring bears the same
scant hope.
</P>
<P>
   Chasing a third straight World Series championship and a fourth
in five years, the Yankees of 2000 are essentially the same
substance that has run through both leagues with such ease in
recent autumns. Elsewhere in the league, young teams _ Oakland and
Toronto _ are getting better while solid contenders _ Cleveland and
Boston _ mass for another rush.
</P>
<P>
   But the plain truth remains that the Yankees' roster has hardly
changed during this historic rush. Outside the Bronx, the anguish
grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we've done to this point, all the division titles
and stuff, won't mean anything until we win the World Series,''
said Indians catcher Sandy Alomar, his club having nothing to show
for five straight Central championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's necessary that we win one. And the thing I'm interested
in finding out is will the fans still come out after we win one?''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' biggest response to New York was adding free agent
pitcher Chuck Finley, which is hardly enough to close the gap
against a rotation of Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, David Cone,
Roger Clemens and Andy Pettitte. The Tribe's firing of manager Mike
Hargrove was more a gesture of frustration than a shift in
strategy, after Cleveland went 10-22 against playoff teams last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see us buckle down and play well against good teams
like that,'' new Indians manager Charlie Manuel said. ``I think
that it's important because it can give you a mental edge when you
play those teams again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West, while Seattle retools for ``small ball'' without
Ken Griffey Jr. and Texas jettisons Juan Gonzalez and Todd Zeile
for pitching, Oakland has emerged as a legitimate force. They might
be the hardest-hitting team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Don't talk to Boston about being hit hard. After the Red Sox's
surprising run last October, the city finds itself in dread about
Sports Illustrated's choice of Boston to win the World Series.
Somehow that worry is great comfort to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good,'' Clemens said. ``That's great. New century.''
</P>
<P>
   And same old Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN LEAGUE PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox have not won a World Series since 1918, the
longest streak in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   1. New YorkHey, whaddya want for 90 million bucks? Two-time
titlists have everything for another Series run.
</P>
<P>
   2. BostonCarl Everett addition puts more bite in very toothy
lineup. Can't match Yankees' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   3. TorontoGood but not quite strong enough to contend. See how
Mondesi likes it in Canada.4. Tampa BayIf home runs were gold,
these Devil Rays would dress out in bullion underwear.
</P>
<P>
   5. BaltimoreThey're old, they're slow, they're run by a buffoon,
and 3 million people show up anyway.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   1. ClevelandCan score runs in the dark but mound shortcomings
persist. One year, they'll get it right.
</P>
<P>
   2. Kansas CityLine behind Cleveland starts 30 games back. Royals
get respectable fast with bullpen help.
</P>
<P>
   3. DetroitHere's hoping Juan Gonzalez likes his new home, or
he's gone in a year, and Comerica dozes.
</P>
<P>
