<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK AT EASE  
 FASSEL WANTS SPEED  
 NO TROUBLEMAKERS  
 ETC... 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Belichick is having a glass of orange juice in a ballroom
at a luxury Florida hotel, his sips being interrupted by glances at
the sandy beach 30 feet away. The green and blue water seems to be
having a calming effect on one of the most intense head coaches in
professional football.
</P>
<P>
   These days Belichick is smiling a lot, and is friendly, even
talkative, at times. These are not images usually associated with
one of the best defensive minds in the game. It is more common to
see Belichick looking disheveled and sounding grumpy.
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly the way he looked during what was the most
chaotic time of his professional life. Remember? Bill Parcells
named Belichick the head coach of the Jets and then, fearing a new
owner might not be supportive, Belichick abruptly resigned,
eventually joining the New England Patriots. It was an awkward,
embarrassing time for both Belichick and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were chastised by the news media and fans for not
knowing what was going on inside Belichick's head. And Belichick
was portrayed as a confused goofball who showed a lack of respect
to Parcells. There were National Football League and team officials
who, after watching Belichick's bizarre news conference in which he
resigned from the Jets job, were wondering if Belichick had had
some sort of breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all is well again with the world. Belichick is trying to
rebuild the Patriots, and the Jets have Al Groh as their head
coach. Groh, in fact, said hello to Belichick at the owners'
meetings last week in Palm Beach, Fla. And believe it or not,
Parcells and the New England Patriots owner, Robert K. Kraft, once
bitter enemies, recently had a brief but friendly chat.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that all the wounds are healed from
Belichick's excellent adventure, in which he went from defensive
coordinator to head coach to unemployed to head coach again within
a span of days. In Palm Beach, when Belichick was asked about
things that did not involve the Jets, he was talkative. But
whenever the subject of the Jets came up Belichick clammed up.
Trying to get his thoughts on the subject was harder than beating
one of his vaunted defensive schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Did he have any doubts during that chaotic period that his
decision to step down was the right one?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Does he ever think about the Jets?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've moved on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few times Belichick smiled while discussing his
former team was after being asked about the trade talks involving
wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson. Belichick said that while he was
with the Jets, he was aware that the organization felt that
Johnson's contract situation would be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Then Belichick quipped, ``I don't think we'll be dealing for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has a tough job ahead of him. The Patriots are a team
in need of a personality. There are times New England plays on a
championship level, and there are times when it struggles. The team
lacks consistency.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are happy to have Belichick on their side because
for many years, when Belichick was in New York, he devised plans
that completely frustrated New England, especially quarterback Drew
Bledsoe. As Belichick has met with Patriots players, all of them
have expressed their glee about having Belichick's brainpower
supporting them instead of trying to shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization showed a lot of trust in me in bringing me to
the Patriots,'' Belichick said. ``For that I am grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants Seek Explosiveness
</P>
<P>
   Several team executives said that the Giants had been approached
by a number of teams about their 11th pick in the April draft.
Ernie Accorsi, New York's general manager, denied that. In fact
only one team has contacted the Giants, the Baltimore Ravens, who
were considering swapping their fifth pick with the Giants in
exchange for the Giants' 11th selection plus additional picks. The
Ravens later changed their mind.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, are the Giants slowly changing the way they evaluate
college draft prospects? Often the Giants have drafted players with
size and power, and not necessarily athleticism. The recent
league-wide trend has been to draft smaller, faster players who are
also great athletes.
</P>
<P>
   One Giants team official said that coach Jim Fassel had been
preaching more and more to draft speedy, athletic players, forgoing
size if necessary. Fassel, the official said, has urged the team to
change the way the Giants look at players, and go for speed. ``We
need explosion,'' Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that Fassel and Accorsi are working well
together, unlike management's relationship with former coach Dan
Reeves, who alienated just about everyone in the personnel
department. Fassel uses reason and logic to get his point across,
while Reeves often tried to bully the organization into doing
things his way by complaining publicly to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get my point across in different ways,'' Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a number of team executives said that Accorsi was
doing one of the best jobs in the league at managing the salary cap
while simultaneously acquiring talent. The Giants lost six free
agents, but have picked up some good players in return, and done so
without destroying their salary cap situation.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos Want Character
</P>
<P>
   One of the most discussed topics at last week's owners meetings
was off-field violence. Some teams have vowed to be more selective
in drafting players, staying away from those with troubled pasts.
</P>
<P>
   Denver coach Mike Shanahan said last week that the Broncos had
already removed 10 players from the draft board because of what he
called ``various problems.'' The issues ranged from having serious
conflicts with the coaching staff to drug abuse to violent behavior
off the field.
</P>
<P>
   And the Broncos owner Pat Bowlen told the owners last week to
put as much emphasis on character as teams do on talent.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Several owners say that the NFL is concerned about the
ever-increasing player salaries, particularly with the signing
bonuses. The league has even gone so far as to lecture teams
sternly to watch their spending habits.... The Jets are still
willing to listen to trade offers for Keyshawn Johnson despite the
proclamation that he is off the trading block. Look for trade
discussions to heat up again in the days leading up to the
draft....More on the draft: The Cleveland Browns, at least for now,
are not going to budge from that No. 1 overall spot, and will
probably select either the Penn State pass rusher Courtney Brown or
his teammate, linebacker Lavar Arrington. Meanwhile the hottest
draft rumor _ and at this time of year there is always lots of
draft gossip _ has Denver trying to trade up to the fourth spot to
pick Florida State wide receiver Peter Warrick....Minnesota coach
Dennis Green is interested in quarterback Bubby Brister, who was
cut by the Broncos. The interest, however, may be intended to put
pressure on Jeff George, who is hesitating to sign a one-year deal
with the Vikings....Instant replay will be back, but for how long?
Supporters don't want it to be voted on on a yearly basis, so after
this coming season, if it again works well, it might be here to
stay for a while.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
