<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-TROUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 ON OPENING DAY, FAR MORE FISHERS THAN FISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN C. SAUTNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSCOE, N.Y. _ On Saturday this otherwise sleepy hamlet at the
confluence of the Beaverkill and Willowemoc Rivers became the
Punxsutawney of the fishing world once again as scores of anglers
came out to see firsthand how the brand-new trout season might
fare.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mr. Trout must have seen his shadow, as most fishermen
went home emptyhanded, settling instead for the opportunity to
simply cast a line on an early spring day.
</P>
<P>
   The morning broke clear and downright cold with a hard frost
covering the nearby ballfield that overlooks Junction Pool, perhaps
the most famous stretch of water in American trout fishing. Dave
Daft, Richard Kress and Moira Dooley joined me as we tugged on
waders and strung up flyrods.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 a.m., 20 anglers lined much of the pool's banks. All around
us, fishers galumphed past in everything from chest-high rubber
waders to blue jeans and baseball caps. They carried an eclectic
array of rods, nets, buckets and coolers. I overheard one angler
pleading to another, ``Let's go the diner and wait till it warms
up.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a far different river from the one I had driven past a
week earlier on a scouting mission. Then, just a handful of
fishermen sat in their cars gazing almost lovingly at their
favorite spots. At Ferdon's Eddy, just downstream of the Junction,
an elderly gent stood alone behind his pickup, having what looked
like his own private tailgate party, complete with a smoky
barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Even Friday afternoon, just a few hopefuls had surveyed the
river. Two men in their mid-30s sipped on bottles of beer and
casually discussed which bait would work best on the morrow. Worms,
they decided.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, the crowd continued to build until it seemed
that half of Roscoe had converged at the Junction. Finally, a rod
bent and a 15-inch brown trout was quickly landed and released.
Another trout, not quite so lucky, wound up on a rope stringer that
held from an old stump in the river.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old Tyler Ratner from the town of Beaverkill, N.Y., did
his best to rollcast a streamer into a deep pocket where he
believed a big brown surely must be hiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summer you can catch trout here and they taste very
good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I then decided to wander up the Beaverkill and began drifting a
tandem rig of a streamer and a nymph through a promising-looking
run. By the third cast, ice had started to build in the guides of
my rod. Twenty minutes later, I retreated back to the Junction to
show Dave my woolly bugger, now frozen solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be opening day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m., the local bed-and-breakfast association began doling
out free muffins and coffee. (On opening day in Roscoe, one can eat
free virtually all day long by strategically hopscotching from one
ceremony to another.) Ten minutes later, a group of men wheeled
down a 20-foot-long wooden rainbow trout to the edge of the
Willowemoc to the delight of a local television crew. It was
definitely time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   We decided to head downriver to a spot that Richard believed
might have warmed enough to produce a hatch of caddis flies.
</P>
<P>
   As we made our way down the old highway that parallels the
river, it became suddenly apparent that except for the Junction,
the Beaverkill looked mysteriously empty. Even Cairn's Pool, which
Dave jokes should be annexed by the state of New Jersey for its
propensity to attract a permanent flotilla of Garden State fishers,
was deserted.
</P>
<P>
   We scrambled down the banks to a beautiful jade-green pool and
immediately began drifting nymphs through its lengths. The wheezy
call of a phoebe came from a grove of maples on the far bank. The
sun began to warm the air, and small caddis flies and early brown
stoneflies began fluttering off the river by the dozens. As we
expected, though, nothing came up for them in the chilly water.
Except for two common mergansers patrolling a shallow riffle
downstream, not a soul was in sight. This privacy seemed as lovely
as any trout we might have caught.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
