<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AL-AMIN-CHESTNUT0402-     04-01 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN-CHESTNUT0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    J.L. Chestnut: A mighty oak
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala. _ When his law office was on Jeff Davis Avenue, J.L.
Chestnut Jr. poured his heart _ and funnybone _ into the sign he
hung on the brick wall outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parking for Afro American only,'' the red block letters still
proclaim. ``All others will be towed.''
</P>
<P>
   The name of Selma's first black attorney _ J.L. Chestnut _ is
written inside a black double-pointed arrow at the bottom of the
sign, showing where the rule applied.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would always park his car right there, and it would
antagonize some people,'' said Lucy Hopson, whose son runs a dental
practice next door to the now-vacant building. ``He's outspoken,
and he always speaks the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   That voice _ sometimes inflammatory, never sugar-coated _ is the
one that speaks in defense of Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, accused cop
killer and 1960s radical once named H. Rap Brown.
</P>
<P>
   That voice carries through Alabama's Black Belt, named for the
dark, rich soil where sharecroppers have toiled for years planting
cotton in the middle of the state. It was here that Chestnut and
Brown met, working together to register black voters in Dallas and
Lowndes counties 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That voice has rippled on radio waves, raging against Joe
Smitherman, Selma's white mayor, in power since 1964, a year before
the ``Bloody Sunday'' march across the Edmund Pettus Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an unbridled opportunist,'' Chestnut has railed on the
air. ``He's an agent of white people. He's not our savior. He's
maintaining white supremacy.''
</P>
<P>
   THE POOR MAN'S COCHRAN
</P>
<P>
   Known to friends as Chess, Chestnut has been the poor man's
Johnnie Cochran.
</P>
<P>
   There is some doubt Chestnut will represent Al-Amin once the
case moves to Atlanta. Cochran, for one, has been mentioned as a
candidate for the job, as have top metro defense attorneys Michael
Mears and Bruce Harvey. But if Chestnut does stay with the case,
expect ``anything,'' says Smitherman, 70, Chestnut's foil since
1964. ``It's going to be a circus. Free admission, except for the
police barricades,'' Smitherman said.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-authoritarian Chestnut style already has shone through
in his defense of Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had my problems with the FBI and law enforcement types
for years,'' Chestnut, 69, said on CNBC after Al-Amin was arrested
March 20 in White Hall, Ala. Al-Amin had fled to the tiny town west
of Montgomery after allegedly fatally shooting a Fulton County
sheriff's deputy and wounding another as they tried to serve a
warrant on him in Atlanta's West End.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been practicing law in Alabama for 40 years. They shoot
at my office at least twice a year,'' Chestnut said of the FBI.
``And I've been threatened more times than a Hollywood cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   As Al-Amin left the Montgomery County jail, shackled and bound,
for court a day after his arrest, the former Black Panther
declared, ``It's a government conspiracy, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose Sanders, one of Chestnut's law partners, concedes they're
in a public relations war; half the battles will be fought openly
before trial starts.
</P>
<P>
   A SEASONED FIGHTER
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. during the Selma
protests of the 1960s, Chestnut has waged this kind of fight for
years. He has sued for black voting rights and decades later
defended charges of black voter fraud. He fought for minority
hiring at City Hall and U.S. Department of Agriculture loans for
black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is he an extraordinary trial lawyer,'' said Sanders,
whose office is adorned with a picture of Nation of Islam leader
Louis Farrakhan, ``but because he was a lawyer for Dr. King,
because he's been a part of the struggle to empower people of all
races, because he's had that experience, he is going to bring
something to that courtroom that is unique.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Chestnut is viewed with something close to
reverence, especially in Selma. Chestnut is associated with civil
rights icons such as John Lewis, Hosea Williams and Ralph David
Abernathy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, when protesters were mobilizing in the Black Belt,
whites threatened to fire their black housekeepers if they marched,
Hopson recalled. So Chestnut and other activists marched for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made us, who couldn't do anything, feel proud,'' said
Hopson, who went to Selma's black high school with Chestnut.
</P>
<P>
   Three times, Chestnut's law firm has outgrown offices on Jeff
Davis Avenue, named for the president of the Confederacy. The
largest black law firm in the state, its new home overlooks the
Alabama River not far from the Pettus Bridge, where white state
troopers and sheriff's deputies beat black voting rights
demonstrators on Bloody Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Against a wall in the lobby, water from a fountain trickles down
15 squares of tile laid three across. On a middle tile, the words
of King are etched: ``Until Justice Rolls Down Like Water.''
African paintings and pictures hang from the brick walls of the
long hallway leading to the attorneys' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done very well for himself,'' Selma City Attorney Henry
Pitts said of Chestnut. Pitts' father once represented infamous
Dallas County Sheriff Jim Clark, who led a mounted posse against
marchers on the Pettus Bridge in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very good on his feet,'' Pitts said. ``He gives most
jurors a sense of sincerity when he talks to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut is a grandstander to some, an articulate speaker who
deftly charms the media while hammering his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chess can blow a lot of wind,'' Smitherman acknowledged, ``but
he's got a lot of substance to back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Socially influential, Chestnut's law firm also has been
politically powerful.
</P>
<P>
   His law partner Hank Sanders, Rose's husband, is Selma's first
black state senator elected since Reconstruction. In 1986, they
helped form the New South Coalition. The group broke away from the
Alabama Democratic Conference, which had been the state's
traditional black political machine. They immediately challenged
ADC chief Joe Reed, a powerful black member of the state teachers'
union.SOBERING LESSONS
</P>
<P>
   Being a crusader in the 1960s took its toll on Chestnut. Alone
at times in his fight, he got sidetracked by the good times on the
``Drag,'' the cluster of nightspots in black Selma.
</P>
<P>
   He socialized for hours at a time at the clubs, where he could
get a pint of bootleg corn whisky as easily as a barbecue sandwich.
Sometimes he'd have liquor on his breath when he met with King.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got so I'd work about three days a week,'' Chestnut wrote
in his memoir. ``The rest of the time, I got drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   A favorite joint was across from the jail. Sometimes, instead of
waiting to be arrested for public drunkenness, he'd plop himself
down in a cell. In the morning, he'd wake up, see the metal bars,
then scream about his constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't arrest you,'' the jailer would say. ``The door isn't
even locked. Push it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut had once figured his ticket out of Selma was learning
the saxophone so he could play jazz clubs in Harlem. As a teenager,
he played at a graduation dance at the Selma Country Club. He saw
how some whites lived; for the first time, he saw the blue water of
a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut's father, who ran the Chestnut Brothers Market and
Grocery in Selma, warned him about whites. ``If you can help it,''
his father said, ``don't work for them. Work for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chestnut reached 12th grade, tax agents forced his father
out of business; thousands of dollars worth of meat had been
slaughtered during World War II but no tax had been collected. His
father auctioned off food, scales and freezers from the store to
pay the debt. It wasn't enough. The state garnished the wages his
mother and aunt earned as county schoolteachers.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the incidents that helped shape the conclusion
of ``Black in Selma,'' Chestnut's autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to persuade me that any white person in power wants
to be fair and work on an equal basis with black people. I assume
otherwise,'' Chestnut wrote. ``In my experience, they want you to
agree with them and let them continue to be in charge of
everything. It takes a lot for me to overcome my built-in
suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother and aunt worked overtime at a cigar factory and
borrowed money to send him to college.
</P>
<P>
   At Dillard University in New Orleans, Chestnut stirred
controversy with a class paper. He argued that black leaders taught
accommodation to their constituents instead of telling them that
blacks could hold equal positions with whites.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut concluded that the establishment wrongfully taught,
``Don't lead black America where white America doesn't want it to
go. Keep your place and work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Selma after earning his law degree at Howard
University in Washington, Chestnut learned his courtroom manner
from Peter Hall, a tenacious black trial lawyer from Birmingham.
Along with Arthur Shores, Hall tried Alabama cases for the NAACP
Legal Defense Fund. Thurgood Marshall would pick up the cases and
argue them before the U.S. Supreme Court, which he would later
join.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aggressive acts always leave the opposition trying to figure
out what to do,'' Chestnut observed. ``I began to get a reputation
as a fighter, someone not afraid of the police and judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
