<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COPS-IMAGE-ART-925     04-01 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COPS-IMAGE-ART-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC ANGER AT POLICE SEEPS INTO OFFICER'S WORK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is not the police officer who killed an unarmed
man on the West Side last month. He is not the officer who tortured
a man in a Brooklyn precinct station house three years ago. He did
not shoot a squeegee man in the Bronx, frequent a Midtown brothel,
run a drug ring from his locker or do anything else to tarnish the
badge that he keeps on a chain around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   He is Officer Eddie Vasquez, and most likely you have never
heard of him. Several days a week, he kisses his wife and two young
daughters goodbye, climbs into his 15-year-old car and joins the
thousands of other Long Island commuters who inch along highways
toward their jobs in the city. His workplace is 5.5 square miles of
Brooklyn known as the 75th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   The precinct, in East New York, is just eight miles from City
Hall, but it may as well be 800 miles. Off in the distance, the
mayor is trying to smooth over his denigrating comments about an
unarmed black man killed by a police officer; his opponent for the
U.S. Senate, who is new to New York, is questioning his
temperament; black leaders are accusing the police of
institutionalized brutality; and the police commissioner is blaming
the news media.
</P>
<P>
   But Vasquez cares less about their opinions than he does about
those of his commander. His world is a precinct that routinely
leads the borough, if not the city, in homicides, assaults and
other major crimes. He has spent his entire career there, six years
as a uniformed patrolman, the last four with a plainclothes
anticrime unit. He knows its streets and bodegas the way others
know their office halls and cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vasquez said last week, the faraway actions and reactions
of others affect him. The other day a man returned his good-morning
greeting with a curse. Some of the neighborhood children now play a
game of reaching into their pockets with eyes wide _ only to whip
out a wallet in mimicry of the last gestures of Amadou Diallo,
killed last year by four officers who thought he was reaching for a
gun. It is a game that makes his heart leap every time.
</P>
<P>
   He says he understands the outcry when an Amadou Diallo or a
Patrick Dorismond is killed by the police: the need to mourn, the
demand for respect. He does not apologize for or explain away the
actions of officers like Justin Volpe, who so brutalized Abner
Louima three years ago. But why, he asked, does Eddie Vasquez pay
the consequences? Why don't people see that he is one of the good
ones, one of the many who do a difficult and sometimes dangerous
job as best they can?
</P>
<P>
   When no answer presented itself, Vasquez returned to the
us-versus-them thoughts harbored by police officers when feeling
scorned by those they have vowed to protect. He says it time and
again, he said: You're damned if you do and damned if you don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``And unless you're a cop, you'll never understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez is only one officer, of course, in a police force of
nearly 41,000. But his feelings of being misunderstood and
unappreciated are especially acute among the rank-and-file these
days. For one thing, they believe they are underpaid. Those with 20
years of service make about $55,000; their counterparts in the more
peaceful Suffolk County, where Vasquez lives, earn about $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the hidden pressures: to hew to training in
split-second moments of life and death; to ``bend like a reed in
the wind'' when dealing with difficult people; to adapt to
sometimes contradictory policy changes and meet quotas; to block
out that scuffle from just a few hours ago and go home as though it
never happened. To shake off the same broad-brushed stigma that
police officers are so often accused of attaching to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy,'' said Eli B. Silverman, a professor at the
John Jay College of Criminal Justice and the author of ``NYPD
Battles Crime: Innovative Strategies in Policing'' (Northeastern
University Press, 1999). ``At a time when crime has gone down so
substantially, we should be in a period of rejoicing. Instead,
we're in a period of recrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene O'Donnell, a former New York police officer and prosecutor
who also teaches at John Jay College, where officers often take
classes, said that many in the police force had no day-to-day
street contact with the public. And when a case like the Dorismond
killing occurs, he said, a desk job seems like home base in a
nerve-racking game of tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``The institutional message for cops is: Who wants to be a
street cop?''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Vasquez does. He has ever since his older sister dated a
police officer back in Brooklyn, when his father worked the docks
at a sugar refinery in Red Hook and his mother kept the home nice.
The boy liked the uniform; it seemed exciting.
</P>
<P>
   He applied to the force when he was in high school, then worked
at various jobs _ video store clerk, construction worker _ until he
got the call five years later. He graduated from the Police Academy
on April 25, 1990, and six months later he was assigned to the 75th
Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   A week or two later, he said, he was pursuing a car that had
fled an area where gunfire had been heard. One of the suspects
leaned out a car window with a machine gun and began spraying
bullets in his direction. It was not until he was in bed several
hours later, after the adrenaline rush and the high-fives over guns
recovered, that he thought, ``What the hell happened to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe as a souvenir or maybe as a reminder, Vasquez has kept a
recording of the police-radio reports of that night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He is 33, burly, with a handshake that squeezes with sincerity
and a Jets baseball cap tugged over his bristly black hair. Sitting
in the booth of a diner, recalling moments from his career between
bites of a turkey sandwich, Vasquez appeared wise to the ways of
the street but not hardened by them. He shared anecdotes of the
dramatic and the mundane to make points about the job, not to
portray himself as heroic.
</P>
<P>
   One time he was sitting with colleagues in a Roy Rogers
restaurant: a child's balloon popped, he and three other officers
jumped as if reacting to gunfire, and the mother laughed. Another
time he and his partner had just ordered a pizza when reports of a
gunman in a nearby building came over their radios. They drew their
guns and ran out for what turned out to be a false report, then
returned to the pizzeria, guns holstered.
</P>
<P>
   The stunned owner asked: This is what you do?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, they said. And they ate their pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Most officers never shoot their guns, but Vasquez said he had,
twice: once at the driver of a stolen van who had struck his
partner, once to return shots fired at him in a building. Neither
time did he injure or kill. He said he had earned several
commendations, and been the subject of a couple of complaints
lodged with the Civilian Complaint Review Board, the city's
police-watchdog agency. The charges were not substantiated, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   As vexing as those complaints were, he said, ``my worst day on
the job was standing on that bridge.'' That was in 1997, when
thousands of people marched across the Brooklyn Bridge to protest
the Abner Louima case, many of them waving toilet plungers in the
air. Vasquez was assigned to crowd control at the Brooklyn end of
the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that they can't be upset,'' he said, his anger
peeking through his confused smile. ``But I don't deserve to stand
on that bridge and have people spit at me and call me names. It was
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The public anger faded for a while, then came back with the
Diallo killing in February 1999. It intensified with the acquittal
of the four officers who shot him, and now has reached a boil with
the Dorismond death last month. Throughout, Vasquez and his
colleagues have been out there, concentrating less on the politics
of it all than on spurts of crime in corners of their turf.
</P>
<P>
   Even on normal days it is a difficult job. The unit's members
are so well known on the street that it sometimes seems they might
as well wear uniforms. ``They know us,'' explained Officer Jake
O'Neill, a colleague of Vasquez. ``They got our plates, our cars,
our clothes, our faces. They see us coming and they say, `Here we
go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the moment is a gang terrorizing a certain housing
project. But whenever Vasquez and his colleagues take in suspects,
witnesses are too frightened to pick the gang members out of
lineups. The gang members leave the station house feeling that much
more invincible, Vasquez said, ``and the people are still scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the manifestations of the Giuliani
administration's quality-of-life crackdown. Vasquez did not
criticize the policy; he said it might be contributing to the drop
in crime. But he sees more people acting furtively on the
sidewalks, their hands inside bulging coats. With suspicions of a
concealed gun, he will investigate _ only to find someone hiding an
open beer can, an offense worthy of a summons.
</P>
<P>
   Take all these frustrations, add the current anti-police mood,
and there sits Vasquez, stabbing sandwich crumbs with his finger.
Yeah, you get hassled for stopping people who are riding bicycles
on the sidewalk, but you've seen the reports of armed suspects
fleeing on bicycles. Yeah, an open beer can is a minor offense, but
your training tells you it is against the law, sets a bad example
for children, and can lead to problems later on in the night. Yeah,
there are officers who are bad, racist, brutal, but you don't know
anyone in the seven-five who wouldn't answer a call of distress.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez has another anecdote, this one about a colleague. The
officer was recently wrestling on the ground with an armed man, and
in the middle of the life-and-death struggle, the officer found
himself questioning whether he was being too aggressive. Such
second-guessing in times like these is natural but wrong, Vasquez
said. ``He should have split the guy's head open.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers all have their styles, some more abrasive than others.
Vasquez said he preferred explanation. If there is a report of a
suspect that is maddeningly general _ a young black man in baggy
jeans and dark jacket _ he will stop those who roughly fit the
description, explain what is going on, treat them with the respect
they may not expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight out of ten times that works,'' he said. ``The other two
times, maybe they're having a bad day. Then it's: `Here's the man
in the blue uniform. Let him have it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lunch was over; there were warrants to check, hot spots to sit
on, gang members to bluff. And when his shift ended several hours
later, Eddie Vasquez got into his old car and melted into the Belt
Parkway traffic flowing east.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
