<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-96     04-01 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE DEFEND FATAL SHOOTING IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN and JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police commanders on Saturday defended two undercover
narcotics detectives who fired a hail of bullets at five young men
on a Brooklyn street Friday night, killing two of them, as the
group tried to rob the officers with what turned out to be a toy
pistol and a pellet gun.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives, who had what looked like three handguns placed
menacingly to their chests, heads and backs, whipped out their own
weapons and killed two of the suspects in a barrage of 23
rapid-fire shots at 9:15 p.m. Friday in Bushwick, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the robbers escaped in the confusion of whizzing
bullets and falling bodies, the police said, and when the smoke
cleared, the undercover detectives, and backup officers who had
rushed in, found beside the fatally wounded youths a toy pistol and
a pellet gun, both wrapped in black electrical tape to give them
the look of real semiautomatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings of Tysheen Bourne, 19, and Andre Fields, 17, both
of Brownsville, were still under investigation Saturday, and
details were somewhat sketchy as detectives interviewed the backup
officers and a few other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the Brooklyn district attorney, the detectives
who shot the teen-agers were not immediately questioned by
investigators. Nor were they identified publicly; the police said
their names were withheld to preserve their undercover status.
</P>
<P>
   The victims _ both troubled youths with police records _ were
the third and fourth young men killed by undercover officers in one
month, and their deaths drew mixed reactions in Bushwick and
Brownsville. Some residents, voicing concerned over aggressive
police tactics, said the detectives had overreacted, while others
defended the officers, saying they had put themselves at risk in a
high-crime area.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike recent confrontations between citizens and the police
that sent neighborhoods into angry turmoil, the reactions to the
latest shootings were relatively subdued as the realization sunk in
that the officers had acted in what they regarded as self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has emphatically supported the
police in previous shootings and usually focused negative attention
on the victims, was out of the city Saturday and had no immediate
comment, a City Hall spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Police commanders, meantime, strongly defended the shootings as
justified acts of self-defense in the face of what appeared to be
extreme danger and provocation by young men with criminal
histories, and they moved quickly to highlight the differences with
earlier shootings by undercover officers, including that of Patrick
Dorismond in Manhattan two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``These individuals pointed these weapons at the two undercover
officers and proceeded to rob one of the undercovers of his gold
chain and bracelet, and the second undercover was robbed of his
cell phone and wallet,'' Assistant Chief Joseph Esposito, the head
of the Brooklyn North Strategic and Tactical Command, said at a
news conference at Police Headquarters on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside a table on which the toy pistol and the pellet
gun were displayed alongside two deadly weapons, Esposito noted
that the assailants were black and the detectives were Hispanic. He
denied that there were any racial implications, and reconstructed
the events of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The two detectives _ officers for nine and seven years and the
subject of no civilian complaints _ are normally assigned to the
Brooklyn North narcotics squad, but were working overtime Friday as
part of Operation Condor, the citywide drug crackdown that has led
to more than 21,000 arrests this year.
</P>
<P>
   The robbery that went awry, Esposito said, took place in Cooper
Street, near Broadway, in one of the city's most dangerous areas, a
locale known for drug dealing, muggings and other crimes. Earlier
in the evening, the detectives had arrested three drug suspects at
Cooper and Broadway after watching them buy marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   After placing them in custody, the detectives, clad in jeans and
leatherlike jackets, returned to the street and were on the lookout
for drug transactions. As usual, backup officers were hiding nearby
in case of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Esposito said, five men approached, three of them
carrying what appeared to be black semiautomatic handguns. The
assailants surrounded the undercover officers, and at various times
in the brief confrontation placed the guns to the officers' chests,
heads and backs.
</P>
<P>
   One yanked a gold chain from the neck of one of the detectives,
and took a bracelet from him as well. Then the assailants demanded
the second officer's wallet, the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of producing his wallet, however, the detective drew his
.380-caliber Walther PPK semiautomatic and began firing the first
of 18 shots. His partner then drew his Smith &AMP; Wesson service
revolver and fired five rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bourne and Fields, who were both believed to have held the
gunlike objects, were hit numerous times, the police said, though
the number of bullets that struck them, the areas of the body in
which they were hit and other details were unclear pending
autopsies. No shots were fired by backup officers, who rushed up
too late to be directly involved.
</P>
<P>
   As they fell, their companions fled. Fields was pronounced dead
at the scene, while Bourne taken to Woodhull Medical Center, where
he was pronounced dead 30 minutes after the shooting. A wallet
belonging to one of the detectives, and the other's cellular phone,
were found in Bourne's possession, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police emergency units, with bloodhounds and helicopters,
searched the Bushwick area until the early morning Saturday, but no
suspects were found, and the third weapon _ or what appeared to be
a weapon _ was not recovered, the police said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One witness, Milton Vargas, 27, who had moved into an apartment
on Cooper Street on Friday, entered his building from the street
only minutes before the shootings and remembered seeing two men _
the detectives apparently _ standing outside. He was in his
apartment overlooking the scene when the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard loud gun shots,'' he recalled. ``I looked out my
window and saw their faces clearly. It was the two guys that I saw
outside standing with their guns drawn. I saw two kids lying in the
street, and there were two guns next to one of them. I told my wife
to move my daughter away from the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Another neighborhood resident, who declined to give a name,
said: ``I heard rapid-fire shots. They sounded like they were
coming from a machine gun. I came out of my house. I saw someone
running down the block. There were dozens of people running around.
I saw someone running down the block. I saw the bodies of the two
kids lying on the street. They looked like babies.''
</P>
<P>
   A neighborhood woman expressed amazement that the slain youths
had approached the undercover detectives unaware that they were
officers, and with fake guns as well. ``If they didn't know these
guys were cops, they were pretty stupid,'' she said. ``Everyone
knows who the undercover cops are in this area. We know what's
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The same woman noted that drugs, muggings and other crimes were
facts of life in her neighborhood, but there was ambivalence in her
attitude toward the police. ``This neighborhood is going
downhill,'' she said. But she added: ``My friends and family are
always being harassed by cops.
</P>
<P>
   Heriberto Perez, 27, a Bushwick resident who heard the shots
from around a corner, said he believed the police ``overreacted,''
saying that ``it was wrong that they pulled out guns on the cops,
but it was wrong that they shot to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   But other residents voiced support for the presence of
undercover officers. ``We need undercover work here,'' said Larry
Bethune, 28, who said residents were often afraid to leave their
homes at night because of drug dealing and robberies. ``I think
what they did was right. The police didn't know the gun was fake.
They did what they had to do. They might have gotten killed.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, an officer who was listening walked over, shook
Bethune's hand, and said, ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   The police were careful to contrast the latest shootings with
those of two unarmed men recently, Dorismond and Malcolm Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, an off-duty security guard, was shot on Mar. 16
outside a bar in Manhattan in a scuffle with an officer backing up
another undercover officer. Dorismond had first taken offense at
being approached and asked for drugs, and then lunged at the one
who shot him, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson was killed in a struggle with a narcotics officer on
the stairway of a Bronx building two blocks from the doorway where
Amadou Diallo was slain in a hail of 41 bullets in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The victims of the shooting Friday night were described by
acquaintances friends as troubled.
</P>
</TEXT>
