<SLUG> BC-SKATE-WORLD-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KWAN ON TOP OF WORLD AFTER HER THIRD TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, France _ Back in the warm-up room while her Russian
opponents took the ice with gold medals on their minds, Michelle
Kwan lay down, stretched and told herself: ``Michelle, you skated
the best program of your life. Whatever happens, be happy, be
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, who had skated first in the final group, had indeed
performed a marvelous free program on the last day of these world
championships.
</P>
<P>
   But because she had held back too much earlier in the week and
came into this free program in third place, Kwan had to wait,
stretch, think and hope that her rivals Mariya Butryskaya and Irina
Slutskaya would not be able to match her excellence.
</P>
<P>
   It would work out just that way. Kwan captured the gold,
Slutskaya the silver and Butryskaya the bronze. And as Kwan left
the calm of the warm-up room and shared the medal podium with the
Russians after winning the title, a tear slid slowly down her left
cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a very emotional person, and I think I must
have cried 5,000 times,'' she said. ``But I think it was more
satisfaction and a feeling of, this may not happen again. This
moment, you have to cherish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her free skating program had been a blend of eye-catching
technical difficulty and fluid moves set to a subdued, complex
piece of music that never had the French fans clapping along with
her until the final strains had faded away and the broadest of
grins had spread across Kwan's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's learned more and more that you can't hold back
and achieve anything,'' her coach, Frank Carroll, would say later.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan is fortunate in a way. Many champions in sport dominate and
then fade steadily from prominence. But at only 19, she has had
ample occasions to understand the ephemeral nature of a gold medal:
winning her first world title in 1996, losing in 1997, winning
again in 1998 and losing again last year in Helsinki, Finland, when
Butryskaya became the oldest women's champion in history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, less than a year after leaving the familiar cocoon of her
training center in Lake Arrowhead, Calif., and enrolling at UCLA,
she is back on top again. ``What happened to the odd years?'' Kwan
said Saturday with a laugh before putting this title, her most
unexpected title, in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the most satisfying championship for me,'' she
said. ``There was a lot of pressure from outside: `You've got to do
triple-triple; got to do this; got to up the ante.' And I was able
to work after nationals with Frank for six straight weeks making
the programs more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Carroll, Kwan has never performed two more
technically demanding programs back-to-back. In her short program
on Friday, she inserted a triple flip in place of a triple toe loop
and had only a slight bobble on one of her landings.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, she landed six triple jumps very cleanly in the
first two minutes of her free program and finished with a total of
seven, including a triple toe-triple toe combination which turned
out to be the only clean triple-triple combination of the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   To win the world title was reward for a regimen in which Kwan
had scaled back on training in the fall, but shifted the balance
back toward skating in the winter, when she moved out of the dorm
and took fewer classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been completely different for me,'' Kwan said.
``It's been a lot of fun. The first quarter at school was hard. I
had a full load and competitions coming up. I didn't skate as much
as I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   A thrilled Kwan added, ``It's looking good for 2002!'' after
becoming the first American since Peggy Fleming's consecutive
victories from 1966 to 1968 to take three world titles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think it was the most satisfying competition for me. I
skated the best program of my life. People kept saying, `She's got
to do a triple-triple,' and I really focused on them after the
nationals,'' said Kwan, who struggled to hold on to her national
title and fell during a triple-toe jump last month in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan had six triples and two back-to-back for the first time in
her competitive career to earn the top votes of seven of the nine
judges with marks that ranged from 5.6 to 5.8 for technical
difficulty and a string of 5.8s and 5.9s for presentation.
</P>
</TEXT>
