<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORS OPEN ARMS TO NEW GROUP HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By COREY KILGANNON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Saturday on Glebe Avenue, a sunny residential
street in the Bronx, the scene at first glance resembled the first
day of college.
</P>
<P>
   Parents helped their children carry golf clubs, stereos and
piano keyboards into new rooms. Smiling staff members standing in
front of balloons and a ``Welcome'' sign greeted and introduced new
roommates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the newcomers were indeed moving away from home for the
first time, but most were in their 30s and 40s and their parents
were mostly elderly.
</P>
<P>
   These were mildly retarded adults moving into the Glebe Avenue
Residence, a group home that opened Saturday in Castle Hill, a
working-class neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss my dad,'' said Lee Jarvis, 35, as he put his
arm around his father, Lee Williams, 79. Williams had bypass
surgery twice last year and is feeling less able to give his son
the daily support he has always needed living in their Harlem
apartment, where he has spent his entire life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife, Lee's mother, died a few years ago, and I'm living
day to day healthwise now,'' Williams said. ``Now at least I know
he's safe here if anything happens to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis met his roommate, Freddy Allen, 40, who was also moving
away for the first time from his home in the Bronx. Allen's mother,
Carole Allen, 61, helped him unpack the neatly folded shirts he had
brought with him.
</P>
<P>
   Outside on the street, residents greeted their new neighbors.
Margaret Strapac and Mary Proscio, who have both lived on the block
for 50 years, stood across the street from the newly renovated
three-story home and watched residents unpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great they're moving in,'' Strapac said. ``We
were afraid we were going to have drug addicts moving in.''
</P>
<P>
   The home is run by the YAI/National Institute for People with
Disabilities, which operates 80 group homes in the metropolitan
region. A year ago, YAI planned to buy two attached houses on
Zulette Avenue in the nearby East Tremont area to use as
assisted-living homes for retarded adults.
</P>
<P>
   Since state law requires that such proposals receive community
approval, the organization submitted its plan to Community Board
10. But many residents near the proposed site complained that there
were already several group homes in the area and voiced their
opposition through petitions and at several raucous meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Then some members of the community board suggested two other
sites, one on East Tremont Avenue, where YAI will open a group home
later this year, and the other a vacant house on Glebe Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time I've ever heard of this happening
successfully,'' said James Vacca, the community board's district
manager. ``So often, when a community suggests alternate sites, it
really means somewhere out in the wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the alternate sites were in similar neighborhoods. At
the Glebe Avenue location, many of the neighborhood residents
signed a petition circulated by a Board 10 member welcoming the
facility.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This was not a `not in my back yard' issue for the original
site,'' said State Sen. Guy Velella, who represents the area. ``It
was simply not appropriate to further saturate that area.''
</P>
<P>
   Community Board 10 includes mostly low-crime, middle-class
neighborhoods in the northeast Bronx. The board district has 40
adult group homes for the disabled, the most by far of any district
in the Bronx, Vacca said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many desirable areas that nonprofits want to move
into,'' he said. ``Yes, there should be a proportionality
borough-wide, but still, we can't just say no to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Glebe Avenue home has several staff members who try to keep
the eight residents on a normal working schedule on weekdays, and
in counseling and organized recreation activities in the evenings
and at weekends. Most of YAI's clients need some daily support and
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly $60,000 annual cost of keeping a resident in a home
is largely financed through the Medicaid allowance for each
resident.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly parents of mentally retarded children are concerned that
there will be no one to care for their children after they die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these people really waited for a long time to get into
these homes,'' said Thomas A. Dern, YAI's associate executive
director. ``You have elderly parents so frantic that they make
suicide pacts, where the child agrees to die if the parent dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among elderly parents who take care of their retarded
children, I often hear, `I hope my child will die before I do.'
It's a terrible position to be in to feel that at least I can die
easy knowing my child won't end up in the street or dying because
of neglect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
