<HEADLINE>
IN CHICAGO, TWO BETS ON AN AREA'S REVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (jw) 
 By ROBERT SHAROFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The first new market-rate housing to be built in many
decades is raising hopes that South Shore, a faded jewel of a
neighborhood on the South Side of Chicago, is due for a revival.
</P>
<P>
   The area, about 20 blocks south of the University of Chicago's
Hyde Park campus and about seven miles south of the Loop, the
downtown business district, has a lot going for it: access to Lake
Michigan; grand, historic architecture; and housing values that
have remained stable, if depressed, for many years.
</P>
<P>
   South Shore came into being in the late 1890s in the wake of the
1893 Columbian Exposition in nearby Jackson Park. The crown jewel
of the neighborhood is the former South Shore Country Club, a
65-acre lakefront property that includes a beach, golf course,
tennis courts, a riding arena and an imposing Mediterranean-style
palazzo of a clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The clubhouse, which is on the National Register of Historic
Places, was designed in 1916 by the Chicago firm of Marshall &AMP; Fox,
which also designed the Drake Hotel downtown as well as some of the
most exclusive apartment buildings on Lake Shore Drive. The
highlight is a much-photographed ballroom _ ``an enormous glass box
with a Wedgwood lid'' is how the ``A.I.A. Guide to Chicago''
describes it _ that remains popular for weddings and parties.
</P>
<P>
   The entire country club was brought by the city in 1973 and now
serves as a cultural and recreational area. The neighborhood is
bounded, roughly, by 67th Street on the north, 79th Street on the
south, Stony Island Avenue on the west and the lake on the east.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, South Shore also had one of the largest and most
elegant commercial districts in the city, which was concentrated
around the neighborhood's main thoroughfare, 71st Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were lots of boutiques and chic salons, and I remember
having to dress up in lace socks and patent-leather shoes to go
shopping there,'' said Leslie Hairston, a neighborhood resident for
more than 30 years and now alderman for South Shore.
</P>
<P>
   No one would describe the street as elegant today. The little
retailing that remains consists primarily of fast-food restaurants
and convenience and liquor stores.
</P>
<P>
   For much of its history, South Shore was known as a largely
Jewish and Irish neighborhood. In the 1960s it underwent a change
as, in the wake of a 1948 Supreme Court ruling that had struck down
the city's restrictive housing covenants, more and more black
residents moved into areas of Chicago that had long been denied to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the neighborhood is home to some of the most prominent
black Chicagoans, including the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Shore never really fell into the disinvestment cycle
that happened in other neighborhoods that underwent a racial
change,'' said Helen Dunlap, the president of South Shore Advisory
Services, a division of South Shore Bank. ``The neighborhood is 90
percent African-American, but that doesn't mean poor. According to
our research, there are 8,500 college graduates living in the area
and over 5,000 households with incomes of $50,000 or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Two things kept South Shore going, longtime residents say: Its
housing stock, much of which is excellent, and the efforts of South
Shore Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a number of a notable lakefront apartment
buildings, there is a three-street neighborhood within a
neighborhood called Jackson Park Highlands that has some of the
most palatial prewar mansions in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The houses and apartments are second to none in Chicago in
terms of aesthetics and the quality of the buildings,'' said
William Trammell, a Coldwell Banker broker.
</P>
<P>
   The South Shore Bank was taken over by Milton Davis and three
other investors in 1974 and given the mission of stabilizing the
area and encouraging new investment in the wake of the racial
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the real estate and financial interests in the city
had decided that South Shore was headed for abandonment and
demolition,'' said Davis, chairman of the bank and a longtime
resident. ``We thought the area had a lot of assets and advantages
that were not being acknowledged. Our goal was to give residents
the resources to rebuild the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, that goal has been met. Over the years, the
bank, with assets of $900 million, has written thousands of
mortgages in South Shore and is by far the main residential
mortgage broker in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Through an affiliate, the Shorebank Development Corp., it has
also built about 5,000 rental apartments _ some of them subsidized
_ in South Shore and Austin, another depressed neighborhood on the
city's west side. But it has steered clear of market-rate housing
because, until now, the neighborhood could not support it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Shorebank is betting that the boom in city living that has
revitalized many older neighborhoods in the last decade has reached
South Shore. The development company recently broke ground on
Lakeshore Pointe, with 87 town houses and condominiums at 71st
Street and South Shore Drive, across the street from the old South
Shore Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The $15 million project was designed by FitzGerald &AMP; Associates,
a leading residential architecture firm in Chicago, and is the
first extensive middle- to upper-income housing development for
sale in the neighborhood since World War II. Units are priced from
$145,000 to $350,000, and 31 have already been sold. If all goes as
planned, the first residents will move in this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, we're leading the market in terms of
price,'' said Cindy Holler, a vice president of Shorebank
Development. ``But I also don't think there's any question that
we'll get it. The early sales prove that.''
</P>
<P>
   The buyers at Lakeshore Pointe are a mix of young professionals
and families, and about half already live in South Shore.
</P>
<P>
   One who does not is Robert Brown, a college administrator who
now lives in Lincoln Park, the prominent lakefront neighborhood on
the North Side.
</P>
<P>
   So why is he moving to South Shore? ``The housing stock is
awfully nice,'' he said. ``And I really like that the cultural
center and golf course are right across the street. It's also a
very good deal. I just see all kinds of really neat possibilities.
I think South Shore is on its way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakeshore Point has already spurred further development in South
Shore. Just across the street is a neo-Gothic 1923 apartment
building that is being renovated into 76 condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   The developer of the block-long project, called the Park Waters,
is the the Poter Construction and Development Co. of Chicago, which
is spending about $6 million on the renovation, expected to be
finished next year. Apartment prices will range from $79,000 for
one bedroom to the low $200,000s for three bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real estate market is hot right now, and South Shore is
positioned to be a low-cost alternative to Hyde Park,'' said Gary
Poter, the company's owner. ``We've also had a lot of interest from
young people who grew up in South Shore and then moved to other
parts of the city. They'd like to return, but up until now there
hasn't been any new housing to speak of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
