<HEADER>
A4387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-COOPS-REAL-4TAKES-     04-01 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COOPS-REAL-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ALL OF NEW YORK, HIGH GOES HIGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No getting away from it: Everywhere in New York City
home prices keep climbing _ from the rarefied heights of Manhattan
where 11 apartments have sold for $10 million or more so far this
year, compared with just six in all of 1999, to every single ZIP
code area in the city's other boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   A studio apartment in Manhattan costs 31 percent more than it
did only a year ago, one survey says; a one-bedroom, 29 percent
more. A family's income now needs to exceed $100,000 to cover the
costs of a well-kept brownstone in Harlem, according to the
president of the neighborhood's real estate board.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a one-bedroom condominium in Astoria, Queens, which
was $95,000 in 1998, climbed to $120,000 in '99. And a detached
colonial in Forest Hills that sold for $267,000 in 1996 went for _
``Are you ready?'' the broker said _ $417,000 last year. Even in
struggling East New York, Brooklyn, the average price for a
single-family house rose 8.4 percent in 1999, from $140,789 to
$152,585.
</P>
<P>
   One family tried to get away, however briefly, from this frantic
house-buying scene, said Susan Goldy, the president of the Bronx
brokerage company that bears her name, and it cost them their dream
house.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled into a hillside in Riverdale, the Mediterranean-style
three-bedroom with a terrace and sunken living room had been
snatched up _ verbally _ for $515,000. ``Then the couple went on
vacation,'' Goldy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came back a week later, and there were three offers
beyond theirs,'' she said, ``and now the house is selling at
$565,000'' _ a $50,000 leap in only two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last people, the ones accepted at $565,000, told the
seller that they were going on vacation,'' Goldy said. ``He, in
turn, told them they had to sign the contract, have everything
done, before they left or no deal.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's a good thing, Goldy said, ``because there are now other
interested parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, so many interested parties _ particularly in buyer-maddening
Manhattan _ are bidding with abandon. ``The bidding is where the
rubber meets the road, a hint of where we're going,'' said Barbara
Corcoran, the chairwoman of Corcoran Group. ``We have dozens of
buyers for every good apartment and a half dozen for every one
that's not so good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months ago,'' Corcoran said, ``our average overbid was 8
percent, meaning the offer over asking price. Since January, that
has jumped to 14 percent. To me, overbids tell more of the story
than the sales prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Henckels doesn't quite know what tale is being told by the
prices in his stratospheric market niche. Henckels is the director
of Stribling Private Brokerage, specializing in homes selling for
at least $3 million, ``but given the increases of the last three
years,'' he said, ``we're probably going to have to double that.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially puzzling is a sudden burst of ionospheric activity.
``All of last year, there were six prewar co-ops in Manhattan that
closed at $10 million or above,'' Henckels said. ``Now, in the
first three months of 2000 there have been 11,'' the highest about
$35 million for the 17,000-square-foot apartment at 740 Park Ave.
once owned by John D. Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' Henckels said when asked why there is suddenly so
much rare-air movement. ``This very high end of the market is
usually conservative, even though the expenditure is a relative
pittance to them. When this group buys, they seem to do it en
masse, as if they'd gotten on the phone the night before and said,
`Let's go shopping tomorrow.' I've watched this for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But even for regular folks, housing costs keep climbing. For the
second straight year, according to the repeat-sales survey
conducted by Case Shiller Weiss, a real estate statistics company,
prices appreciated last year in every one of the 130 ZIP code areas
in Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx and Staten Island (the survey does
not include Manhattan). In 1997, by comparison, 14 areas saw prices
drop, and in 1996 the number was 30.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's house-price picture is not all that different
from that of the nation and the rest of the region, except for one
significant aspect. In 1999, for the fourth straight year, the
national median price for an existing single-family home set a
record, rising to $133,300 from $128,400 in 1998. In the region,
the median price hit $208,000 last year, up from $187,400 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, said Rae Rosen, the senior regional economist
for the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, is that, even more than
its suburbs, the city is ``pretty much landlocked, so we're bidding
up a fixed supply.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, with the economy in its 109th month of
expansion (the longest in history), with the stock market pumping
out bonuses and dividends and with consumer confidence strong,
buyers are out in force.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, more and more of them are out there because more
people are working. ``The job picture in New York City has been
exceptionally strong in recent years,'' said John Weiting, the
regional commissioner of the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics,
``and in 1999 employment in the city's private sector gained more
momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   The city added 81,000 private-sector jobs during 1999, raising
the total to 3.1 million. ``The 1999 increase topped the 76,000
gain in 1998,'' Weiting said, ``with the number of jobs added the
largest for any year in nearly half a century.'' Between 1989 and
1992, during a deep downturn, the city lost 321,000 private-sector
jobs. But by last December, the unemployment rate was 6 percent,
down from 7.6 percent the year before and down from 11.3 percent in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Rising mortgage rates might be expected to take some of the
house-buying steam out of that expanding work force, and financing
costs have certainly risen recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at about four-year highs for the standard 30-year,
fixed-rate mortgage, hovering near 8.3 percent,'' said Keith
Gumbinger, vice president of HSH Associates, a mortgage statistics
company in Butler, N.J. ``But as you might expect, a steady rise in
fixed rates has given resurgence to adjustable-rate mortgages,''
which offer a lower-cost alternative to traditional fixed-rate
financing, at least for a time _ usually three, five, seven or 10
years _ before they are adjusted downward, with any luck, but quite
possibly up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some 30 percent of mortgages being originated right now have
some form of adjustable rate, up sharply from 10 percent in January
'99,'' Gumbinger said. ``And part of the reason home sales have
done so well is because there are these alternatives to rising
fixed rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the reason, in Corcoran's view, is that the
rising rates ``have only added fuel to the fire and increased the
urgency to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are asking, `If not now, when will I buy?''' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All of which leaves Rosen of the Federal Reserve optimistic
about the city's housing prospects. ``You know what's exciting?''
she said. ``Twenty years ago, it used to be that 96th Street in
Manhattan was sort of a cut-off, and now you can keep going, and
the health of the area is clear for almost another 30 blocks.
Storefronts are no longer closed up. There are new window frames
all over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go right outside Forest Hills in Queens, it looks like
a mini-United Nations,'' Rosen continued. ``It's astounding how
various groups have migrated to the United States and invigorated
communities. There's a similar robust Russian community that has
created million-dollar homes in parts of Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Schill, the director of the Center for Real Estate and
Urban Policy at the New York University School of Law, is a little
less sanguine. Given recently released data from the city's 1999
Housing and Vacancy Survey, he said, ``one might be surprised by
the rapid increase in prices over the past few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows that between 1996 and 1999 the rate of increase
for the city's housing supply outpaced population growth. Over
those three years, housing units rose by 1.5 percent while the
city's population went up 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet, despite the fact that housing supply was increasing
faster than population, vacancy rates actually declined,'' Schill
pointed out, from 4.01 percent in 1996 to 3.19 percent in 1999.
Five percent is the statutory benchmark for declaring a housing
emergency, allowing rent regulations to be continued.
</P>
<P>
   There has been considerable increase in residential
construction. In 1999, building permits for 12,421 housing units
were issued, according to the Department of City Planning, a 19.6
percent increase over the 10,387 units authorized in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Schill offers several reasons why the housing crunch has
continued, even though construction outpaced population growth.
Pointing out that between 1996 and 1999, the city's median
household income rose by 11.5 percent, from $29,600 to $33,000, he
said: ``First, families were able to pay more for housing and,
therefore, bid up sales prices and rents. Second, households that
were doubled up with friends and relatives are now be able to move
into their own homes.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Census Bureau may be underestimating
population growth. ``This seems likely,'' Schill said, ``given that
we are experiencing extremely high levels of immigration, a
substantial portion of which is probably illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Other causes for the crunch: Most of the new construction is
luxury rental apartments, not co-ops or condominiums, and
conversions of existing buildings to co-ops and condominiums are,
at best, rare.
</P>
<P>
   All of which pushes up prices.
</P>
<P>
   Divining real estate trends by the numbers is, at best, a murky
exercise. To begin with, co-op sales are not officially recorded
because, technically, they are securities transactions involving
the selling of shares, and not transfers of title. Condominium
sales, however, are officially recorded. As a result, brokerage
houses and appraisal concerns that do studies of co-op data do not
claim to include all transactions in the market.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some market surveys report average prices,
while others use a median _ meaning half the prices are above that
figure and half below. Still, the numbers, along with anecdotal
impressions, can serve as barometers of market patterns.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, the median price for all residential sales _
combining co-op and condominium transfers _ from the Battery north
to West 116th Street and East 96th Street was $320,000 in 1999, up
14.3 percent from $280,000 in 1998, according to Jonathan Miller,
the president of Miller Samuel, the appraisal company that prepares
perhaps the most comprehensive sales survey, the Douglas Elliman
Manhattan Market Report. The number of sales for the same area of
Manhattan was 8,154, up 8.1 percent from the 7,542 transactions in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   For studios, the Elliman report said, the median price was
$136,000, up 12.4 percent from $121,000 in 1998. For one-bedrooms,
it was $260,000, up 10.6 percent from $235,000. The median for
two-bedrooms was $595,000, up 9.2 percent from $545,000; for
three-bedrooms, $1,595,000, up 25.1 percent from $1,275,000. And
for four or more bedrooms, it was $3.4 million, up 13.1 percent
from $3,006,145.
</P>
<P>
   The Real Estate Board of New York offers a localized assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The median price for prewar apartments on the East Side, between
42nd and 96th streets was $632,500, up 7 percent from $592,500 in
1998. For postwar apartments on the East Side, the median was
$350,000, up 40 percent from $250,000. On the West Side, from 42nd
Street to 110th Street, prewar apartments sold for a median of
$432,500, up 31 percent from 1998, when it was $329,000; and for
postwar apartments it was $316,000, up 36 percent from $232,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Heym, the chief economist for the real estate board,
explained that according to the board's guidelines, a studio
usually contains one to two and a half rooms with, perhaps, a
separate kitchen and an alcove. One-bedrooms run from two and a
half to four rooms with a living room, a kitchen and, perhaps, a
dining area. Two-bedrooms run from four to seven rooms;
three-bedrooms from five and a half to 10 rooms including, perhaps,
a maid's room and a library, and four-bedroom apartments contain 11
or more rooms.
</P>
<P>
   For everything south of 42nd Street, prewar and postwar
combined, Heym said, the median price was $264,500, up 30 percent
from the 1998 figure of $202,800.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly a seller's market. ``There's one thing holding
people back when you talk to them,'' Heym said. ``They say, `I'd
love to sell, but then where am I going to go?'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Miller pointed out that the overall numbers _ that 14.3 percent
rise for all co-ops and condos _ may be misleading. ``Because the
economy is so good, due to Wall Street, Silicon Alley and the
entertainment sectors, there's a lot of entry-level younger buyers
moving into the market,'' he said. Those buyers tend toward studios
and one-bedroom apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because so many more smaller apartments are transferring,''
Miller said, ``they pull the overall prices down so that a reader
of the statistics may not fully appreciate how much prices have
actually increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran appreciates it. ``We had, last week, a large
two-bedroom on Fifth Avenue that every broker agreed was grossly
overpriced,'' she said. ``It was overbid by three buyers, 33
percent over asking, from $1.8 million up to $2.4 million.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was stunned,'' Corcoran said, ``including the
hard-to-shock seller.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Halstead, the founder of Halstead Property Co., tried to
put it in perspective. ``Take a Park Avenue building in the high
80s, a distinguished prewar where there are numerous six-room
apartments,'' he said. ``Classic Sixes'' are considered the
prototypical family apartments in Manhattan: living room, dining
room, kitchen, two bedrooms and a maid's room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our records show that four sales of this six-room type in 1990
averaged $606,000,'' Halstead said, ``and in 1999, four more sold _
not the same ones _ for an average of $1,320,000. That's a 120
percent increase.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The hue and cry of the cocktail party circuit is that
apartment prices have gone berserk,'' Halstead said. ``But compare
that 120 percent to financial assets, like the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500, which went up 400 percent over the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Heiberger is the president of Citi Habitats, which
focuses on the expanding downtown market. ``My average number of
calls for people willing to spend $1 million or more has doubled,
to two a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tight rental market is driving up sales prices, Heiberger
said, as is ``the fact that many proposed conversions from
commercial to residential were canceled because the commercial
market went so crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Citi Habitat sales, the median price for a studio
below 14th Street was $165,000 last year, compared with $135,000 in
1998, a 22.2 percent increase. For one-bedrooms, it was $260,000,
up 20.9 percent from $215,000. Two-bedrooms climbed to $462,000, up
21.9 percent from $380,000. And three-bedrooms were $720,000, up
9.1 percent from $660,000.
</P>
<P>
   The upper uptown market is getting pricey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just this winter,'' said R. Kenyatta Punter, the president of
the Greater Harlem Board of Realtors, ``a one-family, three-story
brownstone at 416 Convent sold for $660,000.'' In 1998, it would
have sold for $600,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other than in dilapidated buildings requiring renovation or
government-subsidized new construction, ``it's becoming
increasingly difficult for persons making $50,000 to $70,000 to
find home-ownership opportunities in the Harlem community,'' Punter
said. ``Your income really has to exceed $100,000 in order to make
the kind of purchase I cited.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no central source for price data, by the dollar, for
Brooklyn. But by another measure of the market, the Case Shiller
Weiss repeat-sales index, the direction is clear: every one of the
borough's 36 ZIP code areas saw prices rise last year.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is based on a table showing the average price for all
single-family homes sold by ZIP code area, year by year. To
determine price fluctuations in 1999, the survey took the purchase
price of each home sold in each ZIP code area during the year,
compared it to the price the house brought the last time it sold,
and then, using the annual index, adjusted the earlier price to
what it likely would have been had it sold in 1998. The 1999 prices
for homes within each ZIP code area were then compared with the
estimated 1998 prices to compute the change.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 36 Brooklyn areas, one increased by up to 4 percent, 34
by 4 percent to 8 percent and one _ Bay Ridge _ by 8 percent to 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the rise was universal over all the areas that we deal
with,'' said Christopher Thomas, William B. May Co.'s senior vice
president for Brooklyn, ``there are certain areas with houses at
the lower end of our price spectrum that rose higher than those in
more established communities.'' Thomas' company specializes in the
more affluent areas of the borough, like Brooklyn Heights, with
neighborhoods like Fort Greene at that lower end of the company's
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where in late '98 a four-story town house in Fort Greene was
selling for $635,000,'' Thomas said, ``there's one currently in
contract for $850,000.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn Heights, a year ago, he said, at least half a dozen
brownstones were listed for under $2 million, while now all but two
are listed between $2 million and $3 million. ``Last year, you
could still buy one-bedroom apartments in the $150,000 to $200,000
range; now they go for closer to $300,000,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn's less affluent communities are also appreciating.
Jacob Shayovitz, a certified appraiser and the president of the
Brooklyn Board of Realtors, cited one section of East New York
where the average price last year was $140,789, up 8.4 percent from
$152,586. ``It shows that people are taking more pride in home
ownership, maintaining them better,'' Shayovitz said. In one area
of middle-income Midwood, he said, ``homes sold for an average of
$299,231 in 1998; in 1999, for $301,729.''
</P>
<P>
   In Queens, according to the Long Island Board of Realtors, which
covers the borough, the median price in December was $190,000, up
2.7 percent from $185,000 in 1998. And according to the Case
Shiller survey, 13 of the borough's 57 ZIP code areas experienced
increases up to 4 percent, 24 by 4 percent to 8 percent, 18 by 8
percent to 12 percent and two _ Fresh Meadows and Howard Beach _ by
12 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Frechter, the president of Glenjay Realty in Forest
Hills, said she sold a three-bedroom detached colonial between
Austin Street and Queens Boulevard for $267,000 at the end of 1996,
``and in '99 it sold for _ are you ready? _ $417,500.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The same person we sold that house for bought in Cord Meyer,
the north side of Queens Boulevard where there are large, beautiful
homes,'' Frechter said. ``That house had five bedrooms, a kind of
custom-built split, and it sold for $550,000.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A two-bedroom co-op on Queens Boulevard that sold for $85,000 in
1998, she said, ``would now be $95,000 to $100,000, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   In Astoria, ``because it's so close to the city,'' Frechter
said, a one-bedroom condominium that sold for $85,000 to $95,000 a
year ago ``is now selling for $120,000.''
</P>
<P>
   And a three-family, semidetached house in Astoria that sold for
$270,000 in 1998 ``went for $370,000 in '99,'' Frechter said, a
whopping 37 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics kept by the Bronx Board of Realtors are
incomplete. But the Case Shiller report indicated that all 25 of
the borough's ZIP code areas saw prices increase: one by up to 4
percent, 23 by 4 percent to 8 percent and one _ Throgs Neck _ by 8
percent to 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One broker, Haniff Baksh, the vice president of ERA Besmatch,
conducted his own survey, based on deed transfers recorded by the
Department of Buildings. For Throgs Neck, Pelham Parkway and
Mosholu in the northeast Bronx, 1999 prices averaged $180,000 for a
one-family home and $230,000 for a two-family.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '98, those numbers were slightly less, about $170,000 for a
one-family and $220,000 for a two-family,'' Baksh said. In the
once-desolate South Bronx, single-family homes now average
$150,000, compared with about $135,000 a year ago, Baksh said,
while two-family homes average $200,000, up 10 percent from
$180,000 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of investor activity helping to revitalize these
areas,'' he said. ``There's some subsidized housing, of course, but
that's not the bulk of it; this is private activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldy, the broker in Riverdale, cited rapid-fire price rises in
her neighborhood. ``We closed on a combination apartment _ two
one-bedrooms _ in July at $250,000,'' she said. ``And the very same
apartment, for unusual reasons, came back on the market in January
and sold for $275,000.''
</P>
<P>
   A one-bedroom co-op on Kappock Street sold for $50,000 in
December 1998, she said, ``and we closed on another one-bedroom in
the same building in January 2000 for $74,000.''
</P>
<P>
   On Staten Island, said Sandy Krueger, the executive vice
president of the borough's Board of Realtors, the median price for
single-family homes was $177,000 in 1999, a 7.3 percent increase
over 1998's $165,000. For two-family homes, it was $250,000, up
14.7 percent from $218,000. And for condominiums and co-ops, the
median was $107,000, an 18.9 percent jump from $90,000. According
to Case Shiller, all 12 ZIP code areas on Staten Island saw prices
increase by 4 percent to 8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Getting site-specific, Krueger said that ``in West Brighton, on
the north shore, the median for single-family homes was $151,500,''
a 25.2 percent increase over $121,000. For two-families, it was
$159,900, 10.3 percent over 1998's $145,000.
</P>
<P>
   For Heartland Village, in mid-island, the single-family median
was $202,000, 12.2 percent over $180,000; and for two-families, it
was $279,900, a 14.2 percent increase over $245,000 in 1998. And in
Huguenot, on the south shore, the median for single-family homes
hit $355,000, up 8.7 percent over $326,500 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas of William B. May in Brooklyn proffered perhaps the only
sure-fire solution for price-battered buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple selling a co-op in Brooklyn Heights who signed
a contract to purchase a town house in Prospect-Lefferts for
$325,000,'' Thomas said. ``The house closing took longer than
expected because they had to sell their co-op.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they didn't go through with the deal they would forfeit
their 10 percent deposit,'' he said. ``Then, coincidentally, during
that delay, they inherited a house in Westchester.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though they were not going to live in the Prospect-Lefferts
house, the couple decided to go through with the deal, and then put
it on the market. ``We sold it immediately for $375,000 _ a $50,000
profit,'' Thomas said. ``It just indicates the degree to which the
market rose over just that four-month period.''
</P>
<P>
   A postscript: The couple had bought their Brooklyn Heights co-op
in 1996 for $120,000. They sold it for $320,000. ``They made out
pretty well,'' Thomas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
