<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING IS STILL SHOOTING, AGAINST THE LAKERS AND TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ At times, the game clock has been
cruel to Patrick Ewing. In a career of last-second shots, the
basket has seemed covered in cellophane.
</P>
<P>
   At times, his body clock has turned against him. As he closes
his 15th year with the Knicks, his injuries have become more career
threatening and each recovery less definite.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the tick-tock is audible to everyone but Ewing these
days. On the Knicks' current trip, he came up with two game-saving
plays against Portland last Sunday and two more to calm the team's
nerves in Vancouver on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling as fit as he has in years, Ewing coolly delivered two
free throws and a runner in the final minute at General Motors
Place to turn a shaky one-point lead by the Knicks into a 89-83
escape.
</P>
<P>
   With each time he comes through, a mood that once resembled
storm clouds this season grows a shade lighter. He's doing his
favorite thing: proving everyone wrong. In keeping with his
stubborn spirit, only Ewing would think he could match the Lakers'
Shaquille O'Neal on Sunday in Los Angeles after failing miserably
just two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're prepared,'' Ewing said. ``I know I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago in a 92-87 loss to the Lakers at home, Ewing's
pride seemed to get the best of him. Shying away from driving
inside on the Lakers' mammoth center and taking mostly jumpers,
Ewing launched 20 shots _ and only made six_ while O'Neal gushed
for 43 points at Madison Square Garden. On Sunday, the unabashed
Ewing may take 20 more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he scores, yeah, I'm going to come back and try to score,''
Ewing said. ``If my play is called, I'm going to try to score.
That's the way it's always been.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lot has changed this year. On some nights, the Knicks do
go back in time and lean on Ewing to bail them out. But most of the
time, if Ewing has an off night, there is Marcus Camby, Latrell
Sprewell or Allan Houston to carry on. In tight games, though,
Ewing continues to demand the ball even if it's not always a
popular concept within the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we win, I think everyone will bite their tongue,''
one teammate said. ``Hey, Pat's been big in a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, it was hard to fathom Ewing playing such a
high-profile role on the team. The Knicks were moving on without
him as he recovered from injury.
</P>
<P>
   During training camp, he allowed his thoughts to drift to
retirement. As the season began, he dropped hints about finishing
his career in Miami. Friday night, he left open the possibility
that he will be a Knick after his current deal expires in the
summer of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens, happens,'' Ewing said. ``Honestly, I'm not
worried about it right now. I'm just having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked what he would do if the Knicks approached him
about a contract extension this summer, Ewing referred to his
agent, David Falk. ``I would tell them, `Talk to David,''' Ewing
said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Even if his career in New York is prolonged, the window for
Ewing to win a title is shrinking to the size of a porthole.
</P>
<P>
   If Ewing does get another shot, the ominous Lakers could be
standing in his way. That's why the Knicks want to show O'Neal and
company they can pose a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we capable of beating them?'' said the Madison Square
Garden president Dave Checketts, who joined the team during their
road trip. ``I'd like to think so in a seven-game series.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the NBA finals, though. Not yet. But the way Ewing's
bravado has returned to its familiar levels, it's hard to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big game,'' Ewing said. ``They're the best team in the
league. Hopefully, we'll meet them in the finals. We need to let
them know we're capable of beating them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ewing will admit he will need help in defending O'Neal. The
last time the Knicks played him, they allowed O'Neal to catch the
ball and make a move to the basket before sending help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to stop him one-on-one,'' Ewing said. ``He's big and
strong and he outweighs me by about 70 pounds. Everyone needs to
help each other. It's got to be a total team effort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
