<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-GOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOSS SET BACK BY MISHAP IN YACHT'S MAIDEN TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the British adventure sailor Pete Goss, March will be
remembered for highs and lows of kingly proportions. Just over two
weeks ago, Goss' radical new 120-foot catamaran, Team Philips _ a
craft embodying Britannia's fervent wish to once again rule the
waves _ was christened and blessed by Queen Elizabeth II in an
emotional ceremony in the heart of London.
</P>
<P>
   But last Wednesday, in a cold, gray North Atlantic seaway, Goss'
worst nightmares were realized when a 45-foot section of the
spindly port bow cracked off like an icicle dangling from a sill,
on the third day of the boat's maiden trials. Suddenly, Goss had a
royal problem on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very loud bang,'' the 38-year-old former marine
said in a telephone interview from St. Mary's in the Scilly Isles,
the port to which he, his five-man crew and his crippled sailboat
had been towed after the incident. In typical understatement he
added, ``We found that the port bow had a major structural problem
and was starting to work itself off.''
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, was not supposed to happen to a boat that was
scheduled to undertake not one but two round-the-world voyages over
the next several months. First, Goss had planned an imminent
assault on the so-called Jules Verne record for the fastest
circumnavigation, which is currently just over 71 days. But that
trip was viewed as a mere warm-up for Goss' entry in The Race, the
fully crewed, nonstop, around-the-world competition waged with no
limits on the size of boat or crew. That race will begin from
Barcelona, Spain, on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The record attempt is now out of the question. But Goss vows
that he will be on the starting line for The Race. ``We didn't hit
anything,'' Goss said. ``It's something to do with the structure or
the manufacture. We need to distill it down to that kernel of truth
as to what happened. I feel confident we can resolve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss has gotten into tight jams before. In a desperate feat
during the 1996-97 Vendee Globe single-handed race around the
world, he turned around and sailed 160 miles into the teeth of
hurricane-force winds to rescue a French skipper, Raphael Dinelli,
whose boat was sinking. For his heroics, Goss was awarded the Medal
of the British Empire and the Legion d'Honneur of France.
</P>
<P>
   The shakedown of Team Philips, named for the Netherlands-based
electronics company that is bankrolling the roughly $4 million
campaign, began far less dramatically. After setting out from
Dartmouth on England's south coast, Goss tacked north for the Irish
Sea on the first leg of what was planned as a five-day voyage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were making 21 knots with ease,'' Goss said. ``It was just
fantastic, the boat was sailing like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after midnight last Wednesday morning, Team Philips
jibed back toward Land's End at the mouth of the English Channel.
Just after first light, with the boat cruising at 18 knots in a
20-knot northeasterly, Goss was off watch and in his bunk when he
was awakened by the sound of splintering carbon fiber. The port bow
was in critical condition, but the starboard bow had also incurred
a serious crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``All hands were called on deck in survival suits,'' Goss said.
``We let the mainsheets go and immediately depowered the boat, and
then called the marine rescue control center. They immediately sent
out a lifeboat and a helicopter.''
</P>
<P>
   Team Philips began limping towards the Scillys, some 30 miles to
the south, under her own power. But the port bow parted ways with
the vessel soon after, and the craft was then towed into St.
Mary's. The missing piece was later recovered in a separate salvage
operation. Last Friday, with its rudders removed, Team Philips was
towed backward to Dartmouth, where further inspection awaited.
</P>
<P>
   With an all-up weight of just 44,000 pounds, a 70-foot beam, and
twin, unstayed wing masts, the Adrian Thompson design is one of a
handful of unlimited nautical projectiles setting course for The
Race. There are also plans for at least two American boats to
compete: Steve Fossett's PlayStation, which also has its share of
work-up woes, and Cam Lewis' Team Adventure, currently under
construction in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news, if there is such a thing, is that the damage on
the starboard hull gives us a good indication of where the crack
started,'' said Thompson. ``We believe both hulls failed in the
same manner. We can't attempt a repair until we completely
understand what caused the problem. Next time, this boat has got to
be bulletproof.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss has managed to stay focused on the silver lining of the
dark cloud obscuring his dream. ``In a funny way this has pulled us
together,'' he said. ``It's easy when things are going well; the
real measure is when you're at the bottom. Everyone's pulled tight
as a knot and we're going forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
