<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT NEGOTIATIONS WITH SOFTWARE GIANT FALL APART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Settlement talks in the historic antitrust lawsuit against
Microsoft Corp. collapsed Saturday, as a federal mediator declared
that the differences between the software giant and its accusers
were ``too deep-seated to be bridged.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Richard Posner of the US Court of Appeals in Chicago, who
has been working for four months to broker a settlement, issued a
statement Saturday saying that ``the quest has proved fruitless.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 drafts of a settlement had been submitted, Posner
said, but none was acceptable to all parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed that the government would not agree to a
fair and resonable settlement that would have resolved this case in
the best interests of consumers and the industry,'' said
Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   With the talks at an end, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson of US
District Court in Washington, D.C., is expected this week to
announce his ``findings of law'' in the case.
</P>
<P>
   And given Jackson's scathing criticisms of Microsoft in last
year's ``findings of fact'' ruling, there seems little doubt that
he will rule that Microsoft committed serious violations of federal
antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   The US Justice Department and 19 states filed their antitrust
suit against Microsoft in May of 1998, charging that the company's
Windows software holds a monopoly in the market for operating
systems for desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   The government has charged that Microsoft used this monopoly to
try to dominate the market for Internet browsers, and to try to
destroy a rival software company, Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Posner said, ``I particularly want to
emphasize that the collapse of the mediation is not due to any lack
of skill, flexibility, energy, determination, or professionalism on
the part of the Department of Justice and Microsoft Corp.''
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft source drew attention to this statement Saturday
night, noting that Posner had not praised the actions of the 19
state governments.
</P>
<P>
   The source said that it was a handful of these states who had
spoiled the talks late Friday night, by holding out for conditions
that the source described as ``Draconian minutiae.'' The Microsoft
official declined to name the states that had taken a hard line,
but said that Microsoft decided it would be better off accepting
Jackson's ruling and fighting it on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe ... that it would be as Draconian as what
some of the states were asking for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that Jackson may call for the dismantling of
Microsoft into several separate firms, in a manner similar to the
breakup of the Standard Oil trust in the early 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lande, a Microsoft critic and board member of the American
Antitrust Institute, said that a breakup of the company would be
the only way to prevent further abuses of its power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a repeated pattern of going way, way over the line,
then you do break them up for that,'' said Lande, who added that he
was not surprised by the collapse of the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
