<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-DOCTORS-REVENUE-BOS     04-01 1541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-REVENUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS PUSH PHYSICIANS FOR MORE PRODUCTIVITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to boost their drooping revenue, Boston's elite teaching
hospitals are telling their top-notch doctors they must see more
patients and bring in more money.
</P>
<P>
   Some hospitals are even hitting those who fail to do so where it
hurts: their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   These hospitals _ run by Harvard, Tufts, and Boston University _
employ about 7,000 doctors, who are accustomed to pursuing their
own academic interests and setting their own schedules. Many are
unhappy about the productivity push, which has intensified in
recent months after hospitals suffered record losses in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many doctors feel very frustrated by the pressure to see more
patients,'' said Dr. Frannie R. Kronenberg, medical director of a
physicians' group at Brigham and Women's Hospital. ``They've seen
their income decline, from standards that are already lower in
academic medicine. They feel that their commitment to very
high-quality care and the energy and passion they put into it are
being devalued by the pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals in Boston and elsewhere across the country are using a
variety of rules and incentives to get the message across. Typical
is Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center's request that its 120
primary care doctors increase their annual number of patient visits
from 85,000 to 100,000. In the same spirit, a new salary system at
Brigham and Women's will dock less productive doctors up to 10
percent of their pay this year. That amount will grow to 20 percent
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The requirements are accompanied by a whole new Wall Street
language for doctors, one where patient visits are assigned
``relative value units'' depending on complexity, and where
administrators hand department heads ``balanced score cards''
listing revenue generated and goals met.
</P>
<P>
   While productivity quotas at teaching hospitals in other parts
of the country have sparked union movements and lawsuits from
doctors, so far in Boston, doctors are responding more measuredly.
One common reaction: give up low-paying or volunteer teaching jobs
to work longer hours seeing patients.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in private practice, who essentially run their own small
businesses, have grown used to working longer and faster during the
1990s as health insurance companies reined in medical costs, a
movement known as managed care.
</P>
<P>
   But many academic doctors, who are salaried and divide their
time among teaching, research and patients, have been shielded from
marketplace pressures until recent years. In fact, they went into
academic medicine for this very reason _ to be freed from the
commercial aspect of doctoring so they could focus on providing
cutting-edge care and diagnosing interesting cases.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals, as their reimbursements from insurance and
Medicare dropped, felt the pressure too and started to scrutinize
doctors' workloads. Last year's record losses intensified their
push for productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors worry they are losing the thoughtful culture that has
flourished at academic medical centers for decades. But hospital
administrators say their institutions must adapt to survive. And as
with any change, tensions are high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hospital and the doctors disagree,'' said Dr. Nancy
Gagliano, associate medical director at Massachusetts General
Hospital, where doctors are fighting higher productivity quotas.
``The hospital wants to get more for its money. But the doctors
feel like they're sinking and they're doing the best they can do.
No one wants us to give up excellence and become churning
factories.''
</P>
<P>
   But as long as patients continue to receive top-notch care, said
Dr. David Fairchild, director of primary care at Brigham and
Women's, the productivity push is having positive results,
particularly for patients.
</P>
<P>
   Some Brigham and Women's doctors, for example, are opening their
offices on Saturday mornings and are staying open until 8:30 p.m.
on weekdays, while doctors at Beth Israel Deaconess are promising
appointments within one week to almost half the patients who call.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old system, it worked for the physicians, so there
wasn't much focus on whether the patients were happy,'' said Dr.
David R. Fulton, chief of cardiology outpatient services at
Children's Hospital, who put changes in place last year.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Hospital, which lost $61 million last year, has
approached the issue of physician productivity gingerly, trying not
to upset its doctors, who are considered some of the best
pediatricians in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the hospital set up two side-by-side clinics for
outpatient visits. On one side, doctors treat patients more quickly
_ 20 to 30 minutes for a basic visit _ while on the other,
residents, medical students and researchers take up to an hour or
more with each child. Doctors choose the path.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton was brought in two years ago from New England Medical
Center to increase productivity and efficiency in the outpatient
cardiology clinic, where children and their parents were spending
four to five hours a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Parents made appointments and then ignored them; they knew if
they showed up first, they'd see the doctor first. A child could
wait two hours between having his vital signs read and receiving an
echocardiogram. And doctors wandered in and out, disappearing to
return phone calls, teach medical residents, conduct research, or
check on patients who'd stayed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   That had to stop, Fulton said.
</P>
<P>
   So he asked all the doctors how many patients they could see
each day and how long they needed for each visit. Then he added
exam rooms and more precise scheduling _ and held them to it. Since
he implemented the system in July, the clinic has increased its
capacity from 60 children a day to 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't handcuff the doctors,'' he said, ``but because the
patients are moving through the system faster it makes sense for
them to be close at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   At Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, the 130 full- and
part-time doctors and medical residents who work for Healthcare
Associates _ the hospital's primary care practice _ are throwing
out their traditional scheduling system in their effort to meet
their new quota of 100,000 visits this year, the third year the
hospital administration has ordered up an increase.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors used to make appointments for patients two months in
advance, said Dr. Richard Parker, associate medical director for
the hospital's internal medicine practices. Now, they reserve
nearly half of the appointments for patients calling no more than
one week ahead _ a scheduling technique that reduces no-shows and
allows more patients to see their own doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who see more than eight patients per session _ normally
four hours _ receive a salary bonus of up 15 percent, Parker said.
Beth Israel Deaconess just began switching its 75 community doctors
to performance-based salaries that include bonuses and penalties
based on volume and quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not asking us to be conveyor belts,'' said Parker,
who added that the practice can also hire more doctors. ``But yes,
we feel pressured. We feel pressured every day. We're being asked
to justify our budget and it's difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But doctors are less upset about reshuffling their schedules
than they are about having their daily schedules monitored and
recorded down to the half-hour _ a key component of the
productivity movement and the most controversial.
</P>
<P>
   While some hospitals are still measuring the productivity of an
entire doctors' group, and leaving it to the group to dole out
rewards and discipline, most are now moving to measuring numbers of
patients and revenue for individual physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham and Women's is measuring its primary care doctors'
productivity with relative value units, which vary depending on the
complexity of the case. Relative value is considered a more
sophisticated yardstick than simply counting the number of visits,
especially at academic medical centers where doctors treat the
sickest patients.
</P>
<P>
   With the hospital losing $80,000 to $100,000 on each primary
care doctor, Fairchild said, ``Academic medical centers need to
make money like any other business.'' And, he said, doctors who
work longer hours are pleased to be paid extra.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Britain Nicholson, chief medical officer at
Massachusetts General Hospital, said even relative value units
don't take into account all of a doctor's work _ tasks such as
calling a family to discuss unhappy test results _ an omission that
leads doctors to oppose higher quotas.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the pressure to do more, doctors insist they are not
shortchanging patients. But Dr. Robert Witzburg, chief of community
medicine at Boston Medical Center, said something must give when a
doctor increases the number of patients he or she sees in a
four-hour session from eight to 12, as he has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relaxed time I have with patients has shrunk; it's more
businesslike,'' he said. And that matters ``because when I sit down
and talk to a family about bad news, that conversation goes easier
for both of us if we've established a relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-LONG-CAMPAIGN0402-COX     04-01 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-CAMPAIGN0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A long season of presidential campaigningBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Less than three weeks into the longest general election
season in presidential history, George W. Bush and Al Gore are on a
daily campaign pace that few believe they can maintain.
</P>
<P>
   But, to the chagrin of many Americans, they seem intent on
trying.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a front-loaded primary season that both parties agree
is not democracy's finest moment, Bush and Gore smashed the record
for earliest dual clinchings. Both secured their respective party's
nomination March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, both have been Energizer Bunnying across the nation,
eager to keep the campaign going and goingright up until the Nov. 7
election. The first TV commercials showed up March 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, people went home and relaxed and thought
about things, and on Labor Day the campaign began. That's over,''
said 1988 Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, who
believes the current candidates could drum up some interest by
picking their running mates now.
</P>
<P>
   Short of something dramatic like that, Dukakis and others
wonder, is there much reason for anybody to be listening?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they're going to do between now and
convention time,'' said Howard Baker, a former U.S. senator from
Tennessee and Reagan White House chief of staff, in a television
interview when Gore and Bush clinched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do think there's a risk that the country's going to
get turned off by intensive campaigning between now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since Clincher Tuesday, Gore and Bush have been
campaigning close to nonstop, something made possible by the fact
that both have government jobs that don't seem to require much
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither side wants to risk the other side taking advantage of
the early time frame,'' according to a senior Bush adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush scampered across the nation, including
campaigning in Wisconsin as if the state's Tuesday primary
mattered. Gore also was out and about most of the week.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview at the Governor's Mansion, Bush said he
will maintain a ``pretty active schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the people necessarily want to hear the
full-bore campaign,'' he said, using ``bore'' in the sense of
measurement. ``But there are events we can do and ways to highlight
important issues, and I'm going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   So far that has meant education as Bush tries to put the focus
on his more moderate side and off South Carolina's Bob Jones
University, the Confederate flag and his unity-busting campaign
against Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Though both candidates are ready to campaign until Election Day,
there might be a forced blackout because of the Summer Olympics.
Though the Games always coincide with presidential elections, they
are usually held in July or August, when political attention is at
a low ebb.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's Melbourne, Australia, event begins Sept. 15 and
ends Oct. 1, prime political season. Bush advisers believe their
guy will have to fight for attention during that period.
</P>
<P>
   One way to drum up big attention long before the Olympics would
be to go nontraditional with the selection of running mates.
Dukakis, who candidly admits he didn't exactly write the book on
how to run for president, said both contenders should pick their
vice presidential candidates long before the summer conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Now would be a good time, Dukakis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had faced this kind of situation in 1988, I probably
would have begun that process. I would have tried to pick my
running mate at the earliest possible time and get that person out
there campaigning with me as soon as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan tried an exaggerated form of this in 1976 during
his unsuccessful effort to derail then-President Ford's bid for the
GOP nomination. Reagan announced during primary season that, if he
were nominated, his running mate would be Pennsylvania Sen. Richard
Schweicker.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Dukakis clinched the nomination June 7, though he was
the apparent nominee by late April. He picked then-Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas as his running mate in July. Much earlier would be
much better, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a running mate who is in place, who is working with
you and campaigning for himself or herself. I see all kinds of
advantages,'' said Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are no hints of early selection of running mates.
Both contenders also are not eager to re-create Dole '96, whose
road to defeat began when he ran out of money after the primaries
and was forced into political hibernation until federal money for
the general election flowed after the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The spending caps were no problem for Clinton because he had no
serious primary foe and, thanks to the perks of the presidency, he
could always find ways to make news.
</P>
<P>
   Dole also was hindered by spending caps that came with the
federal matching money he took for the primaries. While Dole was
hamstrung, Clinton was all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not take the government's money for the primaries, so
he does not have to play by its rules. In the period leading up to
the summer convention, he can spend whatever he can raise. Gore,
who took federal matching money, faces spending limits but, as vice
president, has an incumbent's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates will take federal money for the fall campaign.
The Federal Election Commission recently announced that each major
party nominee will get $67.5 million for the period from the
conventions until Election Day. That's all they can spend.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Reed, Dole's 1996 campaign manager, believes Bush, though
unencumbered by the shackles that helped doom Dole, will find that
the longest-ever, pre-convention campaign will come with limits of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it more difficult for the nominee to maintain
interest and momentum through the long summer leading up to a
party's convention,'' he said. ``In a national campaign at this
phase, a day feels like a week and a week feels like a month. It's
very difficult to break through and keep the excitement going about
a candidate, even a good one like George W. Bush, when there is no
defining event for three months.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultant Paul Begala, who helped Clinton navigate
treacherous waters in 1992, said the long campaign season brings
opportunity and peril for Bush. It's what Begala said his ex-boss
would call a ``high-class problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of problem you want, but it's still a problem,''
said Begala. ``It's just flat out impossible to dance in the
spotlight for 34 weeks or whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala knows what it's like to try. In 1992, after clinching the
nomination June 2, Clinton was out-PR'ed by Ross Perot's on-again,
off-again, on-again campaign that proved to be a publicity machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perot took all the oxygen. That's why we went on `Arsenio
Hall.' We were starved for attention. We couldn't get arrested. We
later cured that problem,'' Begala said.
</P>
<P>
   He sees little chance that the public will put up with the
wall-to-wall campaign that Gore and Bush want to stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public right now is tuning them out,'' said Begala, a Gore
backer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they'll tune in for is a gaffe. That's the
reason it's wise for Bush to talk about education. It's the only
subject besides baseball I have ever seen him talk about where his
eyes don't look like a slot machine that hit bar, apple, lemon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both would be better off if they just went fishing for a week
or two,'' said Begala.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Bush campaign hinted it might agree. Gore
accepted an invitation to a foreign policy debate this month, but
Bush said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be plenty of time for debates when the voters are
paying attention to the election,'' said Bush spokesman Scott
McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
