r s BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     04-01 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBLING STUDY IS DISTURBING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the release this week of a University of
Michigan study that revealed that 84.4 percent of Division I
officials have gambled since becoming college officials, the famous
Las Vegas sporting gentleman, Jimmy Vaccaro, cracked:
</P>
<P>
   ``And the other 16 percent are lying.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, can't be proven, but 40 percent of those
collegiate officials surveyed admitted to having bet on sports and
it's indisputable that such an activity has become a wide-spread
phenomenon with the proliferation of outlets in the Caribbean,
Nevada, Mexico and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   What is chilling about the Michigan report is the candid
admission by two officials that their awareness of the point spread
resulted in ``their officiating with a level of bias.''
</P>
<P>
   What is chilling about the Michigan report is that 12 officials
say they knew of colleagues who had not called a game fairly
because of gambling reasons.
</P>
<P>
   What is chilling about the Michigan report is that it reaffirms
a belief I've always privately held that once in a while a judgment
rendered by an official has been swayed by the point spread.
</P>
<P>
   This is not meant to impute that athletics we're talking both
amateur and professional here is rift with corrupt officials, nor
is it meant to tarnish the credibility of all those games we watch
on television.
</P>
<P>
   But the sobering fact is there are instances rare instances, I
think when some arbiter has made a call or even calls that have
been dictated by the point spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there is big money involved, there is going to be a
level of cheating,'' the notorious bookmaker, Harry Gross, once
told me. ``And believe me, I've seen some cheating in athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s and early 1950s, Gross was the biggest name in
his profession in New York, and eventually he would descend on Long
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He was heavily involved in the betting business for more than 50
years, and related titillating stories about fraudulence among both
athletes and arbiters that can't be related here in detail because
of libel laws.
</P>
<P>
   If only a fraction of what Gross related to me was true, one
can't help but forever cast a cynical eye on sporting competitions.
</P>
<P>
   It has been estimated that 10 percent of the male population in
America gambles excessively, and you can be sure or even bet on it
that there are a few referees and umpires who have serious habits.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen countless illustrious athletes over the years gambling
merrily away in Las Vegas casinos.
</P>
<P>
   I often saw the late NBA referee, Mendy Rudolph, in those places
playing high-stakes blackjack.
</P>
<P>
   I know a prominent Las Vegas boxing judge, still living, who
bets heavily on football games.
</P>
<P>
   What if he has a bad week, and owes the bookmaker thousands of
dollars?
</P>
<P>
   Under such circumstances, would he not be more susceptible to a
bribe, or at least more susceptible to making a sizable bet on a
boxing match that he's working?
</P>
<P>
   I also can't tell you how many times across the seasons I've
seen late-game calls especially in football that have defied all
sane calculations and, by the sheerest coincidence, had a direct
effect on the final point spread.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA, in its typical obtuse, inane manner, has been trying
to push through legislation in Washington to ban sports gambling on
college sports.
</P>
<P>
   How would that help?
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I'm stopped from going to Nevada and betting on college
football and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal! I can always make the hour and a half trek down to
Tijuana, where there are plenty of sports books at my disposal. Or
I can open up an off-shore account with one of the Caribbean
outfits. Or I can call up illegal bookmakers, who are all over the
place and will always be all over the place as long as people want
to gamble on sports and horses.
</P>
<P>
   As Harry Gross, a colorful character who, in a fit of
despondency, took his own life in a Long Beach apartment in 1986,
often said, there is always a certain amount of corruption when the
financial stakes are high.
</P>
<P>
   It's like that in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   It's like that in government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   It's like that in almost every business enterprise imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Jimmy Vaccaro sniffs at the NCAA's attempt to forbid
betting on college sports in the Nevada sports books.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it that a place like England has more than 1,000
betting shops around the country (William Hill and Ladbrokes), and
there's no problem?'' wonders Vaccaro. ``Does the NCAA honestly
think that people are going to stop betting on college sports just
because you won't be able to bet on them in the sports books?
Please. Gambling on college sports is here to stay, no matter
what.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
