<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4410 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GIULIANI-PRESIDENT-NY     04-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT LASHES OUT AT FIRST LADY'S OPPONENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton jumped full-force into the New York campaign
for U.S. Senate Saturday, declaring that Hillary Rodham Clinton was
the target of a ``right-wing venom machine'' allied with Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, and asserting that Republicans were prepared to
throw a ``double-ton of money'' into derailing his wife's first
attempt at public office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way they can win is to convince people that we're
space aliens,'' Clinton said at a union fund-raiser on behalf Mrs.
Clinton's Senate campaign in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who has, until now, appeared to take pains to
avoid overshadowing his wife's campaign, was anything but
restrained Saturday, forcefully advocating Mrs. Clinton's candidacy
and portraying Giuliani as a creature of the right.
</P>
<P>
   The president invoked on behalf of his wife some of the same
arguments _ indeed, some of the same phrases _ that he has
marshaled in his own campaigns for office, asserting that Giuliani
was seeking to demonize his wife because he could not defeat her
based on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a complicated deal, and that's why Hillary's
opponent can raise a double-ton of money, besides being mayor and
having special relations with a lot of those people who have it in
New York,'' Clinton said. ``And you have the right-wing venom
machine all geared up against her again.''
</P>
<P>
   The president has taken swipes at Giuliani in the past, and
Giuliani has relentlessly criticized the president in recent
months. But the remarks Saturday were by far the fullest and
harshest attack he has offered against the mayor; indeed, they were
generally tougher than what Clinton herself has been saying during
nine months of campaigning in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's attack on Giuliani appeared to be a spontaneous
expression of frustration, rather than an orchestrated strategic
gambit by Mrs. Clinton's campaign. The $75,000 fund-raiser, which
was sponsored by the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers and held at the Hyatt Hotel on Capitol Hill, was not listed
on her public schedule, and her press aides did not accompany her
to the event. An accounting of the president's remarks was provided
by pool and wire service reporters who routinely accompany the
president for all his public travels.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Clinton, who has less than 10 months left in the
White House, came at a time in which he has appeared increasingly
tempted by the campaigning going on at the periphery of his
presidency. Recently, while in New York, Clinton offered an attack
on George W. Bush, the Texas governor and presumed Republican
opponent of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not running for anything,'' Clinton noted Saturday. ``Most
days, I'm OK about that.''
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, Clinton's attack on Giuliani and his allies
came two days after Mrs. Clinton's campaign was startled to learn
that it was being significantly outpaced by Giuliani's in
fund-raising. Giuliani announced last week that he had raised $7
million in the first three months of this year, compared with $4
million by Mrs. Clinton. (Giuliani's campaign manager, Bruce J.
Teitelbaum, said Saturday night that a more up-to-date tally found
that Giuliani had raised $7.3 million).
</P>
<P>
   The president is extraordinarily popular in New York, one of the
first lady's aides noted Saturday night, and thus may be in a
particularly good position to take on Giuliani, who is far less
popular than Mr. Clinton. That said, Clinton appeared with his
remarks to risk diminishing Mrs. Clinton at a time when she has
been trying to establish her own identity. She offered only
perfunctory remarks at Saturday's fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's allies said Saturday that the episode might be
portrayed as evidence that Clinton, in making her first run for
office, could not stand up for herself.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Clinton's attacks were reminiscent of what has
been a common refrain in the Clintons' public lives: attempting to
present themselves as victims, a point Teitelbaum made when asked
for a response to the president's attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever the Clintons get into trouble, they revert to blaming
it all on a vast right-wing conspiracy,'' Teitelbaum said. ``In
this case, it seems to be an attempt to deflect attention away from
Mrs. Clinton's lagging fund-raising numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's press secretary, Howard Wolfson, asserted that
Clinton, in his remarks, was ``defending a shared set of Democratic
principals that have been good for America and good for New York.''
Asked if mrs. Clinton had asked the president to speak on her
behalf, Wolfson responded: ``The president was saying what he
believed. The mayor has been running a relentlessly negative
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the audience of about 300 people that Giuliani was
repositioning himself politically as he turned his attention from
winning election in New York, a Democratic city, to winning in New
York State, which is relatively more Republican, and in a contest
in which he has relied on financial support from conservatives
across the nation who are unhappy with the notion of Clinton's
serving in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
