A4413 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-FINAL-FOUR0402-CO     04-01 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINAL-FOUR0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spartans march on
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It wasn't pretty. In fact, it was probably as
ugly as the game of basketball can be played. But to Michigan State
coach Tim Izzo, it was thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, the only No. 1 seed left in this totally
unpredictable NCAA Tournament, pushed, prodded and pounded its way
into Monday's national championship game by beating Wisconsin 53-41
Saturday night at the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans (31-7), in the Final Four for the second
consecutive year, will play the winner of Saturday's late game
between North Carolina and Florida in hopes of winning its first
national championship since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time since Feb. 12 that Michigan State had
beaten its Big Ten brother (22-14), which was in the Final Four for
the first time since 1941. Wisconsin, which finished sixth in the
Big Ten, got to Indianapolis with a tenacious defense and a steady
but efficient offense.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, the Big Ten champions, took Wisconsin's game and
simply played it better. Wisconsin made only 15 of 43 shots (35
percent). Michigan State also shot 35 percent in the game (16 of
46) but beat the Badgers 14-2 in offense rebounds. That was the
difference in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After a brutally physical first half, Michigan State outscored
Wisconsin 11-2 in the first six minutes of the second half to take
a 30-19 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin continued to be frustrated as it tried to find room in
the Michigan State defense to take a shot. The Badgers hit only two
of their first seven attempts in the second half and on several
possessions never got a shot off against the rugged Michigan State
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin finally scored again when Kirk Penny hit a 3-point
basket to bring the Badgers to within 32-22. But several
possessions later, with the shot clock near zero, Morris Peterson
picked up a loose ball at the top of the key and canned a long
3-pointer. That gave Michigan State a 37-22 lead and Wisconsin
would never recover.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was anything but an artistic success as the two
teams combined to shoot 26.6 percent (12 of 45) from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State jumped out to a 17-8 lead with 10:01 left in the
first half and it appeared the Spartans would be able to take
control of the game. Wisconsin could do little right in that
stretch, hitting only 3 of its first 11 shots while getting pounded
7-1 on the offensive boards.
</P>
<P>
   But little did Michigan State know that a layup by Mateen
Cleaves with 11:42 left would be its last basket of the first half.
In fact, after a free throw at the 10:01 mark, the Spartans did not
score again until Morris Peterson hit two free throws with 3:34
left. All total, Michigan State missed its last 11 shots in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wisconsin began to grind its way back into the game,
getting 3-point baskets from Penny and Roy Boone. That enabled the
Badgers to climb within two, 19-17, at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
