<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-BELLSOUTH0402-COX     04-01 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BELLSOUTH0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Familiar name, a top slot: Nicklaus
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What's this? Mickelson head-to-head against Nicklaus
in the final round of a PGA Tour event? Some computer simulation
perhaps, linking golf's past with its present?
</P>
<P>
   No, it's real, but there's a twist. It's Phil Mickelson and Gary
Nicklaus, a tour rookie and son of Jack, tied at 11-under par 205
heading into today's final round of the BellSouth Classic at the
TPC at Sugarloaf.
</P>
<P>
   The story lines are numerous, to be sure, but one is better than
any other. Imagine the irony if the young Nicklaus, in the first
year that Augusta National does not invite PGA Tour winners, were
to secure a victory on the eve of the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction would likely be heard all the way out to Arizona,
where Jack, a six-time Masters champion, is playing in The
Tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But Mickelson isn't the only one who can get the Masters
committee off the hook. There are 12 other players within four
shots of the lead _ including 36-hole leader Joey Sindelar, who
fell to three back after a 74.
</P>
<P>
   Tied for third at 9-under 207 are Kenny Perry (70), who hasn't
won on the PGA Tour in five years; and Harrison Frazar (70), who is
looking for a first PGA Tour win. Three strokes off the lead at
8-under 208 are Jay Don Blake (69), Tom Pernice Jr. (69), former
U.S. Open winner Steve Jones (70) and Sindelar.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Cink, with the day's lowest round Saturday, a 5-under
67, is still in contention, tied for 10th at 7-under 209. Franklin
Langham, who has gone 67-69 after an opening 74, is tied for 15th
at 6-under-par 210.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Stankowski, two shots back after 36 holes, slipped to a 74
and is also five back at 6-under.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mickelson and Nicklaus missed closing opportunities to lead
alone today. Mickelson, who shot a 69, took a bogey at the 17th
hole, where he missed the green and then a 3-foot putt. At the
par-5 18th, his second shot, a 2-iron from 250 yards, hit the green
hard and carried over it into a swale. Guarding against the water
beyond the green, the lefthander flopped a wedge back short, onto
the fringe, then missed his birdie putt from about 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was originally just going to bump-and-run it,'' Mickelson
said of his third shot. ``I thought there was a chance that it
could come out perfect and a chance it could roll 30 to 40 feet by.
. .I had to make sure I got underneath the ball. I was on a pretty
good downslope. If I didn't get underneath it, it could be sent off
into the water long.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, who shot a 68, grazed the side of the cup at the 18th
from eight feet for birdie, but made his share prior to that. The
31-year-old, who has never won an event as a professional, bogeyed
two of his first three holes, then ran off four straight birdies
from Nos. 10-13, beginning with a chip-in at the par-5 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Of his mindset for today, Gary, expecting to talk with his
father again before the final round, planned to ``not do anything
different; just keep calm and patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack, who was able to watch some of the BellSouth during a
weather delay, said he got so ``charged up'' after viewing his son
on the telecast that he promptly went out and birdied 13, 14 and
18.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, he's been on the sidelines rooting for me,'' Jack
said. ``Now it's my turn to be on the sidelines pulling for him. .
.I'm very proud of him. I'd love to have him win a tournament,
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion David Duval is playing today only for
exercise. After spinning two balls back off the fifth green for an
8 at the par-4 5th, shot shot a front-nine 41 for 77 and is in 73rd
place at 3-over 219.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
