<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SAY THEY'RE CONTENDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- When the Angels open the 2000 major league baseball
season against the defending World Series champion New York Yankees
Monday night at Edison Field, they will honor members of their
all-time team, which was selected by the fans to commemorate the
franchise's 40th season.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Jackson will be there. Bobby Grich, Brian Downing and
Doug DeCinces will be there. Chuck Finley and Jim Edmonds, however,
have committed to previous engagements.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, voted to the team as one of two left-handed starters,
will be in Baltimore, where his new team, the Cleveland Indians,
are playing the Orioles. Edmonds, the franchise's all-time center
fielder, will be in St. Louis, where his new team, the Cardinals,
are playing the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels promised changes would be made after last season's
debacle, and they were true to their word.
</P>
<P>
   Out as general manager is Bill Bavasi. In is Bill Stoneman. Out
as manager is Terry Collins. In is Mike Scioscia. The entire
coaching staff, with the exception of bench coach Joe Maddon, is
new. The scouting staff was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Finley's departure, changes to the players roster
were slow in coming. Talks of a deal to trade Edmonds for pitching
help went on all winter. And finally, after Stoneman suggested no
deal would be made, a deal was made.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, less than a week before the team broke camp in
Arizona, Edmonds was traded to the Cardinals for 18-game winner
Kent Bottenfield and second baseman Adam Kennedy, who has become
the starting second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   When Stoneman was hired last Nov. 1, there was a lot of work
needed to be done in a short period of time. Now looking at the
roster -- and there might be more changes coming -- the Angels say
they are happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're better balanced now,'' Stoneman said. ``We were
able to add starting pitching. That helps. We were able to add a
second baseman. That helps.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps because going into spring training, those two areas
were the club's biggest holes. The starting pitching is still
questionable, but if they can stay healthy they'll be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill has an arthritic elbow and hasn't won more than nine
games in a season since he won 16 for Texas in 1996. Bottenfield
will provide innings and keep the team in the game. Ortiz, if his
shoulder is healthy, is a Rookie of the Year 9to
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
