<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0402-COX     04-01 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore, not Bush, agrees to debate
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has accepted an invitation to a foreign
policy debate with likely Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush, but Bush hasn't said whether he'll attend. On Friday Gore's
camp prodded Bush to take the bait. ``We hope he will reconsider
his decision,'' Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway said. ``Bush still has
the opportunity to agree to Gore's challenge to drop radio and TV
ads and hold regular debates on the issues.'' The debate has been
proposed by CNN and the Council on Foreign Relations. It was
scheduled to run 60 minutes in late April and feature questions
from journalists and international affairs experts.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN GETS MOST FEC MATCHING FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Former Republican presidential contender Sen. John McCain scored
more than half of the $5.9 million the government will issue in
matching funds to seven current and former presidential candidates,
the Federal Election Commission announced Friday. Totals include:
</P>
<P>
   _ $3.7 million for McCain, who suspended his presidential
campaign after the Super Tuesday primaries March 7. Many political
analysts said the amount signifies McCain's fund-raising strength
after he won the New Hampshire primary in February. That brought
his total to $10.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vice President Al Gore will receive another $718,485, bringing
his total to $13.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley, who has abandoned his campaign,
will receive another $849,553, bringing his total to $12.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patrick Buchanan, who is seeking the Reform Party nomination,
will get $174,185, bringing his total to $3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government matches the first $250 of each individual
contribution for candidates who agree to limit their total primary
spending to $40.5 million. GOP presidential candidate George W.
Bush, who has raised a record $75 million, is not accepting federal
funds and can spend as much as he can raise in his GOP presidential
bid.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AND MCCAIN REACH DELEGATE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   John McCain is giving George W. Bush six of the Michigan
delegates he won and has similar deals or is close to agreement in
several New England states McCain won before suspending his
campaign. The Arizona senator agreed to give Bush six delegates to
add to the six Bush won in the Feb. 22 Michigan primary, leaving
McCain with 46 of the state's 58. The deal allows Gov. John Engler
to attend the National Republican Convention as a Bush delegate and
is the latest move toward GOP reconciliation after the divisive
primary contest.
</P>
<P>
   KEYES TIPS HAT TO GORE
</P>
<P>
   Still pursuing his Republican presidential bid, Alan Keyes told
Wisconsin voters this week that Vice President Al Gore, the
presumed Democratic nominee, has a ``pretty good chance'' of
winning the election. Keyes said Gore would benefit from ``economic
prosperity and peace'' in a race against the presumed Republican
nominee, George W. Bush. Ambassador Keyes, who spoke to voters at
the Monroe County Fairgrounds, said Republicans needed to promote
moral values and oppose abortion, which he called worse than
slavery.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN WEIGHS IN ON OIL PRICES
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan says the United States should stabilize oil prices
in part by lifting sanctions on Iran and Iraq, selling them
oil-drilling equipment and threatening to withhold military help
from Persian Gulf allies unless crude prices fall to $20 a barrel.
``None of these Gulf regimes is worth another war,'' Buchanan said
Friday at Boston University. ``We should play hardball with those
who play hardball with us.'' Buchanan blamed the problem on ``a
global price-rigging conspiracy by oil-exporting nations.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH FAMILY TREE SPANS 16 PRESIDENTS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has always had an impressive family tree. But it
seems he has an even richer political pedigree than the immediate
family and recent ancestors. In fact, according to the
little-noticed 1995 ``Ancestors of American Presidents'' by
genealogist Gary Boyd Roberts, George W.'s relations extend to 16
U.S. presidents. Not only that, but he is distant kin to a bunch of
British monarchs and even Pocahontas, the American Indian princess.
Roberts' president list: George Washington, Millard Fillmore,
Franklin Pierce, Abraham Lincoln, Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
Hayes, James Garfield, Grover Cleveland, Teddy Roosevelt, William
Howard Taft, Calvin Coolidge, Herbert Hoover, Franklin Roosevelt,
Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford and, of course, George H.W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
