<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHST-WISCONSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVE THE NICETIES: SPARTANS REACH THE FINAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It looked like a game played at lunchtime on one
bent basket in an industrial warehouse between two teams of
hard-hatted and work-booted laborers who knew each other too well.
Instead, Saturday night's game was a NCAA tournament semifinal, a
highly anticipated full-court game before a sold-out crowd and a
national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State and Wisconsin knew each other quite well _ this
was the Badgers' fourth attempt at beating the Spartans this season
_ and it showed. On defense, each team played with tenacity and the
intimacy of knowing each other's plays. On offense, however, both
teams were awful, with both shooting 35 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the top-seeded Spartans (31-7) were less awful and
prevailed, 53-41, to advance to the championship game against the
winner of Saturday night's North Carolina-Florida game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's beautiful to be able to play basketball with five
guys and take on superior athletes with more skill and be able to
beat them,'' Wisconsin's Mike Kelley said before the game. ``I
don't know how you can't enjoy that. But I think it is viewed as
ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   The 42,399 who brimmed to the top of the RCA Dome must have
believed they had been transported back to another time, or to 1941
to be exact, the third year of the NCAA tournament when Wisconsin
(22-14) employed equally comatose tactics to win the national title
by beating Washington State, 39-34.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers' jersey-to-jersey defense kept them on pace to match
their forefathers on the scoreboard through a 19-17 first half. But
in the first nine minutes of the second, the Spartans went on a
15-5 run to take 34-22 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Michigan State senior Morris Peterson, who returned
here on Friday from Mississippi and the funeral of his grandmother,
Clara Mae Spencer, who shifted the Spartans briefly from no gear to
first gear.
</P>
<P>
   He had 10 points on 4-of-6 shooting in the run after going just
1 of 5 in the first half. He finished with 20 points to lead all
scorers. His teammate Mateen Cleaves led both teams in rebounding
with 11.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson's grandmother died last Saturday on the morning of the
Midwest Regional final, but his family waited to tell him until
after the victory over Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's going to have the best seat in the house,'' he
said. ``She's going to be sitting right there watching over the
team and guiding us. Hopefully, we can make something happen for
her.
</P>
<P>
   When Peterson hit a 3-pointer with 8 minutes 35 seconds
remaining, his 17th point of the game, the somnambulant crowd came
to life as Michigan State took a 15-point lead. The Badgers closed
to 40-29 with 5:40 to play when their leading scorer in the
tournament, Jon Bryant, scored his first basket of the game, but
they never got closer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
