<HEADLINE>
PEREZ IMPRESSIVE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO - The Dodgers were worried about the final spot in the
rotation because Eric Gagne and Carlos Perez were dreadful early in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with the exhibition season over, Perez's strong finish
has eased some apprehension about the spot in the rotation. And
Chan Ho Park's continued problems have bred concern.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought Perez would be pitching better than Park
entering the season?
</P>
<P>
   Perez finished his spring by allowing one run in four innings of
the Dodgers' 2-1 win against Toronto on Saturday at SkyDome. In his
last four starts, Perez's ERA is 2.50.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Park ended his spring by allowing five runs in four
innings on Thursday. His 7.63 ERA is worse than the 7.43 ERA Perez
had in `99. And after working on mechanics and his change-up during
his first three starts of the spring, Park tried to put it all
together. Still, he had an8.31 ERA in his last three starts and
battled tightness in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positive thing about (Park) is he's getting more
consistent release points, and that's what he's been working on,''
Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said. ``The numbers aren't good, but
so what? The other day he started off stiff, and by the second
inning he loosened up and was throwing the ball really good. But
he's got a lot on his mind, he's trying to do a lot of different
things right.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the battle Park must win to be successful. Manager
Davey Johnson has had several talks with Park about just pitching
instead of letting outside distractions creep into his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had that conversation with him already, and I'm going to
continue to have it,'' Johnson said. ``Don't give him a lot of time
to wait forthe ball. Don't let him wait around for signs. Give it
to him. Work faster. Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said the tightness in his arm was caused by a slight change
in his mechanics with his right leg, but he insists that's over. He
also said he feels fine despite the poor spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy physically, and happy mentally,'' said Park, trying
to rebound from a year in which he was 13-11 but had a 5.23 ERA.
``I did have agood spring. I worked out a lot. I feel like I'm
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro traded to Reds: After spending the last two weeks trying
to trade infielder Juan Ca eD
</P>
</TEXT>
