<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1065(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA HAS `WAIT AND SEE' ATTITUDE TO TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS 16th graf with talks between China and the European Union
breaking down.) 
 (lb) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chinese leaders have told the United States that
they plan to stick with a ``wait and see'' attitude toward Taiwan's
new president and that they are open to resuming a dialogue with
the estranged island, a senior administration official said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese assurances, if borne out, come at a crucial time for
the administration, which is scrambling to put relations with China
on an even keel before President Clinton leaves office and to
persuade Congress to upgrade economic relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Jiang Zemin of China and other top leaders
assured the national security adviser, Sandy Berger, that China's
initial, restrained reaction to the election of Chen Shui-bian as
Taiwan's president last month was part of a ``considered policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen's party had previously called for independence from China,
something Beijing has sworn it will not allow, and he only recently
muted that stance.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have decided, at least for the time being, to try to
reach an accommodation with his new government, which is expected
to be formed in May, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't quite know what to make of the situation,'' the
senior administration official said, describing Berger's two-day
talks with the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they are not inclined to act in a precipitous way and they
want to find a way to reach an accommodation consistent with their
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are working on a formulation consistent with their
one-China principle,'' the official added.
</P>
<P>
   Berger traveled to China in part because the administration is
simultaneously seeking to smooth relations between mainland China
and Taiwan even as it struggles to assemble a Republican-dominated
coalition of lawmakers willing to grant China permanent trading
rights in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders said that any flare-up in tension between
China and Taiwan would almost certainly derail the administration's
hopes to win passage of the trade measure soon. The administration,
in turn, has warned that failure to pass the measure could
seriously set back relations with China and diminish U.S. influence
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an important national security argument for going
forward with permanent normal trade relations, which is if anything
intensified by developments related to Taiwan,'' said the senior
administration official. ``It not only creates a degree of
interdependence between China and the world community but also to
the economic integration of China and Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has in the past threatened to attack Taiwan if it tries
to secede. During Taiwan's election four years ago, the Chinese
lobbed missiles around the island in an attempt to intimidate
voters. Senior Chinese leaders gave a bellicose warning to Taiwan
shortly before the latest elections as well, apparently to persuade
voters to back candidates considered more favorable to
reunification than Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, relieved by Chen's conciliatory comments after his
election, China seems inclined to remain open to dialogue, the
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States has no intention of mediating between
Taiwan and China, the officials said that the two sides had the
potential to work through a complex set of historical formulations
for dealing with each other based on differing views of Chinese
sovereignty, and to resume a dialogue that was broken off in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Though that process would probably take many months, if it
happened at all, the mere prospect reduces the risk of rising
tensions blocking passage of normal trade relations, which Clinton
has called his top remaining foreign-policy priority. A
congressional vote on the matter is expected in May, the same time
that Taiwan's new government takes power.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between China and the European Union over China's entry
into the trade group broke down on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has asked Congress to give up its annual
review of China's trade status, granting it the same trading rights
_ called permanent normal trade relations _ that most other
countries have.
</P>
<P>
   The step is required if U.S. companies are to benefit fully from
a market-opening agreement that the administration negotiated as
part of China's continuing effort to join the World Trade
Organization. Congress has no vote on whether China can join the
Geneva-based trade-regulation body.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is a technical one _ removing China's name from a
dwindling list of nations subject to Title IV of the Trade Act of
1974, also known as Jackson-Vanik.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters argue that the economic rationale for giving up the
annual review is overwhelming. The agreement with China requires it
to open its markets and overhaul its regulatory regime, making way
for foreign competitors in every area from agriculture to the
Internet. But as Clinton has noted, ``it's a one-way deal'' that
does not require reciprocal trading concessions by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has argued that granting permanent normal trading
relations is essential for the national security of the United
States. He said it would support reformers in China's government,
lock China's bureaucracy into a rules-based international trading
regime and contribute to stability in Asia. Rejection would affect
the United States' economic interests, Clinton said last week, but
``the national security consequences would be worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote, however, has become freighted both with ideological
concerns about China's Communist government and with domestic
political worries in an election year. While the U.S. business
community has begun a national lobbying campaign on behalf of the
measure, labor unions have mounted a vigorous opposition designed
to culminate in what unions are promising will be a huge
mobilization of supporters in Washington and around the nation on
April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, both political parties are divided about the wisdom of
granting new trading rights to a country that has a weak
human-rights record and has often made threats to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Senate passage is considered likely. But if the measure slips
through the House, Clinton will have the Republicans to thank;
early counts show that that two-thirds of his own party's members
in the House will vote against permanent normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and the Republican leadership in the House
have begun to work together to build a coalition across party lines
in support of the measure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hastert, the House majority leader, has acceded to
administration pleas and agreed to set a date for the vote in late
May, aides said, even though Republican leaders acknowledge that
Clinton has not fulfilled what they had insisted was a
prerequisite: proving that he can produce enough Democrats to
ensure passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragic irony that while the president has put this at
the top of his priority list, his own party is becoming more
xenophobic,'' said David Dreier, R-Calif., who heads the House
rules committee. ``But the president is engaged and working hard,
and we are willing to work with him to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, getting to 218 votes may prove difficult. Although
business pressure on Republicans has been intense, some members of
the party argue that the administration should work actively for
the overthrow of the Chinese government instead of giving it
upgraded trading rights.
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides say the party will struggle to produce 150
votes in favor of permanent normal trade relations, the same number
that supported annual renewal of China's trading rights last year.
</P>
<P>
   That means supporters will need about 70 Democrats to vote in
favor, and more if Republicans experience any more slippage.
Democratic lawmakers who favor the measure say that this is still
possible, but acknowledge that most of their potential supporters
are still uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has started a campaign _ run out of the Old Executive
Office Building next to the White House _ that is aimed primarily
at securing support from wavering Democrats. Aides said Clinton is
spending more time on China trade than on any other single item on
his agenda. He will make his sixth major address on the subject on
Monday in California and has scheduled numerous evening talks with
lawmakers in the White House this month.
</P>
<P>
   The president has also assigned five cabinet secretaries to make
China their priority. Three of them _ Commerce Secretary William
Daley, the U.S. trade representative, Charlene Barshefsky, and
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman _ have cleared their schedules
this spring to focus on lobbying lawmakers and crisscrossing the
country to drum up support for China trade in the home districts of
key lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an intensive, all-out effort, member by member,
district by district, explaining what this agreement is really
about and what's at stake in terms of relations with China,'' said
Barshefsky, who negotiated the sweeping trade agreement that opened
the door for China to join the WTO. ``What we're saying is that
this decision is about the best way to influence China, not just on
economics but all the surrounding issues as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
