<HEADLINE>
SHAQ IGNORES NUMBERS GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Shaquille O'Neal's drive for the NBA scoring title
may be unintentional - he says he doesn't care whether he gets it
or not - but it's alive and well after his 37-point drubbing of the
Philadelphia 76ers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal heads into today's game against the New York Knicks with
a 29.1-point average, No. 1 in the league. Now the greatest threat
to his second career scoring trophy (aside from the Sixers' Allen
Iverson) is the Lakers' own success.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Lakers (61-12) clinch home-court advantage throughout
the playoffs - they need three wins, three Portland losses or any
combination thereof - O'Neal's minutes will shrink. So will his
scoring opportunities, as coach Phil Jackson plans to rest him for
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Jackson will stick to the status quo, which
means 37 to 40 minutes a night for O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think clinching is something that when it happens, it will
happen. You just play it out and still keep as competitive as you
can,'' Jackson said. ``That's just the only way to play basketball,
for us at least. And yet humanly it's almost impossible not to
relax a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said last week that O'Neal's play would show him whether
he wanted the scoring and rebounding titles. O'Neal's performance
Friday left an impression, but afterward O'Neal once again
downplayed the scoring race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think the more competitive a game, the more he's going
to step up,'' Jackson said. ``He was very active (Friday) night,
not only at the offensive end but defensively. I think that
competitive nature naturally brings it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the judge is the next time we play Golden State or the
next time we play ... an under-.500, non-playoff team, how hard
he's going to play in that kind of a game. It's kind of the
indicator as to what level he wants to win a scoring title, but
he's basically told me it's not important to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest time: Jackson sounds ready to finally give veteran Ron
Harper the extended rest he's been promised.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of indicating Harper would head to the injured list,
Jackson said ``there's a good possibility'' he'll make the move
b%N
</P>
</TEXT>
