<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4434 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DALY-LADN     04-01 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DALY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALY TRIES TO TURN DODGERS AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. - It took the Fox Group 18 months to turn one
of sports' great franchises into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   In the five months since becoming the managing partner, chairman
and CEO, Bob Daly brought back control to a team Fox had allowed to
spiral out of control, returned focus and given reason to believe
the family-friendly days of the O'Malleys are possible again.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are a day from opening the 2000 season in Montreal,
but they are light years removed from the end of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see how things have simmered down,'' Dodgers left fielder
Gary Sheffield said. ``Just having (president and COO) Bob Graziano
back and Daly having some ownership, I think it brought a sense of
urgency for this franchise to get back to where it needs to be to
get along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have new ownership you're going to have
adjustments. You have to make a couple of mistakes, a couple
decisions you feel are right, and then you learn from them. I think
the Fox Group has seen how baseball is operated the past couple of
years and they see they needed to hire certain types of people, and
they did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly's brought a little boy's enthusiasm and passion for
baseball back to Dodgers ownership after two years of facelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Daly ran Warner Bros. and CBS, but he's loved baseball since he
attended a Brooklyn Dodgers game as a 6-year-old. But this is also
business, and Daly, 63, didn't purchase a minority share and agree
to run the club on a day-to-day basis to lose money. Rupert Murdoch
still pays most of the bills, but Daly has a piece, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Daly said the Dodgers lost $22 million last year. The club
figures to lose around $15 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy when I was at Warner Bros. is, `We're in this
together,' '' Daly said. ``I don't think anybody should point
fingers when things don't go right. I think it's critical, that
when we start the season that (manager Davey Johnson) and (general
manager Kevin Malone) and me and (senior vice president Derrick
Hall) and Bob Graziano and everybody are all on the same page. If
things don't go right, I believe you start at the top. I'm
responsible, and I don't mind taking the rap, as long as we're all
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stay together, and last year I have the feeling
the Dodgers weren't together, and I think probably because they
were all shocked how badly they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly preaches stability. During the Fox 18-month
hands-mostly-off run of the Dodgers, the environment created by Fox
executives Peter Chernin, Chase Carey and News Corporation chairman
and CEO Murdoch, was anything but stable:
</P>
<P>
   -The bungled Mike Piazza negotiations that led to the catcher's
trade. From that deal, only Sheffield remains with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   -The firing of manager Bill Russell and general manager Fred
Claire in June 1998. Replacements were interim in Glenn Hoffman and
Tom Lasorda, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   -Malone was hired as the general manager in late September, and,
at the urging of Fox, hired Johnson as manager.
</P>
<P>
   -Pitching coach Charlie Hough was fired last May and replaced
with Claude Osteen.
</P>
<P>
   -Fox hired NBA marketing genius Rick Welts last summer to
oversee all of the company's sports holdings. Welts, who resigned
in December, fired Graziano as president and CEO of the Dodgers in
late September. Daly then entered the equation and brought Graziano
back in November, but only after Chernin, at the October press
conference introducing Daly, said Graziano was never fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I nearly had a heart attack when they changed the pitching
coach, and that's not a judgment call on my part, at all, about one
pitching coach versus another pitching coach,'' Daly said. ``I
bring no judgment, so I don't know. Claude Osteen is a tremendous
pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bringing judgment, no judgment. I'm a manager. I'm a
guy that runs companies. You don't do that, unless you have to; the
guy is incapacitated, he is irresponsible, whatever he is. You
don't do that. That was not, to me, a good idea, because it's just
too disruptive. That's a management decision I would question, not
over abilities, call Claude Osteen better, but to me that's a very
disruptive thing to do to your pitching staff and everybody,
especially after going through previous changes.''
</P>
<P>
   And intertwined through it all was griping players, who aired
their grievances through newspapers. Players complained about a
lack of communication. A battle between Eric Young and Johnson last
season became public, and Raul Mondesi blasted Malone and Johnson
and asked to be traded. That was last year, and Daly saw it all. He
also didn't think it looked very good.
</P>
<P>
   So when center fielder Devon White expressed concern about
knowing his role when spring training began six weeks ago, all
parties were called together to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I think, if you want to call it the new Dodgers,
is we confronted the thing right up front,'' Daly said. ``We took
the thing on right as we got here.... Basically everybody told him
up front, he's going to have to hustle and do his stuff. Everybody
talked to him and he knew exactly where he stood.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly joined the organization Oct. 28, 1999, and has made a lot
of changes. He brought back public relations whiz Derrick Hall and
made him senior vice president, communications.
</P>
<P>
   From his office down the left-field line, Daly watched and
charted the renovations at Dodger Stadium. He jumped into the
player personnel side and negotiated Shawn Green's contract, thus
finalizing the trade with Toronto involving Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   The day the Dodgers traded Young and Ismael Valdes to Chicago
for Terry Adams and two minor-leaguers, Daly and Malone spoke on
the phone six times about it. Daly also played a big role in
signing former Dodger Orel Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   In spring training, Daly met with the front office and coaching
staff to discuss the roster. He talked with pitcher Carlos Perez,
not only about his drunk-driving charge last month, but Perez's
on-field behavior, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a tough winter for a lot of reasons for the
Dodgers, and the way it was handled was great,'' Johnson said. ``A
lot of the clouds were removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly also turned salesman. Between negotiating long-term
contracts for Green, Adrian Beltre, Eric Karros and Mark
Grudzielanek, he sold luxury suites at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, what always distinguished the Dodgers, in addition to
the fact they always had winning ballclubs, is they always had done
things in a total professional way,'' Daly said. ``You may not even
agree with all the decisions they made, but they were professional.
I questioned a lot of decisions the Dodgers made in the '90s. I
have faxes that I sent. Peter O'Malley has a file with my faxes in
it. From the winning of the World Series in 1988, my faxes began in
1989. Losing Steve Sax was my first fax. I could not believe we
lost Steve Sax. I've had a lot of feelings about that, but it was
done in a professional way.
</P>
<P>
   ``My management style says if you're going to make a change, and
sometimes you do, you make it at the right time, unless there's a
reason that is so predominant that you have to do it. Sometimes you
have a wholesale revolt, so you have to do it. But if you're going
to do it, make it at the right time. And I think the problem with
the Dodgers are there were too many changes. You're a Dodger fan,
you don't expect all these changes.''
</P>
<P>
   So, should Dodgers fans expect a change at the general manager's
positions should the team stumble to another 77-85 record despite a
payroll of near $92 million
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Malone made the two trades I find the most damaging to
the Dodgers,'' Daly said. ``The (Henry) Rodriguez trade and the
Pedro Martinez trade were made by Kevin Malone; on the other side
of the fence, he was with Montreal (at the time).... The one thing
I know about Kevin Malone is that he is a very, very good judge of
talent. He's a terrific baseball man.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the first five months are any indication, so is Daly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
