<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ERICSSON-NYT &LR;      04-01 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ERICSSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND-RANKED HINGIS ENDS ON TOP IN ERICSSON
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Lindsay Davenport will become the world's
top-ranked women's player on Monday when the latest WTA rankings
comes out. Yet Saturday she was a distant second in the Ericsson
Open.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis, whose No. 1 position Davenport will take,
administered a 6-3, 6-2 humbling in the final at the Tennis Center
at Crandon Park, taking the $350,000 top prize.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-minute victory stopped Davenport's winning streak at 21
matches, as well as Hingis' five-match losing streak against her.
The last time Hingis had prevailed over Davenport was more than 16
months ago _ on Nov. 22, 1998, in the Chase Championships at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After the victory, Hingis approached Davenport and told her she
deserved to be ranked No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far this season, she's played very well,'' Hingis said.
``But it's different pressure being No. 1 and No. 2. Now I'm the
hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   In this mushrooming rivalry, Davenport still leads overall,
11-8. This is the fourth straight final between the two in
tournaments they have both entered. Not since Chris Evert and
Martina Navratilova, who met in five straight finals spanning 1984
and '85, have the top two ranked women's players met with such
regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport said she felt subpar Saturday, the result of a
three-set semifinal against Sandrine Testud late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost felt like I left everything out there that night and
didn't bring anything today,'' Davenport said. ``I just felt really
heavy today. I was definitely a step slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport made 40 unforced errors to Hingis' 10 and couldn't
rely on her usually potent first serve, in part because of a
persistent breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll meet many more times and I'll beat her again
one day,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, who didn't lose a set in this tournament, took
Saturday's first set in 30 minutes. She broke Davenport's service
in the second and fourth games, in the process making Davenport
look overmatched. One spectator, upset at her plethora of unforced
errors, even boomed, ``Davenport, this is the final.''
</P>
<P>
   She proceeded to win the next three games, breaking Hingis
twice. But just as it appeared there would be some drama after all,
Hingis took charge again. She easily broke Davenport, forcing her
into three forehand errors, and held service to finish the set.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis moved up by 4-2 in the next set, the same spot she was in
two weeks ago in Indian Wells, Calif., when Davenport won the last
10 games to capture the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was different this time,'' Hingis said. ``I broke her many
more times. She was not serving that well. When we got into the
rallies today, I just felt like we were even. She didn't get that
many free points off her serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis broke Davenport in the seventh game after it reached
deuce, hitting a backhand winner and forcing her to send a backhand
long.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Hingis simply held service to wrap up the match.
Davenport watched the clinching backhand whiz by.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis said the blustery conditions favored her patient return
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more chances because I run and try to get as many balls
back as I can, then try to do something,'' she said. ``Here,
Lindsay just can't go for big shots because it's too dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching Davenport labor in the match, Hingis said she was
glad she didn't play doubles in this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when things are going great, it's still very tiring,''
Hingis said. ``It takes a lot out of you. Every time you go out
there, you have to motivate yourself, push yourself one more day,
one more time.''
</P>
<P>
   But she acknowledged that this turned out to be one of the most
satisfying weeks of her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like every tournament,'' Hingis said, ``I got better. I don't
want to take too long off because I feel so good right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
