<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DIMMED PROMISE IN PRAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, April 2:
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright expected a warm reception
when she visited her native Prague, Czech Republic, last month. But
even she was surprised to learn shortly before her arrival that
President Vaclav Havel intended to propose her as a possible
successor. Beyond his admiration for Albright, Havel was trying to
register a larger point. In the decade since the Velvet Revolution
against Communist rule, Prague's political leaders have compiled a
record of disillusioning failure, including the fracturing of
Czechoslovakia into separate Czech and Slovak states in 1993. No
one of Havel's stature has yet emerged to replace him when his term
expires in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Czechoslovakia's expectations were understandably high when it
restored parliamentary democracy and market economics in 1990.
Between the two world wars, it was one of Eastern Europe's most
vigorous and longest-surviving constitutional democracies. Under
Alexander Dubcek in the 1960s, it tested the limits of liberal
Communism. Then, after the Soviet invasion of 1968, its dissident
intellectuals, foremost among them Havel, developed a vision of a
broadly based civil society. By the bleak standards of the Soviet
bloc, Czechoslovakia's economy performed relatively well.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring failures of the past decade have been in
economic management. Under Vaclav Klaus, who served first as
finance minister and then as prime minister until 1997, state-owned
industries were privatized without adequate legal oversight or
accountability. Initially, the results were promising. But more
recently growth has sputtered and a series of corruption scandals
has tainted the reputation of business and political leaders. The
Czech Republic still has one of Eastern Europe's richer economies
and is a candidate for early admission to the European Union. But a
more thoughtful round of reforms backed by more legal safeguards
will be needed to attract foreign investment and revive growth.
</P>
<P>
   Political life has also been disappointing. Klaus, a brash
conservative, saw his early popularity erode as the economy
weakened. Three years ago he fell from office amid a corruption
scandal. A weak Social Democratic government now rules in coalition
with Klaus' conservatives. As president, Havel remains popular and
respected, but his health is poor and his political influence is
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Albright was right to disclaim any interest in the Czech
presidency. It would create an intolerable conflict of interest for
a secretary of state to be looking ahead to directing the affairs
of another country. But if Havel's proposal can jolt Czech
politicians into thinking more creatively about their future
leadership, it will have served a good purpose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
