<HEADER>
A4539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT-HOME-REAL-820&AMP;ADD-     04-01 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHETHER YOU MOW OR MOAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The days are getting warmer, the nights are getting shorter, and
the sun is moving higher in the sky. It is the time of year when
homeowners reclaim their yards and gardens. And what could be more
inviting than the idea of meandering around the yard enveloped by
spring breezes, bird songs and the muffled roar of a self-mulching
gas mower?
</P>
<P>
   Root-canal work, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Well, whether you are the kind of homeowner who can't wait to
plunge head-first into lawn chores, or the type who would rather
plunge into a porch chair and watch a professional do the work, now
is the time to start thinking about your lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say that except for grub control, most everything you're
going to be doing to your lawn you'll be doing over the next month
or so,'' said Tim Elkner, a Penn State extension agent in
Lancaster, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Elkner explained that this is a critical time of year for lawns
because what is done _ or not done _ within the next few weeks will
determine in large part how the lawn will look during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   For a lawn to be at its best in July and August, it has to
develop a strong, hardy root system in the spring. So the first
thing a homeowner should do is to rake the grass to aerate the
soil, and to remove any twigs, leaves or dead grass that may have
accumulated over the winter. It is also wise to avoid the
temptation to cut the lawn too short on the first mowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some folks like to crank their mowers all the way down to get
that wall-to-wall carpet effect,'' Elkner said. ``But if you leave
the grass a little longer right now, anywhere from 2{ to 3 inches,
you'll end up with hardier grass and a better root system.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that will generally not be necessary this year, he
said, is grub control. He explained that grubs _ those small,
white, crescent-shaped critters that eat grass roots on their way
to becoming adult beetles _ are not likely to be a problem this
year, because of last year's dry summer.
</P>
<P>
   Beetle eggs, which are laid in the summer, need moisture to
hatch. ``So unless you watered regularly last summer,'' Elkner
said, ``there probably wasn't enough moisture in the soil for the
eggs to hatch.''
</P>
<P>
   What could be a problem, though, is crab grass.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Long, a vice president of Scotts Lawn Service, a subsidiary
of Scotts Co., the lawn-products manufacturer in Marysville, Ohio,
said that crab-grass seeds would not have been affected by the dry
conditions last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any areas of your lawn had crab grass last year, it's a
good bet you'll have it again this year,'' Long said, explaining
that the only way to prevent crab grass from gaining a foothold is
to apply a pre-emergent herbicide just before the crab-grass seeds
start germinating.
</P>
<P>
   If the herbicide is applied too early, he said, any rain that
falls after the application and before germination could dilute or
spread the herbicide so much that it becomes ineffective. If it is
applied too late, on the other hand, weeds that have already
sprouted have a good chance of surviving the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   So when is the right time to apply a pre-emergent?
</P>
<P>
   ``Once soil temperatures reach 55 or 60 degrees for a few days
running, the seeds will start germinating,'' Long said. ``And
that's when you want to be applying your pre-emergent.'' He added
that now is also the time to do some seeding if the lawn has any
bare spots or areas that were damaged over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general rule of thumb is that any bare spot larger than a
coffee saucer will not fill in over the course of a growing
season,'' Long said. Areas that are going to be seeded should be
raked well before seed is applied, he said, and then the seed
should be raked into the soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``And be sure to avoid applying your pre-emergent on any areas
you're seeding,'' he said, ``because the crab-grass preventer can't
tell the difference between germinating weed seeds and germinating
grass seeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Another routine lawn-maintenance chore this time of year is the
application of fertilizer. ``It's always good to make certain that
you get the lawn fed with a balanced fertilizer,'' Long said,
explaining that most fertilizers contain a combination of nitrogen,
phosphorus and potassium, nutrients that are essential for healthy
lawn growth.
</P>
<P>
   What homeowners need to know when buying fertilizer is the ratio
of those nutrients, he said. A fertilizer with an ``NPK ratio'' of
2-1-1, which is a good ratio for a starter fertilizer for use in
the spring, would be one that contains two parts nitrogen (N), one
part phosphorus (P) and one part potassium (K). A fertilizer with
an NPK ratio of 3-1-1 could also be used at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone has the time, energy or inclination
necessary to rake, seed, fertilize and trim the lawn. For those
people, there are plenty of professionals who are happy to do the
work for them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Our standard service contract consists of mowing, edging,
trimming and blowing once a week,'' said Michael Buczny, the owner
of Groundworks Landscaping, a lawn maintenance company in Long
Branch, N.J. The cost ranges from about $80 to $120 a month or
more, depending on the size of the lot; the number and type of
obstacles, things like swing sets and flower beds; and the length
of the sidewalks and driveways that have to be edged.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Giardino, the owner of C.G. Lawn and Landscaping in New
City, N.Y., said that his company offers a ``full maintenance''
service contract, which includes weekly cutting and edging, along
with mulching and weeding flower beds every two weeks, four or five
applications of fertilizer, the application of herbicides and
insecticides as needed, and weekly trimming of shrubs and hedges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that a ballpark figure for a full-service
maintenance contract can run from $350 to $400 a month'' for an
annual contract, he said. ``And if you include snowplowing in your
contract now, you can get a package deal for as little as $425 a
month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
