<HEADER>
A4541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BOROUGHS-REAL-NYT &LR;      04-01 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOROUGHS-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY CONVENIENCES, WITH TREES AND PARKING
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not everyone who lives in the outer boroughs is an aspiring
Manhattanite, resentful of the high rents that push people to the
north, south or east. On the contrary. Hard as it might be for some
of the more insular Manhattanites to believe, there are people who
prefer, say, Queens, and consider it a desirable and central
location.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Caccavale, who works in Manhattan for Quinn &AMP; Co., a
public relations firm, grew up in Westchester County and graduated
from Hofstra University in Hempstead, N.Y. When she decided last
year that it was time to move out of her mother's house in Pelham
Manor after living there for a year to save money, she did not
really consider Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in suburbia,'' she said. ``I've always had a car. I
knew parking would be a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   She decided to look in Queens because it would put her close to
work, her family, friends on Long Island, and her boyfriend, who
lives in Astoria.
</P>
<P>
   Because she wanted to have a subway commute of only 25 minutes
or so to her office in the West 30s, she looked in neighborhoods
near the N and R lines. Fairly quickly, through an ad placed by an
owner, she found a one-bedroom apartment on 30th Avenue in
Boulevard Gardens, a large co-op complex on the border of Astoria
and Woodside. The 10 six-story buildings are threaded together with
paths bordered by grass and trees, which appealed to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like what I'm used to in suburbia,'' she said, adding
that the neighborhood was also safe and quiet. ``Coming home late
at night, I'm not afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the co-op told her that he had had several offers
well above his initial asking price of $800 a month, including
utilities, but he agreed to sublet the apartment to her for $840 a
month because she seemed the most stable of his prospective
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   And, probably, the most efficient. She got the apartment in late
August, and by the time she moved in in September, she had already
managed to furnish most of it. ``Within three weeks, I bought
everything,'' she said. A Labor Day sale at Jennifer Convertibles
yielded two couches with pillows, a coffee table, two side tables
and lamps, all for $1,000. At a small furniture store on Long
Island she found a bedroom set with two chests, a mirror, and two
bedside tables for $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought everything except the TV and the comforter'' with
money she had saved, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the apartment already feels as if she has lived there
forever, with scented candles gently perfuming the air, Caccavale
says she plans to stay in Queens for no more than five years. She
expects to become engaged this year to her boyfriend of six years,
a police officer, and eventually, to move to a suburb in
Westchester or on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Caccavale has always been a planner, a person looking ahead, and
thrifty, too. ``I would sell my Easter chocolate to my brother,''
she said, preferring the money to the candy. Her cautious nature
was shaped by a difficult start in life: when she was 20 days old,
her father, a detective, was killed.
</P>
<P>
   By living in Queens, she finds it easy to remain close to her
family, whose photos are everywhere in her apartment. Her desire to
stay close to them influenced her career path. Although she studied
journalism in college and expected to continue on that route, ``I
knew I'd have to move to Bumbletown, USA, to get a job,'' she said,
``and I wasn't ready to leave the area.'' And so she took the job
in public relations. She now specializes in travel, working with
clients like the Westin Rio Mar Beach in Puerto Rico, Le Parker
Meridien Hotel in New York and the Aruba Sonesta Resorts.
</P>
<P>
   With E-ZPass reducing her wait at bridge tollbooths, she said,
she can drive to her mother's house in 15 minutes. But usually, she
makes a detour. Almost every Saturday, she drives to her
grandmother's house in the Pelham Bay section of the Bronx to take
her grocery shopping, and then continues on to see her mother in
Pelham Manor _ and to do her laundry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I lived at home,'' she said, ``I don't like the whole
Laundromat thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friends like her new apartment in Queens, she said, because
they can all gather there _ and park their cars on the street _
before going into Manhattan on Saturday nights. Her office even
held its Christmas party there, because it was convenient for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great meeting spot,'' she said. ``Everything is less
than 30 minutes away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
