<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4545 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     04-01 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 9)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; VERA: (Mrs. Vladimir Nabokov) &LR;  By Stacy Schiff. Modern Library,
$14.95. This biography of Nabokov's wife, protector and perfect
reader unravels their 52-year marriage without trying to explain
the enigma that the couple present. ``The triumph of `Vera' is not
just in providing entree to her famous husband,'' Lyndall Gordon
wrote in The New York Times Book Review last year. ``She fascinates
in her own right.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THE RELIEF OF UNBEARABLE URGES &LR;  By Nathan Englander.
Vintage International, $12. The author, a former yeshiva student
from New York who lives in secular Israel, explores the tension
between old and new worlds, tradition and modernity, in his first
collection of stories. Whether writing about Stalin's purge of
Yiddish writers or a Hasidic Jew whose sexual torment is so acute
that his rabbi gives him a special dispensation to visit a
prostitute, ``Englander combines a compassionate grasp of the
Orthodox Jewish world with the skeptical irreverence of one
estranged from yet still oddly defined by it,'' James E. Young
wrote last year. These ``taut, edgy and sharply observed'' tales
form ``a volume of polished gems.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST OF THE JUST &LR; , by Andre Schwarz-Bart (Overlook,
$15.95), is a French novel that chronicles the agonies of a Jewish
family from 12th-century England to Nazi Germany. It is ``part
history, part vision, forged into a single echoing, terrifying
outcry,'' Frederic Morton wrote in 1960. ``It is at once lush and
sardonic, full of dolor and fury and a heartbreaking richness.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU'RE MISSIN' A GREAT GAME: From Casey to Ozzie, the Magic of
Baseball and How to Get It Back &LR;  By Whitey Herzog and Jonathan
Pitts. Berkley, $7.99. The former crowd-pleasing manager known as
the White Rat gives away plenty of trade secrets as he surveys his
half-century in major-league baseball. He also offers some frank
advice for rejuvenating the sport. ``What makes the book work is
that Herzog wants to talk about the things that people don't like
to talk about,'' Bill James wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FENWAY: A Biography in Words and Pictures &LR; , by Dan Shaughnessy
and Stan Grossfeld (Houghton Mifflin, $18.95), pays tribute to a
legendary ballpark that has been a house of pain for generations of
Beantowners. Shaughnessy's text is ``straightforward and
unsentimental'' and Grossfeld's photographs are ``sparkling and
upbeat, evoking not the park's gloomy history but its charming
eccentricities and ever-startling greenness,'' Charles McGrath
wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOW AND INSIDE: A Book of Baseball Anecdotes, Oddities, and
Curiosities &LR; , by H. Allen Smith and Ira L. Smith (Breakaway Books,
$13), canvasses the national pastime between 1860 and the beginning
of World War I, and includes hundreds of tales of figures great and
small, including ancients like Rube Waddell and Germany Schaefer.
In 1949 the reviewer Tallulah Bankhead (a Giants fan) called this
``a fascinating and hilarious collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued the authors' follow-up
compilation,  &UR; THREE MEN ON THIRD &LR;  ($13), which covers the ensuing
years up to 1951 and features accounts of flying grapefruits, wacky
baserunning and a player who caught his own home run. The result is
``a cheery, informative book,'' Rex Lardner wrote in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC FOR TORCHING &LR;  By A.M. Homes. HarperPerennial, $14. This
willfully depraved novel about a disaffected middle-class suburban
couple's walk on the wild side is a long way from Cheever country,
to put it mildly. ``I was at times appalled by the book, annoyed by
it, angered by it,'' Gary Krist wrote last year. ``But even so, I
found myself rapt from beginning to end, fascinated by Homes'
single-minded talent for provocation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARMADILLO &LR;  By William Boyd. Vintage International, $14. This
novel's hero is a London insurance adjuster of Gypsy descent whose
life is undone by an outbreak of zemblanity, the opposite of
serendipity, in the multicultural hubbub of Cool Britannia. The
book ``is full of loose ends, unsolved mysteries and red
herrings,'' A.O. Scott wrote in 1998. ``But it is also charming,
unsettling and sneakily, serendipitously profound.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHOW ME A HERO &LR;  By Lisa Belkin. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $14.95.
A writer for The New York Times explores the polarizing conflict
that followed a 1988 judicial order to build 200 units of low-cost
subsidized housing in Yonkers, N.Y. ``We learn a lot, and we learn
it in impressive detail, about the intimate feelings and motives of
the people who got new housing and the people who tried to prevent
it,'' Nathan Glazer wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PICTURE THIS &LR;  By Joseph Heller. Scribner, $13. This fantasy
about a Rembrandt painting of Aristotle is basically a springboard
for the author's sarcastic musings on justice, money and the
stupidity of war. ``Heller treats the whole panorama of history
past and present with the bravado of Mark Twain in one of his
sassier moods,'' Robert M. Adams wrote in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIDSUMMER NIGHT &LR;  By Uwe Timm. New Directions, $12.95. The
narrator of this German novel is a novelist who travels to
post-reunification Berlin to research an article on potatoes and
finds himself swept up by a city in restless flux. The result is
``a picaresque comedy that is also, unobtrusively and astutely, a
novel of ideas,'' Bill Christophersen wrote in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
