<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-RUIZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUIZ WON'T FALL FOR SUCKER PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The date keeps changing and the court rulings keep coming, but
one thing remains the same for Chelsea heavyweight contender John
Ruiz: His chance is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz is scheduled to fight three-time heavyweight champion
Evander Holyfield July 3 at Caesars Palace. But emissaries from
undisputed champion Lennox Lewis want Ruiz to bypass that fight for
a promise to meet Lewis July 15 in London, assuming Lewis survives
the challenge of Michael Grant April 29.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz is unlikely to fall for that.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz and his handlers believe Holyfield is old and ready to be
beaten, which would give Ruiz more bargaining power as Lewis's
mandatory challenger in the WBC and WBA. Also, Ruiz used to be a
stablemate of Lewis's and distrusts his manager, Frank Maloney, and
promoter, Panos Eliades. They once left Ruiz in Atlantic City
without a room after inviting him to watch Lewis fight and Ruiz's
manager, Norman Stone, has never forgotten it. Ruiz remembers that
slight and many broken promises and does not believe Lewis would
fight him in July if he refuses the Holyfield fight.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a practical reason for Ruiz to take the $1
million-plus purse to face Holyfield now, and Grant's trainer, Don
Turner, understands the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Turner advised Grant against fighting Ruiz before he fought
Lewis, even though the conventional wisdom was Grant could have
scored two big paydays. ``There's no such thing as easy money in
the heavyweight division,'' Turner said. ``Big man hits you, down
you go. Take the biggest fight you got in front of you. For Johnny
Ruiz, that's Holyfield.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what happened to Grant in his last fight when Andrew
Golota dropped him twice before Grant stopped Golota late in the
fight. Grant has been training at Turner's North Carolina camp for
his return against Lewis. Turner insisted Grant looks so sharp,
Ruiz should not be concerned about a title shot with Lewis in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis may have a fight on July 15, but it'll be a
nontitle fight,'' Turner said. ``What Michael said in Ring Magazine
I agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   What the normally soft-spoken Grant said was Lewis would either
``quit or get knocked out'' April 29. If he's right, Lewis won't be
fighting July 15 against anybody, least of all Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   HBO Sports senior vice president for programming Lou DiBella has
heard many reasons for fighters pulling out of bouts, but never one
like Mike Acri gave him when he pulled Razor Ruddock out of
Saturday night's fight with WBO heavyweight champion Vitaly
Klitschko in Berlin. ``Razor had an operation to reverse a
vasectomy a few weeks ago and he got hit low in sparring and the
guy was in agony,'' DiBella said. Ruddock was replaced by Chris
Byrd, a younger and more difficult opponent. ``(Ruddock) had a
bulge in his abdomen and nobody knew what it was,'' DiBella said.
``They were afraid he had cancer. So he got an MRI and it turned
out there was an infection from the (operation). Obviously, he
couldn't fight. As excuses go, it was one of the better ones I've
heard. It's so embarrassing to the poor guy, he couldn't be
lying.'' Promoters were scrambling for a replacement and came up
with the slick-boxing Byrd. When the fight was made, Klitschko's
promoters wanted an opponent like Ruddock, who still had a
reputation and appeared dangerous, although his looping hooks are
dangerous only if you walk into one. Byrd (30-1, 18 KOs) is every
heavyweight's nightmare, a giant Willie Pep, who moves constantly
and seldom gives an opponent an opening. There may have been a
tougher match for the predictable, hard-punching Klitschko, but the
show had to go on . . . Byrd was scheduled to fight former Olympic
team captain Lawrence Clay-Bey but Clay-Bey suffered a detached
retina and was replaced by former cruiserweight champion Alphonso
Washington. Byrd jumped at the opportunity for a bigger payday and
a shot at Klitschko, but promoter Dan Goossen refused to let Byrd
off the Fox television card against Washington without a $150,000
stepaside fee. Goossen said the money will reimburse the Las Vegas
hotel for losing the fight. Sure it will.
</P>
<P>
   Local bleatings
</P>
<P>
   The 45th anniversary of Tony DeMarco winning the undisputed
welterweight title from Johnny Saxton at Boston Garden was
celebrated Saturday night during a Rich Cappiello show at the Roxy.
A clip of the fight was shown and you can bet it was the best fight
of the night . . . Clay-Bey is contemplating retirement after his
latest setback with a detached retina, even though doctors said he
could begin fighting in three months. The Hartford heavyweight is
34 years old and 11-0, but it has taken three years to get in 11
fights because of injuries. Clay-Bey applied for his old job as a
correctional officer in Hartford. His promoters, America Presents,
told him he was facing his first big fight when this latest problem
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Rather fight than switch
</P>
<P>
   Roy Jones fights again May 13 on HBO vs. WBA No. 1 contender
Richard Hall. HBO tried to get Eric Harding, a far more credible
opponent, but Jones wanted an additional $500,000 above his $4
million fee to switch opponents, even though Harding has no more
chance of beating him than Hall does. Promoter Murad Muhammad tried
to get out of the Hall fight, claiming he was not worthy to be the
WBA's No. 1 contender. ``I can't figure out one guy he beat,'' said
one boxing promoter. ``The only guy I ever heard of is the guy he
lost to (Rocky Gannon).'' After the fight was announced last week
in Indianapolis, Muhammad changed his tune. ``Roy and I watched
Hall on tape and found out he has not been given the credit he
deserves,'' Muhammad said with a straight face. ``He's 6-3 1/2 and
a southpaw. He has 23 knockouts in 24 wins.'' So what? He lost to
Gannon, which damaged his credibility . . . Middleweight champion
Bernard Hopkins is on the Jones undercard. HBO signed Hopkins with
the intent of landing a match with Jones, but Jones has not
announced his next opponent. HBO still hopes to make that fight as
well as a match for Jones in Germany . . . Jones apparently is not
ready to follow the lead of Oscar De La Hoya, who refuses to pay
exorbitant sanctioning fees to Los Banditos, the organizations that
rate fighters. ``I have a lot of obligations with three, four, five
titles,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   WBO light heavyweight champion Dariusz Michalczewski will face
Graciano Rocchigiani April 15 at Preussag Arena in Hannover,
Germany. Jones says he's going to fight Michalczewski, but hasn't
yet. If Michalczewski wins, Jones would be wise to challenge him.
The money would be big but the hype would be even bigger, and Jones
could use it . . . Promoter Bob Arum may be in hot water in Las
Vegas. He testified before a federal grand jury to paying $100,000
to have the IBF waive its rules (requiring a fighter be rated
before he can fight for a world title) to allow Axel Schulz to
fight George Foreman. Now a deputy attorney general from Nevada,
with Arum's admittance under limited immunity, might force the
state to revoke his promoter's license. Arum will fight the charges
and claims he did nothing illegal. Somewhere Don King is laughing .
. . Cedric Kushner continues to expand. In addition to a regular
heavyweight card in Manhattan, he added a seven-fight series at the
Hard Rock Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas . . . Concerns that young
Floyd Mayweather has poisoned his career are growing. He recently
broke with Arum and called a multimillion dollar contract with HBO
a ``slave contract.'' Mayweather drew fewer than 2,500 paying
customers to his last fight in Las Vegas vs. Goyo Vargas and was
booed when he entered the ring. In September, he reportedly drew
only 1,750 paid at Mandalay Bay. Despite being one of the world's
best young fighters, Mayweather's future seems in doubt. HBO, which
still has his rights, is concerned he may self-destruct . . . WBC
lightweight champion Stevie Johnson failed a drug test in England
after his victory over Billy Schwer last November. Johnson claims
the substance was in a cold medicine and the WBC has refused to
acknowledge the test results. The British Boxing Board of Control
wants Johnson to be stripped of his title. Fat chance of that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
