<HEADLINE>
MARCH MADNESS FOR NBA COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who wants to coach a millionaire? It's not a game
show, you won't find Regis Philbin anywhere nearby, and there never
seems to be a winner.
</P>
<P>
   But there's just as much drama, as NBA coaches from coast-to-
coast lost control of their teams in a March Meltdown that shows
last year's 50-game season might have been better for the sanity of
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a look at some of the shenanigans that took place in
the past few days:
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee. Coach George Karl and his star, Glenn Robinson, got
into an altercation after a !ital!victory!off! over Boston.
Robinson was reportedly upset that he was taken out of a game, no
doubt adding fuel to the belief he is over-concerned about his
stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dog and I are cool,'' Karl said. ``I took him out early in the
fourth quarter, when we had an eight-point lead. And by the time I
was going to put him back in it was 15 or 16. So maybe he was
(upset) because he didn't go back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle. First, Vernon Maxwell and Gary Payton get into an
altercation during practice, with Payton throwing a chair at
Maxwell, and Maxwell throwing a weight at Payton, which hit Horace
Grant and injured his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Chuck Person, already on the injured list, aggravated
his sore knee while trying to break up the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an argument,'' Payton said. ``That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics moved Maxwell's locker away from Payton's, and
although the pair took their teammates to dinner to eliminate
lingering dissension, coach Paul Westphal finally abandoned his Mr.
Nice Guy persona.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal threatened Maxwell and forward Vin Baker with major
changes if their effort doesn't improve. ``Right now, I'm
emphasizing that we stink,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, just as things were settling down, Payton's agent
said he wouldn't be surprised if the point guard were traded. Just
more wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto. After dropping five of six games, veterans Charles
Oakley and Antonio Davis voiced displeasure over the team's
offense, saying it focused too much on getting shots for phenoms
Vince Carter and Tracy McGrady.
</P>
<P>
   ``(When) the two younger guys get the ball in their hands, they
have to create for us and everybody else shots,'' Oakley said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Davis: ``I try to stay away from questioning the way this
is (run), but I just feel like at times a big majority or a big
percentage of our offense is being run through two guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Raptors coach Butch Carter responded by saying that he didn't
mind going to any player who was scoring, and ripping Davis for
missing three of his first four shots in a recent game. ``No good
coach is against some guy who's producing,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the way Toronto wants to be heading into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Utah. Karl Malone and Jerry Sloan got into their first public
argument ever, after Sloan had the temerity to remove Malone from a
game after he sprained his ankle against Philadelphia. The injury
appeared so serious that John Stockton committed an intentional
foul to stop the game, to give Malone a chance to get to the bench
for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he started yelling at Sloan for removing him. In
another first, Sloan went home right after the game and refused to
talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers. Something happened between their coach and a player,
but we can't remember.` j
</P>
</TEXT>
