<HEADLINE>
YOUTH HELD IN SLAYING AT DELI
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 15-year-old Staten Island boy was arrested Saturday
in the shooting death of a clerk at a neighborhood deli after he
and his mother returned to the store a few hours after the slaying
to retrieve his coat, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old, whose name was not released Saturday afternoon,
was arrested at the deli by investigators from the 120th precinct's
detective squad, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Andrew McGinnis, a New York Police Department spokesman,
said investigators believed that the clerk chased the youth from
the Second Eden Deli, at 281 South Avenue in the Arlington section,
around midnight. Witnesses told investigators the clerk had caught
him trying to steal snack foods, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he left the store, he dropped his coat and produced a gun
and fired,'' McGinnis said.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk, Sarif Saed, an 18-year-old immigrant from Yemen who
lived next door to the deli, was shot twice in the chest and was
pronounced dead at St. Vincent's Medical Center on Staten Island,
officials said. Two other store employees, Susaim Mused, 41, and
Shawn Heyes, 28, were grazed by bullets and declined medical
treatment, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As detectives searched for clues around the store, McGinnis
said, the youth returned, with his mother, to search for his coat,
which officials think he dropped during the incident. ``His mom did
not know he shot anybody,'' McGinnis added.
</P>
<P>
   The youth was taken into custody by detectives.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the Staten Island district attorney, William P.
Murphy, was reviewing the case to determine whether to bring murder
charges against the youth, officials added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
