<HEADER>
A4640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-NICKLAU     04-01 2344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-NICKLAUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLORY IS GONE, BUT NOT FORGOTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time has not dimmed the memory. It still ranks on the top shelf
of his closet-full of great moments. And if you want to call it the
greatest Masters ever, not many people will argue. Certainly not
Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   The image is as fresh as this morning's coffee, the greatest
golfer of our time doing a victory dance around the 16th green at
Augusta National, his putter thrust skyward, caddie Willie Peterson
punching the air with his fist. His most emotional display ever? No
doubt, but for good reason, says Nicklaus. ``How many times do you
hole a 40-foot putt that puts you in the lead on the 70th hole at
the Masters? Sure I was emotional. That was a great battle going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1975 and Nicklaus's spot atop the golf world was
unquestioned. But there was no shortage of players willing to take
a run at him. Tom Weiskopf was big, strong, and fearless. Johnny
Miller had authored a closing 63 at the US Open two years earlier
and was winning weeks at a time. Tom Watson was on fame's doorstep.
Arnold Palmer perhaps couldn't compete week in and week out, but,
at 45, he still knew how to get around Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   And with all the stars aligned, there they all were for four
glorious days in April 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1975 Masters is probably one of the most enjoyable golf
tournaments in which I ever played,'' says Nicklaus. ``Maybe the
most enjoyable. I would say that even if I hadn't won.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but how he won. Much to the despair of Weiskopf, his fellow
Ohio State Buckeye who readily concedes that he was never the same
after that heartache. And at the expense of Miller, who missed his
greatest chance to show the critics that he wasn't an early-season
flash who feasted on desert layouts.
</P>
<P>
   Weiskopf and Miller, bless their souls, had to walk that entire
final round in Bear Tracks, which is to say they followed in the
noise of the Nicklaus gallery. The Golden Bear, starting the day in
second place at 8-under 208, was paired with Watson, who was fourth
(212). Quirky as it may now seem, the last group was the leader
Weiskopf (207) and third-place Miller (211).
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus had stormed to the front that year, opening 68-67 for a
five-shot lead. ``But I've seen some five-shot leads lost and I've
blown some myself to lose tournaments,'' warned Nicklaus, who had
already captured four green jackets. What he got Saturday was his
worst nightmare _ a pairing with Palmer, who had opened 69-71.
</P>
<P>
   Great for golf fans, misery for the legends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said many times that we both got wrapped up in playing
against each other,'' said Nicklaus. ``That's why we sort of hated
to play with or against each other when we were in contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, that held true. Nicklaus shot 73 and relinquished the
lead to Weiskopf, who backed up a 69-72 start with a blistering 66.
And Palmer, who had led through 27 holes, dropped back with a 75
that would signal his exit from Augusta as a serious contender. He
was T-13 that year and would never again finish higher.
</P>
<P>
   But the news of that third day was the blond guy who had already
twice shot 61 that year and won three times. Miller, barely making
the cut at 75-71, was setting the place on fire as Nicklaus,
Weiskopf, Palmer, and Watson hit practice balls. Starting on the
par-5 second, Miller ran off six straight birdies. ``I said to
myself, `Boy, I'm going to shoot zero today,' '' Miller told
reporters after he posted a third-round 65 to get into the hunt. At
the time, it was one shot off the course record.
</P>
<P>
   As the sound reverberated through the pines of Augusta, Nicklaus
warmed up. Did he know what was going on, reporters asked? He may
be colorblind, Palmer told reporters, but ``Jack isn't deaf. He
knows what a birdie sounds like.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller turned in 30 to break Nicklaus's frontside mark of 31 and
surprisingly set his sights on something other than the
leaderboard. ``I was more interested in the course record,'' he
told reporters. ``I wanted to play a good round so you guys
wouldn't say I was a dog this week.''
</P>
<P>
   As impossible as it seems, the final day surpassed the previous
three.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus fell out of the gate, pushing his opening drive right
and making bogey. Miller, playing mind-boggling golf, toured the
front in 32. Weiskopf put up a 34. Nicklaus recovered splendidly
after the first and made his fourth birdie on the front at the
par-4 ninth hole to shoot 33, a stretch that included his second
shot into the difficult fifth that never lost sight of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was three guys coming down the stretch in the last nine
holes,'' said Nicklaus, ``and it wasn't who made bogeys, but who
made the most birdies. And that is hard to do at Augusta.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus felt he let the tournament get away from him when he
hit his second shot to the par-5 13th fat and settled for par. Then
he three-putted the 14th. When Weiskopf, who had made a miraculous
bogey after hitting his approach into the water at 11, came through
and made birdie at 14, he went back into a one-shot lead.
</P>
<P>
   It remained one shot as first Nicklaus (a 1-iron second shot
from 240 yards setting up a two-putt from 15 feet) and then
Weiskopf birdied the par-5 15th.
</P>
<P>
   Which brought the drama to No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   It is a par 3 that has determined so many Masters titles and
this year was no different. Nicklaus fell in love with his tee
shot, but that quickly faded when he saw the ball hit the slope and
stay well short, settling in a spot that would require him to
negotiate two severe breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Two putts would have been a welcomed achievement, but Nicklaus
got more than he bargained for. His putt was pure, it took the
first break, then the second, and found the center of the hole.
When it fell, the stern-faced, always-focused Nicklaus let loose.
He knew exactly what had just happened to the two gentlemen
standing back on the 16th tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``That did them (Weiskopf and Miller) in,'' said Nicklaus.
``That happens. You can't regroup yourself after you have a mindset
of what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Weiskopf and Miller seen the putt? ``See it,'' Miller would
later say. ``I had to walk through the bear prints.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiskopf tried to draw his approach into the pin _ nestled, as
it always is on Sunday, tight left _ but the shot came up well
short. Three putts later, he now trailed by one.
</P>
<P>
   Miller pulled into a tie with Weiskopf for second when he
birdied the 17th, then both hit their approaches within 15 feet on
18. Nicklaus stood in the scorer's tent, having finished par-par
for a 68. ``I felt surely that one of the two would make it and we
would be here on Monday having a playoff,'' said Nicklaus. But he
was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   First Miller. He played for a 26-inch break, but it moved a few
inches more. He settled for a 66 and an incredible weekend that had
produced 15 birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Weiskopf. His 9-iron approach had come to rest some 8 feet
from the pin. He watched Miller's putt break and couldn't believe
it when his didn't curl as much as he had anticipated. A runner-up
for the fourth time in this event, Weiskopf just stood and stared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say how I feel,'' said Weiskopf. ``How do you describe
pain?''
</P>
<P>
   That is left for individuals. As for great drama, you can
describe it as the 1975 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   A good match
</P>
<P>
   Laugh, if you will, but Karrie Webb vs. Tiger Woods is a more
intriguing head-to-head matchup than Sergio Garcia vs. Woods.
Perhaps he will turn things around, stop acting like a spoiled
brat, and quit trying to be the second coming of Woods, but for now
things are not going so well for Garcia. The swing is loose, the
expectations too high, and the schedule overwhelming. By August,
when he is scheduled to play Woods in that made-for-TV event,
Garcia's star could be totally burned out. Who knows? But what we
do know is that Webb is the real deal and since the beauty of golf
is that you can adjust the course to make things even, it is
conceivable that she could give Woods a good match. This would not
be Billie Jean King vs. an over-the-hill Bobby Riggs; it would pit
the two most dominant players in their respective sports, each in
their prime. Set the course up at 7,000 yards for Woods, 6,500 for
Webb and you'd have a fair, competitive battle . . . Dottie Pepper
was the best player in the field not named Webb at last week's
Nabisco Championship. Asked to compare Webb's 10-shot victory with
the way Amy Alcott was playing in 1991, Pepper was her usual candid
self. ``Actually I think it was closer to the way I played last
year, to be honest with you. I set the record by quite a few, I
think.'' You know, Pepper is one player who will gladly keep
challenging Webb on the golf course, something that tour
desperately needs . . . Aree Wongluekiet, the 13-year-old who
finished third in that Nabisco Championship, was penalized in the
final round after tournament officials viewed a replay of an
incident on the 14th green. As she settled into the address
position over her putt, Wongluekiet's ball moved ever so slightly.
She did not move it back to its original spot, which brought about
a two-shot penalty. ``She was matter of fact about it,'' said Barb
Trammell, the LPGA Tour's director of tournament operations, when
asked about Wongluekiet's reaction. ``She obviously would have
called for a ruling, but had no knowledge that the ball had
moved.'' . . . For Len Mattiace, there will always be questions
about the 17th hole at TPC Sawgrass where in 1998 he came unglued
and squandered his chance at victory in The Players Championship.
The class act he is, Mattiace answers them like a man. ``I am OK
with the hole. I did it. It happened, and I am OK with that,'' said
Mattiace at this year's tournament. Flash back to 1998: Holding a
lead and seemingly on his way to a final-round 65, Mattiace flew
the island green with a 9-iron, then hit his third shot into the
bunker. He skulled his fourth shot into the water, ended up making
a snowman, and opened the door for Justin Leonard's victory. The
fact that his mother, confined to a wheelchair and terminally ill
with cancer, was in the gallery made the story even more
heart-wrenching, but two years later Mattiace can face the
questions. ``I know I would have done things differently,'' he
said, ``and I would have hit different shots and all that. That is
put way back in the memory banks to draw on.'' . . . Darren Clarke
earned $1 million for winning the match play title against Woods,
but he noticed that the payout at The Players Championship was
more. $1,080,000 to be exact. ``The extra $80,000 could come in
handy,'' said Clarke . . . There are many players who think the
drop area at the island green 17th at TPC Sawgrass is a tougher
shot than the regular tee. Yet players don't practice shots from
there during pre-tournament rounds. Why? ``That is preparation for
a bad result. It is a defeatist attitude,'' said Hal Sutton . . .
Craig Stadler on his opening round of 83 at The Players
Championship. ``It was a thrill every minute. Actually it was very
enjoyable until we teed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Set your VCRs
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who can't wait until Thursday to get into
Masters mode, take note that USA will televise a one-hour preview
Wednesday night at 10. ``The Course of History'' will be
interrupted by just four one-minute commercials, so the bulk of the
hour will be devoted to a look at this unique tournament.
Interviews with Jose Maria Olazabal, Nicklaus, Palmer, and Woods
will be featured and there will be a look back at Gene Sarazen, the
beloved Squire who passed away at age 97 a month after last year's
Masters. USA will have live coverage of the Masters Thursday and
Friday 4-6 p.m., before weekend action shifts to CBS . . . As a
lead-in to its Saturday and Sunday coverage, CBS will show ``The
Story of Golf,'' a documentary that was produced by two Boston men,
John Carver and Tom Martin. The film is a must for golf fans, rich
in history, broad in scope, captivating in its presentation.
Narrated by Jim McKay, the film earned an Emmy nomination for best
script for George Peper, editor of Golf Magazine. ``It's the best
project of my life,'' said Carver. ``As a former caddie, coming
this far with the film is a great experience.'' It will be shown in
two parts on CBS: 2-3:30 Saturday, 3-4 Sunday . . . The Golf Course
Superintendents Association of America has bestowed its most
treasured honor, The Old Tom Morris Award, upon Nancy Lopez for her
commitment to the game of golf . . . You know there is some young
talent out there when the reigning US Amateur champ, David Gossett,
is ranked 18th in the MasterCard Collegiate Golf Rankings. Gossett
is a sophomore at the University of Texas. Matt Kuchar, a senior at
Georgia Tech, is ranked No. 1. . . . There has been a site change
for one of the upcoming State Four-ball qualifying rounds.
Presidents GC in Quincy will replace Braintree Municipal . . .
Would you like to improve your golf game? Prepare yourself mentally
for the upcoming season? Understand the dynamics of the swing? Get
a better feel for how physical strength could help? Then a one-day
session April 8 at the Radisson Hotel on the corners of Stuart and
Kneeland Street may be of interest. Dr. Patricia Hopkins, president
of Joint Ventures, and Tom Cavicchi, head professional at Wollaston
GC in Milton, have put together a group of experts who will discuss
various topics that can give you a better understanding of physical
golf. Physioballs, astar system, flexibility analysis, swing motion
trainer, balance evaluation _ those are just some of the
discussions and demonstrations to be covered, and a free driving
range is available to help with swing analysis. The admission is
$55 per person, with $20 of that going to the Arthritis Foundation.
The hours will be 9 a.m.-3 p.m. (lunch will be 11-1), and for
further information, check out drjointventures.com. You can pay
on-line, or at the door.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
