<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONNTENN-POINTGUARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG GUNS ARE OLD RELIABLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ For University of Connecticut coach Geno
Auriemma, the rivalry with Tennessee dates back to 1995, when his
team first played the Lady Vols in the regular season, and met the
following March in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Lawson and Sue Bird can look back to a much older rivalry,
one that dates back to when Connecticut's Bird was in the sixth
grade and Tennessee's Lawson was in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   It was an AAU ``under-12'' semifinal that pit Lawson's Vogues
team out of Washington, D.C., against Bird's Liberty Belles from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Both opposing point guards remember it vividly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in Salt Lake City, and we won by 9 points,'' Lawson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Bird: ``We called (Lawson) `pigtail' and I don't know why
I remember this, but she had a great hook shot. She was probably
the best player on her team even though she was the shortest.''
(Both point guards are now 5 feet 9 inches, and are still friends,
as are their dads, who met at that AAU game.)
</P>
<P>
   The next year the teams met again, and that time Bird's team was
victorious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never did face either again in AAU, so I think head-to-head
right now we're 1-1,'' Lawson said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the players are 2-2 if you count their collegiate
games when the schools played this season. UConn (35-1) won the
first game down in Knoxville, Tenn., and a month later the Lady
Vols (33-3) beat the Huskies in Storrs, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   So Sunday night's NCAA final at the First Union Center is not
just the rubber game of the season, but of the two programs. The
schools are 5-5 against each other in games dating back to January,
1995. Three were in NCAA tournament play, and in eight of the
meetings, one of the two teams was ranked No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's every coach's dream to make sure you're playing in the
last game of the year,'' said Auriemma. ``So we're playing in the
last game against the last team that's left besides ourselves, and
you can't get any better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have four players averaging double figures, so the
focus will be on Tennessee's Tamika Catchings (15.7) and
Connecticut's Shea Ralph (14.3).
</P>
<P>
   But the subplot is the battle of the point guards.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson is a freshman, and Bird a sophomore, but played only
eight games last year before she tore her left anterior cruciate
ligament and was out for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know most of the focus is on Shea and Svet (Abrosimova),''
said Bird. ``But that's both bad and good, because it takes the
pressure off.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lawson knows her team has to be wary of more than the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't overlook Sue like we did in the first game, when she
scored (a game-high) 25 points, you have to disrupt her and can't
give her open shots,'' Lawson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson's sporting days go back to when she played Pop Warner
football at 8 years old. She played running back and linebacker,
averaged three touchdowns a game, and was a guest on the ``Today''
show for their Athlete of the Week segment.
</P>
<P>
   But Lawson's father thought she'd hit a dead end with football,
so he talked her into giving it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought there wasn't much a future in it for me, so I just
kind of shopped around and started playing organized basketball in
third grade,'' Lawson said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to playing AAU ball and being a member of the USA
Women's World Team in 1998 that went to the Soviet Union, as a
senior Lawson received the Naismith Award as Player of the Year,
and set every record during her career at West Springfield High
School in Alexandria, Va. Meantime, Lawson started lifting weights
when she was a freshman, and can bench 235 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   So she was hardly a rookie when she arrived at the University of
Tennessee campus. She was asked to move to the wing instead of her
favored point guard spot, and had to defer to the older players
with NCAA playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the season, though, Tennessee coach Pat Summitt
decided to make some changes. The team had lost to Georgia, 78-51,
and Summitt gave the team a dressing down.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson moved over to the point guard spot, and the Lady Vols won
the next 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back to the point, I was glad, because that's
where I feel most comfortable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Summitt said Saturday she did question if a freshman point guard
could lead the team to a national title, ``but I have a great deal
of confidence in her and I believe she can.''
</P>
<P>
   Summitt also assessed the Lawson-Bird matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're two of the best point guards in the country,''
she said. ``I think Sue has a little more experience, but Kara can
really ignite us offensively, like she did last night.'' Lawson
scored a team-high 19 points with three assists against Rutgers
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma also praised Lawson, albeit with qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not a freshman, I don't think,'' Auriemma said. ``I
think we should check her birth certificate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird, meanwhile, is hoping to settle the score on a rivalry that
dates back almost 10 years, with February's loss still fresh in her
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that propelled us,'' she said. ``Now it's a split, and
it's winner take all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
