<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BELICHIC     04-01 2422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK, GROH UNDERSTAND RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bill Belichick may not yet know what the
rivalry between his new employer and his old one has come to, but
he knows what it's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the Army-Navy game,'' the Patriots' new head coach
said last week during a breakfast at the annual league meetings.
``I've learned there's a difference between Army-Navy and
Jets-Patriots. This league is built on winning championships; it's
not built on a one-game rivalry. It's 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Giants, beating the Redskins was beating a big rival,
but that's because they were a team we contended with to get to the
Super Bowl, not because they were a four-hour drive away or
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough perhaps, but as Pete Carroll learned the hard way
during his three years in New England, there is little in the NFL
at the moment to compare to the twice annual war between the Forces
of Evil (the Jets) and the Good Soldiers (the Patriots).
</P>
<P>
   It is a rivalry based not on common sense or common opponents,
but on a history of common hatred that dates back to the sale of
Babe Ruth to the Yankees and was fueled by the defections of Bill
Parcells to the Evil Empire two years ago and of Belichick back to
the Resistance Movement this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the next history of the NFL is written, there will be a
few chapters on what's gone on between the Jets and the Patriots,''
said Jets head coach Al Groh, the former defensive coordinator in
New England and longtime friend of both Parcells and Belichick.
``To say this rivalry doesn't exist or that there won't be those
elements of a rivalry involved when we play is to try and ignore
human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to understand human nature and deal with it is a
key requisite of coaching. The intuitive process in the world has
been all but eliminated. You don't need to figure out how to get
where you need to go anymore, you just call up maps.com. But a head
coach has to think about his team and the game they're going to be
playing to be at its highest level. So when it comes to the
Jets-Patriots, neither side wants to be facing the other at 0-3 in
the fourth game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having grown up in New York and subsequently lived in Boston,
I've seen the New York-Boston rivalry since the DiMaggio brothers
were playing center field. I understand this thing. Fans are
playing into that rivalry. Perhaps it will stay that way with the
fans longer than with the people inside our building, but it adds a
little juice to things. It's not like every third year you meet.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not make Jets-Patriots the Army-Navy game. In some
ways it makes it worse. Much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see some of what's gone on between these two teams and it
explains why nations fight over a taxicab crossing the border,''
Groh joked. ``Internally you may try and say it doesn't exist, but
there will be a few million people out there to remind us.''
</P>
<P>
   They will remind Groh in New York and they will remind Belichick
in New England. They will remind them both that this is not the
Army-Navy game; it's bigger than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think too much about that,'' Belichick said. ``I can't
control it or whatever happens. It's an important game, but it's a
16-game season. For us to go 2-14 and beat the Jets twice doesn't
mean much.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but to go 14-2 and lose twice to the hated Jets means
you're going to hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting the heights
</P>
<P>
   Word is that because of the failures of their recent midget
cornerbacks, the 49ers have decided they will not draft a corner
shorter than 5 feet 10 inches despite the argument that three of
the league's top ones are 5-9 or shorter. Because of the recent
success of tall receivers like the Vikings' Randy Moss and the
Jets' Keyshawn Johnson, the day of the Darrell Green style
fast-but-tiny corners may be, at least temporarily, coming to an
end . . . Like everyone else, the NFL is moving into the Internet
age by trying to figure out how to maximize its income. Some teams
would like to control their Web sites and the income generated from
them, but Patriots owner Bob Kraft is among those who favor pooling
revenue the way the current television setup does. ``The right way
to go is aggregation,'' said Kraft. ``On the other hand, as teams
develop their own home pages some will generate considerable
revenue. In the short term, we could probably do better
(individually), but for a long-term situation, the NFL is such a
name brand, that's the way to go.'' Meanwhile, the owners have
decided to give individual clubs the right to develop their sites
for another year as long as they do not make any deals that would
prevent a league-wide deal later . . . The major reason talk of
creating a flexible schedule for December and January to ensure the
hottest teams the most national exposure died was both Fox and CBS
feared losing its best games to ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' . .
. Groh said despite his team's hot 7-2 finish, it would be unfair
to blame New York's early failures simply on the loss of
quarterback Vinny Testaverde in the first game of the season.
``Sure there were some mitigating circumstances, but they didn't
shoot everybody after Vinny got hurt,'' Groh said . . . Groh grew
up not far from the Jets' training facility in Hempstead, N.Y., and
sees his return in a unique way. ``I earned one of my first
paychecks three-quarters of a mile from where I'm getting my next
one,'' Groh said. He's earning it differently though. His first job
was as a bouncer at a place called Ryan's. Groh, offensive
coordinator Dan Henning, and Testaverde all grew up within 10 miles
of each other and the Jets' home. ``I don't think there's ever been
a situation like this,'' Groh said . . . Here's how Belichick
described the offensive or defensive coordinator's life: ``The week
really starts on Thursday (10 days prior to the game). That's when
you start breaking down the film for the future opponent. Thursday,
Friday, and Saturday you work on that team as well as key up for
the team you're playing on Sunday. Sometimes you walk out for
practice at 1 p.m. and you don't know if it's going to be 80
degrees or 20 degrees. The most important thing after lunch is to
ask somebody who has actually been outside, `What do we wear?' You
learn to gauge what they say liberally. It's important to ask a guy
who knows how you dress in the weather.'' . . . Someone asked
Belichick this week if he would sleep at Foxboro Stadium the way
Parcells allegedly used to at Giants Stadium. ``If he did, it
wasn't often,'' Belichick said, a smirk on his face . . .
Indianapolis president and general manager Bill Polian received the
Sporting News's NFL Executive of the Year Award for his rebuilding
of the Colts. It's the fifth time he has won the award in 12 years.
The last time he won it, he got fired the next year in Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Temptations loom
</P>
<P>
   Belichick had an interesting point of view on ``can't-miss''
draft-eligible college players. This year, four are considered in
that category: Florida State wide receiver Peter Warrick, Penn
State defensive end Courtney Brown, Penn State linebacker LaVar
Arrington, and Alabama tackle Chris Samuels. Without commenting
specifically on any of them, Belichick said the two biggest
variables in the success of any player are time and money, ``the
two things they don't have in college,'' according to Belichick.
``You can't predict how those two factors will affect them. You
can't predict that. You've got to try and project it.'' . . . Old
friend Charley Armey not only has a new Super Bowl champion's ring
but he also has been handed a new contract making him the general
manager of the St. Louis Rams. Armey now will have final say in all
personnel matters, while Jay Zygmunt will become club president and
handle contracts and salary cap issues. Armey said he will work
closely with new head coach Mike Martz on all personnel decisions.
``You've got to get the head coach the players he needs,'' Armey
said. ``It has to be the right fit for him. It can't just be who
you like. I try to take the emotion out of the personnel business
and put the personality of the coach in the forefront. The player
has to fit the coach.'' . . . Browns quarterback Tim Couch has
slapped on an additional 13 pounds this offseason and not all by
lifting weights and drinking MET-Rx. ``Chicken and fish instead of
the cheeseburgers and cookies I used to eat,'' Couch says of his
new diet . . . Couch would love to be dieting on a feast of Warrick
pass receptions, but Browns coach Chris Palmer says Brown may be
just as significant a draft pick. Palmer said Warrick was
originally his leading draft candidate, but he's now also looking
at Brown and Arrington, in part because of Cleveland's woeful
defense. If Cleveland should take Brown or Arrington, Washington
would likely take the remaining Nittany Lion and Samuels, allowing
Warrick to slip to Cincinnati at No. 4. One wise NFC personnel man
insisted that the Bengals would be the big winner in that scenario.
``There's only one impact player in this draft and it's Peter
Warrick,'' he said. ``He's so much better than those other two
guys, it isn't even close. A skill player has to be good in only
one play in 65 to make an impact on the game. Those other two will
be good players, but Warrick is the only one this year who can
change the game.'' . . . The Patriots are in for a treat when they
face the 49ers at the annual Hall of Fame game in Canton, Ohio. All
living members of the Hall have been invited for the league's NFL
Century celebration. Normally 10-, 20-, and 30-year anniversary
inductees are invited back, but this year all 138 living members
will be asked to come . . . Players' Association regional director
Clark Gaines, a Jets running back 20 years ago, was not impressed
by the way Parcells handled the Jets situation. ``Bill Parcells was
his own worst enemy last year,'' said Gaines. ``He showed why a
general manager can't also be the coach.'' Gaines then went into a
mythical conversation between Parcells the coach insisting he
needed a backup quarterback (read Rick Mirer) and Parcells the GM
saying they shouldn't waste the money. ``How can there be any
objectivity in that?'' asked Gaines. ``He made a decision (to bring
in Mirer) that came back to haunt him.'' . . . Gaines also ripped
the Buffalo Bills' claims that they had to let defensive end Bruce
Smith go for salary cap reasons. ``That's bull,'' said Gaines.
``They knew a year ago they were in trouble. (GM) John Butler
doesn't know that, he should lose his job. They didn't go to Bruce
Smith and ask him to renegotiate a year ago. They asked him to take
a paycut at the last minute knowing he wouldn't. They wanted to
retool their team. They decided to go in a different direction when
they got rid of Smith. Look what they did after that (cutting or
refusing to re-sign running back Thurman Thomas and wide receiver
Andre Reed). What did the cap have to do with them retooling their
team? If that's what they're doing, have the intestinal fortitude
to tell the player. Don't blame it on the cap.'' Butler did just
that however. ``When I had to let Bruce, Thurman, and Andre go, I
had to think about whether or not I wanted to stay in this
business,'' Butler insisted this week. ``It's not supposed to end
like that with Hall of Fame players who helped make your team so
great. It was a very difficult thing to do.'' . . . One thing that
made it easier was the presence of end Marcus Wiley, whom Butler
believes is ready to blossom into a superstar pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs, or else
</P>
<P>
   Al Davis isn't the only owner putting the heat on his coach to
get into the playoffs. Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga said this week
that not even the loss of Dan Marino should keep his team out of
the postseason. ``To me, we've got to make the playoffs,'' Huizenga
said. ``To me, worst case, we've got to get into the playoffs. If
we don't, we'd have to examine why.'' (Read new head coach Dave
Wannstedt gets fired)'' . . . The Dolphins may be carrying this
Marino farewell a bit too far. They intend to keep his locker under
glass as a salute to what he meant to the Dolphins . . . Broncos
owner Pat Bowlen knows well the impact of losing a future Hall of
Fame quarterback, having lived through it last year with John
Elway's retirement. What Bowlen knows is that the Dolphins don't
yet know how much they've lost. ``The only thing I can say at the
moment is they're underestimating the effect it will have,'' Bowlen
said. ``I never would have guessed the total impact (Elway's
retirement) would have on the Denver Broncos in every area, even
off the field, (like) leadership in the clubhouse. Players look to
Dan Marino the way they did Elway, as the leader. The loss of that
presence means more than anyone can imagine.'' . . . New Saints
coach Jim Haslett was less than pleased to read the comments of
running back Ricky Williams in a recent Sports Illustrated article,
but his wife helped him get a new perspective on it. ``My wife
pulled out an article with some things I said about Buffalo when I
was 22,'' Haslett laughed. ``I ripped the city and all that kind of
stuff. She said, `Now you go tell him he was wrong.' He's young. He
was built up to be the king. The media didn't want to talk to
anybody else, and he didn't handle it all too well. I just want to
see him come in and run with the football.'' Haslett went back and
reviewed tape of Williams's games at Texas and also spoke with the
university's sports information director about how to best handle
him. But the best news he got regarding Williams came from newly
acquired free agent quarterback Jeff Blake. ``Jeff and I talked
about Ricky last week,'' Haslett said. ``He said, `Don't worry
about him. I'll take care of it.' '' . . . Haslett did learn one
thing though after reading Williams's comments about how his new
coach did not seem concerned about him as a man when the first
thing he asked him was if he'd been working out. ``Coaches don't
say, `How you doing?' '' Haslett said. ``They say, `You been
working out?' Now when I see somebody, the first thing I say is,
`How you doing?' '' . . . Williams is scheduled to meet with the
New Orleans media soon to clarify his feelings. Haslett said the
interview would not be done with Williams's helmet on, as was
Williams's practice last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
