</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RHEALCORMIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORMIER'S RAGS TO RICHES STORY IS RHEAL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was still a child herself when she began to indulge the
dreams of her own children. Jeannette Cormier, who grew up in a big
French-Canadian family, was 13 when she had her first baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father used to say,'' Rheal Cormier said, ``that my mother
could get pregnant from eye contact.''
</P>
<P>
   By 19, she was the mother of five, bagging lobsters in the
Paturel factory and tending to her family while her husband,
Ronald, was away for days at a time, hauling lobsters up and down
the Atlantic coast in his truck.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannette Cormier could never say no when her sons, Rheal and
Donald, came into the kitchen of their trailer home, asking to
borrow a cup of flour. In a place where summer was only a rumor, no
one in tiny St. Andre, or nearby Cap-pele, or perhaps in all of the
province of New Brunswick, loved to play baseball as much as her
little boys.
</P>
<P>
   So, if they needed some flour to draw their bases and foul lines
on the pavement outside, she would never say no. And she would look
the other way when the boys would practice their aim by throwing
rocks at the mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer?'' said Rheal Cormier, bronzed from a winter he spent
in his home on Florida's east coast, followed by six weeks in Fort
Myers preparing to pitch for the Red Sox. ``I know it's not long.
Maybe from the middle of June to the second week of August, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   But in that coastal ocean village hard off the Northumberland
Straits, the weather mattered little to the Cormier boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to play baseball in the snowbanks, sometimes when it
was minus 10,'' Rheal Cormier said. ``I remember one man who used
to drive up and down our street, watching us play. We'd be playing
catch in the snow, and he'd yell at us, `What, are you guys crazy?
What are you thinking about?' ''
</P>
<P>
   There were maybe 250 people in all of St. Andre. Why didn't they
play hockey, like other Canadian boys?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were too poor,'' Cormier said. ``We couldn't afford to play
hockey. If my parents bought equipment for one of us, they would
have had to buy equipment for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier is poor no more. As the only lefthander in the Red Sox
bullpen, he is due to make a salary of $2 million this season.
Jeannette Cormier, living in the house built for her by her son,
doesn't have to bag lobsters anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Cormier, who is 64, could have retired, too, like his son
has urged him, but he's now hauling logs part-time, because work is
what he does.
</P>
<P>
   There are some back in Cap-pele who begrudge Cormier his
success. You have money now, they tell him, but you'll always be
from Pee-Pee street, the derisive name those more fortunate had for
tiny St. Andre.
</P>
<P>
   And you know something? Cormier, who is as modest and humble and
self-effacing as anyone in the Sox clubhouse, tells them they're
right. He wouldn't want it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel bad about the area I lived in,'' he said. ``I
cherish every moment we had.''
</P>
<P>
   All of his brothers and sister still live there. It is only a
matter of time, Cormier said, that he moves back. His wife,
Lucienne, is a native, too. She was 14 when they met in high school
in Shedioc. She went to Paris and studied at the Sorbonne, then
came back and married her ballplaying beau. They've been together
eight years now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get really emotional when I talk in town,'' Cormier said.
``In church, they brought me up front once and I started crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have done so much for me. When I'm done, I'd like to do
something for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an improbable tale, this story of the kid who first saw
Fenway Park when his dad brought him along on one of his lobster
hauls to Boston and made it to the big leagues via a detour through
Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Art Pontarelli now scouts for the Colorado Rockies, but he was a
coach at the Community College of Rhode Island when he first
started running a clinic in Moncton, the capital city of New
Brunswick. That's where he first encountered an undersized lefty
who was self-conscious about being one of the few French-speaking
players on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they wanted me there,'' Cormier said.
</P>
<P>
   Pontarelli wanted him, though. He coached Moncton's team in a
national tournament of teenage players _ Matt Stairs, Oakland's
bashing designated hitter, was on that team _ and Cormier helped
pitch the team to the championship. Pontarelli brought both Donald
and Rheal to play for him in Rhode Island. They lived with him that
first year. When Rheal told him he couldn't afford to come back a
second year, Pontarelli helped him land a scholarship at the
University of New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left after a week,'' Pontarelli says now with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Cormier, who didn't like the coach's approach in New Haven, went
back to St. Andre and chopped wood for several months until he had
scraped enough money together to go back to CCRI. With Donald
Cormier playing second base, CCRI went to the Junior College World
Series for the first time in school history and finished third.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Rheal Cormier was a member of the Canadian Olympic
team. More significantly, he was drafted by the St. Louis
Cardinals, who made him their sixth pick in the 1988 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Within three years, Cormier was in the big leagues with the
Cardinals, and in 1992 he was in the St. Louis rotation, going
10-10 with a 3.68 ERA. He first came to the Red Sox in 1995 with
outfielder Mark Whiten in the Scott Cooper trade, and helped the
Sox win a division title.
</P>
<P>
   But that winter, Dan Duquette traded him to Montreal as part of
the package that brought Wilfredo Cordero to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Cormier hurt his elbow and underwent
reconstructive surgery that essentially sidelined him for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette brought him back as a free agent a year ago last
January. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan thought he'd have to begin the
season in Pawtucket, but Cormier surprised everyone by making the
team out of camp and was one of the team's most reliable performers
last season, appearing in a career-high 60 games, going 2-0 with a
3.69 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this is a second life for me,'' Cormier said of
his recovery from elbow surgery. ``I never thought I'd come back to
where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   And one day, as surely as Jeannette Cormier still has a sack of
flour, he will be back in St. Andre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
