<HEADLINE>
PLUCK EARNS HENDERSON THIS PUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years from now, the puck will be proudly displayed over the
fireplace. And Bruins left wing Jay Henderson will have fun telling
his family about how he got his first goal in the National Hockey
League.
</P>
<P>
   It put the Bruins in front Saturday, 1-0, 16:06 into the first
period against the New York Rangers at the FleetCenter, in a game
that ended in a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, called up three games ago from the American Hockey
League's Providence Bruins, his sixth elevation from the Bruins'
top farm team, also picked up an assist, his third, 12:55 into the
second.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11-inch, 188-pounder had 12 shifts (lasting 10:09)
and took two shots, one each in the first and second periods. But
it was his goal that had everyone's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Mikko Eloranta was skating over the blue line and took a shot,
missing to the left, and the puck bounced to Henderson just behind
the net. He flipped it in front, and it went off Kirk McLean and
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a lucky goal,'' he said. ``Mikko made a great
play, he missed the net, and it was a lucky bounce off the end
boards. I was hoping it would come up more than it did, and I
decided to throw it back up front to the guys going to the net. It
made a nice little bounce off the goalie. It wasn't the prettiest
goal I'll ever score, but I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson notched an assist on the goal by Antti Laaksonen, a
one-timer from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   As they have all season long, however, the Bruins allowed a late
goal, with 1:20 left in regulation, when Mike York tied it. It was
the 26th time the Bruins have gone to overtime this season, with
Saturday their 19th tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think there was anything wrong,'' said Henderson of
the events leading up to the late New York goal. ``I thought we
played very well defensively. Unfortunately, they scored in the
last two minutes. I guess (things like that) have been going down
all season and it's tough they scored in the last two minutes. I
thought we played well and we deserved a better outcome than we
got.''
</P>
<P>
   It's happened too often, and the Bruins have only one win in
overtime against six losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do have to learn to play in the last two minutes,'' said
Henderson. ``You've got to keep the puck in their end if you can.
The puck bounced out and they got a nice goal out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we played, we didn't give them much. They're a veteran
club and they scored a late goal and I'm sure that's not what were
looking for but for us, I thought we played a hell of a game. Any
time you allow a goal in the last two minutes of any period,
especially at the end of the game, it's frustrating. We deserved a
better outcome than we got.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said he was relaxed, partly because there are so many
Providence players with Boston (eight in all).
</P>
<P>
   ``(It was) nice and comfortable. We know all the guys,''
Henderson said. ``It's a little different than the end of the year
when you're not familiar with the faces here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
