<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKATE-WORLDS-KWAN-BOS     04-01 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-WORLDS-KWAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KWAN BACK ON CUTTING EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, France _ She had heard the whispers for months. That she
was washed up at 19, that she was crazy even to think of mixing
skating and classes at UCLA. But Saturday night, before a crowd of
more than 9,000 at the Palais des Expositions, Michelle Kwan
silenced her critics by climbing out of third place and snatching
back the world crown she lost to Maria Butyrskaya last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said, `She's over, she's deteriorating,' ''
said Kwan after she won her third title in five years. ``It felt so
great to skate well.''
</P>
<P>
   No woman ever had regained her title twice, and no one since
China's Chen Lu in 1995 had come from third to win. Kwan did it
despite skating first in the final group, beating two Russians with
no English-speaking judges on the panel and four from former
socialist countries. And she did it by pushing herself to the limit
and daring Butyrskaya and Irina Slutskaya to match her.
</P>
<P>
   When the 27-year-old Butyrskaya went wooden-legged in the
spotlight and Slutskaya failed to land either of her two
triple-triple jump combinations, Kwan was back on top of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first performance where I went on the ice and
pushed and pushed and pushed through the four minutes,'' said Kwan,
the first woman since Katarina Witt (in 1987) to win three titles
and the first American since Peggy Fleming in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, regaining her title was a tall order. Before the
International Skating Union added a qualifying round, any skater in
the top three could claim the title by winning the long program.
But once Kwan finished second to Slutskaya in her Wednesday
qualifying group and third in Friday's short program, she not only
needed to win Saturday night, she needed Butyrskaya to finish
third.
</P>
<P>
   Butyrskaya, who hasn't won a major event all year, was capable
of imploding and Kwan's camp knew it. ``Maria is a beautiful
skater,'' coach Frank Carroll said. ``But sometimes, she chokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, her rivals weren't the issue. Kwan was. She hadn't skated
a clean short and long program in a major event since the 1998
Olympics in Nagano and hadn't done it at the world championships
since she beat Chen for her first title in 1996 in Edmonton,
Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Slutskaya had beaten Kwan at this year's Grand
Prix final by landing two triple-triple combos. And Kwan had to
crawl out of third place to outpoint high-schoolers Sasha Cohen and
Sarah Hughes to retain her US title after falling in the short
program.
</P>
<P>
   If Kwan wasn't up to the mark here, she knew she could miss the
world podium for the first time in five years. So she abandoned
classes after Nationals, went to the rink, and worked herself back
into global form, focusing on the triple-triple she knew she'd need
to win here. ``I'd been saying that I needed to up the ante, but to
say it is easier than to do it,'' Kwan said. ``I have to do what I
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan had been skating brilliantly at her new practice rink in El
Segundo, within buzzing distance of the LA airport. All she had to
do was duplicate it here. ``Let it go,'' Carroll urged his pupil.
</P>
<P>
   She landed a perfect triple loop, hit the triple lutz-double toe
that has bugged her in the past, then nailed the triple toe-triple
toe that she'd once backed off. ``Every time I went into a jump and
thought, `Oh geez,' I went forward instead of holding back.'' Kwan
said. ``I didn't want to have anything left at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went through the triple salchow, triple flip, triple lutz,
seven triples in all. Kwan absorbed the standing ovation, skated
off in triumph, then went to the kiss-and-cry area and watched the
judges pointedly leave room for the Russians. ``I was feeling great
until the marks went up,'' she said. ``Then it was ugh-ugh-ugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she saw the 5.6s and 5.7s instead of 5.8s and 5.9s, Kwan
was resigned to finishing third or worse. There were still five
skaters left, including Butyrskaya, Slutskaya, homegirl Vanessa
Gusmeroli (the 1997 bronze medalist), and the 14-year-old Hughes,
who ended up fifth despite being woefully undermarked. ``I didn't
watch,'' Kwan said. ``I was trying to keep my mind off the skating.
It was a long 30 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   When she heard the marks, though, Kwan could guess at what
happened. Butyrskaya, who didn't even try a combination,
double-footed one salchow and popped another and landed only five
triples. And Slutskaya triple-doubled twice when two triple-triples
would have given her the title after she missed the Russian team
entirely last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy I'm second but I'm angry at myself that I'm not
first,'' said Slutskaya, who was second behind Kwan in 1998 at
Minneapolis. ``But I came back and I'm happy about that and I don't
finish last.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan has as much silver as she needs, finishing second in 1997
and 1999. This year, she wanted the top step again. ``I think I
cried 5,000 times today,'' said Kwan, after listening to ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' with her hand over her heart and a tear
trickling down her cheek. ``It's more satisfying this time. This
may never happen again. This moment, you have to cherish it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
