<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKW-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     04-01 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN NOT AFRAID TO FACE CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Most of Saturday afternoon was spent on lofty
comparisons. The country's two best women's basketball programs
were 36 hours away from meeting _ for the third time this season _
and people wanted historical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Would this UConn-Tennessee national championship game be
equivalent to the one in which Larry Bird and Magic Johnson
participated in 1979? Would it be Ali-Frazier? AOL-Microsoft?
Cain-Abel? Will a good performance Sunday night help sear the
women's game into the national consciousness?
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, when it comes to women's basketball, the
questions seem to go from left to right. As in: How can women do
what men already have done? Based on what we know about the Huskies
and Volunteers, the flow of that question needs to be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Right to left: How can men do what these women already have
done?
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies and Volunteers have shown everyone how to take fear
out of sports. They play in different conferences and are not
required to play one another during the season. But they did it
twice this season _ one win apiece _ and will meet at the First
Union Center Sunday night to play, as classic Southerner Pat
Summitt, the Tennessee coach, says, ``the sugar game.''
</P>
<P>
   This is revolutionary in college basketball and football.
Athletic directors, coaches, and athletes talk about ``meeting
challenges'' and ``overcoming adversity'' so much that it has
become numbing. So numbing that we often miss the obvious: It is
rare when they actually fulfill their words and embrace the most
difficult challenge.
</P>
<P>
   No team in the men's Final Four would ever schedule a
championship-level team twice if it didn't have to. The best
Division 1 football teams wouldn't do it, either. There obviously
isn't an equal amount of cash in the women's game as there is in
the men's, but Geno Auriemma and Summitt still didn't have a lot to
gain by scheduling each other during the season. Both have a
significant fan base, television exposure, and recruits who dream
of playing for them. Both have national titles.
</P>
<P>
   So why do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I crazy? Is that what you're saying?'' Summitt said with a
laugh Saturday. She said she spoke with Auriemma and that they both
had reservations about the home-and-home series. Imagine the
psychological advantage one of them could have had if it had come
into this game 2-0 against the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we did it,'' Auriemma said. ``But it surely wasn't
like, `Wouldn't it be great if we play three times a year?' Because
after a while, that will get old, too. The rest of the country will
go, `We hate both of you guys.' Now half the country likes us, the
other half likes Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Me? I like both of them. I like it when programs don't find
excuses to avoid each other. I think their ``dream'' matchup is
even more intriguing because they already have played twice and it
isn't clear which team is better.
</P>
<P>
   The fearlessness of both teams is not the only thing the men can
copy. Even though I often become nauseated by the annoying NCAA,
the organization is correct to call these women student-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee boasts a 100 percent graduation rate. The Volunteers
also have a brilliant freshman point guard named Kara Lawson. Her
brilliance goes beyond her 235-pound bench press. She was reading
at a fourth-grade level when she entered kindergarten. She says she
has a philosophy paper due on Monday. (Talk about accepting
difficult challenges. Lawson's topic _ same-sex marriages _ cannot
be classified as an easy one.)
</P>
<P>
   UConn has its brainiac-in-residence, too. Auriemma says
sophomore forward Asjha Jones is his smartest player, on the court
and off. ``She's got a great mind,'' Auriemma said. ``You know,
she's just very bright.'' Jones is much quicker than some of the
people who ask her questions. So when she gets a particularly tired
one, she is likely to give a Now-think-about-what-you-just-asked-me
stare.
</P>
<P>
   As for the game itself, I won't be surprised if both teams
approach 100 points in regulation. The Huskies have Big East Player
of the Year Svetlana Abrosimova, a 6-foot-2-inch forward who
probably has more all-around skills than anyone on the floor. The
Vols have Player of the Year Tamika Catchings, who dominated in a
Friday night win over Rutgers, even if she scored only 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Most followers of the game realize that most of the old left to
right questions are irrelevant. These women are playing basketball
and it's not a polite version of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee center Michelle Snow said she would compete against
her mother if Mom was standing between her and the national title.
She also said that she didn't appreciate the comments Auriemma and
Shea Ralph made about the Vols during one of Auriemma's coach's
shows. Snow said the team taped the ``disrespectful'' remarks and
may watch and listen before Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they need to use that as motivation, that's their choice,''
Auriemma said. Later, in so many words, he said the Vols need to
get a life.
</P>
<P>
   These teams respect each other, mostly because they have to.
They were 1-2 in 1990s winning percentage. They are 1-2 in the
national polls. They are 1-2 in recruiting. (Who is No.1? Depends
on whom you're rooting for.)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has a dig at UConn in its media guide called ``Tale of
the Tape.'' It compares national titles (6-1) and Olympians (10-1).
Auriemma dug at Tennessee's ``P.R. machine'' when it comes to
attendance and adding sarcastically, `` &UR; '' &LR; Tennessee is obsessed in
being No. 1 in everything they do.''
</P>
<P>
   If you left these two alone, they probably could produce a new,
highly rated provocative talk show. They clearly don't like each
other. Fine with me. At least they aren't afraid to face each other
on the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2225EST &QL; 
