<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4662 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-WALLACE     04-01 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-WALLACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACES WIN AS A FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a weekend it was for the Wallaces.
</P>
<P>
   They were all winners, in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Kenny Wallace, 36, the youngest of the three
brothers, earned a spot in the front row, joining pole-sitter Steve
Park, for the start of the Food City 500 NASCAR Winston Cup race at
Bristol, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Then last Sunday, Mike Wallace, 41, the second-oldest, won his
second NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series race of the season from the
pole position at Bakersfield, Calif. It was the same day Kenny
started up front and recorded a Top 20 finish _ his best of the
season _ and oldest brother Rusty, 43, won at Bristol, marking the
50th Winston Cup triumph of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolute pleasure to have us win on the same day,
along with Kenny starting in the front row for the Bristol race,''
said Mike, whose victory in the Dodge California Truck Stop 250 at
Mesa Marin Raceway helped him match his two-win total of a year ago
and top the $1 million mark in NCTS earnings. ``Rusty and I spoke
(Tuesday) a little bit and congratulated each other. He's getting
ready to go to Texas, and I have testing planned.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Craftsman Truck Series has an open date this weekend,
the Winston Cup Series will be making its Texas whistlestop for the
Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway near Fort Worth, where, no
doubt, the Wallaces will be riding a tidal wave of momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great weekend for us (at Bristol),'' said Kenny
Wallace, driver of the No. 55 Square D Chevrolet Monte Carlo owned
by Andy Petree. ``It was our best showing of the season, and it
puts us back on track. I'm happy with our top-20 finish and we hope
to continue to qualify well for each race.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Rusty? His 50th career victory couldn't have been any
more momentous. After all, it came on the same track, the .533-mile
bull ring at Bristol Motor Speedway, where Wallace recorded seven
previous victories, including the first of his Winston Cup career
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant so much to me,'' said Rusty, driver of the No. 2
Miller Lite Ford Taurus. ``I've been trying for so long to get that
No. 50, and I got it at my favorite racetrack. I love all these
racetracks, but Bristol has been my home.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace said he had his doubts about whether he'd ever get
No. 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to be almost where it was a jinx,'' Rusty said. ``We
kept talking about No. 50 and the wins just wouldn't come. Some
weird things would happen. Like Daytona, we had such a great run in
the Daytona 500 and I really thought if we could have got out of
the pits we could have won that race, because track position was
the most important thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let that slide and we got to Rockingham and a new track
record (for qualifying),'' he continued. ``We had a great race car
there and then the lugnuts came loose and we lost a lap having to
pit under green and I let that one slide.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was not about to let that happen at Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the radio and I said, `Don't let this one get screwed
up,' '' he said. ``I said, `I want it. This is an important race
for me.' (Crew chief) Robin (Pemberton) was really up on the pipe.
He was on the gas making sure everbody was doing their job right.''
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Wallace tied Ned Jarrett and Junior Johnson on
NASCAR's all-time win list. Wallace said he chatted with both
NASCAR legends during a roast last Friday night for the retiring
Darrell Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept having flashbacks to the early '80s, when I won
all those races and we had all the fun and everything was a little
bit more fun back in those days,'' Wallace recalled. ``But then
when I hit 47 and 48 wins and then 49, I started thinking, `Man,
I'd really like to have that 50th. That would be a special deal.'
''
</P>
<P>
   That it came at Bristol _ where his baby brother Kenny started
on the front row _ on the same day his younger brother Mike won his
truck race at Bakersfield, certainly made it all the more special.
</P>
<P>
   Road to recovery
</P>
<P>
   Almost two months removed from the horrific truck crash he
survived at Daytona, Geoff Bodine will make his first track
appearance at Sunday's race at Texas Motor Speedway. Bodine, who
suffered a concussion, a cracked vertebra, fractures to his right
wrist and elbow, and facial lacerations, hopes it will be the first
step toward a comeback aimed at the NAPA Auto Parts 500 at
California Speedway in Fontana. ``I'm feeling really great,''
Bodine said Tuesday during the NASCAR Winston Cup media
teleconference. ``I'm getting ready to go work out. I've been doing
that a week and a half now. I feel a lot better than I've felt in
the last few weeks. It's amazing how my recovery has gone.''
Initially, Bodine said he was in a constant state of grogginess
from all the pain medication, ``But I've been getting out more the
last two weeks, and this last week I've started feeling very good.
People say I look good and sound good, and I'm looking forward to
seeing everybody this weekend at Texas. We're anxious to see
everyone and get back to the track.'' Asked about his violent
crash, in which his truck was totaled, nine fans in the grandstands
were injured by flying debris, and a 120-foot section of catchfence
along the frontstretch was ripped apart, Bodine said, ``When that
wreck started, I thought it was going to be a normal little wreck
into the wall, no big event. When I hit the wall, it knocked me
unconscious. Right up until that point, I still thought it was
going to be a normal-type thing. I didn't think I was going to get
hurt or come so close to death like I did. I didn't think it was
going to be so traumatic.'' . . . Officials at Texas Motor Speedway
averted disaster when the track and, more important, fans camped
out for Sunday's race were spared injury and damage Tuesday when
tornadoes ripped through the Fort Worth area. ``We were very lucky
that the storms missed us,'' said TMS general manager Eddie
Gossage. ``The speedway sustained absolutely no damage and our fans
in the campgrounds, as well as employees, are fine.'' Gossage
indicated when track officials first learned of severe weather
moving through the area, security personnel were dispatched to
patrol the campgrounds and warn fans to seek cover. ``We were
concerned for the safety of our fans,'' he said. ``We had rain, but
the most severe weather was 20 miles or so to the south and east of
us. Getting to our fans as a precaution was a priority. We are
always cognizant of the potential for severe weather here in North
Texas and will always work to try and make our fans as safe as
possible.'' . . . A calamity of another sort befell former Winston
Cup driver Ernie Irvan when his Mooresville, N.C., home was
destroyed by a fire last Saturday. The fire, which is under
investigation, erupted while Irvan and his wife, Kim, and their two
children were returning from a family vacation in the Bahamas. ``I
feel real lucky that we were not in the house at the time,'' said
Irvan, who lost the entire contents of his home, including a trophy
room that contained all his racing memorabilia. ``I think it will
take a bit of time before we really can react to what has happened
to our home. It is really hard to lose everything. However, we will
continue to move forward with our life.'' . . . Dale Earnhardt
spent Thursday patrolling Interstate 65 near Birmingham with
Alabama state troopers, stopping unsuspecting but law-abiding
motorists and giving them tickets to the April 16 DieHard 500 at
Talladega as part of a race promotion and safe driving campaign.
Although Alabama state troopers ride in Ford cars, Earnhardt agreed
to do the promotion only if he could do so in a Chevrolet, noting
his allegiance to the GM auto maker as driver of the No. 3
Goodwrench Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``I don't think it would have
been politically correct for me to ride in a Ford,'' he joked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
