<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-BANNEDATHLETES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES LEFT OUT IN THE COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, FRANCE _ Even though everybody agrees that Russian skater
Elena Berezhnaya should have read the label before taking the
bronchitis medicine that cost her a chance at a third straight
world pairs title last week, it's time that sporting federations
drew a distinction between ``Sudafed positives'' and stimulants
designed to improve performance.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, winter athletes get congested all the time. Yet most of
the drugs that make them feel better (and which anyone can buy at
the local pharmacy) containe ephedrine. Not massive amounts. Small
amounts. ``We never thought the medicine would improve their
artistry, or the skill of their jumps or the height of their
throws,'' said Tamara Moskvina, who coaches Berezhnaya and partner
Anton Sikharulidze.
</P>
<P>
   Caffeine is taboo, too, but only in massive amounts. A few cups
of coffee or a 2-liter bottle of Coke won't get an athlete banned.
Neither should a normal dose of cold medication. Meanwhile, the
federations are losing the big war against steroids, testosterone,
EPO and human growth hormones _ the stuff that makes the difference
between a gold medal and fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   Save the formalities
</P>
<P>
   Look for the International Skating Union to make the top 20
skaters exempt from the hated qualifying round at next year's world
championships _ as long as they compete in their continental
championships. Another proposal, less likely, is to allow skaters
to start from scratch once they've qualified. ``If it's just to
qualify, I'd land my first two jumps and walk through the rest,''
muses US champion Michael Weiss. Though the quallies count for only
20 percent, they matter significantly in the final tally. When
Michelle Kwan finished second in hers here and third in the short
program, she all but put herself out of contention for the gold
medal . . . No chance for Tara Lipinski to defend her Olympic crown
in Salt Lake City, even if she asks to have her eligibility
restored. No pros allowed, says ISU president Ottavio Cinquanta.
``Never, ever,'' he vows. ``They leave the ISU and decide to skate
outside. No possibility. One hundred percent excluded.'' . . . If
figure skating is a sport, not an art, why is the artistic mark the
tiebreaker in the long program? ``If we both lift 60 kilograms and
you do it smiling, you are better than me,'' Cinquanta reasons.
``That is why the artistic mark is more important.'' . . .
Three-time men's skating champion Alexei Yagudin on the post-Worlds
letdown: ``In 4 1/2 minutes your season is over and you are
completely dead. You are working six to eight months to be dead.''
. . . This year's US figure skating championships in Cleveland set
records for both attendance (118,000 at Gund Arena for the week)
and profits (expected to be nearly $1 million). That's the
benchmark for next year's event at the FleetCenter, which will be
the first nationals held in Boston since 1962, when the site was
BC's old McHugh Forum . . . The heat will be turned up gradually
for the US women's ice hockey team at this week's world
championships in Ontario. They'll start Monday with the Germans and
face the Russians on Tuesday before meeting the Finns on Thursday.
If form holds, the Americans will play the Canadians (who beat them
last year after losing in the Olympics) in Sunday's final . . . The
NHL and the international ice hockey federation aren't any closer
to getting the pros back to Olympus for 2002. European associations
are still pushing for increased transfer fees for players who sign
with NHL clubs and the league doesn't want the issue linked to the
Games. Next meeting will come at next month's world championships
in Russia. Back on the bench as US coach there will be Lou Vairo,
who directed the Americans at the 1984 Olympics in Sarajevo. He's
been USA Hockey's special projects director for the past eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   One more for the case
</P>
<P>
   By winning the Algarve Cup in Portugal recently, the US women's
soccer team grabbed the only major trophy it lacked. Though the
Americans won two World Cups and an Olympic gold medal, they were 0
for 5 at the Algarve, with two losses in the final. Sweet irony for
Brandi Chastain, whose penalty kick was the only goal in the
crowning victory over Norway. Her PK off the woodwork cost her
teammates last year's title match with the Chinese . . . The
shakeup at the US Olympic Committee continues under new chief exec
Norman Blake. Latest to leave (after only nine months) is deputy
marketing director Dave Ogrean. Blake plans to flatten and
streamline the organization and has hired a firm to bring in
outsiders as his top aides . . . Next step toward Olympus comes
Sunday for Fall River judoka Joe Felton, the ex-Detroit Lion. If he
wins a medal at the Rotterdam tournament, he earns the right to go
head-to-head for the Olympic heavyweight spot with top rival Martin
Boonzaayer at the US championships later this month. If not, Felton
gets a final chance two weekends from now at the British Open,
where he won bronze last year. Already on the squad are Lawrence's
Jim Pedro and Alex Ottiano . . . Looks like any straight arrow with
a bow-and-arrow can make the US men's Olympic archery team. Two of
the original three are already gone _ Shane Parker for cheating
(firing two extra arrows) at last year's trials and now double gold
medalist Justin Huish for possessing marijuana with intent to sell.
Though he pleaded not guilty, Huish gave up his spot to avoid
creating a circus around the team. That leaves Vic Wunderle as the
lone ranger; Rod White and Butch Johnson are the replacements. The
good news for Huish is that he's got a wild card for the 2002
Canadian snowboarding team.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the Charles . . .
</P>
<P>
   Boston won't be getting this summer's US Olympic canoe-kayak
trials after all. The federation had wanted to use the stretch on
the Charles between the Harvard (i.e. Mass. Ave.) and BU bridges,
but ran into permit problems with the MDC, which would have needed
to halt river traffic on a June weekend. The federation wasn't
interested in Worcester's Lake Quinsigamond (perennial site of
rowing's Eastern Sprints), since it wanted big-city exposure. So
it'll use Chula Vista, Calif., because it's a ready-to-use venue on
a protected reservoir . . . The US freestyle wrestlers, who picked
up two more Olympic berths at the last-chance qualifiers, will be
one of three countries (with Russia and Ukraine) sending a full
eight-man team to Sydney. The greco-roman side, which picked up one
more spot, will send four . . . How badly does the IOC want the top
soccer players at Sydney? Badly enough to ask the international
federation to grant more over-23 exemptions and to reschedule some
European cup matches that conflict with the Games. In return,
president Juan Antonio Samaranch is offering to move the 2004 Games
in Athens from mid-August to the end of July to avoid clashing with
the beginning of the European club season. That would be a problem
for the Athens organizers, though, since July there is hotter and
more crowded . . . Dominique Moceanu won't be among the 15 elite
gymnasts invited to Bela Karolyi's Houston boot camp this month.
But she's made such ``amazing progress,'' the US technical
coordinator says, that she's been asked to the next one in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
