<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-HINGIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS TURNS TABLES ON DAVENPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ The litle kid (``finally . . . I'm so
happy'') got back at the neighborhood bully.
</P>
<P>
   The stalked one, Martina Hingis, chortled, ``Now I'm the
hunter!''
</P>
<P>
   This may require some interpretation. Hingis, the teen tyke who
at last beat up on her towering tormentor, Lindsay Davenport,
Saturday, 6-3, 6-2, in a whirlwind 58 minutes to win the Ericsson
Open, has been stalked by two people, on and off the tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport has been hounding and haunting Martina for a year,
whipping her five straight times and seizing her No. 1 ranking
early Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday, a man described by Hingis as ``strange . . . maybe
a little crazy'' was arrested by Miami police for trespassing and
stalking (both misdemeanors) at the tourney site, Crandon Park.
</P>
<P>
   He, Dubrayko Rajcezic, a 45-year-old Croat, has professed a
romantic interest in 19-year-old Martina through mail, faxes, and
conversations. She said, ``I told him I already had a friend and
was very happy. I said I didn't want him around so close, and the
police took care of it. I wasn't too concerned because of my
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Her current great-and-good friend happens to be husky Pavel
Kubina, whose sporting tool is a crooked stick with which he toils
for the Tampa Bay Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, now I'm the hunter,'' Hingis said, smiling. ``I'm No. 2,
like Lindsay was, and now I'm after her.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport didn't indicate she would call the cops to restrain
Hingis as they have Rajcezic, who was released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brazilian Gustavo Kuerten will try to handcuff
another favorite, Pete Sampras, in the male showdown Sunday
afternoon. Sampras hungers, having been deprived of his foremost
love (a title) since November.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, the reigning 6-foot-3-inch Wimbledon and Australian
champion, who has an eight-inch and four-year edge on 19-year-old
Hingis, seemed gone with the wind that gusted throughout the palm
tree-ringed stadium. She couldn't control her usually lethal
groundies, which sailed into the net or beyond the lines for a gang
of unforced errors, accounting for 40 of Hingis's 57 points.
Hingis's goofs totalled 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly,'' Lindsay said, shrugging. ``When Martina won the
first four games, I started to feel like Monica (Seles, whom Hingis
whomped, 6-0, 6-0, in the semis). Then I won the next three games.
If I'd got to 4-4 . . . well . . . but she broke me (to 5-3), and
she was fine again. She wasn't visibly frustrated anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   For such a cool cookie, Hingis was surprisingly unable to bury
her anxiety over the way Davenport had been punching her out. She
confessed an inability to deal with Long Lindsay, and appeared
soundly psyched out.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday she handled the wind well, retrieving brilliantly
and pressuring Davenport to go for too much. ``The stronger,
dangerous hitters, like Lindsay, the Williamses (1999 finalists
Venus and Serena), and Mary (Pierce) seem to have trouble in the
wind. I like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking more today, making sure I got my first serve in
(Hingis had 72 percent, compared to Davenport's 51).''
</P>
<P>
   Notably cerebral as a player, Hingis has gone through a period
of trying to outbash rather than outbrain her more sinewy rivals,
but she says that's over, and thinking is back in style for her.
</P>
<P>
   She and Davenport reached 2-2 in the second set, whereupon
Hingis ran the asphalt table, adding this one to her 1997 title
here, to the cheers of 13,529 patrons. She not only ended her own
domination by Davenport but severed the loser's 21-match winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``No excuses, but I felt heavy, flat,'' Lindsay said. ``I had a
hard time beating Sandrine (Testud in a game) that ended after
midnight Friday morning (6-1, 6-7 (4-7), 7-6 (7-5)), and I didn't
recover as well as I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The bully got bullied this time, but, as the kid says, ``We're
gonna play a lot more, and I'm on the hunt again.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2229EST &QL; 
