<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS LOWE SAVED BEST FOR LAST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Derek Lowe is the Red Sox closer, the man who will be
entrusted with the ballgame just about any time the Sox have a slim
lead in the ninth inning. It takes a certain kind of stuff and a
specific personality to handle the role. Lowe thinks he has the
tools.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe is Nuke LaLoosh with great control. He's 6 feet 6 inches, a
bony 200 pounds, with a great sinkerball and all the character of a
class clown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's loose out there, all right,'' says veteran third baseman
John Valentin. ``He's always asking me, `Val, what should I throw
this guy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to kid around,'' says Lowe. ``I'll talk to the ball.
I'll talk to myself out there. On this team, everyone has their own
attitude. You play 162, you gotta stay loose. I like to flip the
ball in the air. Those are my antics. I try to remember that it's a
game and do the same things I've been doing since high school. For
me to change at this stage would be crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have a history of flamboyant closers. In the days before
closers were All-Stars _ pampered with lofty status and bogus
``saves'' _ Dick Radatz would finish a game, then raise his arms
over his head. Radatz was ``The Monster'' and he made a career out
of striking out Mickey Mantle with the bases loaded. John Wyatt,
who came on board in '67, spoke his own language and made news by
getting conked on the back of the head by a catcher's throw to
second base.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had no true closer in 1975. Dick Drago and Jim
Willoughby shared the chore, but when it came down to the ninth
inning of the seventh game of the World Series, rookie Jim Burton
got the ball. Eleven years later, John McNamara kept handing the
baseball to a soft rich kid with scared eyes. Calvin Schiraldi spit
the bit in both Games 6 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   Flash Gordon in 1998 was the best closer the Sox ever had.
Dennis Eckersley and Rod Beck came here after putting out fires in
other cities. And now Lowe is the guy who gets the ball at the end
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Used in long and short relief last year, he pitched 74 innings,
compiling a 6-3 record with a 2.63 ERA. He walked only 25 and
fanned 80 in 109 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm ready for the season,'' Lowe acknowledged.
``As far as closing goes, I got a little glimpse of it last year,
but I really only had like seven or eight true saves. A lot of 'em
were three-inning saves, which really aren't crunch-time saves. But
it's gonna be exciting. The main thing is, I have to pitch my game.
My game is ground balls and make 'em hit it early. I'm not
necessarily gonna try to strike anybody out. But in the last two
years, I've pitched in a lot of tight games, including the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe was 1-1 in the Division Series against the Indians, then
gave up only one run over 6 1/3 innings in three ALCS appearances
against the Yankees. He struck out seven Yankees and walked only
two. When Gordon went on the shelf with arm surgery, he was handed
the closer role. No Beck. No questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   The hard sinker is easy to spot. So is the goofiness. Lowe has
fun. He has an easy laugh. He plays catch with teenagers who hang
around the Sox practice site. When a 9-year-old Jimmy Fund patient
walked around City of Palms Park with a ball in his hand, Lowe
strapped on the catcher's gear and caught the courageous kid.
</P>
<P>
   Good closers don't take the losses too hard. They hear the boos,
answer the media, then forget about it. It's the only way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you have to do,'' says Lowe. ``When you mess up a
game, you may have to pitch the next day. You're gonna get that
ball every single time your team is close in the ninth inning. You
have to have a quick memory _ good or bad. I think that's where my
laid-back attitude is gonna help me because I really don't get too
high or too low. Being around Eck and Flash, and Rod, I see they
are confident, but they're not arrogant. They just know they're
gonna get the job done. I'm hoping to get that confidence from the
team because when Gordon was here, every time he got the ball in
the ninth inning, we knew we were gonna win. That comes with going
out there and proving you can do the job over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Jimy Williams says, ``To me, Derek did a fine job
last year. What really helped him was being in the middle early in
the year. We had Gordon, then we used Wakefield. I think it matured
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Sox are so pleased, they reportedly are putting the
finishing touches on a four-year, $10 million contract for the
closer.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe was originally drafted by the Mariners. In a trade that is
assuming Dennis Johnson-for-Rick Robey dimensions, he was acquired
along with Jason Varitek for the inimitable Heathcliff Slocumb. A
bustout as a starter (``that disappointed me, but I was 3-13 as a
starter, so I understand'') Lowe's proven to be gold in the
bullpen. He's had a fair spring and should get the ball Tuesday in
Seattle if Pedro Martinez is ahead of the Mariners after eight.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's happy to return to Seattle now that the Mariners
play in Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I had a career ERA of 7.50 in the Kingdome,'' says
Lowe. ``I watched the implosion last week and had a smile on my
face. The new park is much more pitcher-friendly. It's nice to go
to Seattle not having to pitch in the Kingdome.''
</P>
<P>
   He pledges not to complain when he's hunted and hounded after
surrendering his first walk-off piece of the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, it's gonna happen. But I enjoy the people in
Boston. Every game means something. If you're struggling, you hear
about it and you should hear about it. But when you're having
success, it's a great place. It doesn't matter if it's April, June,
or September. And that's fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   It's April. Starting Tuesday, the games count. And the Sox are
counting on Lowe to finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2230EST &QL; 
