<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RELEASE CANDIOTTI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The Angels finalized their opening day roster
Saturday and the final cut was the unkindest cut of all for rookie
manager Mike Scioscia, who released pitcher, friend and former
teammate Tom Candiotti.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the move was a surprise since Candiotti,
invited to camp as a non-roster player, had showed he'd recovered
from off-season knee surgery and served as an insurance policy for
the Angels youthful staff. On the other hand, Candiotti is 42.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what you want to call it --- odd man out, old man
out,'' said Candiotti after the Angels' 8-7 loss to the Padres at
Qualcomm Stadium. ``It didn't work out. It was a crowded situation
--- in the end, what's working against you is your age.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, who played with Candiotti for the Dodgers in 1992, had
hinted Friday that Candiotti would be a valuable veteran presence
in the bullpen and said he wasn't afraid to use the knuckleballer
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an easy day,'' Scioscia said. ``He's a friend and
I have the utmost respect for him. He can still pitch, but we have
a lot of good arms. There was no room to keep him. I'd love to have
a role for him, but he was insurance that was too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti was the victim of Mike Fyhrie, who was one of the few
Angels pitchers to shine this spring, and Derrick Turnbow, a
live-armed rookie who was plucked from the Phillies organization
under the Rule V draft and must spend the season with the Angels or
be offered back to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Fhyrie, a right-hander from Ocean View High and UCLA, had a 2.08
ERA, three walks and allowed opponents to bat just .220 against him
in 13 innings this spring. Turnbow, who spent last season at
Single-A Piedmont, allowed two runs in two innings Saturday but
they came when center fielder Edgard Clemente misplayed Jake
Thrower's fly ball into a two-run triple.
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti, who contacted the Angels this winter because of his
relationship with Scioscia and pitching coach Bud Black, a former
teammate in Cleveland, had no complaints about the spring. He got
plenty of work (a 6.85 ERA in 22 1/3 innings), threw reasonably
well considering the thin air of Arizona harms knuckleball pitchers
and isn't ready to conclude his 14-year big league career just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the year I had (a 7.32 ERA with Oakland and Cleveland)
and the surgery, I didn't know if I was going to be able to
compete,'' Candiotti said. ``I think I showed that I could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will start the season with 12 pitchers: starters Kent
Bottenfield, Ken Hill, Jason Dickson and Scott Schoeneweis, and
relievers Fhyrie, Turnbow, Troy Percival, Al Levine, Shigetoshi
Hasegawa, Kent Mercker, Lou Pote and Mark Petkovsek.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker is the only left-hander in the bullpen, but the shape of
the staff figures to change in the next month when Ramon Ortiz,
Jarrod Washburn, Tim Belcher are due to come off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels purchased the contracts of Mercker and utility
infielder Benji Gil after Saturday's game. Gil is one of six
infielders, joining Gary DiSarcina, Troy Glaus, Adam Kennedy, Mo
Vaughn and Scott Speizio. Bengie Molina and Matt Walbeck are the
catchers and Garret Anderson, Darin Erstad, Tim Salmon, Orlando
Palmeiro and Clemente are the outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who have committed 38 errors this spring, didn't
have a good day in the field. Besides Clemente's misplay, second
baseman Kennedy let Wiki Gonzalez's two-out, bases-loaded grounder
get under his glove for two runs that tied the score in the eighth
and Gil, at shortstop, made two poor throws in the ninth inning ---
the final one pulling Matt Walbeck off the plate, allowing Eric
Owens to score the winning run. ... Mo Vaughn hit a fifth inning
grand slam, his fourth homer of the spring, while Garett Anderson
added a solo homer, his sixth of the exhibition season. ... Angels
pitchers allowed two homers Saturday, giving them the major league
lead this spring with 51. Entering Saturday's games, Florida had
allowed 50, Arizona 49 and Boston 48 ---- those are the only teams
that are within 6. ... The Angels play Cal State Fullerton today at
1 p.m. at Titan Field in their final tuneup for Monday night's
regular-season opener against the Yankees at Edison Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
