<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PITINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO IN A SCHOOL DAZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goodness knows, it's a risky proposition taking Rick Pitino at
his word these days. But barring any subtitles when he speaks, we
will take that risk, with the understanding that maybe he means it
only when he says it.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday's rambling, almost Belichickian Q &AMP; A was
revealing in many ways. Do we believe Pitino got religion on the
plane ride after all he has seen this season? Maybe. Do we believe
he will leave next year if his team again misses the playoffs?
Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   What struck me, however, was Pitino's reference to Florida coach
Billy Donovan and what Pitino says moves him the most as a coach.
My conclusion: Rick Pitino should get back to college, pronto. He
is never, ever, going to find in the NBA the ``gratification'' he
seeks as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what he said when asked about his future: ``My decision
will be based on a reality that hit me this week, as I was watching
Billy Donovan up on the podium speaking, as I was watching his team
sacrifice. I started all night thinking about him as like a
Pillsbury doughboy in 1986 and looking at him out there, I was
amazed at how much polish he had and how he has gotten his young
team to sacrifice. And I realized, although it's very small, I had
a small part in his life (as Donovan's coach at Providence).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give some thought process of whether I'm making a
difference in the lives of athletes. Because that's where I get my
gratification. I've been to four Final Fours. And that's nice. It
really is. But, I look at what I accomplished in developing
athletes as basketball players and as people, and that's where I
get my gratification as a teacher. What I'm saying is if there
comes a day where I don't feel I'm teaching all of those things,
then I will look at myself and say, `Maybe it's (time for) a change
in scenery.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If he really wants to affect the lives of his players on and off
the court, it is not going to happen in the NBA. More to the point,
neither Paul Gaston, nor any other owner, wants or expects that of
a coach. Character development simply is not a criterion for an NBA
coach. It may be important to Pitino, but the NBA is not about
``making a difference'' in athletes' lives; it's about making a
difference in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   It's entirely understandable that Pitino wants to make such an
impact at this level. As a pure coach, he might have a chance if he
didn't have himself as a player procurement director. But as a
coach/guidance counselor/therapist, he has no shot. He says that if
it doesn't work for him in Boston, he will seek a pro job
elsewhere. But who would hire him? Pitino would have to surrender
money, power, and buzz, and that's assuming that any team would be
interested in him after what has happened in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino also keeps saying that he wants no part of college
basketball, that he's disturbed by where it is going and, well,
where would he go and what else could he do? He has won his title.
So what? Why not another? He could be the first coach in NCAA
Division 1 history to win a title at different schools.
</P>
<P>
   He also could go where he could put on all his hats and ``make a
difference,'' where he could mold players who are in the moldable
stage of life, where he could charm boosters and alumni, talk up
recruits, and be what he wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   College ball is where he should be because it has what he truly
wants.
</P>
<P>
   Miles ahead
</P>
<P>
   The consensus of the scouts and general managers at last
Wednesday's McDonald's All American festivities was that
6-foot-8-inch Darius Miles of East St. Louis, Ill., emerged as the
clear favorite to be the first high schooler picked in the 2000 NBA
draft. The only thing that could prevent that would be if Eddie
Griffin came out and if Miles blew all his interviews. That's what
happened two years ago to Rashard Lewis, who lasted until the
second round because he had poor visits. Scouts liken Miles to a
Tracy McGrady-type player who can fill up a box score. He's also
apparently not interested in going to school, even though he has
committed to St. John's. Right now, depending on which
underclassmen come out (Stromile Swift, Chris Mihm, and Marcus
Fizer are the big undecideds; Fizer has a press conference
scheduled for Monday at which he is expected to go pro), Miles
could be a top 10 pick. As for the others, Griffin seems intent on
spending some time at Seton Hall. Gerald Wallace, Mario Austin,
DeShawn Stevenson, and Alton Ford are seen now as fence-sitters who
would likely go mid-to-late first round. (Ford committed to
Houston, but coach Clyde Drexler has left, so his situation has
changed.) Jerome ``Buddy'' Harper, meanwhile, still is college
shopping and, scouts say, should keep at it. One GM described
Harper's pro prospects now as ``ludicrous'' . . . This was a big
week for dustups. We had the suspensions/nonsuspensions in Boston.
We had Vernon Maxwell and Gary Payton fighting in Seattle. We had
Karl Malone and Jerry Sloan exchanging unpleasantries to the point
where Sloan skipped the post-game news conference for the first
time in his 14 years as coach of the Jazz. The Mailman passed it
off as two competitive guys going at it. And on Thursday, we had
Antonio Davis and Charles Oakley wondering why Vince Carter and
McGrady are getting all the touches on offense. Geez, by Friday,
the Celtics were a comparative Tranquility Base . . . How's this
for cheap: Lionel Hollins, who took over as Vancouver's coach in
December, still is being paid his assistant's salary. He went
public with his situation last week and it looks like he's caught
between a rock and two owners. The present owner is getting out and
figures he'll simply sit on it. The prospective new one has said
it's not his problem. The Grizzlies, meanwhile, have bottomed out
big time after a few, encouraging stretches. They have lost 15 of
16 heading after dropping Friday night's game with the Knicks, but
needed only one victory in their last 12 games to set a season
record for wins: 20 . . . When the NBA Board of Governors convenes
for its annual April meeting, one issue will be the grandfathering
of all those big, pre-maximum contracts to make them less
susceptible to the upcoming luxury tax. ``There's definitely an
issue there,'' says Indiana GM David Kahn. How might it work? Well,
in the case of Kevin Garnett, perhaps his ``luxury tax'' number
would differ from his real number, with the former being whatever
the maximum would be under the new system. Garnett, Shawn Kemp,
Juwan Howard, Alonzo Mourning, and Shaquille O'Neal are some of the
big contracts signed before the new system went into place . . .
With Orlando hoarding all its cap money and hoping to make a big
hit, we asked Penny Hardaway if there's a downside to playing in
Hooterville as ``the man.'' He knows. So does Shaq. Both got out.
``Part of the problem with me and Shaq is that there were huge
expectations that we brought on ourselves for playing so well,''
Hardaway said. ``I can't speak for Tim Duncan or anyone else, but
the situation didn't work out for me and Shaq. I know they have a
new coach and a new system there, so I can't say how it will all
work out. My experience and Shaq's experience was the same. There's
a lot of pressure on you down there to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Magic reassessment
</P>
<P>
   The more you see the Magic's Darrell Armstrong, the more you
understand just how valuable he is to that team. Pitino calls
Armstrong ``one of the dominating players in our league at what he
does. You don't think of him that way, but you have to give him a
lot of credit. If you look at what he does for his team, he's a
dominating point guard.'' First-year Orlando coach Doc Rivers sees
the same qualities. ``He plays so hard, every day,'' said Rivers.
``And if your best player is also your hardest worker and wants to
practice hard, everyone else falls in line.'' But the reason the
Magic acquired Anthony Johnson was because Rivers was worried about
Armstrong falling apart. Alas, there's another big guard on the
Orlando roster: Chauncey Billups, who, lest we forget, came over
along with Ron Mercer from Denver. He's out for the year, but, he
insists, not out of options. ``Orlando wouldn't do the trade
without me in it,'' Billups said. ``They want a big point guard for
the Eastern Conference. Darrell is 31. And they're thinking to make
his career longer, they want me to be that sixth man, (to) give me
the opportunity here. I know Doc likes me because he sees a lot of
him in me. I think it'll be a good situation.'' Said Rivers, ``I'd
like to talk to (Billups). I think he'd like to stay here. He came
here to rehab when he didn't have to. He could have stayed home in
Denver. That says a lot to me. But he's also not playing, so it's
difficult to judge.'' . . . One of the real, stick-to-it stories
this year has unfolded in Milwaukee with Darvin Ham. He had brief
stints with Denver, Indiana, and Washington and spent last season
in Spain. When Scott Williams ``plateaued'' (George Karl's
description), the Bucks coach turned to the energetic Ham, who was
signed as a free agent last September. He's still starting. Asked
how he maintained his optimism, Ham shrugged and said, ``I just
prayed. I knew when the time came, I'd be prepared to take
advantage. It's hard, going from place to place, not knowing where
you're going to be the following year. But all you can do is stay
focused. There's only about 435 of us in this league and there's
millions of guys who want our jobs. So I can't complain if I'm on
the active roster, inactive roster, whatever. I just have to make
sure I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizin' 'em up
</P>
<P>
   One NBA executive's top draft picks, regardless of whether the
players will declare for the draft. Excluded are players who have
said they will stay in (or go to) college:
</P>
<P>
   1-5 (in any order): Kenyon Martin, Swift, Mihm, Fizer, Courtney
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   6-12: Troy Murphy, Morris Peterson, Mike Miller, Joel Przybilla,
Miles, Etan Thomas, DeMarr Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Teens: Erick Barkley, Mateen Cleaves, Wallace, Jamal Magliore,
Chris Carrawell, AJ Guyton, Jabari Smith, Jason Collier, Vincent
Yarborough.
</P>
</TEXT>
