</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE A MOST VALUABLE ADDITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Ray Bourque we've seen the last three weeks in Colorado
were the Ray Bourque we saw here for the first five-plus months of
1999-2000, the former Bruins captain no doubt would be the Norris
Trophy winner and the Bruins, no doubt, would have a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the 39-year-old Bourque (7-5_12 in 12 games with
the Avalanche) looks like Larry Murphy redux, playing with
enthusiasm and effectiveness, as if the thin air of Colorado
cleansed his soul and erased a decade from his birth certificate.
Murphy looked worn out and lost with Toronto in the spring of '97,
Maple Leafs fans booing his every move. Swapped to the Red Wings at
the trading deadline, he was shaking a Stanley Cup jubilantly above
his head three months later, and yet another (No. 4 in his career)
in the spring of '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``A perfect case,'' said the humble Murphy, ``of how a rising
tide lifts all ships.''
</P>
<P>
   With a week to go in the regular season, and ballots just being
filled out for trophy winners, Bourque has no shot at a sixth
Norris. More important to him, no doubt, is a realistic chance of
shaking that Cup. The Blues' Chris Pronger will be the hands-down
Norris winner, perhaps by unanimous vote, and his superlative play
in the second half is worthy of Hart Trophy (MVP) consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Someone stop the music right now, please, and roll the calendar
back a decade. Bourque collected 84 points in the 1989-90 season,
playing 76 games, unloading 310 shots from the backline. Not that
it factored in the balloting, because awards are based solely on
the regular season, but he also led the Bruins to the Stanley Cup
finals, their last visit to the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   No one meant more to his team that season than Bourque, and
that, folks, is the definition of the Hart Trophy _ ``the player
adjudged the most valuable to his team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Bourque won the Norris Trophy and Mark Messier, with
45 goals and 129 points, won the Hart. Bourque finished No. 2. A
travesty? Not really. Messier was still a strong, vibrant player
for the Oilers, and the belief here is he was a greater piece to
the Oiler dynasty than Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, no one meant more to his club than Bourque. Gretzky
was out of Edmonton in 1989-90, but Messier was still surrounded by
Jari Kurri (93 points), Glenn Anderson (72 points) and Esa Tikkanen
up front, Steve Smith and Kevin Lowe on defense, and the Grant
Fuhr-Bill Ranford combination in the cage. Messier could be joined
by two or three of those guys in the Hall of Fame. Those Oilers
erased the Bruins, 4-1, in the finals, by an emphatic 20-8 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque finished second to Cam Neely (92 points) in scoring that
season, followed by Craig Janney (62) and Bob Carpenter (56). And
let's not forget, the Bruins finished with 101 points _ 11 points
more than the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   So why did Messier win the Hart? For one reason: Bourque was the
clear-cut Norris choice and the members of the Professional Hockey
Writers' Association, then and now, view the Norris as the MVP for
defensemen. The last backliner to win the Hart was Bobby Orr, and
if current wisdom prevails, Orr will remain the last.
</P>
<P>
   History aside, the pick here for MVP is Florida's Pavel Bure.
Take him out of that lineup, and the Panthers are, at best, around
.500, perhaps out of the playoff picture. Remove Pronger from the
Blues and you've still got a respectable club. In fact, the MVP of
the Blues is netminder Roman Turek, whose success is partially
linked to the 6-foot-6-inch, 25-year-old Pronger.
</P>
<P>
   Until we see a defenseman who meant more to his club than
Bourque in 1989-90, all other blueliners can get in line, including
the talented Mr. Pronger.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the picks for this season's awards:
</P>
<P>
   Vezina Trophy (top goalie) _ Turek. No one got more out of the
'99 expansion draft than St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Calder Trophy (top rookie) _ Scott Gomez, New Jersey. He got the
early jump on Philadelphia's Simon Gagne.
</P>
<P>
   Selke trophy (top defensive forward) _ Steve Yzerman, Detroit.
His first, but shouldn't he have more by now?
</P>
<P>
   Lady Byng Trophy (gentlemanly play) _ Paul Kariya, Anaheim.
Imagine if he had a temper?
</P>
<P>
   Adams Award (top coach) _ Joel Quenneville, St. Louis. Great
goalies make great coaches, but it took more than Turek.
</P>
<P>
   A New York minute
</P>
<P>
   The dismissals of Neil Smith and John Muckler in New York
weren't a shock, but the abruptness was startling. MSG president
Dave Checketts said he needed to send a message to the players and
the fan base, underscoring a third straight season without a
playoff berth couldn't be tolerated. Now what? It will be up to the
new GM to pick the coach. Look for ex-Ranger role player Glen
Sather to get a feeler, but that's an annual right of spring for
Slats. One day, though, he may finally get fed up with the tight
purse strings in Edmonton _ and no fewer than 37 limited Oiler
partners _ and take someone up on one of these offers. Early word
along Broadway had ex-Blueshirt Gretzky consulting ownership on
Smith's successor, but the Great One batted that one down right
away. If asked, Gretzky no doubt would endorse Pat Burns, provided
the Bruins ax Burns when the smoke clears here in the Hub. Another
likely landing spot for Burns would be Philadelphia, if Roger
Neilson, now being treated for multiple myeloma, is unable to
return next season. The Blackhawks, also likely to change behind
the bench when the season ends, wouldn't have Burns on the shopping
list . . . Lost in the blur of three-plus overtimes last Sunday at
Albany: St. Lawrence's winning goal was set up by the forechecking
of freshman center Jim Lorentz, son of the former Bruin who was
part of Boston's 1970 Cup-winning squad. The senior Lorentz lives
in suburban Buffalo and is a color commentator for Sabres'
telecasts on the Empire Network . . . No one in the NHL handles the
puck like Boston University freshman netminder Rick DiPietro.
Forget the old adage of a goalie as a third defenseman. DiPietro
looks like a fourth forward. The pro game will change his style _
the red line will mitigate long breakout passes _ but he sure is
fun to watch around the cage . . . Ex-BC Eagle Bill Guerin enjoyed
the BU loss and couldn't wait to call Oiler teammate, and
ex-Terrier, Mike Grier. That Commonwealth Ave. rivarly never dies .
. . Is this the summer that an NHL team takes a serious run at
Northeastern head coach Bruce Crowder? . . . The Canucks have four
games to go, including Sunday's matinee in Chicago. Donald
Brashear, skated last week for the first time since being felled by
Marty McSorley's stick and could be available Wednesday vs. the
Kings. Meanwhile, the Canucks have inched into a fight for the No.
8 seed in the Western Conference. The key? ``The guys are working
hard, and I give a lot of credit there to the coaching staff, for
melding these players into a unit,'' said GM Brian Burke. ``Second
would be (netminder Felix) Potvin _ he's been outstanding _ and
third would be Mess (Mark Messier).'' According to Burke, he told
Messier prior to the trade deadline that the club likely would not
pick up his option ($6 million) for 2000-2001. ``We don't know what
we're going to do,'' said Burke. ``But in fairness to Mess _ so he
could decide what he wanted to do _ I felt I had to tell him how we
were feeling. And it's been a testament to his character that he
didn't bail on us. Without him, we're not in this thing. He's been
the lead dog.'' . . . Provided Pronger wins the Norris, Detroit's
Nicklas Lidstrom likely would finish runner-up for the third
straight season. Ex-Bruin Brad Park, then with the Rangers,
finished second three straight years (1970-72), overshadowed by
Orr. Yzerman on Lidstrom: ``He's the best player I've played with
in my 17 years in Detroit.'' Yzerman, by the way, may be sidelined
with a wrenched knee until the start of the playoffs . . . Imagine
a Bruins team next season that had both Aaron Downey and Martin
Grenier in the lineup. Downey had 401 penalty minutes last year
with Providence and Grenier 479 with Quebec (Junior A). Are you
ready to rumble?
</P>
<P>
   Home away from home
</P>
<P>
   Development plans aren't finalized, but it appears the key
elements _ including ice surface, dressing rooms and about 4,000
seats (the golds) _ will be intact when Maple Leaf Gardens is
refashioned into a condominium and entertainment complex. The
Leafs, now in the sparkling Air Canada Centre, will use it as a
practice rink and passersby will be able to take in their workouts
. . . Don't rule out Devils GM Lou Lamoriello as Rangers GM. If
Lamoriello doesn't have autonomy under the Devils new ownership,
he'll probably take a hike from Exit 16W . . . The deal that sent
Doug Gilmour to the Sabres also included $3 million to help the
Sabres pay Gilmour . . . Colorado insisted on Dave Andreychuk as
part of the Bourque trade and wouldn't have tossed Sami Pahlsson
into the mix if the Bruins didn't part with the one-time prolific
scorer. It was curious then, but even more curious now. Headed into
Sunday's matinee with Dallas, Andreychuk has only 2 points (both
assists) with the Avalanche and now has gone 22 straight without a
goal . . . Chicago's Tony Amonte is hoping to pot a 40th goal for
the third time in four seasons. No. 40 is worth a $300,000 bonus to
the ex-BU Terrier, more than a 10 percent sweetener on his $2.8
million base pay . . . One indication how well the Capitals are
going: Peter Bondra is playing on the fourth line. That, folks, is
depth . . . Lowe sees the same Bourque today that he has seen now
for nearly 25 years. ``He doesn't care how the puck comes over to
him,'' said Lowe. ``When he makes up his mind, he's shooting. He
plays the same today as when I played against him as a junior _
hasn't changed one bit.'' . . . Burke's read on the goings-on in
New York, where he feels Smith walked the plank after carrying out
ownership's orders to bring in high-priced free agents: ``I just
wish that everyone who is dumping on Neil now would just remember
one thing: 1940. He brought honor and glory to that franchise, and
then he gets fired because ownership says he overspent? How does
that work? Smith and Muckler end up taking the blame. The people
there who should be embarrassed are the players who took the money
and didn't perform. The guys who got their heads chopped off did
their best, and I don't think those players can say the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
