<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-DOMESTIC-AZR &LR;      04-01 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2ND CHANCE FOR KILLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KARINA BLAND  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Women imprisoned for killing the men who beat them
could be released under a new law that lets them use longtime abuse
as their defense.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, signed March 24 by Gov. Jane Hull, lets inmates
petition the Board of Executive Clemency to review their sentences
if they were convicted before a 1992 law requiring courts to
consider evidence of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were tried like they just killed a stranger on the
street, without any consideration for the history of the
relationship or how desperate battered women get when they see no
other way out,'' said Bahney Dedolph, director of public policy for
the Arizona Coalition Against Domestic Violence, a non-profit
group.
</P>
<P>
   Women such as Carol Herriman, 52, who was sentenced to life
after she shot her abusive husband as he sat on the toilet in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Or Lisa Shannon, 33, who was sent to prison for 18 years for
asking a co-worker to beat her husband to death in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   And Susan Brune, 40, who said she killed her married boyfriend
in self-defense in 1988. She, too, got life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Elaine Richardson, D-Tucson, who wrote the legislation,
said these women and probably a half-dozen others in Arizona
prisons may be freed, given the changes in law and attitudes toward
domestic violence since their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They deserve the chance to tell their stories,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time inmates have had such an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a law written by Richardson allowed 24 inmates to seek
review of their sentences, but only six, including Herriman, met
the criteria for a hearing:
</P>
<P>
   The inmate suffered from battered person's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   There were at least three corroborated acts of domestic violence
by the victim.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate committed the offense as a direct result of past acts
of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Only the victim died or was seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Just one of the six won release. Sandra Reid, who had been
sentenced to life in prison for killing her abusive father while he
slept in 1985, left prison after 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The new law is aimed at cases like Herriman's. She was denied
release three years ago because she was charged with murder and
conspiracy. The first law didn't allow for conspiracy charges; this
one does.
</P>
<P>
   Herriman was convicted in 1988, four years before Arizona juries
were told to consider how a ``reasonable person'' would react to
abuse in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   State prisons hold 95 women convicted of murder. The Department
of Corrections doesn't track whether the killings were tied to
domestic violence, spokesman Michael Arra says. So, how many
inmates will apply for a hearing this time is only a guess.
</P>
<P>
   Since the battered-person defense was allowed in 1992, some
women who killed abusive husbands and boyfriends have been
sentenced to probation or were never charged at all.
</P>
<P>
   In early December, police decided not to arrest, and Maricopa
County did not file charges against, Stephanie Dunn, who stabbed
her husband to death and claimed self-defense. The couple had a
history of violence.
</P>
<P>
   A FAIRNESS ISSUE &QL; 
``I do not condone murder in any way or form,'' Richardson said.
``But this is a fairness issue. You can't have a different method
of being tried depending on whether you commited the act before
1992 or after.''
</P>
<P>
   These women admit what they did, even if they don't remember the
details. Often, Richardson says, these things happen in stupors of
alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic violence, still considered one of the most
underreported crimes, was once thought best handled by anyone other
than the police.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Ferraro, associate director of the women's studies
program at Arizona State University and an expert on violence
against women, says victims often suffer from low self-esteem,
feelings of shame and guilt and a sense that they are trapped in a
situation they can't escape.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro often is called to testify about the impact of domestic
violence on women. In fact, she testified for Brune and Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   These are women who, because of years of abuse, sometimes think
it's a situation of kill or be killed, Ferraro says.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Imbordino, who heads the family violence division of the
Maricopa County Attorney's Office, says the 1992 law changed how
police and prosecutors handle cases of those who assault or kill
their abusers.
</P>
<P>
   People are better now at reporting domestic violence, whether it
is in their own home or a neighbor's, Imbordino says. So, there is
a better record in deciding whether to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years down the road when the wife says, `I had to kill him
because he was going to beat me again,' there is something to
document that,'' Imbordino said.
</P>
<P>
   And now, police often tape interviews with victims, either video
or audio, and take photographs of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all things they didn't routinely used to do,''
Imbordino said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's bill had the support of the Arizona Association of
Chiefs of Police.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors, however, still are hard to convince that domestic
violence is a valid defense for killing one's abuser.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are more sympathetic because of the publicity,''
Imbordino said, ``but they still require us to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro says jurors still have little sympathy for domestic
violence victims who don't run when they have the chance and even
less for those who are minorities, or use alcohol or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always ask, `Why not just walk out the door?'' Ferraro
said, adding that women are 14 times more likely to be killed by
their abusers after they leave.
</P>
<P>
   Brune and Shannon were turned down during the first round of
clemency hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both cases,'' Ferraro said, ``the board (members) said they
believed they were battered, but it didn't justify what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   SUBJECT NO LONGER TABOO &QL; 
Thirty years ago, she says, no one talked about domestic violence.
Twenty years ago, people may have talked about it, but only in
whispers.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed, says Dedolph of the Arizona Coalition
Against Domestic Violence, particularly since 1994, when the trial
of O.J. Simpson in the stabbing death of his ex-wife thrust the
issue of domestic violence into American living rooms and Congress
passed the Violence Against Women Act.
</P>
<P>
   The federal act provided money to improve law enforcement,
prosecution and victim services in domestic violence cases. For
Arizona, it has meant more than $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   When Richardson first pushed bills dealing with domestic
violence in 1993, she couldn't muster one vote. Now, she gets
little resistance, and other lawmakers introduce their own.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro said the use of the so-called battered-woman syndrome
defense actually started in the early '80s, though not widespread
until the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The ``battered-woman'' defense is actually self-defense with
evidence of domestic violence and a documented pattern of victim
responses and characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   RISKY DEFENSE &QL; 
Whatever the name, less than a third of victims who use it are
acquitted. It requires proof that the victims reasonably believed
they were in immediate danger of death or great bodily injury.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it freed Reid, the only inmate paroled under Richardson's
first bill.
</P>
<P>
   During her trial in 1986, Reid was not allowed to tell the
jurors about her years of physical and sexual abuse at the hands of
her father, Lewis Trimble. Without review of her case, Reid, now
43, would have gotten out in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us condone murder as a solution,'' Dedolph said.
``However, I do believe there are some situations in which victims
felt they had no other choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Inmates will be notified of the reviews by Sept. 1 and have 90
days to apply. The clemency board must finish all reviews by June
30, 2001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at &QL; 
Karina.Bland(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8614. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
