u a BC-TWIN-KILLINGS-NYT     04-01 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWIN-KILLINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWIN BROTHERS ARE FOUND SHOT TO DEATH, THEIR BODIES DUMPED ON A
BROOKLYN STREET
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nineteen-year-old twin brothers were found shot in
the head early Saturday, their bodies dumped into the middle of a
residential street in the Gravesend section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony and Charles DiGirolamo, who would have turned 20 next
week, were found in front of 1794 West Fifth St. by a passer-by
about 4:25 a.m., said Sgt. Elias Nikas, a police spokesman. Their
bodies apparently had been dumped from a car in the middle of the
one-way street, near the corner of West Fifth and Quentin Road. The
twins lived on East Second Street in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the two men, who the police said were identical twins,
had been shot once in the temple, the authorities said. The police
said they had no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said Charles DiGirolamo was free on
bail in connection with an assault case in Brooklyn stemming from a
stabbing in a Sheepshead Bay nightclub, but they could provide no
details.
</P>
<P>
   Two federal law enforcement officials said that when the
brothers were in their early teens, in the mid-1990s, they had been
involved with a group of drug dealers who worked for James Galione,
an organized crime figure who was associated first with the Bonnano
crime family and later with the Lucchese group. Galione, who was
known as Froggy or Frog Eyes, according to the authorities, pleaded
guilty in 1997 to murder and drug charges. The two brothers were
not charged in connection with that case, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers' family could not be reached by phone for comment
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Charles DiGirolamo also was a suspect in the August 1999 killing
of Peter Lanza, a Brooklyn man who was found shot in his apartment
in Gravesend, his hands bound and his head covered by a pillowcase,
a senior investigator said. Lanza, who had a criminal record for
drug and fireworks possession dating to 1992, was on probation at
the time of his killing and was wearing an electronic monitoring
bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   The two brothers had also been identified as material witnesses
in the 1998 killing of a young woman in a sandwich shop in Pinellas
County in Florida, the authorities said. The two brothers, along
with three other men from Brooklyn, had driven to Florida in April
of that year, an investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the other men, Robert A. Pasquince, walked into a Subway
sandwich shop in Pinellas County, jumped over the counter and
demanded money from Ann Marie Sherman, a 24-year-old single mother
who was working her first night as an assistant manager, the
investigator said. He forced her and another employee to lie on the
floor. ``He threatened to kill Ms. Sherman and she begged him not
to, but he did,'' the investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   Pasquince took $277 from the cash register and fled. He was
later convicted of first-degree murder, the investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Florida investigators ever had an
opportunity to question the brothers in connection with the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   The police found the bodies Saturday after a passer-by called
911 and said there were two men bleeding from the head in the
street, Nikas said. One of the brothers was pronounced dead on the
street, while the other was taken to Kings County Hospital, where
he died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
