<HEADER>
A4684 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     04-01 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANY WAY YOU SPELL IT, IT S-T-I-N-K-S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the middle of the night but it wasn't
merely a nightmare. The opening-day images beaming back from Tokyo
last Wednesday really did show umpires wearing caps embroidered
with ``MLB.''
</P>
<P>
   Little things mean a lot in baseball and that little logo
symbolizes the game's shrinking soul.
</P>
<P>
   MLB is not the name on a can of coffee. MLB is short for Major
League Baseball, the sport's corporate name.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago it was rare and strange to see major
league baseball written with capital letters. Major league baseball
wasn't a product in shrink wrap, it was the dream of any
red-blooded American boy, a religion.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball had this special edge on all the other professional
sports. The NBA, NHL and NFL needed such stock-ticker
abbreviations. They were always having to fight off challengers -
the ABA, the WHA, the USFL. The first thing every fledgling soccer
league did was to test-market its initials - MISL? MSL? MLS?
</P>
<P>
   You weren't a factor unless you stretched the alphabet - PGA,
WTA, NASCAR. Now even racehorses have initials - the NTRA, whose
executives behave as if establishing a ``brand name'' is a step
toward the sports big time.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball never needed a brand name. It was bigger than that. It
was just baseball. You'd hear people say they're NBA fans, NHL fans
or NFL fans. Nobody ever said, ``I'm an MLB fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wrote a book called, ``MLB is a Funny Game.'' Nobody in a
movie said, ``There's no crying in MLB.'' It wasn't ``MLB,
motherhood and apple pie.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner didn't profess to act ``in the best interest of
MLB.'' But now that's exactly what Bud Selig seems to have in mind.
Bud Selig, the CEO.
</P>
<P>
   More and more you read Major League Baseball, with the capitals,
in official publications, in television graphics and in
undiscriminating newspapers. And lately it's just MLB.
</P>
<P>
   But until the base umpires at the Chicago Cubs-New York Mets
games in Japan put on their MLB caps instead of the traditional
``NL'' and ``AL'' hats, I don't remember that symbol making its way
onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   If this is a regular thing, it's an unpleasant reminder that not
only are baseball teams all about business anymore, so is the game.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about the labor politics that have resulted in a
weakened umpiring corps falling under the authority of the
commissioner's office instead of under the separate control of the
National and American leagues.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about the further blurring of the line between the
two leagues.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about baseball's - make that MLB's - effort to extend
its following across the International Dateline.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say there's anything wrong with corporations,
which obviously have their place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   That place just doesn't happen to be on a baseball diamond.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate mentality applied to running a baseball league
means constant attempts at self-justification. Who, except an
executive with too many blank lines on his desk calendar, would
come up with this plan to break the National League into four
divisions and leave the American with three and a wild card?
</P>
<P>
   When the commissioner's office suspended John Rocker, the move
was justifiably protested. If the Atlanta Braves wanted to suspend
him, that would be fine. The Braves are Rocker's employers.
Baseball is not.
</P>
<P>
   But the boys at Major League Baseball probably don't see it that
way. Rocker is just a member of the firm. So is everybody else on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   If this makes you as uneasy as it makes me, maybe the solution
is to wear MLB caps in protest. That's MLB for minor-league
baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4685 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CONGRESS-ARI-AZR &LR;      04-01 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ARI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY GROUP ENTERS STATE POL ITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - A secretive group of New York financiers plans to put
as much as $100,000 behind a single candidate for Arizona's 1st
Congressional District primary in September, a race that promises
to be one of the most tumultuous in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Club for Growth, dedicated to electing fiscal conservatives
to Congress, plans to back Jeff Flake, a former director of the
Goldwater Institute who agrees with the group's views on cutting
capital gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP primary field is already teeming with outspoken
personalities, including Sal DiCiccio, a frequently dissenting
member of the Phoenix City Council; state Sen. John Huppenthal,
R-Chandler, a conservative education activist; Tom Liddy, a lawyer
and son of Watergate figure G. Gordon Liddy; and businesswoman and
lobbyist Susan Bitter Smith, a former member of the Scottsdale City
Council.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for the Club for Growth, the group's
members may pump thousands of dollars into the race in television
ads, along with the $100,000 in contributions earmarked for Flake's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll raise as much as it takes to win (the Sept. 12
primary),'' said Leila Bate, executive director of the Club for
Growth, regarding the group's effort in the predominantly eastern
Arizona district. ``We want him to win. And if he needs additional
help, we're committed to do that.'' &QL; 
A MYSTERY INSIDE AN ENIGMA
</P>
<P>
   The Club, many of whose leaders have Wall Street pedigrees, has
raised more than $2 million while remaining shrouded in mystery,
refusing to release its full membership list. According to
columnist Robert Novak, it is prepared to spend $10 million to
unseat moderate Republicans in favor of ones more to its liking.
</P>
<P>
   One of the incumbents who has found himself in the bad graces of
the Club for Growth is Arizona Congressman Jim Kolbe of Tucson.
Other moderates include GOP Reps. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, Jim
Greenwood of Pennsylvania, Jack Quinn of New York and Greg Ganske
of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Flake, who also has received the endorsement of the district's
outgoing incumbent, Rep. Matt Salmon, has proudly listed the Club
for Growth's endorsement on his Web site. And he already has begun
receiving the group's checks in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are serious about this,'' Flake said, adding that his was
the only unanimous endorsement from the organization's board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should help,'' Flake added, in what could be an
understatement. Novak reported that the Club could spend as much as
$500,000 in the race on any candidate it endorses. &QL; 
RAISED EYEBROWS
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, director of the Center for Responsive Politics,
said the emerging prominence of political groups such as the Club
is troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could buy the election,'' Makinson said. ``They are
basically saying, `Damn the limits, full speed ahead.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Makinson said that by engaging in both issue advocacy ads and
the bundling of hard-money contributions, the Club for Growth comes
perilously close to crossing one of the bright lines of campaign
finance law, which prohibits coordination between candidates and
third-party groups that spend money independently of the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bate said that the Club is aware of the prohibition against
coordination between candidates and groups that engage in
independent expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely a consideration, and we do not want to cross
that line,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we are not communicating with our candidates at
all,'' Bate added, ``except to the extent that we send bundled
contributions, so that we reserve the right to do issue ads
independently.'' &QL; 
THE KOLBE QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   In addition to coming to the aid of tax cutters in swing
districts, the organization is targeting moderate Republicans whom
it considers are opposed to tax cuts or in favor of government
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bate said Kolbe is no longer a target of the group. But she
would not rule out future action against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really our freshman year, and we want to target very
carefully who we choose (to oppose and support),'' Bate said.
``That's not to say we are not going to keep an eye on Kolbe; at
this point . . . we haven't ruled anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Rosenblum, a spokesman for Kolbe, said the group's
decision to target the Arizona congressman is off the mark because
the Tucson congressman scores well on ``99 percent of their
(fiscal) issues.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a source close to Kolbe, the group was persuaded to
back off after a number of his supporters called to complain.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have asked the group to cease its targeting of
incumbents is House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, who strenuously
objected that the group's efforts threatened to unravel the GOP's
attempts to maintain its already-tenuous majority status.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether it was appropriate for the group to consider
targeting Kolbe, Flake demurred, saying that he believes in Kolbe's
record but also that he supports the group's right to criticize a
member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have every right to do so, but in Kolbe's case _
Kolbe, from my standpoint, has been quite good on fiscal issues,''
Flake said. &QL; 
OPPONENTS REACT
</P>
<P>
   The out-of-state group's intervention and its threatened
involvement in Kolbe's race also has rankled some of Flake's
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Liddy, who said he was unaware of the group until recently,
said, ``I'm a little bit surprised that Jeff Flake is willing to
take $100,000 of (out of state) money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it translates to except out-of-state
money,'' Smith agreed. ``I would be a little concerned if I were
(Flake). They are amassing money, but their first priority is to
knock off some sitting Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of interesting that nobody knows who these
guys are,'' DiCiccio said. ``It's like the Pace Picante commercial:
`Noo Yo-ark City?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But in a measure of the influence of money in congressional
races, even those who are now critical of the group once sought its
endorsement. Realizing what an infusion of $100,000 could mean to
their aspirations, both DiCiccio and Smith contacted the Club for
Growth seeking its support.
</P>
<P>
   They both were rebuffed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at &QL; 
Kris.Mayes(at)ArizonaRepublic.com &QL; 
or (602) 444-8285.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
