<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN SEASON DECLARED ON DUMB PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Arizona politicians are well aware of how stupid the
majority of you people are. But, being politicians, they've failed
to act on it, at least until last week. That's when your luck ran
out.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state Legislature finally figured out a way to make your
dimwittedness work for them and their cronies.
</P>
<P>
   They passed a resolution that will add to the Nov. 7 ballot a
proposal requiring all voter initiatives dealing with wildlife
management to pass by a two-thirds majority, rather than the usual
51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the plan say they simply want to leave wildlife
management to the ``experts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take politics out of it,'' Brad Kerby told me
Friday, April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Kerby is chairman of a group calling itself Arizonans for
Wildlife Conservation. It's a collection of hunters, outdoorsmen
and others who believe there's a conspiracy of do-gooders in our
state trying to prevent grown men from wearing fluorescent orange
jumpsuits in public.
</P>
<P>
   And also from shooting animals.
</P>
<P>
   Kerby happens to be an attorney as well, making him a expert at
manipulating dumb guys. For example, columnists.
</P>
<P>
   He told me the proposal being put to voters in November isn't
meant to rob us of the sacred notion that ``majority rules.'' He
also said requiring a ``supermajority'' for an issue like wildlife
management doesn't set a bad precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it'll make it a lot more difficult for regular folks to
have a say in the matter, but he believes it's even more important
to have wildlife decisions made by ``people who have greater access
and more exposure and more connection with the wildlife itself, and
more appreciation for the challenges wildlife face.''
</P>
<P>
   When you put it that way, it sounds like a thoughtful,
well-reasoned approach to a difficult problem.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what they're hoping it'll sound like to all us
nincompoops.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, democracy is messy. It doesn't rely on experts. It
relies on amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   On us.
</P>
<P>
   If we were going to pass a bunch of laws saying we should let
experts decide things, I'd like to believe even knuckleheads like
us would pick an issue slightly more important than hunting and
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Health care, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   If experts were important, we'd let doctors make the decisions
about medical care instead of insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Or education.
</P>
<P>
   If experts were important, we'd let educators decide what our
kids learn, not politicians or political appointees.
</P>
<P>
   One of the experts supporting the special two-thirds rule for
wildlife initiatives is state Game &AMP; Fish Commission Chairman Hays
Gilstrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our wildlife are at the mercy of whatever might happen,
politically,'' he said, adding that initiatives affecting our furry
friends should require a two-thirds majority because animals don't
have a voice in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do poor people, but we don't require a two-thirds
majority before passing laws that make their lives rougher.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the legislators who went along with this wildlife scheme
are confident you'll fall for it.
</P>
<P>
   They figure you're not capable of seeing through a politically
motivated campaign claiming to take ``politics'' out of an issue.
</P>
<P>
   How could Arizona politicians know with such certainty that
Arizona voters are gullible enough to fall for something like that?
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way:
</P>
<P>
   You elected them, didn't you? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at &QL; 
Ed.Montini &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com &QL; 
or (602) 444-8978. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
