<DOCNO> NYT20000401.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-CAROLINA-FLORIDA-     04-01 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CAROLINA-FLORIDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GAME OF ATTRITION, GATORS WEAR DOWN THE TIRED TAR HEELS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Florida is a young, exuberant basketball team
that loves to run and trap and press. But when the game gets
gritty, the Gators get greedy.
</P>
<P>
   Ask North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels threw their size, experience and tradition at
Florida. The Gators snapped back. In fact, there was little Florida
could not handle on its way to a relentless 71-59 victory over
North Carolina here in the RCA Dome that showed why Florida (29-7)
is in the national championship game. It meets Michigan State here
on Monday night for the title.
</P>
<P>
   Florida threw a trap at North Carolina _ on the court and in the
Tar Heels' minds _ that turned the game its way. The Gators
pressured Carolina all night with a variety of full-court presses,
and the result was 17 Carolina turnovers. It made sure the game was
played with speed and pace, the way Florida likes it.
</P>
<P>
   And, most of all, Florida baited Carolina into serious foul
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Joseph Forte and forward Jason Capel fouled out in the
final minutes for Carolina. Both played most of the second half in
foul trouble. So did point guard Ed Cota. Even center Brendan
Haywood (20 points, 12 rebounds) played a long time with four
fouls.
</P>
<P>
   It was Florida's quickness, and its deep bench, that pushed
Carolina to fouls and to the brink. The Florida bench outscored
Carolina's by 37-2. While nearly all of the Carolina starters
played at least 35 minutes apiece, Florida kept rotating, using its
numbers, remaining fresh and putting the Tar Heels in a bind.
</P>
<P>
   Balance was Florida's staple. Three players (Mike Miller, Udonis
Haslem and Brett Nelson) scored in double figures and Florida shot
38.7 percent from the floor. Carolina was limited to 33.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina had won seven straight games over teams from the
Southeastern Conference. But Florida was too balanced, too focused,
too fresh. It matched Carolina in rebounds and showed its quickness
with nine steals, compared with only three for Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Gators played 13 or more minutes. All 10 scored.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing for the final 16 minutes 5 seconds of the first
half, North Carolina began the second half with flair. The Tar
Heels were the more energetic team and turned a three-point
halftime deficit into a 45-42 lead. But Florida regrouped and
bounced ahead, 60-54, with 7:07 left. A 3-pointer from forward
Major Parker and a basket from Nelson provided the scoring, and the
lift that Florida needed.
</P>
<P>
   From there, with many of Carolina's starters in foul trouble, it
became a game of attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Which team had enough left to survive? To impose its will? To
reach the final?
</P>
<P>
   That would be Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-00 2317EST &QL; 
