<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-01 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-1ST     04-01 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A CHILDHOOD DREAM FOR TWO COMES TRUE
</HEADLINE>
  (REPLACES original column) 
 (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ There are not many good arguments anymore for
staying in college for four or five years, passing up the pros.
Such a mercenary cesspool at this level where the blind lead the
blind.
</P>
<P>
   But the game has its moments.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night in the happy but subdued Michigan State locker
room, Mateen Cleaves and Morris Peterson offered a compelling
result _ if not an argument _ for sticking it out. Cleaves, the
Spartans inspirational point guard, was 1 of 7 and scored 11 points
in Michigan State's 53-41 victory over Big Ten Rival Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, Cleaves' friend from Flint, carried the day with 20
points in a clutch performance.
</P>
<P>
   Now Michigan State is a victory away from capturing the
Spartans' first national championship since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans have to go through a hot, young Florida team to
complete a dream season. After Saturday night's victory, Cleaves,
jumping the gun, said that a matchup between Michigan State and
Florida might be the matchup of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago Peterson was attending his grandmother's funeral.
Clara Mae Spencer, 72, died at home in Mississippi after a stroke
she had had weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson answered questions _ ``Were you thinking of her? Did
she inspire you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, when the game was hard, I was tired, I didn't think
about her,'' Peterson said. He even joked that his grandmother's
spirit may have guided in a couple of his shots.
</P>
<P>
   The grieving will come on Tuesday, after the basketball is over.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for Saturday's victory over Wisconsin came from
imaginary playground games Peterson and Cleaves had played as
children on the playground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about this ever since we were little kids,''
Peterson said. ``I'd be Jalen Rose, he'd be Steve Smith or I'd be
Magic and he'd be Greg Kelsor. We played like that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, Cleaves flirted with going to the NB A. The
decision to come back, ultimately, had to do with whether he was
ready for that level or not.
</P>
<P>
   But the carrot dangling to lure his return to Michigan State was
winning a national championship, playing for a national
championship. Playing for it with his childhood friend was
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he came back,'' Peterson said. ``For this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The quality of the game that got them there was forgettable.
Cleaves even laughed when someone asked him what he thought the
game looked like to a national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people probably turned the game off and on,'' he
said. ``It was ugly. But I don't care, really. I don't get hung up
on statistics and how things look. I get hung up on winning. And we
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a team gets the luck of the draw _ we all do, now and
then. Planets and stars aligned
</P>
<P>
   That is what happened to Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers crushed Tarkanian's Fresno team, caught Arizona
without its star player, whipped a young Louisiana State team that
had never faced their type of defense before. Then they defeated
conference rival Purdue by a point and here they are.
</P>
<P>
   The road ended Friday night with a thud against a granite wall _
the same granite they had crashed into three times.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 Wisconsin won the championship by defeating Washington
State, 39-34.
</P>
<P>
   Same ugly game. On Saturday the Spartans led by just 19-17 at
the half, a score just shy of the intermission score in the 1941
championship game when Wisconsin was ahead by 21-17.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, with an ideology not so far removed from 1941,
Wisconsin banged and bruised the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk about odds catching up to Michigan State. They
had defeated Wisconsin three times this season: 61-44 in February,
59-54 at East Lansing and 55-46 in the Big Ten tournament.
</P>
<P>
   How can you beat one team four times?
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Michigan State was simply better. With Cleaves scoring
11 points and providing defense, Morris Peterson providing the
spark for the offense, Michigan State was better.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, Cleaves finished third in player of the
year voting behind Wally Szczerbiak and Elton Brand.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be that close this year but he will be playing for
the national championship Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Now the two friends can think about those crazy days in the park
where one pretended to be Jalen and the other was Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Not a lot of basketball players get to live out dreams like
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met so many people through basketball,'' Cleaves said.
``I've met some of the greatest basketball players in the world. A
lot of them have never played for the national championship; a lot
of them have never even gotten close.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is a moment I really want to cherish.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson attended his grandmother's funeral on Thursday; he'll
play with Cleaves Monday night for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   So rare that childhood dreams come true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
