<HEADLINE>
NBA DRAFT COULD BE INTERESTING _ IN 2001
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ready or not, only 87 days separate us from David
Stern's plaintive wail of ``With the first selection in the 2000
NBA Draft, the Los Angeles Clippers select ...''
</P>
<P>
   OK, the Ping-Pong balls won't speak until May 21, but history
and karma conspire to remind us that the injury to first-pick bait
Kenyon Martin virtually guarantees a Clipper lottery triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Or would they still lose by winning?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it may seem a bit premature or even irresponsible to
contemplate this year's lottery roll call, so we've decided to go
completely cuckoo by mulling the 2001 draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Tyson Chandler draft.
</P>
<P>
   Gotcha.
</P>
<P>
   Well, in addition to Chandler _ the marvelously bouncy, 7-foot
junior from Dominguez High _ the 2001 draft expo could yield a
relative bonanza. (The word ``relative'' is attached because, every
year, the self-anointed smarties of draft evaluation claim the
current talent pool is just begging for a siege of chlorine.)
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, a few college prospects actually began
threatening to remain in school. Maryland forward Terence Morris
has pledged his senior season to the screaming desperation of Terps
coach Gary Williams. Iowa State point guard Jamaal Tinsley doesn't
seem to care that several NBA scouts have accused him of being a
top-five talent right now.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley has decided to achieve seniority as a Cylone.
</P>
<P>
   Texas center Chris Mihm may choose a fourth term in Austin. LSU
sophomore forward Stromile Swift, who jumps with the alarming
quickness of an abundantly caffeinated intern, has all but declared
an embargo on his inevitable leap into the draft's top five.
</P>
<P>
   Another downshift in the going rate was provided by Arizona
center Loren Woods, who has committed to a fifth year in college.
</P>
<P>
   Such news is just ducky to the big thinkers of sports journalism
and a few general managers whose jobs could be compromised by their
inability to tell if the aforementioned scholars can play or not.
</P>
<P>
   They will enter the standard plea of ``He's not ready,'' thereby
chucking the responsibility back to the likes of Arizona coach Lute
Olson. Lute has declared that the 7-foot-1 Woods a cinch top-seven
selection if he went professional now requires another year of
seasoning before attempting the brain surgery of an NBA rookie
year. Coincidentally, the ~ &QL; {]3
</P>
</TEXT>
