<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOLINSKI MAKES KEY PLAY FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _The biggest play in the biggest game belonged to
Bryan Smolinski, who is going to the playoffs in his first season
with the Kings after missing the last four years with the New York
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski stopped a potential go-ahead goal by the Ducks Ed Ward
in the second period of Saturday 2-1 Kings' victory by sticking out
his skate in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really remember the play,'' Smolinski said. ``I just
remember that we didn't want to hang (goaltender Stephane Fiset)
out to dry after the great effort he had given.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's shot came on a rebound of a blast by Anaheim's Paul
Kariya with 5:13 gone in the second. Moments earlier, the Kings
finally took their first shot of the game and Kelly Buchberger tied
it at one. But the momentum still was up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski knows a little about momentum shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, with the first line depleted by injuries,
Smolinski's second unit carried the offense.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past 22 games, he has one empty netter and a two-goal
game against the Ducks on March 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Bryan Smolinski to be better,'' Kings coach Andy
Murray said earlier in the week. ``He is an excellent player who
really has contributed for this club. But I probably shouldn't say
that since he is in the final year of his contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski was traded to the Kings last July with Ziggy Palffy.
Even with the scoring drought, he has 20 goals and 56 points.
</P>
<P>
   But the best part of the season clearly lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to get that playoff spot,'' he said. ``It's so
tough when you're left out year after year. These guys have played
so hard all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Goal scorer: The Kings didn't get Kelly Buchberger from Atlanta
for his scoring. They got him for for his grit and the lessons he
learned helping Edmonton win three Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchberger now has two goals in his last two games,
including the tying goal Saturday. It came at 4:29 of the second
period and was the Kings first shot of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't getting shots, but I didn't think we were laying
down,'' Buchberger said. ``We just hadn't found a rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger said he has seen the Kings confidence grow all
season, first from watching them on tape and during the last nine
games since the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that has grown a lot this season,'' he said.
``There was trade talk all season and I watched them a lot. Now,
that I'm here, I've seen it continue to grow. It's great to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
